<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS     02-28 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Trivia question: Which starting pitcher did the
Astros use their first-round pick on in 1993?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Answer: Closer Billy Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   It may have taken a few years for Wagner to find his calling,
but ever since it has been a match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting how decisions are made that seem
insignificant at the time but could totally change a kid's
career,'' said general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   The change almost didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   With all the hype befitting a No. 1 pick, Wagner entered spring
training in 1996 with a shot at making the Astros' rotation. There
was lobbying for Wagner, the talk of the organization at the time
because of his ability to fling a baseball at ungodly speeds, to
break camp with the club.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker balked. Wagner was sent to Class AAA Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The flirtation with Wagner and a starter's role didn't end
there. A few months later, Hunsicker went to watch Wagner pitch and
couldn't believe his eyes. What he saw was a starting pitcher in
need of three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hunsicker, Wagner had a fastball ``that was
certainly good but not great'' and little control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually one of those situations where I was
disappointed,'' Hunsicker said. ``I guess it was because the
expectations were so great. Many times that happens, when the
expectations become so great you can never quite live up to them. I
came out of there scratching my head because I didn't see the
polish I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, bad is good. After 70 starts in five minor-league
seasons, Wagner made it to the big leagues _ as a reliever. Billy
The Kid was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' said Wagner, who was eased into his new role
after an injury sidelined closer Todd Jones. ``I was all for being
a reliever, even before they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years, 158 appearances, 62 saves and a $10.3 million
contract later, he hasn't looked back.
</P>
<P>
   The questions, however, beg to be asked:
</P>
<P>
   What if the Astros hadn't needed help in the bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   What if Wagner had remained a starter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably still be in the minors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at 27, Wagner is one of the game's top closers. And one
of the hardest throwers, with pitches that approach 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's 30 saves last year (despite missing almost a month
after being hit in the head by a line drive) were the third-best
total in club history. Doug Jones holds the record with 36 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you get 30 saves in the league nowadays, it's
average,'' said Wagner. ``I think getting 30 saves for a guy on a
team like ours should be nothing. I think it's hard work to get 30,
but we won 102 games. I should have had 45 saves. I don't think you
can be one of the top closers until you've saved 40 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner converted 30 of 35 save opportunities in 1998, including
a stretch of 19 in a row. He averaged 14.6 strikeouts per nine
innings, fanning the side on 11 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations may be greater now with his salary increase
from $280,000 a year ago. But his approach will remain what it
always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know they have faith in me and that I'm going to
be the closer for the next three years. The financial security
makes things a little bit easier,'' Wagner said. `` I go out there
and try to do my job converting every save. There are going to be
games I blow, unless you have one of those great years where
everything goes your way. I still go out with the same mind frame:
`Hey, I've got to get this guy out; I can't let him score.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going out there saying, `If this guy scores, no big
deal because I'm already getting paid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker recalls the caution taken in addressing Wagner's
then-pending move to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   As a starter, there was no doubt about Wagner's velocity, which
showed flashes of 95 mph. The concern was that he had little
control and still needed to develop secondary pitches to complement
the fastball. The idea was to use Wagner's strength in shorter
stints.
</P>
<P>
   And what once was a 90- to 92-mph fastball as a starter became a
consistent 94 to 96 when Wagner became a closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a natural in that role,'' Hunsicker said. ``He
just took to it right away. He never missed a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wagner: ``I would go all out as a starter, and I never
would be able to pace myself. I'd get to the seventh inning, but I
was exhausted and wasn't able to go into the eighth or ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner doesn't have to pace himself any longer. And National
League hitters have no time to adjust. But by no means does Wagner
consider his on-the-job transition into a reliever complete.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the much-publicized effort to develop an
effective second pitch. His fastball is still the pitch of choice,
but Wagner is using this spring to work on a changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the fastball) is my No. 1 pitch as always,'' Wagner said.
``I'm coming into camp with a good changeup. I've had it for years
but never used it. As I start to use it more and more, I've started
to get more consistent. Most hitters can jump on a fastball. You've
got to have something else as an equalizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner has gotten a crash course in throwing a changeup from his
best friend and neighbor, former Astros pitcher Donne Wall, and
all-time strikeout king Nolan Ryan, who spent a day with Wagner in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker thinks Wagner could already have developed
his second pitch had the opportunity to test it come up.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Former catcher) Brad (Ausmus) very seldom called for anything
other than a fastball,'' Dierker said. ``We tried to get him to,
but he felt like we were doing hitters a favor if we threw them
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The learning process continued this winter when Wagner toured
with a group of major-leaguers in Japan. He used the time to pick
the brains of other top closers, particularly San Diego's Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell there's a difference already,'' Wagner said. ``I've
got a little better understanding on what I need to do and what I
want to do with the ball. Hopefully, it will pay off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
