<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-HNS &LR;      02-28 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Jeff Maggert expected to be here playing for the
PGA Tour's biggest payday ever.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His opponent in today's finale of the Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship had far more modest expectations. Andrew Magee
was so certain he would be lounging by the pool at his Arizona home
by now, he didn't pack enough clothes for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep having to iron another shirt at night,'' Magee said.
``I had to go buy socks, too. Two pairs at $10 each.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, he said, they ought to call this place ``La
Cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the ritzy La Costa Resort is a perfect backdrop for
today's conclusion to a week in which golf's top 64 players have
been whittled day by day, all in the pursuit of the $1 million top
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after The Woodlands' Maggert came from behind
to take down golf's brightest star, Tiger Woods, he proved again he
could rally in the clutch as he came from three holes down to beat
Steve Pate 1-up Saturday in the semifinals. Magee also was down by
three holes early in his match but pulled ahead and beat John
Huston 3 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   And so, it's Magee and Maggert in today's final. The winner's
share is more than either of them has won in a full year of play.
The loser gets $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The first inclination is to wonder if the Andersen Consulting
people should feel cheated because the Touchstone Energy Tucson
Open ended up with a better field over the weekend than was left at
La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   But everybody thinks it's terrific when there are upsets in the
NCAA Tournament. Why should it be different in golf?
</P>
<P>
   The lack of star quality on the final two days hasn't hurt the
caliber of golf. Maggert shot 32 on the back nine Saturday to pull
off the victory. He pulled even with Pate on the par-4 15th when he
made a 10-footer for birdie. He then got a gift on the 16th when
Pate made bogey to fall one hole behind.
</P>
<P>
   Magee's comeback was just as impressive and even more
unexpected. Unlike Maggert, who has played solidly during the first
two months of the PGA Tour season, Magee has been inconsistent,
which is why his hopes weren't high coming to La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed for the LA Open (last week) and for maybe half of
this week,'' Magee said. ``I figured I'd be going home for a nice
weekend off. But now, I'm just thrilled about it. I figured I'd
come here and win 25 grand (the reward for losing in the first
round). And now, I'm going for a million. I'm having a great
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't having a great time after the first three holes
Saturday. He lost all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was ready to start playing the consolation
match,'' Magee said. ``That changed in about 10 minutes when he
(Huston) bogeyed the fourth hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Magee drew even on No. 10 and went 1-up with a birdie at the
par-5 12th. He went ahead two holes when Huston bogeyed the 16th.
Magee chipped in for birdie on the par-5 17th to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Magee will try to win for the fifth time in his career when the
final commences today.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert, meanwhile, will try to avoid his 14th second-place
finish compared with a single victory in his PGA Tour career.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he's not about to apologize for being in the final
of the most lucrative tournament in PGA Tour history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way professional sports are,'' he said. ``Whether
it's basketball, football or golf, the superstars make it a great
game. If it wasn't for Tiger and David (Duval), our sport wouldn't
be what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have a very competitive sport. When you play a guy who
is playing good, it doesn't matter who you are. You'd better play
good, too, or you're going to get beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of close calls the last five years. But I'm
going to continue to keep putting myself in a position to win. And
I know sooner or later it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert is 13 under par for the five rounds he has played at La
Costa. That wouldn't have gotten him into the top three last year
at the Mercedes Championship, which was the tournament La Costa
hosted in '98.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, it's good enough for a minimum of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot of money, more than I've made in a whole season,''
Maggert said. ``But winning the golf tournament is going to mean a
lot more to me than the million dollars. I want the victory a lot
more than putting a few more dollars in my bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert played an atypical round Saturday. Normally consistent,
he made bogeys at No. 6 and No. 8, both par-4s, to put himself in a
2-down hole. That went to 3-down when Pate rolled in a 12-footer
for birdie at the par-3 11th.
</P>
<P>
   But Maggert turned on the jets after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about the way I played the last nine
holes,'' he said. ``I gave away some holes early in the round with
some silly bogeys, and I was upset at myself. That's not what I
normally do when I play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give holes away with a bogey, it's like taking the
momentum and handing it to your opponent instead of making him earn
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 3-down is a significant margin, especially when you've
only got seven holes left. Usually, the only way you can come back
from that is to make some birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   Or eagles, which Maggert did on the par-5 12th hole. He reached
the green in two shots, then drilled a 40-footer for eagle. He then
got a gift on the next hole when Pate's approach bored into the
sand and left him hopelessly sunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 13, I thought I had a chance,'' Pate said. ``He hit his
approach well behind the pin, and I was kind of in between clubs. I
decided to try to beat a sand wedge because I was downwind, and it
didn't clear the front bunker. I had a terrible lie and couldn't
get it close.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert had come from two holes down to beat Woods on Friday. He
said he falls back on his instincts whenever he gets behind in a
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get two or three holes behind, you have to get
aggressive,'' he said. ``You can't wait for your opponent to make
mistakes. I've always been the kind of player who isn't afraid to
fire at pins. If I'm in the fairway, I'll shoot at pins that are
tucked behind bunkers or the water.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
