</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-SPRING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS GETTING WITH PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Let the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' second spring season swings into focus this
week with intrasquad games on Monday and Tuesday, an exhibition
against the University of Arizona on Wednesday and the opener of
the Cactus League schedule against the Colorado Rockies on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things to keep an eye on this spring as the club,
full of new faces, searches for an identity: &QL; 
A test for Tony &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Tony Womack, acquired from Pittsburgh in a
trade on Friday, can steal bases, but what about his defense? Is he
capable of handling a move from second base to right field?
</P>
<P>
   It will be the job of outfield coach Dwayne Murphy to help the
transition go as smoothly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he'll probably be nervous, because it is difficult to
make a change like that,'' said Murphy, a six-time American League
Gold Glove winner with Oakland in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to be able to get a good jump on the ball, and then
there's reading the spin and the angle. He'll have to start during
batting practice, because doing it with fungoes is not that much of
a help.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack's arrival means more crowding in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter initially was leaning toward keeping five
outfielders and 11 pitchers, but that could end up being six and
10, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Four outfielders appear to be locked in _ Womack, Steve Finley,
Luis Gonzalez and Bernard Gilkey. The other one or two will come
from incumbents David Dellucci and Yamil Benitez, newcomer Dante
Powell, and non-roster invitees Pete Incaviglia and Ernie Young.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has been impressive early, particularly on defense, while
Dellucci and Incaviglia have been swinging the bat with authority. &QL; 
Oly's safety net &QL; 
Veteran right-hander Gregg Olson resurrected his career as a closer
with 30 saves in 1998. He will assume that role again this season,
but what if he struggles or is injured for a long period of time?
Who could step in?
</P>
<P>
   Right-handers Ben Ford and Vladimir Nunez are seen as
possibilities for the future, but they are not ready. So, short of
diving into the trade waters, the most likely candidates, believe
it or not, would be two starters from last season, left-hander
Brian Anderson and right-hander Amaury Telemaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian is a control pitcher and `Tele' would fit because he has
a pretty good fastball,'' pitching coach Mark Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the National League in fewest walks per nine
innings last season (one). &QL; 
Cutting the K-rations &QL; 
Arizona batters led the majors with 1,239 strikeouts. Showalter
would like to avoid a repeat performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more mental than anything,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Jim Presley said the addition of veterans such as
outfielders Luis Gonzalez and Steve Finley should help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of young guys last season, and that's what young
guys do when they're trying to make something happen,'' Presley
said. ``They can be overaggressive. But the older guys need to work
on it, too. We've addressed that this spring and will continue to.
We have to have a better approach with two strikes and generally be
more selective.'' &QL; 
No shortage of bodies &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The battle for starting shortstop between Tony Batista and Danny
Klassen is expected to go down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   The move of Jay Bell from short to second base is expected to be
permanent, but he could move back if necessary. Womack began his
career as a shortstop and could figure into the mix. Andy Fox has
been getting more work there, and veteran Dale Sveum, a non-roster
invitee, can handle the job. &QL; 
Pitchers' progress &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From left-hander Randy Johnson through the other members of the
rotation, the key will be keeping them healthy and building arm
strength, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, starters will be limited to between 35 and 40
pitches. The number will increase. &QL; 
Another Andy &QL; 
Fox proved to be one of the club's most valuable players last
season. In 1999, Greg Colbrunn will play a similar role. He will
back up Travis Lee at first base, Matt Williams at third base,
could see a few innings in the outfield and will don the catching
gear in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn showed up early to get work with the pitchers and
catchers, but he was glad for the chance to get work at the other
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting a bit weary,'' Showalter said. ``He finally
threw down his gear and told the other catchers, `See you next
spring, boys.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a blue-collar guy. I sat across from him in the
other dugout (against Colorado and Atlanta last season) and you
don't want to have him with a bat in his hand in a situation that
can hurt you (as a right-handed pinch-hitter). He can really help
us.'' &QL; 
Lee locks in &QL; 
After finishing third in Rookie of the Year voting, how much can
Lee improve?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has more of an `I belong,' `I can do this' air about him. I
think he's more comfortable all the way around,'' Showalter said.
``After getting squeezed a bit last year, he should benefit from a
better strike zone. Incavigila told him that umpires stuck his bat
so far in his ear during his rookie season that he still hasn't
found it, but the second year was much, much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Presley: ``He's more mature, more relaxed . . . he knows
what it takes. Everything he does is natural.'' &QL; 
More deals ahead? &QL; 
The club has made significant upgrades over the winter, but might
not be done yet. Anderson continues to be an attractive target to
other clubs, but Arizona is leaning toward keeping him. The club
would like to add another right-handed hitter and improve the
bullpen, although nothing is likely to happen until later in the
spring, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more depth than last season and a lot more options,''
Showalter said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
