</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SCORING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T LOOK NOW _ IT'S PRETTY BAD  
 NBA SCORING, SHOOTING FALL TO HISTORIC DEPTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA's marketing hook for this post-lockout, abbreviated
season may just be wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love this game,'' the slogan goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to love?'' might be more fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, don't say you weren't warned.
</P>
<P>
   With only two weeks of training camp, often with incomplete
teams, and two preseason games instead of the usual eight, sloppy,
ugly basketball was predictable this season for the NBA's 29 clubs.
And with a compacted schedule, teams have few days to practice or
work on conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, shooting is off, scoring is down and turnovers
are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some well-played basketball games, but some of them
have seemed sloppy,'' said forward Tom Gugliotta of the Suns, who
play host to the Golden State Warriors tonight at America West
Arena. ``Players are loose with the ball, especially at the
beginning of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is timing, getting used to new players. But in the
last five or six minutes of close games, most teams seem to be
playing at a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   But they're not scoring at the high levels that pushed the NBA
to new levels of popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday night's games, none of the NBA's 29 teams was
averaging even 100 points a game. The Sacramento Kings led the
league at 99.6. Not since 1953-54 has the NBA failed to have at
least one team average 100 points a game, and that was the last
season before a guy named Danny Biasone, owner of the Syracuse
Nationals, came up with the idea of a 24-second shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen teams were averaging 90 points or fewer per game,
including the Chicago Bulls, who were at 79.
</P>
<P>
   The league average for scoring was 91 points a game, almost five
points a game fewer than last season. And the 29 teams were
shooting 43 percent, the worst leaguewide shooting since the
1961-62 season. In one game, the Chicago Bulls shot 26.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But is it just the lockout? Or has the labor dispute simply
magnified a downward trend in scoring that has been apparent in the
NBA for the past decade?
</P>
<P>
   Consider that most people assumed teams such as the Utah Jazz
and Indiana Pacers, who made few changes in their core of players
and had rosters loaded with veterans, would not be adversely
affected by the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   And both are among the teams with the best records. But the Jazz
scored only 56 points in a game in Seattle, the second-lowest
output since the shot clock was instituted. The Pacers set the
record last season when they scored 55 against San Antonio in
March. That performance can't be blamed on a lockout or
early-season rust.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most efficient offensive clubs in the NBA during the
past decade, the Jazz made only 21 field goals against Seattle, two
more than the all-time NBA low. Indiana is shooting only 44.5
percent for the season. The Pacers have won four games this season
without scoring even 90 points.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the ragged play, fans still are watching on
television and passing through the turnstiles. The Suns had their
home sellout streak snapped, but they still have had a full house
for four of six home dates.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 130 games played around the league, attendance
was actually up slightly from the first 130 games a year ago,
averaging 16,571 compared with 16,556 last season, a league
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   And, the NBA's ratings on NBC and Turner Sports are slightly
higher than last season _ up 2 percent on NBC, 18 percent on TNT
and 19 percent on TBS, said Seth Sylvan, director of the NBA's
sports media services.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley, over-the-air broadcasts of Suns games on Channel
45 have averaged a 10 rating, equal to the average rating last
season, according to figures provided by the club.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lockout, many teams have simplified their
offenses, and they still aren't executing well. Shooters are rusty.
Three-point shooting also is down, and even free throw shooting has
dropped from almost 74 percent last season to 72 percent this year.
Turnovers are up from an average of about 15.5 last season to 16
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely been a little hit in the quality of play,''
said Todd Quinter, Suns scout who evaluates teams the club is going
to play and provides breakdowns of their offenses, defenses and
personnel for the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's almost like every other year,'' he said.
``Offenses are always simplified early in the year, and as they go
along, coaches are adding things, players are getting in better
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just looking at the statistics, scoring and shooting are way
down, and I think that can be attributed to guys just not being in
shape yet. It's also attributed to so many players changing
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, spacing of players on the floor and their timing
with other players as a play unfolds often are just as important as
the play itself. Quinter said he sees many teams struggling with
those aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups of players on a team may click together well, but
other groups that aren't accustomed to playing together struggle.
Thus, there can be moments of great play and sloppiness in the same
game.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody is blaming the lower scores entirely on the
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the evolution of the game of professional basketball,
where intense, energetic effort on defense is the name of the
game,'' Miami Coach Pat Riley told the ``Fort Lauderdale
Sun-Sentinel.'' ``It's never been like that before. Teams simply
realize the only way to win games is to be consistent in your
effort defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why scores are being held down. That's why field goal
percentages are down. The lockout might have contributed to it a
little bit, but not a whole lot. As much as the people in the
league office don't like what they're seeing, this is what they're
going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   And teams are better prepared than ever to play that type of
defense. Scouting is more sophisticated than ever. Scouts such as
Quinter break down every tendency of teams and players. Video
scouts such as the Suns' Garrick Barr break down opponents
play-by-play. As a result, every team knows virtually every play
the opponent is calling and how to defend it.
</P>
<P>
   With offenses simplified, it would seem to make that task even
easier this season. But Suns Coach Danny Ainge said it never has
been that complicated, and that when conditioning and familiarity
improve, so will the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is that as long as I've been in basketball, I
think it's been simple,'' Ainge said. ``In Boston, we had to defend
the post-up, the pick and roll and the fast break. Defending those
and isolation plays are still what it boils down to at any level of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing, I always knew what the other team was
running. It's trying to stop it that's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as difficult as it used to be, though. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
