<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRANKLIN-SAMPRAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS FINALLY BACK IN SCOTTS DALE  
 WORLD'S NO. 1 PREPS FOR OTHER U.S. EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - Things certainly have changed for Pete
Sampras since he last played a professional tennis match in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1988, and Sampras was 17 and ranked 157th in the world.
After upsetting Jim Courier in the second round, Sampras was
eliminated by Kevin Curren.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras returns to Scottsdale this week for the Franklin
Templeton Tennis Classic at the Canadian Pacific Scottsdale
Princess Resort in the prime of his career _ the big dog of pro
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the No. 1 player on the ATP Tour for a record six
straight years. He's one Grand Slam title away from tying Roy
Emerson's record of 12. Naturally, he's the top seed in this
tournament, followed by Patrick Rafter and Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras might not have played here this year except he wanted to
tune up for upcoming Mercedes Super 9 tournaments at Indian Wells,
Calif., and Key Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've struggled a little bit at Palm Springs over the past
couple of years,'' he said in a conference call last week, adding,
``I've heard a lot of good things about the tournament in
Scottsdale. My brother is actually involved in it, so I have the
family guilt on me to play.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes conditions here will prep him for Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there is a little altitude there (Scottsdale),''
Sampras said. ``I've always struggled a little bit in those
conditions. When you have a field like that, it's really a true
test to see where I'm at.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras caused a stir in the tennis world in January when he
passed up the Australian Open, the first Grand Slam event of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Before the San Jose ATP tournament in early February, where
Sampras had to withdraw after injuring his leg, he said that he
needed to rest after a grueling season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give myself a good off-season this year,'' he said
at that time during a conference call, ``and obviously we have some
tournaments that are coming up _ San Jose, Scottsdale. Then you
have Indian Wells, Lipton (in Florida), which are big tournaments,
and those are events that I'll have to play. But I would have loved
to have gone down to Australia. I just wished it started in
February.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sampras rested and played golf, namely at the
celebrity-filled Bob Hope Chrysler Classic. And even though he
didn't play in Australia, he retained the No. 1 ranking when No. 2
Yevgeny Kafelnikov lost a quarterfinal match Friday in the Guardian
Direct indoor tournament in London.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is only 11 weeks away from Ivan Lendl's career record of
270 weeks at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said last week, the leg is completely healed.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was asked if he still intimidates other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question you have to ask the other players, if they
enjoy playing me,'' Sampras said. ``If anything, I think players
know this year that I'm ready, that I'm fresh and mentally ready to
go. Parts of last year I felt a little worn out and not really
enjoying what I was doing. It showed in some bad results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this year I think guys know that I'm eager. When I'm
eager and fresh, I'm tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like I'm going to get better. I feel like this
year is going to be a great year for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said that even if he would have fallen from No. 1 after
the Australian Open, it would have been no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what you're ranked in February,'' Sampras
said. ``It matters what you're ranked in December.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
