r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMA     02-28 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2-REFEREE SYS TEM WORKS LIKE CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Coyotes captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk had a message he
wanted to deliver to NHL Commissioner  &UR; Gary Bettman the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see him,'' Tkachuk said, ``tell him we not only want
the two-referee system in the playoffs, we want it from ``now''
until the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Bettman said he understands the sentiment but the simple
truth is there aren't enough qualified referees to make it work for
the full slate of remaining regular-season games. The end of
February officially triggers the end of the two-referee system
phase-in period, as promised.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said it wouldn't be fair to continue the practice in
only selected games down the stretch. And he's right. It could be
construed as some teams having a competitive edge. Besides, the NHL
couldn't be sure the system would be embraced as well as it has, so
it was agreed that each team would get an equal 20 games to test
it.
</P>
<P>
   It's been such an overwhelming success, Bettman suggested it's
virtually a lock that two refs will work each playoff game this
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general managers overwhelmingly endorsed it, which means
it's on track from their standpoint,'' Bettman said. ``But I told
the owners I would take their pulse after the last game in
February, and I intend to do that. I would be surprised (if they
rejected it), but don't want to second-guess or position the
owners, so I want to hear what they have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect the two-ref system to be given the green light within two
weeks. And within the next couple years, expect it to be a daily
part of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Other items of interest Bettman addressed:
</P>
<P>
   The future of overtime games. The American Hockey League, at the
NHL's beckoning, has been experimenting with skaters going
four-on-four during the entire extra period. In the first 27 games
the system was used, only four went to overtime but three of them
were decided in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   There is some talk the NHL might adopt an AHL-like policy of
awarding one point to each team when a score is tied at the end of
regulation regardless of a loss or tie. Two points would be awarded
for an overtime win.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no trap and no left wing lock when you're playing
four-on-four and if you're playing in the context where you've
already got your point . . . we're going to look at that,'' Bettman
said. ``Whether or not it's for next year, it's too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential labor strife. The collective bargaining agreement
doesn't expire until 2004, but both sides have agreed the next
round of talks very well could lead to a major work stoppage. The
Players Association already has compiled a war chest in the event
of a strike or a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the speculation and it's unfortunate because we are in
a period of prolonged labor peace and nobody knows what the world
will look like by then,'' Bettman said. ``The first two years of
the CBA, revenues were growing faster than salaries. The last two
years, salaries are growing faster than revenues. There's an ebb
and a flow. If we keep ebbing, 2004 may be difficult from our
standpoint. If we flow, it may be difficult for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll deal with that in three or four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic participation. A decision probably will have to be made
within the next two months, possibly longer if the World
International Hockey Federation agrees it can wait. The NHL wants
guaranteed prime-time exposure on NBC, something the network can't
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going, it's got to make sense,'' Bettman said.
``There's a possibility it will make sense, but we're not done
yet.'' &QL; 
Gretzky's condition
</P>
<P>
   It took a New York minute for the conspiracy theorists in the
Big Apple to put two and two together and speculate that  &UR; Wayne
Gretzky's neck injury is a definite prelude to his retiring after
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it, although Gretzky still could surprise nearly
everyone and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Gretzky said, when the inevitable question came
up that the injury could lead to retirement, especially given his
age. ``I'm a young 38. If we would have known in January what the
problem was, I probably only would have missed two or three weeks
to rectify the problem and we wouldn't even be talking about it
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who had appeared in 223 consecutive games and was
leading the Rangers in scoring with 57 points in 58 games, is
suffering from a disc protrusion between vertebrae in his neck. The
protrusion, revealed in a magnetic resonance imaging test taken
Thursday, is causing stiffness and numbness in his neck and the
right side of his shoulder, back and arm.
</P>
<P>
   It will not require surgery, but Gretzky will be sidelined at
least two weeks and possibly longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to rest and then get ready to play hockey again,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton Oilers General Manager  &UR; Glen Sather wasn't so sure
after Gretzky presented his former boss with an autographed stick a
few days earlier, thanking Sather for his support during their days
together in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking later, `Is this Wayne's way of saying he's
quitting?' '' Sather said. &QL; 
Chicago fallout
</P>
<P>
   After canning first-year Coach  &UR; Dirk Graham last Monday,
Blackhawks GM
 &UR; Bob Murray said the former Chicago captain's kick-in-the-pants
style wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he took a lot of  &UR; Mike Keenan's qualities and thought
he could separate one from the other,'' Murray said, referring to
the ex-Chicago coach currently out of work after getting dumped in
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant  &UR; Lorne Molleken has replaced Graham behind the bench,
but it is widely rumored that fellow assistant  &UR; Denis Savard will
eventually take over next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll respond to a fresh direction and a fresh
attitude. I hope those guys play for Lorne, I really do,'' Graham
said. &QL; 
Seeing is believing
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Stars defenseman  &UR; Richard Matvichuk had his eyes examined
the other day after teammates  &UR; Derian Hatcher and  &UR; Shawn Chambers
noticed he was squinting. Turns out Matvichuk needed glasses. He's
in the process of getting fitted with contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can
be reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
