<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS' INERTIA MAY BE CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way the Cardinals are doing business, they must have
forgotten that they have a stadium vote in May.
</P>
<P>
   It's naive to think whether they re-sign outside linebacker
 &UR; Jamir
 &UR; Miller, offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown and free safety  &UR; Kwamie
Lassiter will determine the outcome of the May 18 election on the
Rio Solado Crossing, but it could sway some voters.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this was supposed to the warm and fuzzy off-season,
the one in which Cardinals players who experienced the team's first
playoff victory in 51 years lined up to re-enlist and free agents
from other teams dashed to the Valley to play for an up-and-coming
team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cardinals are in danger of having the off-season
become a disaster, and of having the organization take huge public
relations hits.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who thanked the Cardinals for not placing the dreaded
franchise tag on him and allowing him to test free agency, is
frustrated that the team hasn't made him a contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   It's really very simple. The Cardinals aren't going to make him
an offer until they know what it will cost to sign him.
Translation: They want him back as cheaply as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way proactive teams such as the Denver Broncos,
who have won back-to-back Super Bowl titles, do business. They
entered free agency with all but one of their starters under
contract and then targeted one free agent, Kansas City cornerback
 &UR; Dale Carter, and went out and signed him.
</P>
<P>
   Doing business Cardinals Vice President  &UR; Bill Bidwill Jr.'s way
is risky. Miller could go out and get a deal elsewhere and then not
give the Cardinals a chance to match it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the Cardinals wouldn't have been in this fix with
Miller had they torn up the final year of his contract, as he
wanted last spring, and extended the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Brown, who appears to be leaning toward joining the
Browns, is more curious.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Cardinals seemed to have him all but wrapped up;
he even said so. Then the money-rich Browns, tired of haggling with
free agent offensive tackle  &UR; Blake Brockermeyer of Carolina,
started getting serious about going after Brown, even though it is
odd for an expansion team to want a player who will be 36 next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Cardinals saw that the Browns, who have been snatching
up free agents throughout the league, were becoming serious about
Brown, why didn't they get the deal done before he visited
Cleveland? Aggressive organizations would have done that.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter, who has felt underpaid his entire career, received a
three-year offer from the Cardinals at the start of free agency. He
didn't think the money was enough, so he started looking around and
visited San Diego last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals think their offer is fair. He thinks he can get
more, which often is the case.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Cardinals get some of these players signed soon, the
momentum they gained from last year's winning season will be lost.
It's already in peril.
</P>
<P>
   The public also is getting annoyed. Signing a couple of their
big three remaining free agents would pacify fans.
</P>
<P>
   If they get much angrier, Cardinals Vice President  &UR; Michael
Bidwill, who has spearheaded the stadium drive, will have to
explain how big brother Bill Jr., who is in charge of the purse
strings, let things go awry.
</P>
<P>
   Their dad, team owner  &UR; Bill Bidwill, then could pay the ultimate
price at the ballot box. &QL; 
Reliving history &QL; 
Ten years ago, an event that some Dallas Cowboys fans consider the
darkest in franchise history occurred when owner  &UR; Jerry Jones fired
Coach  &UR; Tom Landry in what became known as the ``Saturday Night
Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   What infuriated fans was a ``Dallas Morning News'' photo of
Jones dining with Landry's replacement,  &UR; Jimmy Johnson, at Landry's
favorite Mexican restaurant while the only coach in team history
didn't know he was about to be dumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, it looked bad,'' Johnson said of the photo on the
front page. ``We were staying at a hotel, and Jerry came by the
room and said he wanted to take me to a little out-of-the-way
place. I told him I didn't think it was a good idea. It was Friday
night. Every place would be packed. But he was positive no one
would recognize me.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys owner  &UR; Bum Bright wanted to be the one who
informed Landry he was out, but Jones insisted that he tell Landry
face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Landry was at his home in Austin playing golf. So Jones went to
Austin, interrupted Landry's golf game and told him the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't going to be easy,'' Johnson said. ``I felt bad.
Coach Landry was an idol of mine growing up in Texas. . . . But
Jerry stood right up to it. He would not let Bum do the firing. He
would not let
 &UR; Tex ( &UR; Schramm, then general manager) inform Tom with a phone call.
He would not phone Tom himself. Jerry said the deal couldn't get
done until he told Tom face to face. And Tom had gone to Austin to
play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry then put everything on hold, got on a plane, flew to
Austin and found Tom on the golf course. Contrary to popular
opinion, Jerry was not a close friend of mine, and I hadn't been
around him much. But after seeing that, I walked out that afternoon
really impressed. . . . On this part, I strongly defend Jerry.'' &QL; 
Family feud? &QL; 
 &UR; Denise DeBartolo York made sure last week that everyone in the San
Francisco 49ers organization knew she was in charge, not her
brother,
 &UR; Eddie DeBartolo, who remains in limbo since voluntarily stepping
down in December 1997 because of his involvement in a federal
gambling probe in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   She sent out a memo to team employees that said her brother can
have little to do with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie and his representatives have been directed to
communicate in writing exclusively through (team official)  &UR; John
McVay, with copies to me when he requests information from the
team,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's requests for reimbursement of expenses, further
advancement of team funds or use of team assets must be directed to
me for approval before payment or use.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media resources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
