</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DRAKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' FEARLESS WING PUTS SOUL ON ICE  
 DRAKE'S CHECKS MAKE FOES BOUNCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Every year at Christmastime, Coyotes captain Keith
Tkachuk dreams up another crazy gift idea for his closest friend on
the team and roommate on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk never divulges what he buys, but he's been known to drop
some serious cash when it comes to good buddy Dallas Drake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll get Dally a new dental plan next year,'' one
Coyotes player joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' said another. ``What Dallas Drake needs is a good
accidental death and dismemberment policy.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a hockey player in the NHL who tries to jeopardize
his career every single night on the ice, it's Dallas Drake, the
Coyotes' wiry and wacky 6-foot-1, 185-pound right wing from Trail,
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   His full-length picture should be in every doctor's office in
North America for preventive medicine or future case studies. Just
draw a line and point it to each of the body parts he has mangled
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, just take this season alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let's see. I had a concussion, but I only missed two
games,'' Drake said. ``Then I had the leg problem, a fracture I
didn't know was even there. But I only missed one game because of
that. Then I tore up my elbow, but that only cost me one game, too.
And then this shoulder separation thing came along. But that's
pretty much par for the course for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Drake forgot a few other maladies along the way. There
were the split tongue and damaged teeth from a puck in the face.
There was the broken toe. A butt end of the stick caught him in the
eye. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but it's not just me,'' said Drake, who has eight goals,
21 points and is a plus-13. ``Everybody gets that stuff. Those are
just the bumps and bruises that everybody in our locker room has to
go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake, who is becoming widely regarded, pound-for-pound, as one
of the toughest and hardest-hitting players in the game, returned
to the Coyotes' lineup Friday after missing 13 games with the bum
shoulder. He will be back on the ice again at 10 a.m. today, when
Phoenix will meet the New Jersey Devils in an effort to avoid
losing for the seventh time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad he's back,'' Tkachuk said. ``I really think we've
missed a lot without him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it doesn't take long for Drake to bounce back. He's
like Gumby. You can pull him and stretch him and tie him into a
pretzel, but he snaps back into form.
</P>
<P>
   His body makeup isn't any different from anyone else's, Coyotes
head trainer Gord Hart said, but ``his desire level is extremely
high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him for quite a few years now,'' Hart said, ``and I
have so much respect for his ability to play like that day in and
day out. Every time he steps on the ice, he doesn't hold back
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the point, KGME-AM (1360) radio held a contest last
week in which listeners were asked to vote for various Arizona
athletes and sports personalities in different categories. Drake
was the only double winner in the annual ``First'ies Awards,''
winning both the Most Underrated and Most Underappreciated titles.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent trip to Buffalo, Drake was called ``the
prototype hockey player'' by Sabres Coach Lindy Ruff. When asked
which Phoenix player he felt his team had to try to take out of the
equation for that night's game, Ruff didn't mention Tkachuk, Jeremy
Roenick or Rick Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drake's the guy you've got to really be careful with,'' he
said. ``He can do a lot of different things. He'll go in the
corners and battle for the puck. He'll go to the front of the net.
He'll bang along the boards. And he'll throw some pretty mean
checks. And it doesn't matter how big you are, either. If he sees
you, he'll drill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Philadelphia Flyers giant Eric Lindros, who dwarfs Drake in
stature and build like Paul Bunyan would Pee Wee Herman. Drake has
given Lindros more than a few bone-rattling jars over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I definitely know who he is,'' Lindros said during an
interview before the All-Star Game earlier this month in Tampa. ``I
remember one game, I think, where he knocked me down at least three
times. He's a pretty good hockey player. Tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Los Angeles Coach Larry Robinson has something nice to say
about Drake, who nearly took off Doug Bodger's head during a
monster check into the boards on the Kings' defenseman back in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's got great grit,'' Robinson said. ``He's not a big
man, but he comes to play every night, and that's all you want from
a hockey player. You can ask a lot of a hockey player every night.
Having great hands or being a great scorer, those are things that
usually are God-given. But the one thing that I feel all players
are capable of giving is an honest effort every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. I still think that hit by Drake (on
Bodger) was a dirty hit. But he brings it every night. He gives you
that effort every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake is unique, a walking contradiction of sorts. But he said
he is no different from any other hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give credit to all hockey players,'' he said. ``I have never
met a guy who doesn't want to play or won't play through injuries.
Everybody I've played with or played against, if they can get on
the ice and contribute, they will. It doesn't matter how you feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are just blue-collar guys, guys who grew up in
small cities and never probably felt they'd play in the NHL. They
don't want to screw it up, so they'll do whatever it takes to play,
whether they have to play through a broken leg or a broken foot or
whatever.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
