<SLUG> BC-BKC-NAU-WEBER-ST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAU LOSES HOME EDGE FOR BIG SKY TOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JARED PAGE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OGDEN, Utah _ Northern Arizona's bid for a third consecutive Big
Sky Conference regular-season title hit a roadblock Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   NAU, one of the top shooting teams in Division I, hit just 37.5
percent of its shots in the second half and dropped a 77-57
decision to Weber State in front of 9,148 fans at the Dee Events
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Weber State (22-7, 13-3 Big Sky) wins the Big Sky's
regular-season title and the right to host the conference's
six-team postseason tournament, which begins Thursday. NAU (20-7,
12-4) will enter the event as the No. 2 seed and play the highest
remaining seed from the quarterfinal round at 7 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing,'' NAU Coach Ben Howland said. ``It's
a tough loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks, who led by three points at halftime (31-28),
struggled with the Wildcats' pressure defense and were outscored,
49-26, in the final 20 minutes of play. Thirteen of NAU's 21
turnovers were committed in the second half. Weber State also
outrebounded NAU, 30-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win when you have 21 turnovers and you got
outrebounded by seven,'' Howland said. ``That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Land led the Lumberjacks with 16 points on 6-of-10
shooting, and Michael McNair added 11 before fouling out with 6:45
to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona, the Big Sky's regular-season champion the past
two seasons, shot 63.6 percent (14 of 22) and led by as many as
seven points in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were picking us apart,'' Weber State Coach Ron Abegglen
said.
</P>
<P>
   WSU forward Harold Arceneaux hit a three-pointer to give the
Wildcats a 42-40 lead and they gradually extended that advantage to
20 before the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Arceneaux, a favorite to win the Big Sky's Player of the Year
award, led Weber State with 18 points, nine rebounds and two
blocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
