</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-STANFORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD SUCCEEDS UA AS CHAMPION OF PAC-10 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ You walk into Stanford's Maples Pavilion, in
the middle of one of America's really smart people's universities,
and you just feel your IQ surge 15 points or so.
</P>
<P>
   Which could only help Arizona, given its performance Thursday at
California.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wildcats on Saturday needed more help than that. They
picked up where they left off, suffering defensive lapses, making
numerous fouls against a team with the Pac-10's two top free throw
shooters, shooting poorly and quickly falling behind sixth-ranked
Stanford by 20 points en route to a 98-83 blowout loss. Stanford
guard Arthur Lee scored a career-high 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   With it, defending champion Arizona surrendered the Pac-10
title. The Wildcats had not lost two in a row since dropping the
final two of the regular season in 1997, also on this trip, before
recovering to win the NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus for the past several games has been just playing
each game and trying to get better,'' UA Coach Lute Olson said.
``If you lose, you lose. What is important is do you get better as
a result of that? We're just trying to be better each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside, there has been a lot of talk of our possibly winning
or tying for the conference championship. That's been more a case
of other people's attention rather than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing the crown was one of the few plays the seventh-ranked
Wildcats (20-6, 11-5) completed all evening. After both of its
power forwards, Michael Wright and Eugene Edgerson, had two fouls
each and had sat down by midway through the first half, the
sixth-ranked Cardinal (24-5, 14-2), which won its first conference
title since 1963, had little trouble controlling play inside.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford also had little trouble controlling Arizona point guard
Jason Terry, who on this trip suddenly looked mortal. Coming into
this trip as the Pac-10 Player of the Week, Terry didn't look
himelf in either game. Olson gives Terry time off in practice
because Terry plays nearly every minute of every game. But the
question lingers whether Terry is beginning to feel the fatigue of
a season of long minutes, in which he has been asked repeatedly to
put a young team on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had suffered a collective brain malfunction at Cal,
sleepwalking through an 89-76 pounding _ its largest setback of the
season before this _ after allowing the Bears to shoot 51.6
percent, only the second game in which a UA foe has shot better
than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In this one, the Wildcats were thwarted by the league's
stingiest defense. Stanford has climbed to the top of the Pac-10 by
limiting foes to 37.8 percent shooting and 59.4 points per game.
Although the Wildcats were above those numbers, Stanford made its
point.
</P>
<P>
   With UA unable to score, the Cardinal was scoring in threes with
long-range shooting and pulled away in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona players were visibly frustrated, but they weren't
the only ones who blew their cool. With 7:22 to go in the opening
half, Olson was assessed a technical foul by official Mark Ayotte
after grumbling about the lack of calls inside. Olson then began to
charge onto the court before he was restrained by associate coach
Jim Rosborough, or Olson likely would have been given another and
ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Olson came into the game anticipating that Stanford would be
allowed to hammer away after watching the tape of its overtime win
Thursday over Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that staying out of foul trouble was huge for us,''
Olson said before the game. ``I watched the Stanford-ASU tape. How
many free throws did Stanford shoot, 39 to 10, was it? I have a
hard time figuring that out. I thought ASU was the aggressor taking
the ball to the basket. ASU was much more physical and aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you've got to figure out is how in the world do you
keep them off the line?''
</P>
<P>
   Those proved to be prophetic words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
