</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-CAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS RESEMBLES OTHERS FOR ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Had anyone been beamed down from somewhere or awakened
from a long nap, having missed the entire Arizona State basketball
season to date, Saturday's game against California would have been
enough to get caught up.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils led early. They led late. They did a lot of
things well. They lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of how it's been all season,'' guard Eddie House
said after the Golden Bears beat ASU, 78-73, at the New Arena. ``It
comes down to a few plays, a few fouls, a few things going the
other team's way, and us coming up on the short end of the stick.''
</P>
<P>
   House played 39 minutes and scored 26 points. For only the fifth
time, the Sun Devils made at least half their shots. They
outrebound Cal by one. And the defense?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to work awfully hard against their defense,'' Cal
Coach Ben Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? How did ASU (14-14, 7-10 Pac-10) lose for the
fifth time in six games, putting even their NIT hopes in jeopardy
while keeping Cal's NCAA Tournament dreams alive?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint: The Sun Devils had 27 turnovers, the most in more
than two years. Senior forward Mike Batiste had nine all by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   House scored only two points in the final 10 minutes, a harmless
basket with 1.2 seconds left. Senior forward Bobby Lazor, who forms
with House and Batiste the highest-scoring threesome in the Pac-10,
was held to 10 points. Cal defender Sean Lampley had something to
do with that.
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas Kilgore, a senior guard for this maddeningly
inconsistent Cal team (16-10, 7-9) that belongs on the same
psychiatrist's couch as the Sun Devils, scored 12 straight points
for his team while the Bears were erasing an eight-point ASU lead
with 5:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the usual dose of weird stuff that has
characterized the ASU program for the better part of a decade.
</P>
<P>
   With 25.8 seconds left, Alton Mason drove to the basket, scored
and got fouled to bring the Sun Devils to within 70-68. Then he
missed the free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Boyd, a muscular, 6-foot-5 junior forward, rebounded for
the Bears and was fouled by Jason Patton. After the call, Boyd
swung an elbow, clipping Batiste in the chest. Angered, Batiste
took a half-hearted swipe. Boyd did the same, and both squared off
in a boxing pose straight from the Marquis of Queensbury rules.
</P>
<P>
   As teammates grabbed Boyd and Batiste, official Jerry White
called a double flagrant technical foul and ejected both players.
That was a good trade for Cal. Boyd is a reserve and Batiste starts
and is ASU's No. 3 scorer.
</P>
<P>
   With Boyd gone, Braun summoned Ryan Forehan-Kelly from the bench
to shoot the free throws. Braun's first choice was Dennis Gates,
but he had a jammed finger. Forehan-Kelly is a walk-on freshman who
had played 18 minutes all season, had scored the grand total of
nine points and is not mentioned in the media guide.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he made both foul shots. Cal led by four.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for the Sun Devils, according to a new rule approved
by coaches, Cal got to keep the basketball because it last had
possession. Under the old rule, ASU would have gotten the ball.
With 21.4 seconds left, Geno Carlisle made two more free throws,
and the Bears led by six to sew it up.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the play warranted the ejection of both players,
ASU Coach Rob Evans said, ``I don't think so.'' He also said he
never heard of the rule change, and when told that a Pac-10
observer said the coaches approved the rule, said, ``All Pac-10
officials and all observers, you know, they all cover each other.
They're all going to say it's the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not familiar with that rule. I didn't vote for it, and I'm
at every meeting that goes on. I didn't vote on it at all.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
