<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS NOT HURTING ANY BODY; IN FACT, HE'S HELPING PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Three words for those who think  &UR; Garth Brooks'
presence at San Diego's spring training is bad for the game: Get
over it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Steve Howe and  &UR; Rupert Murdoch have done more damage to
baseball's credibility than Brooks ever will. He's not taking a
roster spot. He's raising money for charity, and he's living proof
that a well-paid celebrity ($54 million in 1998) still can connect
with fans. Brooks typically spends two hours after workouts signing
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awfully polite,'' Manager  &UR; Bruce Bochy said.
</P>
<P>
   At-bat we hope to see: National League Rookie of the Year,
Chicago Cubs pitcher  &UR; Kerry Wood, vs. American League Rookie of the
Year, Oakland Athletics outfielder  &UR; Ben Grieve. The teams meet on
March 15 in Mesa and March 28 and April 1 in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Best bullpen in the Cactus League? Here's a vote for the San
Francisco Giants, who had the No. 1 bullpen ERA in the NL last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason is the overpowering  &UR; Robb Nen, who had a 1.52
ERA, 110 strikeouts and 25 walks. Even with  &UR; Jose Mesa gone, San
Francisco returns  &UR; John Johnstone (3.07),  &UR; Julian Tavarez (5-3,
3.80) and  &UR; Rich
 &UR; Rodriguez (4-0, 3.70) and adds  &UR; Alan Embree.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe spending $105 million for one player is a little
over the top, but the Los Angeles Dodgers' decision to give green
to Brown only magnifies what the Cubs didn't do in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   What was lost in the aftermath of their first playoff appearance
since 1989 was that they still finished 12{ games back in the NL
Central. Their biggest off-season move was the $2 million signing
of free agent catcher  &UR; Benito Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice for the game if a team didn't have to buy its
victories, but it probably also would be unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Position battle of the week:  &UR; Troy Glaus vs.  &UR; Dave
 &UR; Hollins for the third base job in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, 22, a highly regarded rookie, was impressive defensively
when he replaced Hollins in late July, but his struggles at the
plate led many to believe he was called up too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins, 32, who underwent shoulder surgery last summer, wants
the job, but Glaus is expected to put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Giants first baseman  &UR; J.T. Snow has said goodbye to his
switch-hitting career and will commit to being a left-handed
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. In 1998, he batted .265 against right-handed
pitchers, .164 vs. lefties. From 1995-97, it was .298 vs. .219. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Granted, $80 million will do that to you, but you have to like
 &UR; Mo Vaughn's attitude with his new team, the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn showed up a week ahead of other position players to get
acquainted and was overheard telling his teammates, ``The hard work
starts now.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman has set the end of spring training
as a deadline for signing a contract extension. San Diego would be
nuts not to accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who converted 53 of 54 save opportunities last season,
is believed to be seeking a four-year, $30 million extension with a
no-trade clause. The Padres' last offer was for four years and $24
million.
</P>
<P>
   Milestone worth watching in 1999: San Diego outfielder
 &UR; Tony Gwynn is expected to reach 3,000 hits, probably in June.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay third baseman  &UR; Wade Boggs and Baltimore third baseman
 &UR; Cal
 &UR; Ripken also are expected to get there this season.
</P>
<P>
   From the here we go again department, Milwaukee appears to be
heading into another season without a true No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   New pitching coach  &UR; Bill Campbell has his work cut out for him.
Last season, the Brewers set a major league record for fewest
complete games in a season _ two _ and recorded only two shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   No Milwaukee pitcher has won more than 13 games since  &UR; Cal
Eldred posted 16 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Cactus League players to report lighter was Milwaukee
pitcher  &UR; Steve Woodward, who dropped 30 pounds from last season's
243. &QL; 
Staff writer Paola Boivin can be reached at 602-444-8956 or at
Paola.Boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
