<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAN BALLS FLYING, BUT THEY'RE VERBAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a time when so many fans believe baseball is nothing like the
old days, the last week provided a striking reminder that this game
remains basically the same as it was during its glory years in the
1940s and '50.
</P>
<P>
   From the camps of Philadelphia and St. Louis to New York and
Toronto, the war of the words heated up big-time last week,
reminding old timers of the good old days when no one was spared a
nasty word or pot shot.
</P>
<P>
   First we had Phillies outfielder  &UR; Ron Gant attacking St. Louis's
 &UR; Tony
 &UR; La  &UR; Russa, all but calling the three-time manager of the year a
racist with unethical morals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't control you, if you're not one of his yes-players,
he doesn't want you around,'' Gant said. ``That's just his
insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa fired back at Gant, saying, ``You can say I'm a stupid
manager. But unethical? Immoral? That's very strong stuff. That's
like lying, cheating and stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Toronto assistant general manager  &UR; Dave Stewart,
firing off some verbal cannon shots aimed at old nemesis  &UR; Roger
Clemens. Stewart poked Clemens where it hurts him most, attacking
his 1-2 record in eight playoff starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A true ace is the pitcher who helps you win in the
postseason,'' Stewart said. ``In my opinion, Clemens hasn't proven
that he's a postseason pitcher yet. When you talk about the two,
Roger's been in the postseason, but has not really won in the
postseason.  &UR; David Wells (who was traded from the Yankees to
Toronto for Clemens) has been in the postseason and he's won. Let's
not make Wells look like a lesser guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was this beauty delivered by Wells during his
introductory press conference after the trade: ``For starters, I
would just like to tell MSG (the Madison Square Garden Network),
the ``Daily'' ``News'' and ``Bay News 9'' to go ``expletive''
themselves for coming out to my house the night of the trade when I
asked to be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't forget the sniping going on between general managers
in San Diego and Los Angeles, where GM  &UR; Kevin Malone has already
predicted a Dodgers-Yankees World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pure and simple, this is baseball at its best, not the
namby-pamby everyone loves everyone that's come to represent the
game in the past decade or two. Somewhere,  &UR; Don Drysdale, who hated
his opponents, is smiling. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who are the career leaders in steals of home in the American and
National Leagues? &QL; 
A subtle shot at The Unit &QL; 
This dispatch comes courtesy of the ``Seattle Times,'' which noted
that &UR; Edgar Martinez is in the final year of his contract, a similar
situation that sometimes paralyzed the Mariners last spring with
 &UR; Randy
 &UR; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was asked if he is going to be miserable because of the
uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean frown? Stomp around the clubhouse feeling bad?''
Martinez said. ``No . . . no, that's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 36, is wondering how much longer he will stay in the
game. Just in case this is his final go-around, he reported to camp
in the best shape he's been in for years, determined to make it
another solid season in an already distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this will be my last year,'' said Martinez,
who three times in the past four years has been named the
outstanding designated hitter. ``If the Mariners show interest,
I'll stay. If that doesn't work out, I don't know what I'm going to
do.'' &QL; 
No sympathy here &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week we showed you how seemingly out of touch Kansas City
outfielder  &UR; Johnny Damon was after losing his arbitration hearing
and taking $2.1 million instead of the $3.2 million he sought.
</P>
<P>
   This week's version on the same topic comes from Baltimore
catcher
 &UR; Charles Johnson, a very decent person who surprisingly had this to
say after losing his hearing and taking the club's $3.6 million
offer instead of the $5.1 million he sought:
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like my agent and his staff did a great job with the
case, and I thought I had a very good chance to win,'' Johnson
said. ``It was very disappointing to me that I won a Gold Glove,
hit 19 home runs and has almost 60 RBIs and only got a $300,000
raise. But that's the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Damon share one thing: Agent  &UR; Scott Boras. &QL; 
Dreaming of Havana &QL; 
Baltimore owner  &UR; Peter Angelos' attempt to have his Orioles become
the first major league club in 52 years to play a game in Cuba
against a team of All-Stars from that island appears all but dead.
</P>
<P>
   While the Orioles are somewhat disappointed with the prospects,
they now face stiff competition to play on the communist island
nation when, and if, negotiations heat up again.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels applied to the U.S. Treasury Dept., for the
necessary license to play any kind of game in Cuba. In addition,
Cuban officials have asked about the possibility of the New York
Yankees, long considered the favorite club of most Cubans, coming
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Baltimore have the inside track? I don't know,'' major
league spokesman  &UR; Rich Levin said. ``That's impossible to answer
right now. Major League Baseball will certainly be involved and
will certainly have a say as to who goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba was home to the Havana Sugar Kings, a Triple-A affiliate of
the Cincinnati Reds, in the 1950s. &QL; 
Atlanta misfortunes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves, who once again figure to be among the elite
in the National League, are off to a terrible start in spring
training. Consider some of the calamities that have stricken the
Braves camp so far:
</P>
<P>
   The first week of workouts featured the revelation that first
baseman
 &UR; Andres Galarraga has been diagnosed with lymphoma in his back;
third baseman  &UR; Chipper Jones has seen his marriage go down in
flames; outfielders  &UR; Brian Jordan and  &UR; Gerald Williams each had to
leave camp for undisclosed family emergencies and catcher  &UR; Eddie
Perez suffered a ruptured testicle on a foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot to be excited about,'' pitcher  &UR; John
Smoltz said. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ty Cobb's 50 steals of home plate are the most in AL history,
while
 &UR; Max Carey's 33 is the NL record. The player with the most steals of
home plate whose career began after 1950 is current Anaheim hitting
coach  &UR; Rod Carew, with 17. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Just one of the guys, eh?: New Cincinnati outfielder  &UR; Greg
 &UR; Vaughn arrived at the Reds' Sarasota complex last week in a white
stretch limousine. His first words: ``I just want to be one of the
guys, be a small part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; He may not be able to hit a curveball, but his head
 &UR; is in the right place: Country singer  &UR; Garth Brooks, in San Diego's
camp on a lark, spent four hours signing autographs after a Padres
workday last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Tom Tresh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wonder whether his horse, Champion, will be featured
 &UR; also?: Anaheim players will wear a patch during the 1999 season
honoring the late  &UR; Gene Autry, Angels owner for the club's first 37
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hurry up: Today is the last day to sign up for local Nike
baseball camps that will feature Seattle's  &UR; Alex Rodriguez and
 &UR; Mark Grace of the Cubs next weekend. Application forms are
available at all Sports Authority stores in the Valley. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Baltimore Manager  &UR; Ray Miller is contemplating hitting
slugger &UR; Albert Belle third instead his customary cleanup spot.
Belle, who leads the majors in home runs, doubles, RBIs, total
bases and extra-base hits since becoming an everyday player in
1991, has taken all but 29 at-bats in the fourth spot of a lineup
in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's  &UR; Alex Fernandez, last seen in a major league game
during the 1997 playoffs, threw from the mound last week and
reported no pain in his surgically repaired rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Orel Hershiser's contract with Cleveland allows him to leave
free and clear on or after March 21 if another club is offering him
a spot on a 25-man roster. Only an injury to an Indians starter
( &UR; Charles Nagy, Jaret Wright, Bartolo Colon, Dave Burba and
 &UR; Dwight Gooden) would seem to prevent Hershiser from bolting.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs instituted a lottery system for single-game
tickets, which came under fire, but the results have brought in a
record number of sales. The Cubs sold 300,000 tickets, which far
exceeded the number sold in 1985 and 1990, seasons following their
most recent trips to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rockies equipment manager  &UR; Dan McGinn will not issue
uniform Nos. 25, 14 or 18 anytime this season.  &UR; Don Baylor and
 &UR; Bruce Ruffin, the only Rockies to have been with the club through
their first six seasons, wore 25 and 18, respectively. No. 14
belonged to  &UR; Andres Galarraga, recently diagnosed with lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals, a shell of their former selves, have a
record 68 players in camp. Even the expansion 1969 Royals had fewer
at 62. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
The Diamondbacks have been on the sending and receiving end of
recently proposed deals that seem nearly impossible to come true.
The D-Backs asked Philadelphia whether it would consider sending
talented outfielder  &UR; Bobby Abreau this way for  &UR; Brian Anderson.
Then the D-Backs got a call from Texas, asking about  &UR; Omar Daal.
It's doubtful either one will happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees plan to take a long look at  &UR; Ricky Ledee in center
field this spring. If the World Series hero looks like he can
handle the chore as  &UR; Bernie Williams' backup, look for New York to
try to deal  &UR; Chad Curtis and his $2 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati shortstop  &UR; Barry Larkin, who over the winter made
strong overtures about wanting to be traded, has reversed his
thinking and now says he is going nowhere. ``It is no longer even
an issue,'' he said. ``I'm here and I'm staying. And I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto is seeking an outfielder and may be able to work
something out with San Francisco, who has an extra one in  &UR; Stan
 &UR; Javier, who hit .290 with 21 stolen bases in 26 chances last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides strongly deny that anything is being bandied about,
but rumors persist that Atlanta is talking to the Giants about the
availability of All-Star left fielder  &UR; Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Club doctors now fear that San Diego second baseman
 &UR; Quilvio Veras, rehabilitating after shoulder surgery, may not be
ready to return before mid- to late May. That leaves open the job
for rookie
 &UR; Damian Jackson. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
