<HEADLINE>
BIG RUNS FOR AMATO, MCCLENATHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, ARIZ. - That was close.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joe Amato and  &UR; Cory McClenathan, each sleepy-eyed after nights
of tossing and turning, finally qualified for today's Checker
Schuck's Kragen Nationals at Firebird International Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Amato made it into the 16-car field with a nifty third-round
pass, then moved to the top of the list on his final run with a
4.545-second blast at a career-best speed of 325.30 mph, both track
records.
</P>
<P>
   McClenathan made it with a 4.635-second pass, good for No. 8 on
the ladder. At least McClenathan made it.
</P>
<P>
   Through three rounds, McClenathan barely could peddle it down
the quarter-mile dragstrip, jeopardizing an eight-year streak of
136 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make it, I can't even go get hammered because I
don't drink,'' a visibly nervous McClenathan said before the run.
</P>
<P>
   And now that McClenathan safely is in the field?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one (good run) underneath the belt, so watch out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out for Amato, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Friday night) was pretty sleepless,'' said Amato, one of the
sport's all-time greats. ``I knew were going to get it (right), but
the big question was if it was going to be (Saturday) or Monday in
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never gone 325 miles per hour in my life,'' a somewhat
stunned Amato said. ``I didn't see Elvis (Presley), but I did see
the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can make it through a couple of rounds today and
make the racing exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no change atop the Funny Car qualifying ladder as
 &UR; John
 &UR; Force in a Ford Mustang remained No. 1
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Cruz Pedregon in a Pontiac Firebird did jump to No. 2 with
a sterling pass of 4.888 seconds. &QL; 
Like father, like son &QL; 
For the umpteenth time,  &UR; Warren Johnson and son  &UR; Kurt Johnson have
qualified 1-2 in Pro Stock.
</P>
<P>
   For the second successive day, the elder Johnson set track
records for elapsed time (6.920 seconds) and speed (199.64 mph).
And with 104 career No. 1 qualifying positions, he also became
NHRA's all-time leader in No. 1 qualifying positions, breaking a
tie with  &UR; Bob Glidden. &QL; 
Slowpoke &QL; 
 &UR; Gary Scelzi knows what it's like to be the fastest driver in NHRA
history, having uncorked a 326.44 mph pass last November.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Scelzi also learned what it's like to be one of the
slowest in a sprint car.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi drove a World of Outlaws machine during a practice
session at Manzanita Speedway, and while not fast, he still had
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Friend)  &UR; Danny Lasoski whizzed by me once and said I was only
going about 80 mph,'' Scelzi said. ``I looked like a little girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't scare me, but I can't imagine 24 guys out there all
running together. It's dark and there's a lot of dirt. Guys passed
me and it felt like they were throwing bricks at my face shield.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
