<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-WASHINGTONSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS WASHINGTON STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last home game of the season also meant one
more halftime for USC to get chewed out in its locker room.
</P>
<P>
   No, Saturday night's Sports Arena season finale didn't start out
much differently than many others for USC, as Trojans coach Henry
Bibby took his team to task for a lackadaisical effort.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the majority of their Pacific-10 Conference home
games, the Trojans acted upon Bibby's words and routed Washington
State 83-62 before 3,094.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans played their final 20 minutes before the home crowd
with energy and intensity, holding Washington State to just 23
points. And they sealed the victory with a 20-2 scoring blitz seven
minutes into the half that included a trio of 3-pointers from
senior guard Elias Ayuso.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Bibby say at halftime, when USC held a slim 42-39
lead?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to know,'' Bibby replied. ``In the first half,
we played no defense. They scored every time they wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's message worked, because USC's defense in the second half
was as stingy as Thursday night, when the Trojans held Washington
to 57 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us we needed to pick it up,'' Ayuso said. ``He
said, `This is the last-place team in the Pac-10 and they are
starting to smell some blood.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ayuso played a major role in quelling Washington State's upset
bid, scoring 15 points in the second half and finishing with 18 in
his final home game. Ayuso also had a career-high six steals and
moved into second place on USC's all-time career 3-pointers list
with 157.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad it came this fast,'' Ayuso said. ``But it's
time for everyone to move on. You can't stay in college forever. I
wanted to do well because this is my last home game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory secured a winning record for USC (14-11, 6-10) in
the regular season, and more importantly, kept their slim hopes
alive for a bid to the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Center Brian Scalabrine, who had a game-high 20 points, said USC
needs to sweep its two games in Arizona this week for a chance at
postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, with Cal's situation, I think we have to win
two,'' Scalabrine said. ``Against Arizona (in Tucson), our backs
are against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal (16-10, 6-10) has two road games remaining against the
Oregon schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial goal was to go to the NCAA Tournament,''
Scalabrine said. ``This year, to make a step forward, we have to go
to a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, who is loath to discuss the NIT, did attach significance
to the winning season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means everything,'' he said. ``You can look back and say we
have made progress. I'm very pleased and proud of them. Everyone's
expectations have been super high. After the nonconference season,
I realized we were in for a dogfight in the Pac-10. My expectations
dropped then. We had a lot of growing pains, but we've made
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC has won two straight games for the first time since
Dec. 29-Jan. 2, when the Trojans defeated Arkansas State and
Arizona State.... Eddie Miller of Chatsworth High led Washington
State (11-17, 4-13) with 15 points and seven rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
