<HEADLINE>
INCAVIGLIA GIVES UP NUMBER TO WOMACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ New acquisition  &UR; Tony Womack is due to arrive in camp
tonight and will be on the field Monday. He will wear No. 5, which
is now being worn by non-roster outfielder  &UR; Pete Incaviglia. But
the veteran agreed to switch to No. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys said he should have given the number up for
money, but Inky doesn't care,'' Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said. ``He
just wants to play baseball.'' &QL; 
Melted Butter &QL; 
When  &UR; President Clinton visited the Diamondbacks' camp on Thursday,
things got a bit hectic. Just ask  &UR; Brian Butterfield, the
third-base coach who has the additional assignments of infield
defense and baserunning.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton was touring the fields, visiting with players,
Butterfield looked to another field and yelled, ``Pres! Pres!''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Butterfield was yelling at his boss, a Secret Service
agent approached him and said, ``Is there a problem here?''
</P>
<P>
   Gulp. Butterfield explained that he was yelling at hitting coach
 &UR; Jim Presley to get some players over to his field to begin the next
drill.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, when Butterfield went to leave Tucson
Electric Park later that night, he found himself locked inside the
complex. He called Showalter to rescue him. &QL; 
Tissue issue &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; John Patterson, one of the club's top prospects,
began to sneeze uncontrollably Friday. He sneezed 30 straight times
before team trainers took him to a hospital as a precaution. It was
allergic in nature, but nobody is sure to what. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
