<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LIDSTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN LIDSTER ANSWERS STARS' CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS, Texas _ Doug Lidster had already decided his NHL career
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Working as an assistant coach/player for the Canadian National
Team in Calgary, Alberta, the 38-year-old defenseman was ready to
take the next step in his life _ a transition into coaching.
</P>
<P>
   That was until the call came ... and not from one NHL team, but
two _ the Stars and Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally caught off guard,'' said Lidster, the Stars'
newest addition, who could make his debut in today's 2 p.m. game
against the Los Angeles Kings. ``One of my first comments was it
took me a couple of months to make the decision to retire, I didn't
know if I could make the decision to return in five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lidster did make a decision, but he took his time and chose the
Stars. The Capitals wanted him to play last Wednesday. The Stars
told him not to rush. The Capitals wanted him for a run to qualify
for the playoffs. The Stars wanted him for a run at the Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key factor,'' said Lidster, who already has his
name on the Cup as a member of the 1993-94 New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Stars have a little defensive depth, and Lidster has a
chance to stretch his legs one last time in the NHL. He comes with
great credentials, teammates say, a mix of on-ice intensity and
off-ice calm, which makes him the perfect seventh defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in such good shape, always lifting'' weights, said
Sergei Zubov, Lidster's teammate on New York's Cup-winning team.
``I remember in the Finals, he came out of nowhere and played
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Lidster rode the pine for the first 14 games of the Rangers'
playoff run, but then was given his first chance to play in the
memorable Game 6 of the Eastern Conference Finals against the New
Jersey Devils in which then-captain Mark Messier guaranteed
victory. Lidster played, the Rangers won and then-coach Mike Keenan
never had a reason to take Lidster out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Lidster played all seven games of the Finals, scored two goals
and earned his Stanley Cup ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching that series, and he was huge,'' said Stars
winger Pat Verbeek, also is a former teammate of Lidster's.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Lidster is like former Stars defenseman Grant
Ledyard, a good skater with steady hands. However, both Verbeek and
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock say the 6-foot-1, 200-pound Lidster is
tougher in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Rangers in '93-94, Lidster was one of the
Vancouver Canucks' most dependable defensemen, voted the team's top
blue-liner four times ('84, '85, '86 and '91). With the Rangers, he
became more of a role player, the kind of defenseman who might sit
for two weeks and then play three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done that role before and it's one I'm comfortable
with,'' Lidster said. ``I think it comes easier with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is the perfect example of what awaits Lidster. Defenseman
Darryl Sydor has recovered quickly from the strained medial
collateral ligament in his left knee and could play. However, the
decision to use Sydor _ the Stars' leader in defenseman scoring
with 40 points _ won't be made until game time. Lidster has to be
ready to play or sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something he's done in his career and something that
does take a little bit of a special individual,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said. ``Doug has skills both on the ice and off
that can be helpful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lidster, in fact, learned even more patience in his stint with
the Canadian National Team _ a situation in which he played more
than he expected, but said he was hoping to blend into a coaching
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was what I thought was a unique way to end a career,''
Lidster said. ``Now, I'm looking at \Rthe Stars\S the same way.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
