r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-H     02-28 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-HAYES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL OF FAME PLAQUE NOW TAYLOR-MADE FOR BOB HAYES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I proudly call to order this morning, The Committee to elect Bob
Hayes to the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Our co-chairmen will need no introduction. Mr. Roger Staubach
and Mr. Tex Schramm already have plaques hanging on the Hall's
walls in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, until one month ago there was no such committee.
Over the years, an occasional ``it's a shame about Bob Hayes''
would be heard, but sadly, there was no getting around the prison
time served in Huntsville back in the '70s. And truthfully, his
dope-selling conviction, along with questions about Hayes having
ever straightened out his life, seemed to leave Bullet Bob without
Hall of Fame hope.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this personal failure in his past, Hayes was not even
a Ring of Honor member at Texas Stadium. Nor a Texas Sports Hall of
Fame member in Waco. He was and is overwhelmingly deserving for
both, but around here, character counted.
</P>
<P>
   In Canton, however, it doesn't. This was just learned a month
ago when Lawrence Taylor, former New York Giants linebacker, was
elected to the Hall of Fame. As a side note, I, too, would have
voted for Taylor, even though this man appears to be a loosely
wired time bomb, ready to crack, so to speak. Bet me on this _
another ugly scene from Taylor is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Those Hall of Fame electors who opposed Taylor over the
character issue certainly had that right. And they had a good case.
</P>
<P>
   But large segments of the New York media reacted with utter
disgust at the anti-Taylor group. In some instances, they
lip-locked with Lawrence, and took pandering of a troubled jock
down to Switzer level.
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, a good lesson. And also a great Canton opening
for Bob Hayes. Without one doubt, now we know the Pro Football Hall
of Fame stands for only this _ what happened on the field during a
career. So be it.
</P>
<P>
   This means Bob Hayes has to be voted into the Hall of Fame at
the next election in late January, the Saturday before the Super
Bowl in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hayes committee still has much work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, based on football achievement, Bob was qualified
long ago,'' said Staubach, as successful a Dallas businessman as he
was an NFL quarterback. ``He was one of the special few who stepped
on a football field and totally changed the way the game was
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you factor in this Lawrence Taylor debate _ and I
admit I was back and forth on Lawrence _ this takes Bob's chances
to a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   As an Olympic gold medal speedster, Hayes hit the field for the
Cowboys in 1965 and immediately destroyed the traditional
man-to-man concept of how a secondary planned its coverage. To this
day, zone coverage should be known as ``Hayes coverage.'' Zone
coverage was invented out of necessity, just to contain Bullet Bob.
</P>
<P>
   You want numbers _ in his first four seasons (14-game seasons),
Hayes scored 45 touchdowns. Even though limited by injuries in '69
and held to four TDs, Bob totaled 59 touchdowns in six years. As a
punt returner, Hayes made Deion Bay-bee look like Nate Newton. He
played 10 seasons, but with injuries a problem, he was most
productive in the first seven.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question, however, Hayes stacks up stat-wise for the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never about numbers on Bob Hayes,'' said Schramm, for
29 years the team's president-GM. ``It is only about Bob being in
prison; otherwise, he's in the Hall of Fame, and I'd certainly have
put him in the Ring of Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Schramm and Staubach served as character witnesses at
Hayes' 1978 trial in Dallas on three counts of delivery of illegal
drugs. To this day, Schramm is angry at the 5-year sentence Hayes
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob had his problems, but he was not a drug dealer,'' said
Schramm. ``He was totally set up by an undercover cop trying to
take down a big name. Bob has spent most of his life trying to
please everyone, and it has caused him great personal pain.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also well-documented that through all his problems, before
and after prison, Hayes always had a helping friend in Staubach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, Bob is a super person and a decent human being,''
said Staubach.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm: ``I don't agree that only performance matters, but
since a Taylor is now the standard for the Hall of Fame, Bob Hayes
is way overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   Now residing in Florida with his mother, Hayes cried last week
when told by phone there were those in North Texas pushing hard for
him to be in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had given up on that a long time ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In August, a committee will meet in Canton to put the names of
senior players on the next ballot. The campaign for Bob Hayes has
hereby begun.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
