<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRA-STAGING-AZR &LR;      02-28 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-STAGING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO STOCK WORLD A STAGE  
 DRAGSTERS PLAY HEAD GAMES TO START RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Pro Stock gunslingers Warren Johnson and Scott Geoffrion, it
might as well have been high noon at the O.K. Corral.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it was near dusk and the site was Houston, one of
several stops on the National Hot Rod Association circuit.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Geoffrion were in the finals, and each driver
cautiously approached the starting line after their burnouts.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lit the Christmas tree's pre-stage light first.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Geoffrion.
</P>
<P>
   Then . . . nothing.
</P>
<P>
   No one budged. No one buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Geoffrion each refused to be the first driver to
light the second bulb, called staging, which precedes the start of
the quarter-mile drag race.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two minutes, they remained motionless.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, NHRA chief starter Buster Couch reached his own boiling
point. He instructed both drivers to back off the starting grid and
switch off the ignitions of their race cars.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Couch got in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``He yelled at us as if we were two schoolkids,'' Geoffrion
said.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the sometimes topsy-turvy world of ``staging games,''
a ploy some drivers use in an attempt to upset the mental balance
of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it works.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   In that particular episode at Houston five years ago, it worked
for Johnson but not for Geoffrion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a bit of difference if I stage first or
second,'' said Johnson, one of Pro Stock's all-time greats. ``But
that Wayne County team (Geoffrion) considered themselves somewhat
renegades from the standpoint they felt they could do anything they
wanted. They made a statement that come hell or high water, they
were going to stage last. I took a little measure of dislike to
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we (returned) to the (starting grid), I decided to go
ahead and stage first. (Geoffrion) was a relative rookie, and I
could tell he was getting pretty nervous. Their engine expertise
wasn't very good, so I knew the engine was at the point that it was
already boiling water. I saw them steam, and I knew (Geoffrion) was
cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me who stages first, either,'' Geoffrion
said. ``I just felt at that particular time that (Johnson's car)
had a performance advantage, and it would be foolish to not try and
take that away from him. He had lane choice and a faster car.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you really studied him at that point in his career, he
was as good as anybody if he staged last. But if he staged first, I
felt he was vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won that one, but I faced him six more times the rest of
the season, and I beat him all six times. And that was after he
made all those snide comments (at Houston) about me, calling us
jerks and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the NHRA rule book doesn't stipulate the amount of time
one driver has to stage after another driver already has staged,
chief starter Rick Stewart, who has replaced the retired Couch,
said, ``It shouldn't take long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let the drivers mess around a little bit in pre-stage,
but once that first driver sets the staging light on, the second
driver better get himself in there at a very rapid rate, because
I'm counting,'' Stewart said. ``My job is to maintain a level
playing field, and a drag race should be won or lost by two things,
driver reaction and car performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be won or lost by who stages first or second or
who plays the best game. My job is to make sure these games don't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch always attempted to make certain drivers stage within
three seconds of each other. In the memorable showdown in Houston,
however, it never got to the final stage. Not initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Geoffrion) says I yelled at them like two schoolkids, it's
because they were acting like schoolkids,'' Couch said by telephone
from his Georgia home. ``I had to scold them. If they were going to
act like kids, I'd treat them like kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a time when Bob Glidden and Larry Morgan did the
same thing. I finally told them to shut off their cars and I went
up to (Glidden) and said, `Bob, you're a chicken if you don't stage
first.' Then I went and told Morgan the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They about ran over each other trying to stage first.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrion, however, doesn't see anything wrong with staging
games. In fact, he believes staging games are a useful tool in
spurring more interest in the division, which mostly takes a back
seat to Top Fuel dragsters and Funny Cars as far as media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Top Fuelers and Funny Cars got us covered in noise,
excitement and blowing up,'' Geoffrion said. ``If we can't create
excitement with some staging battles, our class would be pretty
boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staging games is one way to give the fans some excitement. I
don't think we should hang out the other guy. We should have to
stage within four seconds. But if two cars want to sit there and
play games, we should let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Staging games rarely happen in Top Fuel and Funny Car because
the longer those 6,000-horsepower machines are subject to idle
time, the more it affects the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit there too long and you'll upset the tuneup of the car
and put more heat in the clutch,'' Top Fuel driver Eddie Hill said.
``These cars are so expensive to run, you can't afford to throw
away runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, if somebody does it to me at this race, I'll darn
sure do it to them at the next race.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill likely won't have to worry.
</P>
<P>
   But keep an eye on those Pro Stock drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell Alderman and I had a deal a few years ago at Columbus,
and (Stewart) finally put down the starting mechanism and
disqualified us,'' Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen said. ``I don't
think that was right. I don't think a starter should determine the
outcome. But in that case, not staging first didn't work for either
of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of racers feel if you can control the other person,
it's to their advantage to play these games.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it still happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me one way or the other, and I think Warren
(Johnson) is a much better driver than he was (in 1994),''
Geoffrion said. ``But I think you can still irritate him. And if
you do that, you've gained an edge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
