<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-Z-NAMES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Z Whiz! Four in Rangers camp have last names with rare leadoff
letter 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Zero in on the Rangers' spring training
roster, and it becomes zestfully obvious this is a team bearing the
mark of Zorro on the verge of making baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Zealously, it can been recorded that the Rangers' campers
include Todd Zeile, Gregg Zaun, Jeff Zimmerman and Mike Zywica. If
all were to make the team, the Rangers would have the first
zinc-plated roster in history featuring four players with the last
name beginning with Z.
</P>
<P>
   Zounds.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a zany etymologist's dream. Zonk would be banging
his drum in glee at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surrounded by greatness,'' Zaun said. ``Three other
guys with the last name beginning with the letter Z. What more
could a guy ask for? You grow up dreaming about something like
that, but you never think it could materialize.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaun and Zeile made history last year with the Florida Marlins
by being the first two Z's to ever appear in the same lineup
together. But that wouldn't even be in the same zone with having
four Z's on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would have to fire Johnny Oates and bring back Don
Zimmer as manager.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this. The Baseball Encyclopedia lists only 59 players
in this century whose last names begin with the letter Z. Zeile and
Richie Zisk are the only two to have played with the Rangers.
Zeile, Zaun and Twins infielder Jon Zuber were the only Z's to play
in the majors last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a thrill to be in the majors, but four Z's in the
same lineup?'' Zimmerman said. ``That would be something.''
</P>
<P>
   The big winner in all this would be Zywica, one of the Rangers'
top minor-league prospects who is in the big-league camp for the
first time. If Zywica were to zip up to the majors this year, he
would be absolutely last alphabetically among every baseball player
who ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   That singularly Zirconian honor is currently held by George
Zuverink, who pitched for the Indians, Reds, Tigers and Orioles
from 1951-59.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met anybody, I don't want to say has a worse name
than mine, but falls behind mine,'' said Zywica, who comes from
just outside of Chicago and is of Polish ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the best Scrabble names in baseball history,''
Zeile said. ``You've got to get a double bonus out of Zywica.''
</P>
<P>
   What would make Zywica's appearance even more special is that
Hank Aaron is first alphabetically. So from that zero hour on, the
major-league roll call would run the gamut from Hank Aaron to Mike
Zywica.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be nice, to be in the same company as somebody like
that,'' Zywica said. ``I've never thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zywica does serve at least one useful purpose in spring
training. He keeps Zaun, Zeile and Zimmerman from having to be last
alphabetically, something they've had to endure forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been persecuted all my life,'' Zimmerman said. ``Last at
my high school graduation, last guy when they were taking
attendance, you're always at the end no matter what list you're
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Zimmerman said, ``I don't think anybody could be
behind Zywica. It would have to be Zyy.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually if the Rangers did have four Z's in the same lineup,
Zaun would come first alphabetically, a mindboggling experience for
him. His previous claim to fame was hitting the first home run into
the swimming pool at Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually be the first among the Z's, that would be a first
for me,'' Zaun said. ``To be the first in a list of something,
anything ... wow.''
</P>
<P>
   Having four Z's on the roster also could lend Zeile moral
support in his historic pursuit of Gus Zernial, the all-time
home-run leader among the Z's. Zernial hit 237. Zeile enters this
season with 159.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to shoot for,'' Zeile said modestly. ``It might
do something to combat my other record, four errors in a game by a
first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether he could endure the mounting pressure
and national media attention that comes with epic home-run
pursuits. Look what happened to Mark McGwire last year.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have four Z's on the same team, lives could be changed
forever.
</P>
<P>
   All Z team P Tom Zachary Won 184 games with Browns, Senators,
Yankees, Braves and others (1926-36).
</P>
<P>
   C Chief Zimmer Caught for the Pirates at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   1B Rollie Zeider Infielder who played with the White Sox from
1910-13 and the Cubs from 1916-18, is all-time leader with 223
stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   2B Heine Zimmerman Cubs infielder (1907-16) is all-time Z leader
in games (1,456), runs (695), hits (1,566) and RBI (796).
</P>
<P>
   SS Don Zimmer Dodgers shortstop on 1959 World Series winner.
</P>
<P>
   3B Todd Zeile With 642 runs and 707 RBI, he's poised for a run
at Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   OF Gus Zernial AL outfielder of the 1950s hit 237 homers.
</P>
<P>
   OF Al Zarilla Hit .329 for the Browns in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   OF Richie Zisk Second all-time with 207 homers and 792 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
