<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES DISAPPOINTED WITH RODRIGUEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates yesterday
voiced his disagreement with catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status he has attained in this game makes him a leader
whether he wants to be or not,'' Oates said of his seven-time
All-Star. ``Now, what kind of leader he wants to be is up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates addressed Rodriguez's late arrival to camp for the first
time yesterday morning after discussing the matter with his
27-year-old catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a leader,'' Rodriguez said Friday
after ending his eight-day absence. ``I consider myself just
another player who's got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates argued that Rodriguez's actions seta bad example for
younger players in the Rangers' system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes much farther than just throwing and catching the
ball,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager reiterated his disappointment to Rodriguez during
their private conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge knows how I feel about it,'' Oates said. ``He knows
exactly how disappointed I am.''
CLAYTON GOAL ACHIEVED
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers failed twice in their attempt to acquire a No. 1
starter for their rotation, but the organization fulfilled their
No. 1 objective this winter by retaining shortstop Royce Clayton,
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe getting a shortstop was more important,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect that Clayton's presence for an entire season
will help their rotation, which posted the American League's worst
earned-run average (5.46).
</P>
<P>
   Clayton's range factor during the 1998 season ranked fifth among
the 28 shortstops who played at least 600 innings at the position.
Range factor measures the number of successful chances _ putouts
plus assists _ handled per nine innings. The top 10 were: Shortstop
Team Range Neifi Perez Rockies 5.12 Kevin Stocker Devil Rays 4.98
Deivi Cruz Tigers 4.96 Mike Bordick Orioles 4.95 Royce Clayton
Rangers 4.91 Miguel Tejada Athletics 4.90 Omar Vizquel Indians 4.88
Ricky Gutierrez Astros 4.85 Pat Meares Twins 4.78 Mike Caruso White
Sox 4.77
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-LEAGUE START
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan for center fielder Ruben Mateo and second
baseman Kelly Dransfeldt to begin this season with Triple-A
Oklahoma of the Pacific Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers view Mateo and Dransfeldt the apparent heirs to
center fielder Tom Goodwin and second baseman Mark McLemore, both
of whom can become free agents after this season.
</P>
<P>
   How close are the two to being ready for significant roles at
the major-league level?
</P>
<P>
   Mateo and Dransfeldt ``would not be embarrassed in the big
leagues this year,'' Oates said.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and ESPN anchor Dan Patrick began taping their
commercial for ``ESPN Magazine'' yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Oates scheduled intrasquad games for Wednesday and Thursday at
Charlotte County Stadium.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
