<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES     02-28 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Scottie Pippen demanded a
third-quarter kill, barking his command in no uncertain terms. He
doesn't remember what he said, or didn't want to repeat it in mixed
company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But a third-quarter Rockets collapse, so routine it might be
promised in fine print on the back of tickets, would not be
tolerated, not against Vancouver and especially not with the Lakers
having done nothing more strenuous lately than hold news
conferences and slap around the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of their third-quarter failings, and the unpleasant
prospect of having to sweat out a game with the Grizzlies, the
Rockets produced their best third-quarter stretch of the season
Saturday. They easily put away the Grizzlies early before coasting
to an 86-74 win on their way to today's meeting with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen was not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been much easier,'' Pippen said. ``We had an
opportunity to put this team away. We have a game tomorrow. We
should have taken care of the lead and taken them out of the game.
We had our opportunities to take them out of the game. We allowed
them to regain momentum and were never able to put them away.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he can solve that with a simple order as completely as
the Rockets solved their third-quarter travails, Pippen might rival
Charles Barkley for memorable timeout exhortations.
</P>
<P>
   Having averaged 18.3 points per third quarter this season, the
Rockets outscored Vancouver 33-19 in the third period Saturday,
pushing their lead to as large as 20. They made 13 of 18 shots in
those 12 minutes, their best shooting quarter of the season. And
their offense worked so smoothly that of those 13 field goals, 10
came off assists. The Rockets had 17 assists for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them, `Come out and keep the energy up, and let's
not have the third-quarter letdown,''' said Pippen, who tied Hakeem
Olajuwon for team-high honors with 18 points. ``That's been the
thorn that's been killing us this season. We haven't come out and
established ourselves in the third quarter. When you're playing on
the road, you have to keep the same intensity and control of the
game, and keep the fans out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a leader and made sure we stayed on top of our
game. I said, `Stay aggressive, keep our energy up, and get to the
loose balls.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets markedly improved in those areas. After forcing just
four turnovers against the Hawks on Thursday, the Rockets forced 20
on Saturday. Ranking 25th in the NBA in blocked shots with an
average of four, the Rockets had 11 on Saturday, five by Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our season high for deflections for our defense,''
Tomjanovich said of one of his favorite measures of effort. ``After
a game when we didn't get a lot of loose balls and didn't shake
things up, we went out and got a lot of loose balls and scrambled
them up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Having gotten the defensive intensity so sorely lacking in
Thursday's debacle, the Rockets made the offense seem easy. The
Rockets went the entire quarter without taking a difficult shot,
with almost everything set up by quick, precise passing and fast
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knocked things loose, got some open-court situations,''
Tomjanovich said. ``And when we move that ball and get good shots,
this is the best shooting team we ever had. We just have to trust
each other and not force things and keep the ball moving. There's
so many good shooters out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that first timeout, Brent Price had set up Michael
Dickerson and Olajuwon for layups, Othella Harrington passed
outside to Dickerson for a 3 and Pippen set up Price for a 3.
Having let a lead as large as 13 slide to just four by halftime,
the Rockets scored on nine consecutive possessions and 15 of 23
times they touched the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were focused about going out and saying we will execute,''
Olajuwon said. ``The execution was, I think, the best (this
season). It flowed so naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Harrington: ``It definitely felt better. You can definitely
tell when everything's moving. When the ball is moving around and
guys are making their shots. It's obvious when the ball is moving
around and it's all working.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets couldn't make that last. The Grizzlies did
enough offensively to shut off the transition offense that had
worked well for the Rockets in the third quarter. And though they
continued to set each other up for good shot opportunities, the
Rockets, the second-most accurate shooting team in the NBA, fell
into a shooting funk, making just five of 17 shots in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich had begun to think about a chance to rest his
regulars as the charter warmed up. But the Grizzlies started the
fourth quarter with a 6-0 run to move within 14 and with 2:06 left
were back within nine. Price hit a 3-pointer 15 seconds later to
push the lead back to a safe 84-72.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure wanted to have that thing taken care of,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``They started to make that mini-run. We'd make a good run,
but they would get it close to single figures.''
</P>
<P>
   But having turned around other problem areas _ forcing
turnovers, blocking shots and showing up in the third quarter _
Pippen, with the slow finish, had something new to demand during
timeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
