<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-28 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT wasn't The Pit, 1983 and all the majesty of one last-second play
and one breathtaking moment for all the marbles.
</P>
<P>
   It was a half-empty Hofheinz Pavilion _ half-full, if you're an
optimist. It was an emaciated talent pool of legitimate talent for
the Coogs _ thin, if you're an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the kind of iron-rattling free-throw shooting that
had to inspire only the sponsors of the upcoming Conference USA
tournament _ an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody duck. The Cougars are stepping up to the line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a couple of teams that were mediocre at best, horrible at
worst and mixing it up with a No. 4 seed in next week's C-USA
tourney on the line for the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   But it was something. A start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it for the last two games,'' Cougars coach
Clyde Drexler said. ``It would have been nice to get that No. 4
seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations, obviously, have been lowered considerably for
Drexler and Houston Cougars basketball over the years, but that's
why Coach Clyde came back in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   He came to lift spirits and banners. He came to rekindle
emotions, pride and respect.
</P>
<P>
   You start with a No. 4 seed and build to a Final Four. You start
with Gee Gervin, Kenny Younger and William Stringfellow and build
to a team that can go more than three-deep without fans having to
cover their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In a sort of torch-passing gesture from the glory days to
Drexler's days before Saturday night's game, legendary Cougars
coach Guy V. Lewis even handed Drexler a polka-dot towel similar to
the ones Lewis clutched on the way to all those Final Fours.
</P>
<P>
   This could have been a nice night, all right. A nice start.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final regular-season game of his first year as head
coach, there was no avoiding that this was a thin 10-15 team
Drexler put onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Marquette Golden Eagles tried and tried again to help the
Cougars take the bold step into the conference tournament, never
holding more than a five-point lead in the final 13 minutes. The
Golden Eagles never looked like anything but a sub-.500 team
themselves. Which they were.
</P>
<P>
   But in something of a metaphor for UH's entire season,
ultimately the basketball the Cougars played Saturday was nowhere
close to what will be needed to get over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to sugarcoat it,'' Drexler said. ``There was no
sense of accomplishing something. We played just to play. I thought
that was our worst game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 seeds will have to wait for another year. Final Four bids
still are nothing but a dream.
</P>
<P>
   This was the pits, 1999 and Drexler practically losing his
marbles over all the silliness he had to endure Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Technical foul on Marquette coach Mike Deane with 12 minutes
left: Gervin missed back-to-back free throws.
</P>
<P>
   One-point game with 4:10 left: Younger missed back-to-back free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Two-point game with 3:47 left: Gervin missed one of two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Three-point game with 2:48 left: There was a lazy pass and a
turnover by Stringfellow.
</P>
<P>
   Three-point game with 2:23 left: There was a bad pass into
traffic by Gervin and another turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Two-point game with 1:30 left: Derrick Fernandez missed
back-to-back free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't camouflage this,'' Drexler said. ``They kept
trying to give it to us, but we found every possible way not to
take a lead in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Cougars found a nearly impossible way to miss a chance
to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   With just 13 seconds remaining and the Coogs on a fast break,
Fernandez somehow shot an airball on a layup. By the time Younger
was fouled on a last-second 3-point attempt, meaning he could have
tied the game with three consecutive free throws, the verdict
already was in.
</P>
<P>
   Not this night. Not now. Younger missed the first of the three,
leaving the Cougars a horrendous 12-for-29 for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler rubbed his hands over his face in disgust with the first
miss and walked up the tunnel shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tough,'' Drexler said. ``We couldn't ever get over the
hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like the entire season, there were lots of chances
Saturday, yet it never happened. But you've got to start somewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
