<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TUCSON-THIRD-ROUN     02-28 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TUCSON-THIRD-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMOUR, CHEESMAN SHARE 1-STROKE LEAD AT TUCSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Tommy Armour III has tasted victory in the desert
before. He made the 1990 Phoenix Open his one and only PGA Tour
victory.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that's a bit of a reach when it comes to picking a
favorite for today's conclusion at the Touchstone Energy Tucson
Open. Armour's moment of glory was nearly 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs, like the bogey-free, 5-under 67 he posted
at Tucson National on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking forward to this,'' said the man with the
famous last name, a throwback to his grandfather, Tommy Armour, the
legendary ``Silver Scot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I knew I was going to play good soon, so I've been
getting ready for this.''
</P>
<P>
   He could not have chosen a better arena. With most of the best
players in the world skipping this PGA Tour event to play in the
WGC Match Play this week, Armour has his ducks in a row. And there
are some easy potshots in this group.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Cheesman might get in his way. The former baseball player
is tied with Armour at 10 under after a 69. But he's never won.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nice, because I haven't been that hot, that's for
sure,'' said Cheesman, who has made just three cuts in seven
outings this year.
</P>
<P>
   To show how weak this field is, 30 players are within 5 shots of
the field. Of those guys, only eight have been to the winner's
circle.
</P>
<P>
   If Armour has a challenger, it's Tommy Tolles, who is tied at 9
under with some guy named Mike Weir. Tolles finished second at the
Hawaiian Open earlier in the season, and he has game, even though
he could do no better than a 71 on this sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   Weir is a left-hander, and he is not to be confused with Phil
Mickelson, even though he won the 1998 PGA Tour Qualifying School.
It's doubtful he can follow up with another 67.
</P>
<P>
   There's a whole bunch of others, like second-round co-leaders
Gabriel Hjertstedt (8 under) and Scott Gump (7 under), who are in
contention. But for the most part, it's a thin list, which brings
everything back to Armour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on my game,'' said the 39-year-old Texan.
``But the big difference (this week) is you just make a few more
putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My season has been close. I played good in Phoenix, but I
always play good in Phoenix. But I also played well last week at
the Nissan _ I was 5 under after 10 holes and leading the
tournament. I'm close.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheesman, who was drafted by the St. Louis Cardinals and played
minor-league baseball for the then-California Angels and New York
Yankees, also is hoping he can finally hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play the game for these types of situations,'' said
Cheesman, who has intrigued the galleries this week with a driving
iron called the PRGR, which he hits approximately 270 yards off the
tee instead of a driver.
</P>
<P>
   Cheesman would have had the lead outright if not for a bogey at
the 18th hole, where he bunkered his approach shot. But he did make
five birdies to offset one other bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Others of note still in contention included the Scottsdale
contingent of Kirk Triplett, Tim Herron and Jim Carter. Triplett
was 7 under after a 70, and Herron and Carter were 6 under after
shooting 71s.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a disappointment, at least from the gallery's
standpoint, it was John Daly, who was 8 under before bogeying two
of the last four holes. The nosedive left Daly in a melancholy
mood, although he said he had no regrets about coming to Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved coming here,'' said Daly, who had a 71.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Match Play, I don't mind missing that at all.
That 12 weeks I missed last year to get my life together was a lot
more important than any golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he still have a shot, even though he's 4 shots off the
pace?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can shoot another 64 out there,'' Daly said,
referring to R.W. Eaks' score from the first round. ``You'd have to
make every putt, and that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, I can't even make an 8-footer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
