<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     02-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE WINS IN `STREET FIGHT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Players were flying to the floor, elbows
were being thrown and trash-talking had gotten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a men's college basketball game that Pepperdine and
San Francisco were playing. It was macho street ball, and USF was
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them thinking,'' Dons senior guard Gerald Zimmerman
said. ``We had them questioning their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves responded with cold calculation, short on emotion but
long on results. They outplayed the Dons in the most important
second-half of their season and beat USF 67-65 on Saturday in the
first round of the West Coast Conference Tournament at Toso
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (19-11) advanced to the second round for the first
time in three seasons under head coach Lorenzo Romar. The Waves
will play either Santa Clara or Loyola Marymount today at 8 p.m. in
the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine escaped overtime when USF's LyRyan Russell missed an
eight-footer with one second left. As the players walked off the
court, Russell and Pepperdine's Jelani Gardner had a brief heated
exchange, typifying the intensity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loyola (Marymount) is supposed to be our rival,'' Gardner
said, ``but USF is our rival. We knew it was going to be a fight
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Romar was the right to the point in the postgame press
conference: ``When you play the Dons you have to be prepared for an
all-out street fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner deserved to raise his fists in the air after the buzzer.
He was awful when the teams last played; a 1-for-11 performance
from the floor in a 56-44 loss at USF resulted in his removal from
the starting lineup for the first time in his two-year Waves
career.
</P>
<P>
   A good week of practice put Gardner back into the lineup for the
tournament, and he played 37 minutes Saturday, including the entire
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jelani put us on his back,'' Romar said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner came out firing, making his first two shots and helping
the Waves to an early 16-8 lead. But USF (12-18) didn't buckle and
zoomed by Pepperdine in the last five minutes of the first half
with a 14-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine was down 46-35 and facing a first-round exit in the
first round for its third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that everything was at stake in the next 20 minutes,''
Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves went on a 20-7 run to start the half, and the source
of the turnaround was sophomore forward Kelvin Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, who didn't make the all-conference team, became a force
on the boards, getting all 12 of his rebounds in the second half to
go along with a team-high 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coaches and my teammates felt I should have been on the
all-conference team,'' Gibbs said. ``I told myself I'm going to
come out in the tournament and show (them) ... I should have been
an All-WCC selection.''
</P>
<P>
   USF hurt itself with poor shooting, especially from the
free-throw line. The Dons shot only 22 percent (6 for 27) in the
second half from the floor and at one point missed six consecutive
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had (open) shots,'' USF coach Phil Mathews said. ``We just
didn't knock them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman scored a game-high 20 but made only 8 of 24 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pepperdine) guarded me pretty tough,'' he said. ``I ended up
taking more shots than I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   In other tournament games:
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's 65, San Diego 60: The sixth-seeded Gaels (13-17),
inspired by the return of 7-foot-3, 380-pound center Brad Millard,
who missed almost all of the past two seasons with injuries, upset
the third-seeded Toreros (18-9) in overtime. Millard, college
basketball's biggest player, scored 10 points in 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga 84, Portland 63: The top-seeded Bulldogs built a
16-point lead and cruised into the semifinals for the second
consecutive year. Richie Frahm scored 19 to lead four Bulldogs in
double figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
