<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT-TEX 
GEEKS WHAT DOCTOR ORDERED FOR LA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weirdo with the radically long hair, geeky horn-rimmed
glasses, ferocious picks on opponents and kamikaze dives after
loose balls? That's Kurt Rambis, new coach of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   And the weirdo with the radically colored hair, geeky tattoos,
ferocious kicks on cameramen and kamikaze dives into
cross-dressing? That's Dennis Rodman, new leader of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they are just what the Dr. Jerry Buss ordered.
</P>
<P>
   No matter their unique style, Rambis' and Rodman's substances
are all about winning. That in itself is a significant upgrade from
the star-studded but struggling Lakers that lackadaisically
stumbled to a 6-6 start under grandfatherly coach Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who patted players on the back when he should have
kicked them in the butt, should have been fired after his
more-talented Lakers were swept by Utah in the Western Conference
Finals last season. Sure, Harris had a stay of four-plus years in
which he was coach of the year and posted increasing win totals of
48-53-56-61, but his old-school teaching didn't get through to his
Gen-X students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just looked like there was a deterioration,'' Lakers
president Jerry West said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rambis and Rodman, there will be a revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis won four championships in the '80s and long ago won the
respect of players that Harris never earned. He will put on his
shorts and bump Shaquille O'Neal in practice, then lose his cool
and yell at Kobe Bryant during games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the trenches, in the wars,'' O'Neal said. ``He's
more like one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rodman will miss practice, be late for games and draw
numerous suspensions and fines, he too will help the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, he gives LA its first rebounding champion since
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar in 1981. In his debut Friday in a 16-point win
against the Clippers, Rodman grabbed 11 rebounds and dished out six
assists. He took two shots, and didn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   His unselfishness will rub off on shot-aholic Bryant, and his
dirty work will allow O'Neal a cleaner life in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Rodman's constant distraction will actually help
the Lakers. Instead of focusing on the grapple for control of the
team between Bryant and O'Neal, all anyone at the Great Western
Forum is going to care about today is what color Rodman's hair is.
(Here's hoping Carmen persuades him to change from the black,
yellow and purple mess that looked like moldy fungus Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, like Rambis, also won't hold back in publicly ripping
his teammates. Even before he signed his two-year contract that
will pay him $500,000 this season and $1.1 million next, he
criticized the Lakers' lack of maturity and togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should that upset us?'' Robert Horry said. ``It's the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have beaten one winning team this season and are too
young to win a championship. But Del Harris was too nice a guy to
lead them. With the down-and-dirty Rambis and Rodman in control,
the Lakers are in the right hands.
</P>
<P>
   And, if nothing else, LA sure became more attractive to two
sitting Bulls named Phil Jackson and Michael Jordan.
SPOTLIGHT ON ... PAT RILEY
</P>
<P>
   Wonder why Pat Riley is the league's best motivator?
</P>
<P>
   It's because he keeps players from getting bored, first and
foremost. On the way to a recent practice, Riley had the team's bus
driver veer to a theater, where he treated the Heat to a matinee
showing of Waking Ned Devine. And when players showed up at Miami
Arena for their home opener, they found huge, laminated pictures of
an NBA championship ring with their names engraved on it in their
lockers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he was up to it again.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's pregame speech last week in Detroit was about a coach
dunking one of his players in a bucket of ice water, lifting the
player's head at the last minute and saying, ``You will win when
winning is as important as that next breath.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game _ an impressive Heat win _ Riley asked his
players whether they wanted to dunk his head into one of the ice
buckets used to soak feet. Of course, they declined. But Riley went
ahead and dunked himself _ long enough to scare players like
forward P.J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, man, this dude is crazy,'' Brown said. ``He
finally came up, slobbering, and he's like, `Until your last
breath. Until your last breath.'''
QUICK HITS
AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino fined stars Antoine Walker and Kenny
Anderson for their on-court yelling match last week in Washington.
Walker yelled for Anderson to pass him the ball, to which Anderson
retorted ``Get to the right spot and maybe I will. Said Pitino:
``I'm very disappointed that it happened as a coach because it's
unprofessionalism at the highest level.'' ... After somebodies
named Rusty LaRue and Matt Steigenga soiled the sacred cubicles
with two-game stints, the Bulls last week boarded up the lockers of
Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen at the United Center. ... Grant
Hill has a legitimate excuse to not play for his country next
summer. Hill is getting married to Canadian singer Tamia Washington
in late July. ``I can't delay this,'' Hill said. `You think David
Stern's tough ...''
AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   Don't count Minnesota's Stephon Marbury among those hypnotized
by Sacramento rookie magician Jason Williams. While Williams
conjures up images of Pete Maravich with nasty crossovers,
fake-behind-the-back passes and wrap-around dribbles, the
22-year-old Marbury shrugs at Williams' immature game. ``I was
doing those crossover moves and things when I was 13,'' Marbury
said. ``He has to learn to play at two speeds. I used to play like
that, but I had to learn.'' ... Silliest feud in the league lives
on between Rockets forward Scottie Pippen and referee Hue Hollins.
What started in 1994 when Hollins' controversial foul call against
Pippen on Hubert Davis' last-second 3-pointer gave the Knicks the
Eastern Conference championship continued last week when Hollins
ejected Pippen in Orlando. ``He just needs to meet me outside in
the parking lot and we'll settle it,'' Pippen said. ... The Nuggets
posted win No. 3 last week in their 11th game, after taking 41
tries to get three last season.
OFFBEAT BEAT
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of Black History Month, here's to Earl Lloyd. He
doesn't get near the recognition as baseball's Jackie Robinson, but
Lloyd broke basketball's color barrier in 1952 as a forward for the
Syracuse Nationals.
BEST AND WORST
</P>
<P>
   Best player not chosen for Olympic team: Maybe Jason Kidd needs
to average a triple-double before he gets an invitation. The former
Mavericks player is having an early MVP season, recording four
triple-doubles in six games and willing the Suns to a winning
record. ``I don't know what more I can do,'' Kidd said. ``I already
gave them my address.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst player named to Olympic team: We can't do better than a
player who missed 29 of his first 33 free throws and is averaging
career-lows in scoring and rebounding? If it was last season, Vin
Baker was deserving. But this season he's almost an embarrassment
in Seattle.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves had to wait 483 weeks for their first NBA
player of the week. The franchise that began play in November 1989
got on the board when Stephon Marbury won for posting four
consecutive double-doubles in points and assists and leading
Minnesota to a 3-1 mark. The key game was a 40-point, 12-assist,
no-turnover performance in a victory against Houston, only the
fifth time that a player has scored at least 40, dished out at
least 10 assists and not turned over the ball. The other four are:
Player Year Team vs. Opponent P-A-TO World B. Free 1986 Cleveland
vs. Atlanta 43-11-0 Alex English 1987 Denver vs. Milwaukee 46-10-0
Joe Dumars 1990 Detroit vs. Cleveland 42-11-0 Larry Bird 1990
Boston vs. Orlando 46-10-0
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
