<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS DAVIS' SHOW BUT GADZURIC'S TREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The wristbands were Baron Davis' idea.
</P>
<P>
   That figures.
</P>
<P>
   In a home finale that had all the appearances of a certain
sophomore's swan song, Davis sliced and diced the Washington
Huskies and incited the Pauley Pavilion crowd. So why should it be
any surprise that Davis also was behind the gesture so nice it made
Dan Gadzuric smile in spite of his pain?
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric watched the No. 15 Bruins' 79-62 win over the Huskies
Saturday in street clothes, at the end of the bench. It was the
first time his teammates had seen him since he left Wednesday's
practice limping after landing awkwardly on his left knee during a
routine drill.
</P>
<P>
   If no one seemed overly concerned at the time, there was a good
reason. Tendinitis in both knees has left Gadzuric with a gait
that's more John Elway than Johnny Gray on the best of days.
</P>
<P>
   Only Davis had reason to suspect there was more misery in store
for Gadzuric than met the naked eye. His worst fears were confirmed
when the freshman from Holland offhandedly mentioned that he had
heard his knee pop.
</P>
<P>
   Experience told Davis right then and there the news from the
doctor wouldn't be good.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, of course. Gadzuric had torn a lateral meniscus in
his knee. He underwent surgery Thursday, bobbed in a sea of
painkillers Friday and felt well enough Saturday to hobble to the
game on crutches that looked like they belonged on either side of
the steps in the deep end of the men's gym pool.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the arena, Gadzuric saw that his teammates had
written his name and/or jersey number (50) in indelible ink on
their wristbands. Davis, who missed the start of this season after
suffering a knee injury during the NCAA Tournament, had been the
one to suggest it and everyone followed his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the whole knee thing, it hits home,'' Davis said of
Gadzuric's season-ending setback. ``Because of everything I've been
through, I know he has to go through some tough things within
himself. I just wanted to show my appreciation for him as a player
and as a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy for Gadzuric to sit on the same floor where six
days earlier he had played one of his finest games, contributing 12
points, nine rebounds, three blocked shots and three steals in a
93-69 win over Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing,'' Gadzuric said. ``I wish I was in
there. It's a hard thing to just sit on the bench. It's a hard
concept for me to accept. I've got to just deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Providence saw to it that he'd have ample support. Gadzuric's
parents Biba and Lance just happened to be visiting him last week
(they are leaving today). His mom was at Disneyland when the injury
happened. His dad was in the stands, blithely watching practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad that it happened,'' Biba Gadzuric said, ``but it was
perfect timing. If I was in Holland and I heard (Dan) was in the
hospital I would have thought he was dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither father nor son thought it was any big deal at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it first happened, I thought I was going to recover from
it and play (Saturday),'' Gadzuric said. ``The doctors say I'm out
and I just have to settle down with that and stay positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the painkillers, but he's already managed to spot a
few silver linings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my tendinitis is going to be better,'' Gadzuric said,
``because I'm going to have a lot of rest.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said his upper body will be stronger, too. The crutches
will see to that. ``It's another part of my conditioning,''
Gadzuric said.
</P>
<P>
   If Saturday's game was any indication, there may be an
out-of-the-blue benefit for the Bruins, too. Freshman forward JaRon
Rush elevated his game _ quite literally _ in Gadzuric's absence,
pulling down a career-high 15 rebounds and scoring 12 points for
his third double-double. Rush was angling for his ninth offensive
board in the final minute when he was hit in the head and knocked
out for a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, sounding perfectly lucid, Rush said, ``We know that
with Dan gone we all have to pick up our games.''
</P>
<P>
   That they thought to pick up Gadzuric's spirits, too, might have
been worth far more than the win in the long run. After feeling
their love, Gadzuric barely felt his pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate what they did for me a lot,'' Gadzuric said.
``It's a very important aspect to know your teammates are standing
behind you. If they don't, you have no one to rely on. It's hard,
but their support makes me want to work to get back as soon as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the way Davis has come back from his knee surgery gives
Gadzuric hope. The gritty, gifted guard plans to take Gadzuric to
lunch some time soon to explain just how it's done. In the
meantime, Baron settled for showing him spectacular plays like his
windmill dunk late in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   When Gadzuric saw that, he couldn't help himself. He stood up
sans crutches and clapped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
