<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUN-SACRAMENTOSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE ROUTS SACRAMENTO STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One by one they climbed the ladder and grabbed the
scissors in one hand while the other held the net steady and then,
they just snipped away. It was the icing on the cake for the Cal
State Northridge women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ceremonial cutting of the basketball net after a
lopsided 93-59 victory over visiting Cal State Sacramento on
Saturday night. But the celebration was not in honor of dominating
the Hornets; instead, it was for capturing their first Big Sky
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good, it feels really good,'' said Lynda Amari.
``Nobody believed we were going to make it. Everyone kept bringing
up coach Michael (Abraham) and they weren't even looking at us and
it feels good to see that they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They huddled around the Matadors' sign at half court, arms
stretched out in support of each other and asking what all
champions ask before a game begins: What time is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's showtime,'' the Matadors answered in unison, and came out
blazing.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge women's basketball team appeared to
have an extra spring in their step as they took the floor. Maybe it
was because they had just secured their first Big Sky title before
Saturday night's match-up with a 60-47 win over Weber State on
Thursday or perhaps their confidence came from knowing that they
were facing a team with an overall record of 3-23, 1-15 and a
last-place standing in Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Matadors (19-7, 13-3) were in the zone
Saturday night and finished the regular season with an 8-0
conference record at home.
</P>
<P>
   But the question now is: What's next? The Big Sky tournament
begins March 4 with Northern Arizona and Montana State facing off
around 5 p.m. and following that game will be the Montana and Weber
State match-up. Northridge could be facing any one of these teams
on March 5 and the outcome could possibly bring them one game
closer to reaching the NCAA Division I tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to enjoy this today and tomorrow, then come Monday
we're going to re-focus,'' said Northridge coach Frozena Jerro.
``Like I said there are bigger and better things waiting for us if
we can get it done. We are two games away from the NCAA tournament
... All six teams are fighting for the same thing and it's going to
be a dog fight at the Matadome next week ... I think they can taste
it, they got a taste of this Big Sky Championship and they want
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Any one of the Matadors could have been the player of the game.
Edniesha Curry had one of her explosive nights scoring 18 points,
12 of them on 3-pointers. Keisha Harris was the story of the second
half, racking up 13 points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was Amari's performance once again that kept this
engine running. Amari, the Big Sky Player of the Week, passed, shot
and rebounded well. But it wasn't only what her statistics said (15
points and four steals), but the hustle and defense she showed on
the floor which proved to be invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle St. Clair added 16 points. Julie Wastell had 14 for the
Hornets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
