<HEADLINE>
LONG ROAD TO THE TOP FOR MIKE SKINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Skinner's climb to the top of the NASCAR Winston Cup points
standings has taken 78 races and bits and pieces of 10 seasons,
time enough to realize that even running wide-open in a stock car
has its limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't turn back time. I'd love to be 21 and know what I know
now,'' said Skinner, who at 41 typically is not mentioned among
NASCAR's rising superstars. ``That's what Jeff Gordon is _ he's got
the experience and he's young. I'm 41, and I'm not probably going
to break a lot of records in my career. But it's not too late to
have a great career in Winston Cup racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two races of 1999, Skinner methodically has
served notice that he is this year's ``breakthrough driver,''
following the tracks laid by Jeff Burton in 1997 and Jeremy
Mayfield in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner ran fourth in the season-opening Daytona 500 on Feb. 14,
when his victory bid was foiled by the lack of a drafting partner _
a black list topped by a snub from Richard Childress Racing
teammate Dale Earnhardt. Skinner followed with a sixth-place run at
North Carolina Speedway last Sunday, when he and 1989 Cup champion
Rusty Wallace were the only drivers to record top-10s for the
second consecutive race.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the Las Vegas 400 next Sunday, Skinner has forged a
tenuous 29-point lead over Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Skinner has established himself as the best
driver not to have won a Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win a points race,'' said Skinner, who has won
NASCAR exhibition events in Japan the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner and veteran crew chief Larry McReynolds, paired in a
shotgun marriage-style swap of top wrenches at RCR eight months
ago, have taken a pragmatic approach to the 1999 championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully early. This is our third \Rfull\S year in Winston
Cup, and we're excited to be running well,'' said Skinner, driver
of the No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``Our realistic goals
for 1999 were, first, to win a points race. The second goal was to
finish in the top 10 in points. If we can't, we'd like to be around
that area. Getting on that stage \Rat the postseason awards
banquet\S for a good top-10 would be awesome for this year.
Anything above that would be unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds, the winner of 23 Cup races as a crew chief since
1986, sent the series a message via Skinner's victory at the Twin
Ring Motegi oval in Japan last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``All winter long, I kept telling people this race team has what
it takes,'' said McReynolds, 40, who joined RCR in late 1996 after
a high-profile tenure at rival Robert Yates Racing. ``I've been in
situations where race teams were awfully good and where race teams
were not awfully good. The last time I remember feeling the fire in
my belly I feel now about a team and a program was 1994, with the
28 car and Ernie Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just knew it was there, and I feel the same way about this
31 team.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner exchanged crew chief Kevin Hamlin in the swap that
brought McReynolds aboard from Earnhardt's team after 13 races last
year. With the exception of an eighth-place run in the 1998 Daytona
500, Skinner's early season was a disaster. The lowlights included
grinding crashes at Atlanta Motor Speedway (42nd-place finish) and
at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth (33rd) that left Skinner's
body and ego battered and reduced his superspeedway Monte Carlos to
scrap iron.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner sat out three consecutive races to allow his injuries to
heal, a period marked by rumors that Childress was planning to fire
the native Californian. The rumors proved false, and subsequently
were trumped by the shocking switch of crew chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that McReynolds was supposed to help deliver Earnhardt
his unprecedented eighth Cup championship when he signed with the
No. 3 GM Goodwrench team. But the Earnhardt-McReynolds association
produced only one victory _ in the season-opening 1998 Daytona 500
_ with Skinner, ironically, proving a willing and able bump-draft
partner.
</P>
<P>
   An admittedly crestfallen McReynolds packed his tools for the
move into Skinner's shop last June, and immediately began
fashioning a championship-caliber outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at Mike, I don't look at age,'' said McReynolds,
who helped shape the budding career of Davey Allison before his
death in July 1993. ``I look at what type of driver Mike is and
what he's looking for. Mike and I hit it off pretty good. We are
going to do whatever it takes to win races. That's the biggest
thing we have in common.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 20-race association with McReynolds last year,
Skinner racked up three top-fives and eight top-10s. He advanced 15
positions in points to 21st, and then repeated in Victory Lane in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to get a bond there and confidence in each other's
opinions,'' Skinner said. ``Larry has been a great coach as well as
a great friend and great crew chief. Larry has brought a ton of
depth to this race team. Team-wise, I think everybody's trying to
pull the rope in the same direction. You don't hear guys walking
around the 31 shop talking under their breath. These guys want to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   They also want that first team-defining, points-paying Winston
Cup victory. Skinner believes that could happen on the flat,
1.5-mile Las Vegas track, where Skinner plans to run the same car
he won with at Twin Ring Motegi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at it as our next race is our next opportunity
to win our first Cup race,'' Skinner said. ``I think Vegas is
potentially one of our best racetracks. I'm not a bookie and don't
know where I'd put our chances ... 100-to-1 and then I'd go bet
everything on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our chances. We'd love to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mike Skinner file Date of birth: June 28, 1957, Ontario,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Susanville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Car: No. 31 Lowe's Home Improvement Chevrolet Monte Carlo
</P>
<P>
   Car owner: Richard Childress
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief: Larry McReynolds
</P>
<P>
   Career Cup starts: 78
</P>
<P>
   First Cup start: April 27, 1986, Martinsville (Va.) Speedway;
started 27th, finished 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   First pole: Feb. 9, 1997, Daytona International Speedway, 16th
career start.
</P>
<P>
   1995: Won first race of the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series at
Phoenix International Raceway, and went on to claim the inaugural
driver's championship.
</P>
<P>
   1996: Substituted for an injured Dale Earnhardt in the Brickyard
400; finished 47th in Cup points after running five races.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Won Winston Cup rookie of the year after finishing 30th in
Cup points for RCR; won second NASCAR Suzuka Thunder Special 100
demonstration race on road-course in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Finished a career-best 21st in Cup points; won third
NASCAR demonstration race at Twin Ring Motegi oval in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   1999: Moved to top of Cup points standings with back-to-back
top-10 finishes after two races.
</P>
</TEXT>
