<HEADLINE>
AL WEST COULD TURN ON THE WAY KEN HILL PITCHES FOR THE ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may not be a more pivotal player in the American League
West than Angels pitcher Ken Hill.
</P>
<P>
   If he can come all the way back from last year's elbow trouble,
the Angels are much more formidable competition for the Rangers. If
he doesn't, the Angels will have a hard time staying competitive
unless they get extremely lucky with one of their young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing ... it's not just important for me to come
back, it's important for all of us,'' Hill told the Los Angeles
Times. ``I need to be healthy. I need to get my game back together
so I can help this club get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill missed 21/2 months last year with elbow trouble, then was
erratic when he returned in September. So far this spring he's
thrown the ball well with the help of a more compact delivery that
puts less stress on the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's workouts have been a bright spot for a team rattled by
the injury to shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who broke his left forearm
early on his first day in camp. DiSarcina was hit by coach George
Hendrick's fungo after stepping out of the batting cage, after
taking only his first seven swings of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The injury was an emotional slap for a team that was feeling
good in the off-season after the signing of Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into camp with an upbeat attitude, we can't let this
get us down,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``We can't start
saying, `Here we go again.' I am not going to let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are looking at Jeff Huson, Craig Shipley, Andy
Stankiewicz and Luis Rivera as possible replacements until
DiSarcina is ready in April. Third baseman Troy Glaus, a shortstop
at UCLA, may also play there, with Dave Hollins stepping in for him
at third.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also haven't solved their overloaded outfield
problem. Tim Salmon spent last year at designated hitter because of
a torn ligament in his left foot, but said he's ready to move back
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have talked about rotating Salmon, Garret Anderson,
Jim Edmonds and Darin Erstad at designated hitter. But Salmon said:
``I'm healthy. I feel I can play every day in the outfield. I don't
plan on being part of any rotation in the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle has been called almost everything by fans across
the country. He said his favorite was, ``Some guy yelled at me,
`You're one hot dog away from being Cecil Fielder.' I got the
biggest laugh out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker isn't panicking. He has lost
All-Star outfielder Moises Alou for most of the year, but he thinks
he can get by with Richard Hidalgo in left, Carl Everett in center
and Derek Bell in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as bad as if we were to lose Jeff Bagwell or Craig
Biggio,'' Dierker said. ``We've got three everyday outfielders that
have fielding ability, strong throwing arms and can do damage with
the bat. We don't have anybody backing up second base or first
base. Nobody is going to replace Alou, but we've got guys who can
come close.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has four members of his five-man rotation set in Shane
Reynolds, Mike Hampton, Jose Lima and Sean Bergman. He also said
Chris Holt, who missed all of last year with a shoulder problem, is
healthy and competing with Scott Elarton and Brian Powell for the
fifth spot. Dierker said Elarton is still a couple of years away
from being a dominant major-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why people think Belle will be much more productive with
the Orioles than the White Sox. Over the past three years,
right-handed hitters have hit 7 percent more home runs at Camden
Yards than they did at the average major league park. They hit 6
percent less at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals were 40-46 before the All-Star break
last year and 43-33 afterward. They were 18-7 in September. Manager
Tony LaRussa said that shows all the attention directed toward Mark
McGwire does not distract the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have a flat day when that many people show up at
the stadium,'' LaRussa said. ``There's no doubt in my mind he's a
huge plus.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner has merged the Yankees with the New York
Nets of the NBA, putting together a sports and entertainment
company similar to the Rangers and the Stars. That allows the
Yankees to become much more attractive to a regional cable company
when their current contract with Madison Square Garden runs out
after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees already get approximately $50 million a year from
local broadcasting revenues, a figure that blows all other clubs
out of the water. It could get even more lucrative if ESPN or
Time-Warner decide to step in and form a New York-based regional
cable network to compete with MSG or Fox Sports New York.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox pitcher Jaime Navarro showed up to camp one day late,
announced he didn't want to pitch in the bullpen again and got into
a clubhouse argument with outfielder Jeff Abbott. The two had to be
separated by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas, who thought the rest of his career would be as a
DH, said he wants to play 120-125 games at first base. The White
Sox will probably accommodate him, leaving Paul Konerko as their
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   pitcher Ed Vosberg, the ex-Ranger who missed all of last season
with a bad shoulder, showed up in camp throwing hard again and
breaking off sharp curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball's aim is not to get veteran umpires to
change their strike zone. Baseball officials are only hoping to get
the younger umpires to call the high strike and somehow reverse the
trend over the past several years of the shrinking strike zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
