<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appeals court's ruling shows plants, animals matter
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta artist Michael Murrell's sculpture ``No Place
Wild,'' with its bare-looking metal globe sitting on a pile of
empty tennis shoes, says what I feel about America's shrinking
wilderness. It's fitting that Murrell is on exhibit in Atlanta
because an unlikely group has taken his message to heart: the 11th
Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that could set national precedent for the way the
U.S. Forest Service operates, the federal appellate judges
overturned a district court judgment and halted seven timber
projects in the Chattahoochee and Oconee national forests. The
court said the Forest Service didn't bother to consider imperiled
plants and animals in the area. Its own regulations require it to
do so. Forest Service officials admitted sensitive species and
their habitat would be destroyed by the timbering. But officials
claimed the species would be OK since they exist elsewhere in the
forest. So much for the brook trout or the cerulean warbler.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kirby, former Southeast director of the Wilderness Society
(one of several environmental groups involved), worked on the
lawsuit for five years. He notes that the appellate court's ruling
doesn't halt all logging in the forests involved, but it sets a
precedent for other challenges to the Forest Service around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   It confirms what a recent federal audit report found _ the
agency hasn't been doing the environmental assessments the laws
require. In an audit of 12 timber projects over a three-year
period, the U.S. Agriculture Department's inspector general found
the Forest Service's evaluations didn't consider sensitive species.
In fact, in one in which the forest service recorded no imperiled
species, auditors found there were 127 either threatened or
endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the landmark court ruling, there's another ray of hope
for reforming Forest Service policy, for recognition at last that
all but one third of remaining national forests now contain roads,
most built by loggers at taxpayer expense. That hope is new Forest
Service chief Mike Dombeck. Dombeck is moving slowly to change the
myth that the highest and best use of every forest is logging.
(Most of this nation's timber doesn't even come from national
forests anymore, and shouldn't.) In a speech last month, Dombeck
said, ``It's my expectation that (our) long-term road policy will
significantly limit, if not eliminate, costly new road construction
in sensitive areas that can cause erosion, imperil rare species or
fragment habitat.'' He's enforcing an 18-month freeze on road
building in roadless areas.
</P>
<P>
   I stood at the end of an invigorating hike atop Georgia's
second-highest mountain, Rabun Bald, last weekend. I gazed on
roads, golf courses, cellular towers and other interferences with
the 365-degree view of the glorious Blue Ridge Mountains. In the
past 10 years, protected roadless acreage on Rabun Bald has shrunk
by half. In fact, only 15 percent of Georgia's forest lands are
preserved as wilderness, compared to 30 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   It's good that the 11th Circuit set a precedent with a case out
of the Southeast. We need it most. I can't hike this week, but I
can take in works of Murrell at City Hall East in Atlanta. His
reverence for nature also helps soothe the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
