A2223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-FUNERAL01-COX     02-28 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-FUNERAL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former truck driver says he paid for funeral of Jasper victim
 &HT;    By Brad Mayhari
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A former Los Angeles truck driver says that he _
not basketball star Dennis Rodman _ helped pay for the funeral of
Jasper dragging death victim James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   After a 12-man jury sentenced the first of three white suspects
in the crime, John William King, to the death penalty, 62-year-old
Henry Crump told The Lufkin Daily News he wanted the world to know
that he paid for the vault at Byrd's gravesite instead of the
flamboyant Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from his Southern California home,
Crump, who has experience working in funeral homes, said he felt
compelled to go public about his contributions to Byrd's funeral
after continuing to hear the victim's family attribute the deed to
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'm going to do something so that it can be with me in
my heart and I'm going to keep my mouth closed, so that I can do
something that is right and will always be with me,'' Crump said of
why he waited almost nine months after Byrd's funeral to go public
about his contribution. ``So I did it, and I kept my mouth quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one of my family members knows about it, and one neighbor
and about 13 other people _ over half of them I don't even know.
The reason I mentioned it to them is because I was in the grocery
line, and they was all hyped up about what Dennis did, and I said
I'm the one who did this or I bought that, and they just looked at
me. When I tell the average person that, they resent it. They
resent this because I'm just a nobody knows who I am, little black
dude out here in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Crump said Rodman kept his promise of sending money intended to
cover funeral expenses to the Byrd family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's accepted because of who Dennis Rodman is, and I feel sad
for him, because they bring him on nationwide TV knowing that they
didn't use the money _ knowing they didn't do it,'' Crump said.
``They know right from wrong. I don't know if (Rodman) sent it to
them or took it to them, but he's been on nationwide TV saying he
paid for the service, which he probably gave money, but it was
kept. Who knows what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Crump said he took offense when members of the Byrd family did
not contact him last fall when they traveled to Los Angeles to
appear on ``The Roseanne Show'' with Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two sisters came out on the Roseanne Barr show, and I live
two and a half miles from the doggone studio, and they didn't have
guts enough to say: `Henry Crump, we're in town. Thank you, bye
bye, can't see you, but we'll see you later,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister Mary Verrett of Houston, said Crump's name sounded
familiar, but she could not recall who paid for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received so much mail and so many contributions from
individuals,'' Ms. Verrett said. ``It this point it's hard to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Byrd's sisters, Clara Taylor, could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Crump on Friday afternoon faxed The Lufkin Daily News several
documents, which included a copy of his sales receipt from the
Robinson Community Funeral Home in Jasper. The receipt listed
expenses totaling more than $2,400 for the bronze triune vault, a
service fee, as well as tents and chairs used at Byrd's graveside
service, which Crump paid for with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The faxed papers also included a thank you note from the funeral
home on a company letterhead, Crump's credit card bill for the
month of June 1998 and a typed thank you note from the Byrd family,
which Crump cited as the only time he ever heard from the family.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing of Byrd's brutal murder last summer, Crump said he
decided to help the family because the crime reminded him of a past
personal experience in which his cousin fell victim to a fatal hate
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'm going to do it to have a lasting memory inside of
me of all the things that I've seen in my life,'' he said. ``I did
it for James Byrd because I felt so bad, but I did it so the family
would always have a beautiful remembrance to always remember that.
I did it from the bottom of my heart. I didn't do it to tell
everybody the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Crump said U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno contributed the
remaining funeral expenses, however, no documentation of Ms. Reno's
contributions were available as of presstime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to go down in the history books,'' Crump said.
``If we don't clear it up, the lie is going to go down in the
history books. I'll be dead and gone, but those kids that are going
to be reading about this maybe when all of us are gone are going to
be reading a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
