<P>
   CULTURE (Coded e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-CURATORS (New York) _ For the first time in its 68-year
history, the Whitney Museum of American Art will be producing its
mammoth Biennial with a team of outside curators, representing
different regions of the country. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   RIDEAU-PROFILE (Angola, La.) _ Profile of Wilbert Rideau, a
Louisiana prison inmate and documentary filmmaker whose 23-year
fight for clemency may be jeopardized if his film, ``The Farm,''
wins an Academy Award this year. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   UPDIKE-COLUMN (Undated) _ John Updike inaugurates a new column,
``Writers on Writing,'' by having a celebrated character, Henry
Bech, interview the author. Or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   PODHORETZ-CONNECTIONS (Undated) _ Something has changed about
the nature of friendship on the intellectual scene during the last
30 years, as revealed in Norman Podhoretz's new memoir,
``Ex-Friends.'' The Connections column, by Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   JOHANSEN-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ David Johansen looks back to
the 1920s in an evening of blues and hillbilly songs. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW (Boston) _ The Wang Center for the
