<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-BLACK-MEDIA-AR     02-28 1757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-BLACK-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES(1,060)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHLEEN BLACK SHAKES UP THE CULTURE AT HEARST MAGAZINES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the closest you could get to a debutante party
in the mud-slinging, ego-bruising, advertising-hungry world of
magazine publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion: a dinner in early February hosted by the American
Jewish Committee in the ballroom of the New York Hilton, in honor
of Cathleen Black, the president of Hearst Magazines. But, alas,
all eyes were not on Ms. Black.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, heads swiveled toward Tina Brown and Ron Galotti, the
editor and publisher of Talk magazine, the Hearst Corp &UR; . &LR; 's newest
joint venture _ who sat, smiles firmly in place, at a table behind
Ms. Black, in their first public appearance as affianced partners
of the Hearst company. And a Hearst executive, noticing the
rubbernecking, nodded his head toward the pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're showing them off tonight,'' he said in the tone a proud
father might use to describe a glowing daughter. ``Our new gems.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Hearst executives were swooning over Ms. Brown
demonstrates the dynamic of what has become an emerging strategy at
Hearst: partnership. In this case, the muscle of Hearst coupled
with the ceaseless chattering chorus that seems to follow Ms. Brown
everywhere. At a time when magazine publishers, feeling a squeeze
at the newsstand, are wary of introducing new magazines unless they
are guaranteed sure things, the partnership formula seems to be
working for Hearst. The company's two other joint ventures, Smart
Money (which is published in conjunction with Dow Jones &AMP; Co &UR; . &LR; )
and Marie Claire (with Marie Claire Album, a French company) are
two of the strongest titles in the industry. With the Talk deal,
Hearst has attracted attention from the advertising community by
teaming up with two well-known magazine figures _ but only assuming
half the financial risk and half the estimated $50 million start-up
costs.
</P>
<P>
   But not all eyes will remain glued to Talk; many will be
monitoring Ms. Black's progress in changing the company to increase
advertising revenue. This decision to become a partner with Miramax
Films is a definite change of pace for Hearst. Hearst's
$1-billion-a-year magazine division _ which publishes 19 titles in
the United States, including Cosmopolitan, Popular Mechanics and
Good Housekeeping _ has long been considered the most middle of the
road, least daring of the four major magazine companies, as
compared with the stylish Conde Nast, the mainstream but
news-oriented Time Inc. and the scrappy, growing Hachette
Filipacchi Magazines. This decision adds one ingredient advertisers
love: glamour. And at half-price.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Black has changed the company slowly; in three years, she
has fired or reassigned only a handful of publishers and editors.
(By contrast, when Steven T. Florio, the chief executive of Conde
Nast, was named publisher of the company, the magazine division of
Advance Publications, he made dozens of personnel changes in the
first months.) She has concentrated on rehabilitating the magazine
company's image among advertisers, who had grumbled loudly in 1995
when Hearst cut its magazines' guaranteed circulation rates. (The
decision prompted many big advertisers to slash their spending for
advertising in Hearst magazines.)
</P>
<P>
   She has maintained Cosmopolitan's status as a market leader,
despite high-level editorial changes, and it routinely pummels its
arch rival, Conde Nast's Glamour _ now edited by former
Cosmopolitan editor Bonnie Fuller _ at the newsstand, a success
that must be sweet for Ms. Black. In December _ in another
advertiser-oriented move _ she restructured the company's magazines
into two groups, in an attempt to encourage advertisers to buy
pages in several magazines at once, in effect offering package
deals.
</P>
<P>
   An extroverted and aggressive seller, Ms. Black is known for her
close ties to the advertising industry, and sits on the boards of
two of the country's largest advertisers, the Coca-Cola Corp &UR; . &LR;  and
IBM. She said that to woo advertisers, brand names like Dow Jones
and Miramax, a unit of the Walt Disney Co &UR; . &LR; , are essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do a joint venture with anybody,'' she said, ``we want
them to be major corporations. Apart from the consumer audience,
your advertiser audience is saying, `Gee, Dow Jones and Hearst,' or
`Gee, Miramax and Hearst are behind this,' then they know we're
putting a lot of resources and talent and energy behind the product
that an individual entrepreneur just doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her company, Ms. Black is frill-free. A self-described
Catholic school girl from Chicago, she started her career at
Holiday magazine, then moved to New York magazine, becoming
advertising manager of Ms. Magazine when it was founded by Gloria
Steinem in 1972. (``It was real lick-your-own-envelopes-at-midnight
work,'' she said.) She was named publisher of New York in 1979, but
made her mark at USA Today as publisher in the 1980s by smartening
it up in the eyes of advertisers wary of a newspaper nicknamed
``McPaper.'' In 1991, she became president of the Newspaper
Association of America and then moved to Hearst as president of the
magazine division in January 1996. (Her husband, Tom Harvey, is a
lawyer; they have two children, a dog, and a country house in
Connecticut.)
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is a privately held company, and Ms. Black will not
discuss numbers, even good ones, choosing instead to highlight the
successes of Smart Money and Cosmopolitan. In an effort to build on
Cosmopolitan's growth and the popularity of magazines for
teen-agers, Cosmopolitan plans to test a title aimed at teen-age
girls in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But onlookers say Hearst still is not sufficiently focused on
fresh editorial product. One advertising agency media director who
works with Hearst and spoke on the condition of anonymity said:
``Nothing's really happened since she's gotten there. At Conde
Nast, they love to toss the thing around. You get the sense that
they're constantly stirring the pot. At Hearst, it still feels
status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Fennell, the chief operating officer at Hachette
Filipacchi, who has worked with several editors who are now at
Hearst, said that Ms. Black had stepped into an insider culture.
``Hearst used to be a country-club, old-boy environment,'' Fennell
said. ``For Cathie to step in at the level she did and make the
changes she did, even if they are not enormous ones, was a dramatic
move.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Former Hearst editors say the company's culture is not directed
toward creative tinkering. ``At Conde Nast, editors are treated
like entertainment impresarios. At Hearst, they're expected to put
on green eyeshades and sign expense vouchers from the photo
department,'' said Randall Rothenberg, an editor at Wired, which is
owned by Conde Nast, and a former executive editor at Esquire,
which is owned by Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Black sees no conflict between the bottom line and
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an incredible group of lively, energetic, talented
editors here, who break new ground every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Talk deal is a change of tactics for Hearst, it
signals a shift for the magazine industry in general as more
companies move toward joint ventures in a publishing economy that
feels increasingly unsure. Among other problems, magazine newsstand
sales are suffering. And editors worry about consumers who spend
more time surfing the World Wide Web than curling up with their
favorite magazine, a trend that is ominously called ``usage
erosion'' in the industry. The general interest category that Talk
is entering is already crowded, with advertisers increasingly drawn
to niche publications.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in this tenuous market there is only room for sure
things and joint ventures. Later this year, Smart Money will test
what could become yet another Hearst joint venture, a magazine
aimed at parents concerned with their children's financial futures.
</P>
<P>
   E. Daniel Capell, an authority on magazine circulation and the
editor of Capell's Circulation Report, said that joint ventures are
very appealing, especially to a company like Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst has all these other arms available: subscription
fulfillment, distribution, circulation, so that makes it very easy
to do joint ventures,'' he said. ``The amount of money required to
launch a new magazine is so big and you have so much at risk, that
when you can split the risk it makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hearst had time to mull the deal, because the Talk team
approached both Time Inc., which is part of Time Warner Inc., and
Hachette Filipacchi, a unit of the Lagardere Group, first. But Time
executives balked because they believed that Ms. Brown had never
run a profitable magazine in the United States. At Hachette,
executives simply did not want to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   In an intriguing hint of that much-overused term, synergy, Talk
may be able to offer unprecedented package deals to advertisers,
because its other corporate parent is Disney's Miramax. Galotti has
said that advertised products may even get placement in Miramax
films. Say, for example, Prada buys 50 pages of ads, does that mean
that Gwyneth Paltrow will wear Prada loafers and tote a Prada
handbag in a Miramax film?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to help people market products to consumers
whatever way we can,'' Galotti said. ``If there's an opportunity to
work with them that way, then we will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hearst editors seem to bear no ill will against the new
venture and the $25 million Ms. Black will sink into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad she's made Hearst give her the resources to class
up the joint,'' said one Hearst editor, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``And that's part of the reason she wanted Talk. She
has realized that there is an upside to pursuing glamorous things.
It gets advertisers excited.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, advertisers await their invitations to the
launch party, the all-important soiree at which guests are plied
with cocktails and enjoy solicitous bowing and scraping by the
publisher. Will it be held at the Four Seasons? Nobu? Or in London?
Will there be many supermodels in attendance? Galotti said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do something more low key,'' he said. ``How about a
cookout?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
