<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PODHORETZ-CONNECTIONS     02-28 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PODHORETZ-CONNECTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF ENEMIES, THE WORST OF FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN 
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norman Podhoretz is not one of my ex-friends. Over
the years, in many wide-ranging conversations, we have not had any
stormy arguments. Though I have written for Commentary, which he
edited for 35 years, I never pulled a piece from the magazine in
outrage. I have never attacked him in print or conversation. We
have never wrestled over issues involving anti-Communism,
anti-anti-Communism or anti-anti-anti- Communism. We don't avoid
each other at parties.
</P>
<P>
   But this shows the serious limits of our friendship because
there are probably few friends of his who have not engaged in some
of these activities, which makes them very similar to some of the
ex-friends he describes in his new memoir, ``Ex-Friends'' (Free
Press). So hotly contested is he as a political and intellectual
figure that simply the declaration of friendship or ex-friendship
with him has tended to be viewed in some circles as a declaration
of war.
</P>
<P>
   I mention all this because something has changed about the
nature of friendship on the intellectual scene during the last 30
years. Friendship now tends to be less fractious and enmity more
ruthless. Podhoretz focuses in his book on the ways in which his
positions on various issues in the 1960s and 70s caused tensions
with such friends as Norman Mailer, Hannah Arendt, Lillian Hellman
and Lionel and Diana Trilling. He even describes how opposition
could lead to a peculiar form of closeness, as when he served as a
nemesis to Allen Ginsberg.
</P>
<P>
   But all these relationships were formed in an intellectual and
cultural universe far different from the one in which we now dwell.
They involved the close-knit group of intellectuals that gathered
around such publications as Commentary and Partisan Review in the
decades before the 1960s counterculture hit its stride. Murray
Kempton called that group the Family; Podhoretz made the term
common parlance. The Family, though, was itself riven with
controversies and jealousies. At old Family parties, Podhoretz
points out, one of the passions was for ``gossiping with the
wittiest possible malice about anyone who had the misfortune not to
be present or to be out of earshot in another part of the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Enmities may have been more extreme versions of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the Family romance. I would guess that nearly
every intellectual who began to come of age in the 1970s read
Podhoretz's 1967 autobiography, ``Making It,'' assuming that, in
some way, the harsh self-critical glare of Family life lay waiting
in the wings. But by then, as Podhoretz points out, the Family was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the varied intellectual circles I occasionally sample,
friendship is far less aggressive and enmity far more absolute.
Circles of acquaintance seem circumscribed by shared premises about
culture and politics. Internal disagreements tend to be muted;
premises are taken for granted; a sense of beleaguered opposition
to external forces is common.
</P>
<P>
   This is not completely new, of course. There were lines in the
sand in earlier eras. Podhoretz, for example, was surprised to meet
Lillian Hellman at a party at Lionel and Diana Trillings', because
Hellman had been Stalinist in her views and the Trillings were
liberal anti-Communists. I doubt whether many of the group
Podhoretz calls ``country club Republicans'' ever showed up at the
left-leaning Family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   But within the Family the range of disagreement was often
startlingly combative. Not even Philip Rahv and William Phillips,
the editors of Partisan Review, could be counted on to be in
alignment. Podhoretz's writings from the late 1950s embodied
opposing trends in themselves. His first book of literary
criticism, ``Doings and Undoings,'' for example, contains traces of
radicalism (urging Saul Bellow, for example, to start to take on
the ``institutions'' of American life) as well as conservatism
(attacking, for instance, the low intellectual standards of the
``Beat'' writers and ``their poisonous glorification of the
adolescent in American popular culture'').
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Family began to break apart in the late 1960s,
there was still an extraordinary assemblage of disparate figures
finding common cause in the pages of Commentary, ranging from
Irving Howe and Paul Goodman to Irving Kristol and Hilton Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to this contentious assemblage?
</P>
<P>
   Many suggestions have been offered in recent years: The change
in the nature of political confrontation in the 1960s, the leftward
movement of liberalism, the rightward movement of neo-conservatism.
Podhoretz adds another: Family members needed one another. They saw
themselves as more brilliant, more subtle, more visionary than the
American populace, government politicians or university scholars.
``Who else,'' Podhoretz writes, ``could properly understand the
things they were writing and saying and the ways in which they were
writing and saying them?''
</P>
<P>
   But after the late 1960s they no longer wrote solely for one
another. They dreamed of wider influence. Academe became more
powerful. ``Policy'' intellectuals eventually settled into
Washington, and higher fees were offered by magazines like The New
Yorker or even Vanity Fair. There was a vast assimilation of Family
life into American culture.
</P>
<P>
   This weakened clan allegiance, but for some time a unifying
sentiment remained. Lionel Trilling called it ``adversarial'' and,
when not directed at American power, it tended to be opposed to the
American middle-class and middle-brow culture.
</P>
<P>
   Podhoretz suggests that ``Making It'' inspired such animus among
Family members because it was an assault on one of their core
notions. It celebrated the bourgeois aspects of intellectual life _
ambition for success, fame, power _ and the values that
intellectuals and the wider liberal culture considered vulgar and
demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   But over time even scorn of the middle class became one of the
defining characteristics of the middle class. Meanwhile the idea of
middle brow weakened under the impact of popular culture. In the
1950s most intellectuals shared a devotion to the highest
achievements of art, music and literature; in the 1980s many
writers were arguing that such distinctions had little meaning.
</P>
<P>
   So the social and intellectual bonds loosened. At the same time,
the life-and-death issues that define Family life metastasized.
Compare the three or four decisive responses to Communism in the
1950s with the opposing positions that began to multiply in the
1960s over race, culture and foreign policy. One of the most
divisive issues now among intellectuals may be whether one agrees
with Podhoretz about the existence of a ``regnant leftist culture''
and its effects.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate it is now far more comfortable to use premises to
define friendships than to use friendships to explore premises. We
have a Balkanized politics to match our Balkanized culture. So
friendships become more like alliances and enmity makes argument
seem futile. Podhoretz is elegiac, missing the Family and honoring
it, despite its errors and frenzies. I never knew Family life, but
I'm not about to disagree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
