<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH-MEDIA-750&AMP;ADD     02-28 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-MEDIA-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW OFFENSIVE IN BRITAIN'S WAR OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Are interviewers on British television and radio
programs too rude? Are British newspapers too obsessed with trivia?
Are reporters irresponsible scandal-mongers who overlook important
policy questions?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, would be the answer if you asked the Labor government,
which has had an extraordinarily rocky relationship with the news
media here since it came to power on a tidal wave of good will
nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the government's complaints are the same as those
frequently leveled against the American press. But in Britain,
where there is no sense of open government or of the public's right
to know, the government has had little compunction about openly
attacking the news media when it does not like the way it is being
covered.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, relations between the two sides took a turn for
the worse when The Sunday Telegraph published an article about a
leaked government-sponsored report on racism and the police.
Furious that his carefully laid plans to release the report in its
own time had been so badly thwarted, the home secretary, Jack
Straw, persuaded a judge to issue an injunction forcing the
newspaper _ which had already printed and shipped off some 290,000
early edition copies _ to remove the article from later editions.
Though Straw was forced, embarrassingly, to back down the next day,
the move stirred up the ire of the news media yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Straw's reaction was not unusual in a country where there is no
American-style tradition of freedom of the press, and where the
judiciary is temperamentally inclined to support the government in
disputes with the news media. And it was not a surprise, said
reporters and editors, who have become used to the Labor
government's efforts to manage the news and to its reluctance to
pursue media-friendly legislation it once supported, like a freedom
of information bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an extremely controlling bunch,'' said Alan
Rusbridger, the editor of The Guardian, a liberal-leaning
newspaper. ``They are adept at manipulating the press, so when
something like this happens, their reaction is to suppress and
control. They went right over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   How did things get to this point?
</P>
<P>
   Elected by an overwhelming majority in 1997, the Labor Party
soon seemed to squander much of its built-in advantage with the
news media, pursuing a series of highly public disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were particularly irked by what they saw as rough
treatment from BBC interviewers, who tend to be far more combative
and aggressive than their American counterparts. In 1997, for
instance, the Labor Party protested after Harriet Harman, then the
social security secretary, underwent a particularly rough interview
on the ``Today'' radio program.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion of government proposals to cut welfare benefits
to single mothers, John Humphrys, the program's take-no-prisoners
interviewer, asked the same question 13 times in an increasingly
irritated way. Afterward, the party's chief media spokesman, David
Hill, complained bitterly about ``the John Humphrys problem'' and
threatened to withdraw the party's cooperation from ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Humphrys interrupted so much that she was never permitted
to develop a single answer,'' Hill said. The BBC responded that one
of Ms. Harman's answers had, in fact, lasted a full minute, and
argued that Humphrys was simply ``seeking a direct answer to a
simple question'' about benefit cuts. ``I thought the encounter
demonstrated John's characteristic strengths,'' said Jon Barton,
the editor of ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight took another turn last summer, when Alastair Campbell,
the government's chief spokesman, attacked the notion that Labor
officials seem reluctant to submit to radio and television
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Most government officials, Campbell said, hate the way they are
treated by BBC interviewers like Jeremy Paxman, one of the hosts of
``Newsnight,'' a late-night show that is similar to ABC's
``Nightline.'' Paxman, who has a biting intellect and a
super-confident manner that many feel borders on arrogance, is
known for his ability to ``kebab'' guests when they dodge or
waffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one minister said to me recently when I tried to get him to
appear on the program, `What is the point of traipsing out late at
night so that Jeremy can try to persuade the public that I'm
actually some kind of criminal?' '' Campbell said in a letter to
The Times of London.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But many journalists say that in the absence of a strong
Conservative Party _ Tony Blair, the prime minister, holds an
overwhelming majority in Parliament and is subject to very little
in the way of serious opposition _ it is up to the news media to
ask the tough questions. ``There are two sides to every story, and
no one has a monopoly on the truth,'' Paxman said. ``There are
those in government who cannot see the need to explain themselves
to the public. You can see their point. `What's in it for me?' as
one minister put it to me when I suggested he might like to explain
a policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Campbell went on the attack again. In a
speech in London, he denounced what he called the news media's
tendency to report on ``scandal, gossip, personality clashes, the
price of a Concorde trip'' at the expense of things like jobs,
transportation policy and education.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their disillusionment at the failure of the BBC ``to
let democratic politicians speak for themselves,'' Campbell said,
government officials were more likely to appear on ``soft''
interview shows and to bypass the usual media outlets for things
like regional newspapers and ``the women's media.''
</P>
<P>
   The mainstream news media were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop trying to tell us how to do our jobs,'' Humphrys, the
``Today'' host, said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Rawnsley, a political columnist for The Observer of
London, said that in Campbell's dream world, there would be ``one
television channel, one newspaper and one radio station'' _ all run
by the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
