<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-TERM-LIMITS01     02-28 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-TERM-LIMITS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Term limits set to rattle politics in Florida
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Tuesday, March 6, 2001, some are convinced,
is the day Florida politics goes to the dogs: decency and
statesmanship disappear, with all power shifting to unelected staff
and hired-gun lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   No, others argue with equal passion, the morning of March 6 will
bring a breath of fresh air, an end to a system that rewarded
mediocrity and staying power over talent and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever side is correct, one thing is certain. March 6, the
first day of that term's new legislative session, will bring a new
face to Florida politics: at least 54 new faces in a House of 120
members, at least 11 freshmen in the 40-member Senate, as ``term
limits,'' the overwhelming will of Florida's electorate, finally
take their toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock strikes 12 and everybody goes home,'' said
Jacksonville's Jim King, who recently left a House seat doomed to
expire in another year to jump at a newly opened spot in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   King's departure is only slightly ahead of the wave, as six
dozen of his colleagues likewise must choose between finding
another position to run for or retiring from politics altogether.
Indeed, over the next decade, term limits will sweep both chambers
clean of every single member currently there.
</P>
<P>
   And as senior members go, so will the level of seniority. In
past years the elder members of each chamber typically have served
16, 18, even 20 years. Starting in 2001, the most senior House
members will have served but six.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, with its staggered four-year terms in districts
redrawn every decade, will always have half its members permitted
to serve a total of 10 years. And members elected in out-of-cycle
special elections will likewise be eligible to serve just under 10
years in the House and just under 12 years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Those exceptions notwithstanding, the reduction in seniority in
both chambers is dramatic. Seniority of the average House member
will drop from 4.9 years this year to _ if all eligible incumbents
run and win; historically, not a bad assumption _ 1.9 years. In the
Senate, the number drops from 6.5 years to 3.8.
</P>
<P>
   Not all ``term-limited'' legislators, of course, are willing to
step down so easily. A pair of perennial senators, Gainesville's
George Kirkpatrick and Quincy's Pat Thomas, as well as two-term
colleague Jim Hargrett, of Tampa, hope to overturn the
constitutional amendment through a lawsuit filed by some of their
constituents. Oral arguments before the Florida Supreme Court are
scheduled for early this summer, with a decision expected this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Sen. Jim Scott, R-Fort Lauderdale, plan to raise
money and have made it plain to those who would replace them that
they aren't giving up just yet, in case the court should rule in
their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think eight years is not enough time for someone to come up,
learn the process and leave,'' Scott said, adding that many of his
constituents are urging him to try and stay.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature's longest serving member, Sen. W.D. Childers,
R-Pensacola, said he isn't waiting on the court for anything. He's
definitely running: as a write-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they got to do is write `W.D.' It's like a literacy
test,'' Childers said. ``If they can't do that, I don't need their
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding those few hoping to undo or outmaneuver the 1992
mandate, though, most legislators have come to accept the notion of
leaving whatever office they currently hold and planning for their
next.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings about another interesting side effect of limiting
lawmakers' and Cabinet members' terms: The intense competition
among legislators for an ever fewer number of seats available at
the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Dudley, two years away from being forced from his Fort
Myers Senate seat, decided to try to knock off incumbent Attorney
General Bob Butterworth. Two fellow Republican House members fought
to replace him. Sen. Burt Saunders won; former House member Ralph
Livingston is out of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Pruitt and Rep. Sharon Merchant, also both Republicans,
are also both campaigning hard for the seat held by Sen. William
``Doc'' Myers, R-Hobe Sound. King even abandoned the coveted
chairmanship of the House budget committee to run for the vacated
Senate seat of Bill Bankhead rather than sit out two years and run
against an incumbent for it in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The departing members take with them their institutional
knowledge, the years of seeing why some approaches to things work
while others do not. ``Knowing how to get something done is as
important, almost, as knowing what's a good thing to get done,''
said King, who was and is, nonetheless, a term-limits supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a society without any grandparents,''
complained term-limit opponent Rep. Lois Frankel, a West Palm Beach
Democrat who, thanks to a gap in her 10 years in the House, will be
spared the term limit ax for two more years. ``It's very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that argument that ``good government'' groups like the
League of Women Voters and Common Cause unsuccessfully used against
the measure in 1992. Big contributors who provide the bulk of
campaign money will figure even more prominently in determining who
among a host of inexperienced candidates will win, said Common
Cause of Florida director Sally Spener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special interest groups will be able to pick the next guy, or
gal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, she said, whatever power given up long-serving
legislators will most likely devolve to the legislative staff and
the lobbying corps.
</P>
<P>
   Term-limit supporters counter simply by pointing to how the
legislature works today: Lobbyists already write most bills and
most amendments, with staff performing the analyses and legislators
most of the time voting on bills and amendments that they have
never read.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Warner, who will quit his House seat this summer for a
job in Butterworth's office rather than be forced out the following
fall, remembers when he came to the House in 1992. ``Health-care
lobbyists were writing all the health-care bills, with staff,'' he
said. ``Members weren't writing those bills. It's up to the members
to pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Feeney, the first likely beneficiary of term limits,
said Warner is right, to a degree, but thinks term-limit opponents
do make a point, particularly on complicated legislation involving
telecommunications or insurance. ``There'll be fewer legislators
able to know what a lobbyist is up to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney, who interrupted his legislative service for two years in
1994 to become Jeb Bush's running mate in his first run for
governor, is likely to become the first House speaker in the term
limit era. Had he not left the chamber five years ago, he, like
nearly half of his colleagues, would have been forced to retire in
2000. Yet his four years of experience prior to leaving give him an
advantage seeking the speakership over those elected for the first
time in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He said the chamber's leadership cadre will potentially suffer
the most under term limits. Where under the old system would-be
speakers and budget chairman had many terms to develop the
expertise and friendships to work with a large, diverse body, the
new era will give House members only six years before they take the
reins. The likely Republican candidate for speaker in 2002, Plant
City Rep. Johnnie Byrd, came to the House just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Senate, which traditionally has been
filled with former House members, will probably continue in that
regard, so that many if not most new senators will have six or
eight years of experience in the House, Feeney said.
</P>
<P>
   The ascension of Byrd and Feeney, of course, presumes that
Republican control of the House, now a comfortable 73-47 majority,
will be able to survive an election with at least 54 open seats _
traditionally seen as wild cards.
</P>
<P>
   And it is that potential for suddenly and radically
reapportioning the balance of power that Frankel, who would become
speaker should her Democrats win back 14 seats next year, sees as
term limits' only saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits are terrible, unless of course they let the
Democrats come back to power,'' she quipped. ``In that case, I
think they're great.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
