<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIDEAU-PROFILE-ART-2T     02-28 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDEAU-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(1,100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A LIFER, OSCAR NIGHT MAY OFFER FAME BUT LITTLE HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGOLA, La. _ By any measure, Wilbert Rideau has compiled an
impressive resume during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist and editor, he has been honored with some of the
profession's most coveted prizes, including the George Polk Award
and the Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award. A collection of his
reporting was published n 1992 and is now in its seventh printing.
</P>
<P>
   When he diversified into broadcast journalism, National Public
Radio eagerly retained his services. Now he has branched out into
film making, and only his second work, ``The Farm,'' has been named
the best documentary of 1998 by several groups, including the
National Society of Film Critics. Earlier this month, it became one
of five movies nominated for the Oscar for best documentary
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Rideau touches, it seems, turns to gold.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, that is, except for the iron bars surrounding his
dormitory at the Louisiana State Penitentiary here, where Rideau
has entered the 38th year of a life sentence for one of the most
vicious murders ever committed in Calcasieu Parish.
</P>
<P>
   While Liz Garbus and Jonathan Stack, the New York-based
producers and directors of ``The Farm: Angola U.S.A.,'' will join
the glitterati in their tuxedos and sequined gowns at the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles on March 21, Rideau (pronounced
REE-doh) plans to watch the broadcast, in his prison denims, from
the cluttered office of The Angolite, the prison magazine he has
edited since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau, 57, is credited as the co-director of the film, and he
is acknowledged by all involved as the guiding spirit of its
humanizing, and yet dispassionate, portrayal of life within one of
America's most infamous prisons. Nonetheless, Rideau realizes that
if the film wins an Academy Award, it will make little difference
in his daily routine, and may complicate his 23-year crusade to
gain clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Oscar wouldn't alter my existence one iota,'' he said in an
interview in the Angolite office. ``The one thing about winning
awards when you're in prison is that it keeps everything in
perspective for you.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory on Oscar night might blast Rideau, already one of
America's most celebrated inmates, into a new stratosphere of fame.
But unlike those actors and directors whose currency inflates with
each gold statuette, Rideau has found that prominence is not his
friend.
</P>
<P>
   While Louisiana governors have commuted hundreds of life
sentences over the years, including those of a number of
first-degree murderers with lesser records of rehabilitation,
Rideau has been repeatedly denied clemency. On three occasions
between 1984 and 1991, the state's pardon board recommended that
Rideau be freed, only to have governors reject the advice of their
own appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau and his considerable band of supporters argue that he is,
in essence, a political prisoner. In the current tough-on-crime
climate, which seems to value punishment far more than
rehabilitation, Rideau maintains that he has become a victim of his
own celebrity, an inmate so conspicuous that no governor can afford
to release him.
</P>
<P>
   If he had done his time quietly, without ambition or
achievement, he would have been freed long ago, Rideau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' he said. ``It has worked for everybody
else. It has worked for all the lifers of my generation. It worked
for everybody who was on death row with me the day I got there.
What distinguishes me from them? It's my prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   The recurring theme of Rideau's work, both in print and on film,
has been the persistence of hope in a place that would seem to
defeat it. In ``The Farm,'' so named because Angola is an
18,000-acre former plantation where the crops are now tended by
inmates rather than slaves, that theme is explored through the
stories of six prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Because Academy Award rules specify that only two names can be
attached to each documentary, Rideau is not cited in the
nomination. But both Ms. Garbus and Stack, who made an earlier film
with Rideau about an execution at Angola, praise their colleague as
an invaluable, if sometimes difficult, collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilbert is really the genesis of the film,'' Ms. Garbus said.
``What has made `The Farm' successful is that we were able to
achieve some kind of truth that was hard to achieve by outsiders.
And that is because of Wilbert.''
</P>
<P>
   Rideau, a school dropout and self-taught writer who earns 20
cents an hour as editor of The Angolite, is presumably one of the
few inmates in the United States with his own business cards. Fit
and trim with a bushy mustache , he works in an office with
computers purchased with proceeds from inmate enterprises like
Angola's annual rodeo. He is reasonably free to roam the main
inmate housing complex and to use the Angolite's telephones to
receive calls from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Angola, which is bordered on three sides by the Mississippi
River, was once considered the most violent prison in the country.
In an effort to relieve inmate tensions by giving them a voice,
prison officials began allowing The Angolite to publish without
censorship in the mid-1970s. Over the years, it has thoughtfully
addressed topics like homosexual rape and prison hospital
conditions, and its revelations have led to reforms that make
Angola a safer place today.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau ranks fifth out of Angola's 2,324 murderers in length of
imprisonment, and two of those with longer tenure committed murders
while incarcerated. By contrast, Rideau has been written up for one
infraction in 38 years, that coming in 1976 when he took a bottle
of Wite-Out from the Angolite office back to his dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``His record has been impeccable,'' said N. Burl Cain, Angola's
warden. ``From what I know of Wilbert here and how he's done his
time, sure, I would vote to let him go. But I don't know the crime.
And for the victim, there's no appeal from the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   His continued imprisonment, Rideau contends, reflects a betrayal
of American ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think that in America you would reward productivity
and initiative as opposed to punishing it,'' he said. Instead, he
said, his example demonstrates that inmates seeking freedom should
not draw attention to themselves. ``Forget all that rhetoric about
making amends and trying to make a contribution and all that,'' he
said. ``It's going to come at great cost to you, especially if you
do good, because you can do too good. And that shouldn't be so.
Nobody in this country or this world should ever be able to do too
good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In Calcasieu Parish, near the Texas line, Rideau's victims and
the prosecutors who put him away retch at such moralizing.
</P>
<P>
   What they recall about Rideau, in detail that has not faded over
four decades, is that he walked into a Gulf National Bank branch in
Lake Charles as it was closing on Feb. 16, 1961. He forced the
manager at gunpoint to fill a suitcase with $14,000 and ordered the
manager and two tellers into a car. Rideau, who had turned 19 and
had no prior record, worked in a nearby fabric shop and knew all
three employees.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction ended in a swampy area outside of town where
Rideau ordered the three out of the car, lined them up and shot
them one by one, said Frank Salter, the former district attorney
who prosecuted the case. The branch manager, J.H. Hickman, stumbled
into the bayou and escaped. One of the tellers, Dora McCain, was
shot in the neck and played dead, even as Rideau kicked her
repeatedly to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   The other teller, Julia Ferguson, begged for her life, reminding
Rideau that she took care of her father. ``Wilbert, think of my
poor daddy,'' she said. ``What will he do without me?'' Brandishing
a hunting knife, Rideau responded, ``Don't worry, this will be
quick and cool.'' He then stabbed her in the heart and slit her
throat. Ms. Ferguson died, but Hickman and Ms. McCain survived.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Bryant, the current District Attorney in Calcasieu Parish,
maintains that Rideau has received more clemency than he deserves.
He was tried three times _ the first two convictions were reversed,
one because of excessive pretrial publicity and one because of
improper jury selection _ and each time he was sentenced to death.
But in 1972, the U. S. Supreme Court invalidated the death penalty,
and after more than a decade of confinement Rideau was released
from death row and given a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that he received his commutation in 1972,'' Bryant
said. ``He's very fortunate to be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rideau signed a confession shortly after his arrest, and has
never denied responsibility for the crimes. The argument he makes
is one of equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the first to point out, I've got no right to
freedom,'' he said. ``But the fact of the matter is when you are
letting everybody else out, isn't it wrong to single one guy out
and keep him in when his qualifications probably exceed all the
rest of them?'' He added: ``One guy that got out of here killed
four people. He sends me Christmas cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda LaBranche, a coordinator of the Rideau Project, which is
affiliated with the Twomey Center for Peace Through Justice at
Loyola University in New Orleans, found that nearly 700 clemencies
have been granted to Louisiana murderers during Rideau's 38 years
in prison. Of the 31 murderers sent to Angola in 1962 with
sentences of either death or life in prison, all but Rideau have
gained their freedom through either clemency or court reversals,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Louisiana lifers once were paroled routinely after 10{
years, a life sentence today means just that. These days, the only
avenues for hope for Rideau and the 2,875 other lifers at Angola
are appeals to the courts for reversals and to governors for
commutations.
</P>
<P>
   Jaymee O. Burleigh, a spokeswoman for the Louisiana Board of
Pardons, which was created in 1975, said that governors have signed
2,707 commutations during the board's existence. Of those, 458 were
granted to inmates serving life sentences, including 21
first-degree murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Edwin W. Edwards, who commuted scores of murder
sentences, has said he promised Ms. McCain, one of Rideau's victim,
that he would not release him as long as she objected. Former Gov.
Buddy Roemer, who twice rejected Rideau's appeals for clemency,
said he too was persuaded by the nature of the crime and the pleas
of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau, he said, is ``just hiding behind'' the argument that
politics played a role. ``Anytime you let somebody go, it's going
to be in the newspaper,'' Roemer said. ``Now admittedly, with him
it might be with a picture above the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's current governor, Mike Foster, has not commuted any
sentences during his three years in office and is not likely to
grant relief for violent offenders, said Cheney C. Joseph, his
executive counsel.
</P>
<P>
   That has led Rideau to place his faith in the courts, where he
is challenging the racial composition and selection process of the
grand jury that indicted him. A federal magistrate recommended in
1997 that his conviction be overturned, but Judge Frank Polozola of
U.S. District Court has yet to rule.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rideau is considering his next project. Perhaps
he will write an autobiography. Perhaps he will make a film about
religion behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Warden Cain is considering how an Academy Award should be
celebrated at a maximum security prison. ``I tell you what,'' he
said, ``if we win, the next day we're going to have Cokes on the
yard for all the inmates. We're going to have a party, at least as
much as you can have a party in prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
