<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURNITURE AND WEAKNESSES: OUR FAMILY TRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A daughter is relocating to more spacious lodgings and is
desperate for furniture to fill the place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It means for us, the parents, an opportunity to unload some
things we no longer need. There's even a chance that, in time, I
might once again have use of the garage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the pieces we let go was a low, daybed kind of affair that
I've always heard spoken of as the fainting couch. In my memory, no
one around here has ever fainted. But nevertheless that's what it's
been called: the fainting couch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My wife brought this curiosity to our marriage, along with her
white cat, and it served as our first sofa. There's no knowing how
many friends it may have cost us. For while it would be ideal for
use by anyone who has just lost consciousness, it's an agony to sit
upon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Either you perch on the front edge, without any support for your
back. Or it can be placed against a wall. But then, if people of
normal height are to take advantage of the wall's support, they
must sit with their legs thrust out straight before them, like
infants in a highchair or dolls on a shelf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In later years _ the last 25 or so _ it has been in an upstairs
back room that briefly was my writing place, but then evolved into
a catch-all storage area. No sooner had the thing been carted away
than my wife announced plans for the space thus liberated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to bring the sewing machine up from the basement,''
she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If we hadn't already given away the fainting couch, I might have
used it right then! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What in heaven's name for?'' I screeched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sewing machine is of the treadle kind, manufactured by the
Singer company and very popular 50 or 100 years ago, but found now
only in the thatched huts and sweatshops of Third World countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or in basements like ours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want that upstairs?'' I demanded to know. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' she said defiantly. ``I might want to sew.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But you hate sewing!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a girlhood project _ for home economics class, it must have
been _ she set out to make some simple garment, but ripped out
seams and restitched them so many times that, before she could
finish it, the fabric just disintegrated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has many gifts, but sewing is not among them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're about as likely to use that machine as I am to take up
plumbing,'' I said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She considered that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``I'm more likely.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was, of course, alluding to the drippy bathroom faucet,
about which I once recklessly observed that all it needed was a new
washer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From that moment, hardly a day has passed when she has not asked
if I intend to replace the faucet washer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have any washers on hand,'' I tell her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you'll have to get one, won't you. Probably at the
hardware store.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``First I'll have to find out the size.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You could measure the old one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, and I'll do it, too,'' I tell her. ``One of these
days.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I haven't any clear notion at all about how one
goes about changing a faucet washer. Or if the washers come in
different sizes. Or if that model faucet even has one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm bluffing _ just as she's bluffing about taking up sewing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You sometimes hear that marriage is two people combining their
strengths. But we've come together, merging our baggage of
weaknesses, and somehow we've made a life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
