<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT LOOKS TO BE AN OFF YEAR FOR TAX RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taxpayers become orphans in nonelection years, which probably
means significant tax cuts aren't likely in '99. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seem dead set against major relief, preferring to
push the claim that anticipated budget surpluses should be used to
``save'' Social Security. It's a con game, to be sure, but a
complex enough scam to gull most average Americans. A standard line
being used to fend off tax-cutters is tax cuts would be reckless. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, lick their wounds as polls show they
lost ground politically from their efforts to oust the president.
There is talk in GOP circles of mounting a tax-relief effort, but
it seems merely talk without much passion for really doing it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, unless a presidential hopeful in the Reagan mold
happens along to champion the taxpayer cause, the future of working
Americans looks bleak indeed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How bleak? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Current estimates put total federal revenues during the first
decade of the next century at $22 trillion. Somewhat more than 10
percent of the income is forecast to be in excess of what Uncle Sam
will spend. If projections are correct, it will equate to an
average cumulative overpayment of $27,000 by each taxpaying
household, according to an analysis by the Citizens for a Sound
Economy Foundation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The key characterization here is ``overpayment,'' because it's a
reminder that the money belongs in the first instance to the
taxpayers. Unfortunately, those who would keep the money in
Washington have become increasingly successful in selling the
notion that they should have carte blanche dibs on all paychecks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If taxpayers understood how heavy their aggregate burden has
become, there might be more grass-roots support for tax-relief
champions in Washington. Tax revenues during fiscal year 2000 are
forecast to be 20.7 percent of the Gross Domestic Product, which is
the value of all economic output. As a share of GDP, this would be
almost as much as the federal government spent in the last full
year of World War II, when America was fighting for its very
existence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Washington takes nearly as much as it needed during
the darkest days of the gravest threat ever mounted to this
country's existence. This is happening despite the fact that the
country is in the midst of the longest peacetime economic expansion
in its history and perhaps the greatest period of sustained overall
prosperity ever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans faced similar depredations at Washington's hands in
the 1970s, when bad policy created inflation that propelled workers
into ever higher tax brackets that allowed government to profit
from its own mistakes at taxpayer expense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things obviously are much improved, but it should be remembered
that it took some of the worst economic times in history to
convince Americans to make the political moves that would improve
their economic situation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What the '70s and '90s do have in common is a federal government
ignoring the interests of those whose labor and income make all
things possible and acting instead as though all such hard-earned
tax money belongs to the state. When that idea becomes politically
acceptable enough to dominate fiscal policy, working folk are
reduced to serfdom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
