<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKBINDER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKBINDER'S THRIVING BUSINESS IS WORTH A BOOK OF ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELDEN, Kan. _ In any given year, about 100,000 books move in
and out of tiny Selden in northwest Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody reads them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a word,'' said Richard Koerperich, owner of Selden's
biggest business, Koerperich Bookbinders, one of only 34 such
enterprises in the nation certified by the American Library
Association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people here, say at lunch, looking through books,''
and the books are ``going to get messed up,'' Koerperich said.
``That's not what we're in business for.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company binds all sorts of books _ law books, town and
county histories, student theses, family genealogical works, high
school yearbooks, old Zane Grey yarns, scientific treatises, back
issues of cattle breed publications, even self-published novels and
books of poetry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, an occasional life-and-death situation has
resulted from those last two categories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had rush orders,'' Koerperich said. ``Some old person's
worked on a novel or a book of poetry for years. And it's finally
done, and they bring it to us. Then they take sick. They're
literally on their death bed. And what is that one thing they want
more than anything? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see their book between its covers before they
die. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not kidding. That's happened more than once, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, most of the work is rarely that intense. The
majority of the work is the binding of new books and the mundane
restoration of library and law books and schoolbooks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those latter volumes, what's between the covers is still
fine. But the outside is frayed, dog-eared, beat up _ probably the
result of too many library loans, innumerable legal consultations
or the busy fingers of bored youngsters, who figure what's inside
the spine of a book is far more interesting than any of the words
on its pages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The books come from all over the United States and arrive in
Selden _ all of 240 souls about 25 miles from Colby _ to be sewn,
trimmed, cut, edged and stamped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A tiny sign outside the front door of what once was a bank and a
liquor store before it became a bookbindery gives the only clue as
to what's inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Koerperich doesn't advertise. His business is all by word of
mouth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, he said, just a few years ago, the word around was that
his business and others like it were albatrosses. Computers and
video screens, the big brains predicted, would send books the way
of the great auk and along with it, the bookbinding business. Who,
the thinking went, would look at a book instead of a video screen?
Or ever want to rebind one? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hasn't happened, said Koerperich. Business is booming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People will always want books,'' he said, adding that some
folks just like to leaf through the pages and pick and choose.
Plus, there will always be special books. Koerperich made his point
by taking from a shelf a small volume a grieving family put
together in remembrance of a 22-year-old local man killed in a car
accident. The title was /{Brad, We Hardly Knew You/}. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This belongs in a book,'' said Koerperich, 58. ``Not on a
screen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, one category of bookbinding has taken a nosedive over the
past few years. Most newspapers now are preserved electronically,
much to Koerperich's relief. No longer does he have to work with
pages that don't want to stay even and cheap, mediocre paper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate newspapers,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What he does love is binding books, a skill that goes back to
the fourth century. Compared with bookbinding, printing is a recent
innovation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Koerperich apprenticed himself four years to an
uncle who was a bookbinder in New Mexico. He learned the trade,
returned to Selden, farmed, and started bookbinding in his garage.
He moved to town a couple of years later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there he's been ever since, the business growing, his sons
joining him, and taking care of clients, be they printers who sends
boxloads of unbound pages to be turned into thousands of books or
the individuals who show up with a single beloved volume, scuffed
and worn from uncountable readings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He still farms some. But bookbinding is his passion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several towns have come to Koerperich, offering everything short
of the moon if he'll relocate. With 12 to 24 skilled employees,
depending on the time of year and the workload, getting Koerperich
would be a feather in the cap of any municipality wanting to expand
its employment base. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No thanks,'' has been Koerperich's reply. He likes Selden.
It's home. He likes small-town people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to give tours until our insurance company made us quit
because of liability,'' Koerperich said. ``It was funny. People
were just fascinated with how the books are bound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd always tell them anybody can bind books. All you need
is a needle, thread, cardboard and paper. And maybe a pencil to
write the title on the book. It's easy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Koerperich smiled. Well, maybe not that easy. &QL; 
 &LR; tag1:To reach Jim Fisher, Mid-America correspondent for The Star,
call {(913) 681-2320} or send e-mail to {jfisher &LR; sound.net} &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
