r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEAPONS-POLL-KAN &LR;      02-28 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEAPONS-POLL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED CONCEALED-WEAPONS LAW LACKS SUPPORT IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Kansas Citians have their way, Missouri won't pass a
concealed weapons law any time soon, according to a poll by The
Kansas City Star. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the Kansas City voters surveyed, 60 percent oppose legalizing
concealed handguns, compared with 23 percent in favor. If voters
approve the ballot measure April 6, Missourians will be able to
carry concealed weapons for the first time since 1875. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   City residents also solidly reject the argument that a
concealed-carry law would reduce crime, the poll showed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City alone will not decide the election on concealed
weapons. Gun advocates are counting on strong support from rural
areas. Concealed-carry opponents are hoping that expected
opposition from Kansas City _ and from St. Louis _ will be enough
to defeat the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City a majority of every group except gun owners
opposes the concealed-weapons measure, according to the poll of 601
registered voters in Jackson, Clay and Platte counties. Even among
gun owners support was tepid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet interviews with people surveyed showed a strong streak of
ambivalence in their responses, fueled in large part by fear of
crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mitchell, 29, of south Kansas City, reflects those
conflicting feelings. He said he planned to vote against concealed
weapons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just make things worse,'' Mitchell said. ``You
couldn't tick anybody off. You step on my shoes, and I get mad and
pull out a gun and bam! Another one bites the dust. This is not
going to solve anything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if Missouri voters approve concealed weapons, Mitchell plans
to go through the training and get a permit. Just to even up the
odds, he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be for protection,'' Mitchell said. ``If everybody in
Kansas City is carrying, there's no way it would be a fair fight.
So I'd want to be able to defend myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poll uncovered several key trends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men, for example, were twice as likely as women to support the
proposal and were nearly 2 1/2 times as likely to own a gun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Black and white voters showed similar support for concealed
weapons, but blacks were twice as likely to say they would apply
for a permit to carry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suburban Kansas City residents who live in Clay or Platte
counties also supported concealed weapons slightly more than their
neighbors in Jackson County. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter their gender, race or residence, a majority of
Kansas Citians surveyed Feb. 10-14 said they opposed concealed
weapons. The survey had an error margin of plus or minus four
percentage points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve McGhee, president of Missourians for Personal Safety,
which supports concealed weapons, said his group had found
ambivalence toward concealed weapons even among gun advocates.
People are accustomed to thinking that only bad guys carry
concealed guns, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of soft supporters who think it's a good idea
but don't know whether they want everybody carrying guns,'' McGhee
said. ``I say people already are carrying guns. They are called
criminals. Is the person who goes through all those hoops to get a
permit really going to worry you?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poll's findings indicated that many Kansas Citians rejected
two of the gun advocates' key arguments: that women want to carry
guns for protection and that concealed weapons deter crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say a gun in a woman's purse can even the odds against
a male attacker, who is usually bigger and stronger. McGhee said
women made up more than 80 percent of the students in his firearms
training classes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City women, however, opposed concealed weapons nearly 5-1
in the poll and were far less likely than men to say they would
apply for permits. One in three men would apply, while one in 13
women would be interested in a permit to carry a concealed
firearm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women also were much less likely to say concealed weapons would
reduce crime. Many also did not think they would ever need to use a
gun to stop a crime. While 60 percent of men thought they would
need to draw their weapons, only 33 percent of women expected to do
so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Howard, 61, who lives in the Waldo neighborhood, opposes
concealed weapons. She says too many guns are on the streets
already. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frightening when I watch the news every night and even
little kids are involved with guns,'' Howard said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alyce King, 75, who lives south of the Plaza, said she would not
carry a gun herself but supported concealed weapons for
philosophical reasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a governmental body has overstepped its bounds when
they prohibit people from protecting themselves,'' King said.
``Policing is rather impossible when criminal elements can arm
themselves and the rest of us are left at a disadvantage.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deidre Thurman, 23, of south Kansas City, wants a permit because
she believes carrying a concealed gun would make her feel safer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a female it's not safe to ride home alone late at night _
on the bus or in a car,'' Thurman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even gun owners, however, do not put much stock in the power of
concealed weapons to deter crime. Only 37 percent thought concealed
weapons would; 55 percent said they would not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gun owner David Boyle, 53, belongs to the minority who do
believe concealed weapons can reduce crime. He bases his view on 4
1/2 years in Houston, where, he said, crime was so rampant he
learned to work a bank cash machine while holding a gun in one
hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminals have to be reluctant to commit a crime if they know
the victim might be armed and might be faster than them,'' said the
Kansas City, North, resident. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Black residents polled were more likely to expect to use a gun
to stop a crime, even though they were less likely than whites to
say concealed weapons reduced crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Emanuel Cleaver said most blacks opposed concealed weapons
because they did not want their community to grow even more
violent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the victims,'' Cleaver said. ``African-Americans are
disproportionately transported to funeral homes with gunshot
wounds.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William Clay Jr., a St. Louis Democrat, said he never
bought the argument that concealed weapons reduced crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said most black residents opposed the referendum because they
feared they would be victims of shootings done in the name of
self-defense. But others in the black community want concealed guns
to protect themselves from others who have guns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver agreed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans tend to be paranoid, with some
justification, about not being able to protect themselves,''
Cleaver said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poll backed up Cleaver and Clay. About 30 percent of black
respondents said they were inclined to get a gun permit if the
measure passed, compared with 15 percent for whites. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
