<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An intensifying late winter storm near Montreal will draw mild,
moist air into northern New England on brisk winds from the
southeast. Heavy rain will taper off during the afternoon, but
flooding is likely on some streams and rivers due to the combined
rainfall and snow melt. A swath of relatively dry, but cooler air
will cover southern New England where winds will be brisk.
</P>
<P>
   The backwash of chilly, moist air associated with a large vortex
at 20,000 feet over New York will bring clouds and snow showers to
much of the eastern Ohio Valley and central Appalachians. Several
inches of wet snow will accumulate from southwest New York through
western Pennsylvania to central West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of high pressure in the eastern Gulf of Mexico
and the storm over Quebec will produce a dry and cooler air flow
over the Southeast. Abundant sunshine will boost afternoon readings
to seasonal levels. Florida will be less humid with bright and
pleasant conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A push of very warm air into the central Plains will proceed a
cold front from the Pacific. Near record temperatures are likely
from west Texas to central Kansas. Clouds will vary in coverage
over the Midwest and northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Light snow will fall in northern Wyoming and parts of Montana as
cooler air pushes into the region. Onshore winds will promote
clouds and some showers along the Northwest Coast. The Southwest
will be sunny and a bit warmer as high pressure builds inland
across California. It will become windy in the deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Two Faces of Spring &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tornado drills had to be canceled in North Carolina last week
due to a wintry weather. On Sunday, forecasters in the Carolinas
found themselves in another quandary. A strong cold front was
promoting the risk of severe thunderstorms near the coast while
cold, moist air rushing into the Smokeys was prompting winter
weather advisories for snow. Winter and summer conditions can meet
in March as large temperature contrasts are juxtaposed by powerful
fronts. Indeed, this week should feature more incidents of winter
and summer in the same state due to a front in the middle of the
nation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
