<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING THE ENVELOPE FOR A GREAT PASTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Oggie, oggie, oggie, oi, oi, oi!''
</P>
<P>
   You won't hear that cheer rising from a crowd at the Kingdome,
KeyArena or Husky Stadium. That's because Seattle's sports teams
don't attract nearly enough athletes or fans from Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   Can Gary Payton, Ken Griffey Jr. or Mike Holmgren accurately
describe an oggie? I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   Have any Seattle fans ever tasted an oggie? Not likely. Their
mouths are stuffed with hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   As any Cornishman could tell you, a ``tiddly oggie'' is a
meat-and-vegetable-filled delicacy also known as the Cornish pasty.
The crust is shaped something like an envelope, which is why some
Welsh miners described it as ``a letter from home.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife was raised on pasties in Butte, Mont., where Cornishmen
once arrived in great numbers to work in the mines. We were
reintroduced to them a year ago when we traveled through the
village of Polperro, where pasty shops outnumber churches and
public houses.
</P>
<P>
   One bite of a steaming-hot pasty immediately inspires
enthusiasm. Which is why Cornish sports fans holler, ``Oggie,
oggie, oggie, oi, oi, oi,'' in support of local heroes at rugby
matches and the occasional women's lawn bowling final.
</P>
<P>
   They take their pasties very seriously in southern England.
</P>
<P>
   An authentic Cornish pasty must contain potato, onion, meat and
turnip. The vegetables must be sliced, not cubed. The meat must be
cut, never minced. Some of the toughest kinds of beef, like skirt
or chuck steak, produce the best pasties.
</P>
<P>
   A law passed in 1967 decreed that any pasty sold in a shop or
restaurant must contain 12.5 percent meat. Tradition dictates the
dough surrounding the filling should be crimped across the top, not
the sides. It must be brushed with water or milk and a small slit
in the top acting as a chimney is judged both on size and neatness.
</P>
<P>
   The pasty was mentioned in English literature as early as 1300.
The cook in ``Canterbury Tales'' was chastised for serving pasties
that had been reheated.
</P>
<P>
   Pasties are recommended as a meal to be taken into the mine.
Carried aboard a fishing vessel, it is an evil omen more dangerous
than a floating mine. If the captain discovers a pasty aboard his
vessel, his only remedy is to immediately break off both ends. This
lets the devil out.
</P>
<P>
   The above information is contained in ``The Pasty Book'' by
Hettie Merrick. She apparently is known far and wide as the Pasty
Queen of Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   My wife never claimed a similar title in Butte. But she makes a
pretty good pasty and she makes it like this.
</P>
<P>
   Alice's Pasty
</P>
<P>
   For pastry:
</P>
<P>
   3 and three-quarters cups flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-quarter cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup very cold water
</P>
<P>
   For filling:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups peeled and thinly sliced red potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 turnips, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half pounds skirt or flank steak, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cut the shortening into the flour and salt until crumbly. You
can do this by juggling six carving knives or, better yet, with a
kitchen tool known as a pastry blender.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg and vinegar together. Add cold water and stir. Add
liquid to flour and shortening and mix just until dough holds
together. Divide into 6 balls.
</P>
<P>
   Roll each section of dough out on a floured board. What you want
to create is a crust 8-by-8 inches with rounded corners.
</P>
<P>
   Create a layer of potatoes in the center of the pastry square.
Salt and pepper. Top with a layer of onion and turnip, then a layer
of meat, then more salt and plenty of pepper. Repeat until you have
six pasties.
</P>
<P>
   Bring two sides of each pasty together and crimp the dough
across the top, folding ends in. Create a small hole or vent in the
top of the pasty. Bake in a 350-degree oven for about an hour,
brushing the dough with milk halfway through the baking process.
</P>
<P>
   I like my pasty served with beef gravy on the side, but that's
not going to be practical if you insist on eating yours at the
bottom of a tin mine.
</P>
<P>
   Do your own thing. I think I'll add a side dish like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Devonshire Carrots
</P>
<P>
   5 carrots, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Cover carrots with water in skillet and cook just until tender.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, mix sugar, cornstarch, salt, ginger and orange juice.
Stir-cook to thicken. Add the butter and when it has melted, pour
the sauce over the carrots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
