<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, March 1. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-VOTE (Lagos) _ Results in Nigerian presidential
election. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ Having retreated on plans to revise
Germany's citizenship law and its intention to reduce the country's
dependence on nuclear energy, the Schroder government is off to a
bumpy start. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Four Israeli soldiers, including a
general, are killed in attacks in southern Lebanon. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-LEGACY-II (Alburquerque, N.M.) _ Special Weapons and
Tactics squads, once used exclusively for the rare urban terrorist
incident or shootout, have transformed themselves through the crack
years into everyday parts of city life. In big urban areas,
paramilitary units now do everything from routine street patrols to
nightly house raids. Even small towns have formed paramilitary
police units. The Cape Cod town of Harwich, Mass., for example,
population 11,000, has trained a 10-man SWAT team. Encouraged by
federal grants, surplus equipment handed out by the military, and
seizure laws that allow police departments to keep much of what
their special units take in raids, the special units have grown
dramatically, even in the face of plummeting crime figures. (Second
of two parts.) By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-BUSH (Sacramento, Calif.) _ In unprecedented fashion,
Republicans of all stripes are lining up behind George W. Bush _
sight unseen. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-BOOMERS (Detroit) _ The auto industry is starting to
redesign its vehicles to meet the needs of older Americans _
without being obvious about it. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-FRANCE (Paris) _ Williams plays Mauresmo in the finals of
the Gaz de France.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BODE-MEDIA (Washington) _ After clashing with a new boss who
thought Washington Week in Review's quiet discussions of targeted
tax cuts and Kosovo needed a little more edge and attitude, Ken
Bode was pushed out last week and had to tune in from a friend's
place and watch his fill-in smile and thank him for his five years
of service. He had wanted to go on one last time and, before saying
``So long,'' get a panel of four Pulitzer Prize winners talking
about the nature of punditry, the argument culture and the ``TV
wasteland.'' The trend toward news reporters, who are suppposed to
be objective, loudly sharing their opinions all over television has
been a concern of Bode's for years. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-DOCTORS (New York) _ Despite some recent gains, the top
tiers of medicine have remained inaccessible to many women,
largely, experts say, because they are unwilling or unable to find
a balance between the years of study those specialties require and
a life outside of medicine. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-PROFILING (New York) _ The superintendent of New Jersey's
State Police was quoted in Sunday's Star-Ledger as saying that
while racial profiling will not be condoned, he believes that most
of the cocaine and marijuana trafficking is done by minorities.
Black legislators, ministers, and NAACP officials responded by
calling for his ouster.
</P>
