<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-770(     02-28 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POPULAR CHANCELLOR, EVEN IF HIS GOVERNANCE SOMETIMES WAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ There he was last week, the German chancellor, no less,
on a television talk show being asked if he would submit to a test
that would determine if the color of his abundant dark brown hair
was real. Yes, Gerhard Schroeder said with a coy grin, ``This is
all genuine, really everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment that captured the extent of Germany's
transformation during the four-month rule of the 54-year-old
Schroeder. His predecessor, Helmut Kohl, rarely appeared on talk
shows, let alone to talk about his (gray) hair. Schroeder, a
white-toothed modern image merchant, has popularized the exercise
of power.
</P>
<P>
   Germans tend to like the change: Schroeder's personal popularity
remains high. But has Germany's first Social Democratic chancellor
in 16 years also trivialized governance, to the point where
Europe's most powerful country is sublimely coiffed at the top but
dangerously rudderless?
</P>
<P>
   Abrupt policy shifts on immigration and nuclear power,
discordant ministerial voices, rising unemployment, signs of
recession and messy decision-making by committee have all raised
sharp questions about Schroeder. ``Where is the line?'' the
conservative weekly Die Zeit asked. The centrist Berlin Tagespiegel
was blunter last week, alluding to ``lunatic amateurism.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodo Hombach, the chancellor's chief of staff, said in an
interview that the government needed time. ``In many ways we are a
blocked society, but you cannot push things through here over the
objections of others,'' he said. ``Action by consensus is an old
German tradition, and we will build the necessary bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   But time seems short. Uncertain government matters less when an
economy is strong and a country's self-image stable. But Germany's
combination of stalled growth, an aging population, disappearing
jobs, uneasy relations between its eastern and western regions,
charged politics of immigration and a continuing quest for a
``normal'' identity appears treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, Europe's infant common currency, has fallen 7 percent
against the dollar in a month as Germany's economics minister has
done something long unthinkable: He has bickered with central
bankers. The German economy shrank 0.4 percent in the last quarter
of 1998, a grim sign when unemployment under Schroeder, far from
falling by 1 million as he promised, has already surged to 11.5
percent, from 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the international front, Germany's relations with its
European allies and with the United States are in the midst of a
difficult adjustment reflecting the arrival in power of a new, more
assertive postwar German generation.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Glavany, the French agricultural minister, expressed his
country's dismay by declaring last week that Schroeder's demands
for a cut in Germany's huge contribution to the European Union
budget reminded him of Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   From a Gallic source, such criticism suggests that the
French-German alliance, long at the heart of European integration,
is in trouble _ or at the very least in flux.
</P>
<P>
   Elected, like Bill Clinton in 1992, on a largely domestic
agenda, Schroeder has found himself thrust abruptly into difficult
international issues _ among them reform of the European Union
budget and NATO _ for which his government has sometimes appeared
poorly prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allies are somewhat flabbergasted,'' said Joachim Krauze,
deputy director of the German Society for Foreign Affairs.
``Germany demanding its interests in an assertive way, Germany no
longer viewing the independence of the European central bank as
sacrosanct. It's worrying and I don't think it's productive.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it is what most Germans want. Although opinion polls
have recently shown that Schroeder's coalition of Social Democrats
and environmentalist Greens would be defeated if a new election
were held today, the chancellor's own popularity was estimated at
more than 70 percent last month by Der Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear that the chancellor's glad-handing style, his
informality, his preference for talking about the future rather
than the trauma of Germany's past, his popular touch, even his
readiness to talk hair have struck a chord with a generation of
Germans tired of Kohl's history lessons and ``visions'' of
Germany's place in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Schroeder has understood that people want to be left in
peace,'' said Bernhard Schlink, the novelist. ``What we have is a
generation of nice passive consumers who are busy in a nice passive
way. Why should they bother about big ideas, projects, goals and
ambitions?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, though, that Germany does appear to have to resolve
some basic problems in order to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   One is whether this is ``a country of immigration,'' as
Schroeder's coalition initially proposed. Another linked question
is whether Germany's vaunted ``social market'' economy, built on
consensus between unions and employers and on extensive social
insurance, has stalled irrevocably. If it has, immigration could
clearly become an explosive question. No sinking economy embraces
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Schroeder was obliged to reverse course on a major
element of his proposal to make German citizenship easier to
acquire for the country's 7.3 million foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Faced by a petition that had already gathered 1 million
signatures against his plans, and by a defeat last month to
Christian Democrats in a state election in Hesse, he dropped a
proposal that dual citizenship be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was important because many of Germany's more than 2
million Turks are reluctant to give up Turkish citizenship (that
alone confers the right to buy land in Turkey) although they want
to become Germans, and gain, for instance, the right to vote in all
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the chancellor perceived _ albeit belatedly _ that his
entire immigration revision, aimed at changing a 1913 citizenship
law based largely on blood lines, would collapse if this measure
was not abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as in an earlier reversal on banning the export of
nuclear waste, he appeared to have been carelessly drawn into an
untenable position by his Green coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated the reaction on dual citizenship, but we
will still get a new immigration law that will critically redefine
German identity,'' said Karsten Voigt, a Social Democratic Foreign
Ministry official. ``That is the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder seems certain to face a battle even on the rest of
his proposed law allowing foreigners to request citizenship after
eight years of residence _ instead of 15 _ and granting automatic
citizenship to children born here who have at least one parent who
has lived in Germany since the age of 14.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Stoiber, the powerful conservative governor of Bavaria,
was in a thunderous mood in Parliament last week as he declared,
``The majority of German people don't want this law.'' Wolfgang
Schauble, leader of the Christian Democrats, said Schroeder was
``responsible for chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that the immigration issue has become steadily more
sensitive as Schroeder has so far failed in his central electoral
pledge: to reduce the number of unemployed in Germany by at least 1
million people.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, unemployment lines have lengthened by more than 500,000
people in just four months.
</P>
<P>
   If the chancellor has a discernible passion _ rather than issues
that are merely material for image management _ it is putting
Germans back to work. Unlike Kohl, the new chancellor does not seem
deeply moved by either European integration nor the trans-Atlantic
relationship. In personal and political terms, unemployment is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Schroeder, who likes to moderate quietly between
opposing factions rather than lead from the front, has asked
Hombach to take the initiative at the head of a so-called Alliance
for Jobs. This group of labor unions and employers is reviewing
issues including taxation, social security, working hours,
pensions, wages, training and education.
</P>
<P>
   Call it German consensus-making writ large. It is unwieldy,
slow, and just possibly productive. A lot of people seem to agree
on the basic problem: the German labor market is too regulated and
too weighed down with high social security charges to generate
jobs. But, as Hombach said, ``To get from knowledge to action in
this society is extremely difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hombach, about $350 billion is earned annually in
the German black economy. ``We probably have four times more worker
hours in this black economy than we need to get rid of unemployment
completely. So the problem is clear: How do you get this labor out
from under?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he said, was clear enough: bring down the taxes and
charges on legal salaries that make people prefer the combination
of off-the-books wages and unemployment benefits to a regular job.
</P>
<P>
   But that, of course, might eventually imply a partial
dismantling of the health and other insurance benefits enjoyed by
Germans and immigrants _ an explosive suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as Nixon was the only American who could go to China and
make peace, the Social Democrats are the only ones who can
eventually push through a reform of our economic model,'' Hombach
said. ``But any solution has to be one that allows everyone to
benefit from our economic success. American style ultra-liberalism
is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany still seems very far from agreement on reform. Indeed a
wage rise of 4 percent (with inflation at close to zero) won last
month by the huge IG Metall engineering union _ which sets the bar
for all other unions _ had many business executives in a fury.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Schroeder is tempted to emulate Tony Blair of
Britain. But Blair, of course, could build on what Mrs. Thatcher
had already done. The chancellor, by contrast, has everything to do
and a divided Social Democratic Party to deal with, in which
resistance to market reform and deregulation remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   The figurehead for that resistance is Oskar Lafontaine, the
economics minister and party chairman. He and the European central
bank governor, Wim Duisenberg of Holland, have been engaged in
extraordinary low-level warfare as Lafontaine suggests lower
interest rates are really the answer to Germany's _ and Europe's _
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Duisenberg said pointedly _ and huffily _ that he had
never read the book on economics written recently by Lafontaine and
his wife, and that he had ``absolutely no intention'' of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   As in many of his government's tiffs and travails, Schroeder has
not intervened decisively, leaving the impression that Germany is
ready to abandon its long sacrosanct monetary orthodoxy in pursuit
of murky new goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic decisions have been left untaken, basic lines left
unclear,'' said Krauze, the foreign policy expert. ``A lot of time
has been lost on issues that are basically luxuries _ like giving
up nuclear power. We need direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has promised to provide it soon, speaking of
``technical problems'' in the first months. He leads a coalition
made up of a party that has not been in power for almost a
generation and another that has never been in power. Teething
problems were probably inevitable. But further drift looks
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will get there,'' Hombach said, ``and with a style that is
less encrusted, more relaxed, more open, more frank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
