<HEADLINE>
HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES TOP ALBRIGHT'S AGENDA IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Every time a secretary of state comes to China,
Congress watches closely. And perhaps no more so than on this
week's brief visit by Madeleine Albright, who arrived here Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before she left, the Senate passed a unanimous resolution
calling on the Clinton administration to condemn China's human
rights policy at the meeting this month of the U.N. human rights
commission in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   While she was en route, the State Department released its annual
human rights report chastising China for regression on the matter
and expressing disappointment that China had not delivered on the
improvement in human rights it had promised.
</P>
<P>
   On board her plane, Albright's spokesman, James R. Rubin,
described as deplorable the detention of one dissident and the
18-month sentence given another late last week by the Chinese
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has prided itself on broadening its China
policy in the last several years from being focused on just human
rights to encompassing other issues, including trade and developing
what the administration dubbed a ``strategic partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the budding relationship with China in retreat,
Albright will touch on a host of problems that enrage the Chinese,
from a proposal for a theater missile defense system in Asia to the
cancellation of the sale of a U.S. satellite to a company with ties
to the Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will also grill the Chinese on why they cannot help out
more in controlling nuclear developments in North Korea, and gauge
their readiness to join the World Trade Organization,
administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, insisting on anonymity, declined to put an order
of priority on the long list of problems that the Chinese would
raise with Albright or that she would put to them.
</P>
<P>
   But one of her tasks, Rubin said, will be to ``tell it like it
is'' about Washington's expectations on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rubin and other administration officials who
have prepared Albright for this trip said they were uneasy with the
approach of many in Congress who believe that sponsoring a
resolution against the Chinese in Geneva is the best policy.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have argued in recent weeks that a
resolution against China may make members of Congress feel good but
does not necessarily reap results.
</P>
<P>
   China objects to the resolution as an infringement of its
sovereignty. It sounded a similar tone in its official response to
the State Department human rights report, expressing indignation
and resentment at what it termed U.S. meddling in China's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Chinese officials have argued that because of
the nation's mounting economic problems and unprecedented numbers
of unemployed, they cannot allow political dissent from the ruling
Communist Party. The government has expressed concern about the
potential of sudden widespread social instability, particularly in
the 50th anniversary year of the Communist takeover of China and
the 10th anniversary of the student protests and deaths in Tianamen
Square.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright's talks could serve to assess how the Chinese would
react if Washington went ahead with a resolution in Geneva in late
March. The problem is made even more vexing because the Chinese
prime minister, Zhu Ronghi, is due in Washington for an official
visit on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time since 1991, Washington did not
introduce a resolution against China in Geneva, saying China had
made some progress in human rights. The Chinese would see any U.S.
move toward a resolution this year as a sharp deterioration in
their relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But with three democracy activists jailed late last year for 11
to 13 years and deepening pressure from Congress to take a stand in
Geneva, the administration must decide soon what to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva resolution has become such a flash point among China
policy makers in the administration that one senior official
involved in the decision said he refused to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   This official said Albright would not merely ask the Chinese to
release political prisoners, or review their number, but encourage
China to develop its legal system to provide more protection for
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong office of the Information Center of Human Rights
and Democratic Movement in China said Sunday night that the
organizers of a planned seminar on human rights in Wuhan over the
weekend had been detained.
</P>
<P>
   The office also said members of the banned Democracy Party in
Beijing had written a letter to the National People's Congress,
which is scheduled to meet here on Friday, urging its deputies to
ratify two U.N. covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In what the administration viewed as a move forward, the Chinese
government signed the covenants last year. But they have yet to be
ratified, and the State Department human rights report complained
that the Chinese had not given any indication when that might
happen.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Wu Yilong, the founder of a banned political party,
was detained in Hangzhou for questioning, and a liberal
intellectual, Peng Ming, who had tried to run an independent
discussion forum in Beijing, was sentenced without trial to 18
months in a labor camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
