<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2342 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI     02-28 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S MACHINIST UNION DOING P.R. IN ADVANCE OF NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Worried that Boeing's management may try to please
Wall Street at the expense of workers, the company's Machinists
union is launching a campaign to woo public support before contract
negotiations begin this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The International Association of Machinists District Lodge 751
has a Seattle public relations firm, Pyramid Communications, and is
working to counter the extraordinary reach of Boeing's lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, union leaders met with President Clinton's National
Economic Council and members of Vice President Al Gore's staff at
the White House, and with Sens. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Machinists plan to carry on the campaign in
Seattle, meeting with state and local elected officials, editorial
boards, and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give our message to the community and also some
of our elected officials back here, to give our union's perspective
of how we think Boeing is doing leading up to negotiations,'' said
Linda Lanham, legislative and political director for the
Machinists. ``We wanted to tell a little bit about ourselves, what
we'd like from them, the economic impact we have on our community,
so that they are well informed long before we go into the process
of negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The machinists' four-year contract expires Sept. 1, and formal
talks aimed at the next contract are expected to begin in August.
But the two sides have already been talking informally for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations come at a tough time for Boeing, whose stock
price has been rocked by production troubles and whose upper
management is under fire. The company has set out an ambitious
production schedule this year, even as it is making dramatic
reductions in its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Although union leaders say they want to avoid labor strife this
year, recent history is not encouraging _ the machinists struck in
1995 and 1989. And the union leaders make no bones about pointing
out how harmful a strike can be, not only to workers, but also to
the company and to area businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing points out that the company's leadership has changed
since the last labor strife, and that the company has negotiated 30
union contracts over the past two years without a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our point of view is that we do not want a strike, and we are
working very hard at all levels to avoid such an outcome,'' said
company spokesman Peter Conte. ``Any prudent company can not go
into this type of negotiation without at least preparing for any
eventuality, but that is not a threat. Our driving intention
throughout this year, and as we go through the negotiations, is to
avoid that outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The union, the largest single-employer private sector bargaining
unit in Washington, has 40,000 active members and 10,000 retired.
The members _ who work in the Seattle area, Spokane, Portland,
Ore., and Wichita, Kan. _ are overwhelmingly male, highly paid and
experienced, with an average age of 43 and an average 10 years at
Boeing, according to union representative Larry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Union President Bill Johnson said the machinists have four major
contract goals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Job security. The union wants to stop the company from
``out-sourcing'' _ transferring jobs from machinists to non-Boeing
workers. This issue has become particularly important to the union
as the company reduces its payroll through layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health care. The union is insistent that its members should
not have to pay any portion of their medical costs, and Johnson
said any proposed co-payment requirement ``is the quickest way to
have a strike in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pensions and retirement. The union wants better retirement
benefits for former Boeing Machinists, some of whom, they say, now
live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work schedules. The union says Boeing wants to make people
work on weekends without paying them overtime. Johnson say this is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are adamant _ they want the option to have
weekends at home with their families,'' he said. ``If the company
demands that they work on the weekends, we demand premium pay. This
issue is crucial _ our members want more time with their families.
They will strike over this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Conte said none of the issues mentioned by Johnson come as a
surprise. On the issue of weekend work, he said the issue must be
negotiated, but that ``the bottom line is that Boeing needs to be
more competitive, and one area to pursue in becoming more
competitive is having a workforce that is as flexible and talented
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the company and the union agree that a work stoppage would
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any disruption of Boeing is a serious blow to our regional
economy,'' Lanham said. ``The 1995 strike cost Boeing billions of
dollars. Boeing has announced plans to deliver 620 aircraft, up
from 559 in 1998. A strike this year would be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she came away from her briefing optimistic about the
union's posture.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I heard them say is that they really want to avert a
strike, and they want to work together as they did in Long Beach,''
she said, referring to the union's ability to reach an agreement
with Boeing over the possible transfer of some 737 jobs to
California. ``Historically, these negotiations have been
contentious, and everybody wants to make sure we go into this
without that kind of rancor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-BOOMERS-ART-2TAK     02-28 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-BOOMERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMAKERS SHOW NEW AWARENESS OF AGING CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Engineers at Lear Corp., the world's largest
independent supplier of automotive interiors, labored for months
last year to come up with a vehicle that would meet all the needs
of older Americans. The seats swivel out for easy access, the
dashboard controls and displays are unusually large and the trunk
floor partly rolls out at the back for easy loading.
</P>
<P>
   When the engineers were finished, they showed the prototype to
the 82-year-old father of the company's chairman _ and were
crestfallen at his response. Looking at the swiveling seats in
particular, he was dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't need it,'' said Marilyn Vala, Lear's
product-analysis manager.
</P>
<P>
   The aging of the U.S. population poses quandaries for businesses
in many industries, but few companies face as many difficult
decisions as automakers and their suppliers. Power, sex and youth
have long been used to sell cars, so anything that suggests to
buyers that they might not be as virile and agile as they once were
could easily backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers don't want to admit they're getting older,'' said
John Wolkonowicz, an auto industry consultant at Arthur D. Little.
``You can't be too catering to age; you have to do it invisibly _
you have to give people vehicles they can get excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet driving or even climbing into a car can be difficult and
sometimes painful for aging bodies. And with millions of baby
boomers every year now entering their 50s, the auto industry is
starting to redesign its vehicles to meet the needs of older
Americans _ without being obvious about it.
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, the average age of new-car buyers is
rising even faster than the average age of the overall population.
Many of these older buyers would be better served by vehicles
designed differently from vehicles for younger buyers, to reflect
the less acute vision and reduced muscular flexibility of bodies
that are 50 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, older Americans have shown little interest in buying
vehicles tailored to their needs, and automakers have paid fairly
little attention to selling such vehicles. Automakers have long
been obsessed with luring young buyers in the hopes that brand
loyalties, once formed, would persist over the 10 or 15 new cars a
prosperous American might buy in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Even car divisions like Buick, Cadillac, Jaguar, Lincoln and
Oldsmobile, which have done very well selling to older Americans,
have shifted their marketing focus to drivers in their 40s and
younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is always going after the young buyer,'' said Ben
Level III, Ford Motor Co.'s executive director of market research.
``You very rarely hear about anyone going after the old buyer _
maybe it's cultural.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs now that attitudes are beginning to change.
The main reason for the subtle shift is the enormous and growing
market that older, more affluent Americans represent. As automakers
try to accommodate their needs, however, they are trying to be as
subtle as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The result _ new car features that are easy to overlook but
reflect a new awareness of older Americans' needs. When the new
Chevrolet Impala midsized sedan goes on sale later this year, for
example, it will have the ignition on the dashboard rather than the
side of the steering column _ a seemingly unimportant choice.
</P>
<P>
   But the ignition will be on the dashboard because General
Motors' engineers and consultants found that slightly arthritic
hands could turn a key sideways more easily if the wrist was not
already bent.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the new Ford Focus, a small car that will replace the
Ford Escort later this year, has front-door openings that extend
farther forward on the car at knee level, to make it easier for
older drivers to swing their legs into the car. The Focus and the
new Dodge Neon also have seats that are slightly higher off the
street, partly because many older Americans find it harder to climb
in or out of a low vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Even the new Chevrolet Corvette sports car, long a symbol of
youthful virility, has been redesigned to make it easier for aging
baby boomers to climb in and out. And the trunk has recently been
enlarged to carry golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Auto suppliers say that they are starting to receive many
requests from automakers for parts that are designed for older
Americans. ``The interest is there now _ why it wasn't there five
years ago, I don't know,'' said Kenneth Way, the chairman and chief
executive of Lear.
</P>
<P>
   Lear will publicly display its prototype for an older person's
vehicle on Monday, at the opening of the auto-parts industry's
annual convention here, an event that is expected to include many
products aimed at an aging America. Lear extensively modified a
Dodge Caravan minivan to show all the products that could be
installed on cars to make them easier for older people to use.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, seat-belt manufacturers are working on belts that are
mounted on both sides of each seat and clasp in the front, so that
older customers will not have to twist their bodies to find and
pull seat belts around and across their bodies. Manufacturers are
designing thicker door handles with more contoured grooves for
passengers' fingers, to make them easier to grip.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler and other automakers are experimenting with
prototypes of sedans that would not need side pillars. The rear
doors would open backward with hinges at the rear, so that there
would be more room to climb into the vehicle and so that disabled
drivers could readily swing a folded wheelchair in behind the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Dashboards increasingly feature big knobs and large displays
that are easy to read even with imperfect eyesight. Auto designers
say that such details also attract young buyers at a time when
other fashions include kitchen tools like ice-cream scoops with big
rubber handles that were originally designed for arthritic hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming from the younger generation; they're showing us
that suspenders are OK, and the little granny glasses,'' said Jerry
Hirshberg, Nissan's president of North American design. ``It used
to be if there were a lecture with ergonomics in the name, I'd
probably skip it, but now it has a zing to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto designers and consultants say that no single car will
include all of the possible devices for older Americans, but many
cars will quietly incorporate some features. An old, slightly
ageist, adage in the auto industry says that an old man will buy a
young man's car, but a young man will not buy an old man's car.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Detroit automakers are leery of going too far in
catering to older buyers. They recall the early 1980s, when younger
customers defected in droves to foreign automakers and domestic
manufacturers like Chrysler were left with mostly older drivers,
said David Bostwick, DaimlerChrysler's director of North American
corporate market research.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the median age of new-car buyers in the United States has
risen to 47 from 40 over the last decade, while the median age of
buyers of sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickups has climbed
to 43 from 39, according to automakers' research. Over the same
period, the median age of all Americans has only crept up about
three years to 34.9.
</P>
<P>
   Americans over the age of 55 make up a fifth of the population
but control up to three-quarters of the nation's financial assets,
market researchers estimate. They have benefited handsomely from a
nearly two-decade-long stock-market boom, so they can afford new
cars even though the average price is now around $20,800.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harvey Kornblit and his wife, Doris, who are both 71 years
old and live in Houston, have just bought a new $30,000 Jeep Grand
Cherokee Limited with such features as radio controls on the
steering wheel, so that they no longer have to lean over to change
stations. But the couple chose the vehicle not because of these
features but because they liked the solid feel of its exterior,
Mrs. Kornblit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want is a sturdy body that's metal, not plastic,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Late-model, well-equipped used cars have become increasingly
popular as substitutes for smaller, similarly priced new cars, but
this national trend has taken place mainly among younger buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ideas now being considered to accommodate older
drivers represent a revival of concepts tried and abandoned before.
The former Chrysler Corp., for example, offered optional, swiveling
seats in the late 1950s, although they were not powered and were
marketed to women leery of clambering into cars while wearing tight
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Piaskowski, DaimlerChrysler's director of passenger-car
and minivan interior design, said that the company would take
another look at swiveling seats. ``Sometimes old ideas,'' he said,
``are good ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
