<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tth-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-MISSILES-SPI &LR;      02-28 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MISSILES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA MISSILE THREAT BECOMES MORE OF A CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just a brief comment by the chairman of the House
International Relations Committee, but it was enough to make
Northwesterners sit up and take note.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 40 years, North Korea posed a threat to 37,000 American
troops and the South Korean capital of Seoul,'' Rep. Benjamin
Gilman, R-N.Y., told his committee in Washington, D.C., on
Thursday. ``Now they are threatening our mainland. In short, we
must now worry about our safety in Seattle, not just Seoul.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman was referring to reports by U.S. and Japanese defense
experts that North Korea now has the technology to launch a
long-range ballistic missile capable of reaching the northwest
coast of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department says the liquid-fueled Taepodong-2 missile
could be tested as early as this year, for the first time putting
this corner of the continental United States within possible range
of North Korean weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scenario that worries a lot of people, including
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Testifying before Gilman's
committee, Albright called North Korea a ``huge threat'' to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The menace posed by North Korea and other so-called ``rogue
states'' has brought renewed calls for a national missile defense
system. On Thursday, the House Armed Services Committee
overwhelmingly approved legislation to make it national policy to
deploy such a system to defend against incoming missiles. It does
not specify a time frame, the costs or the specifics of the system.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's activities also have added urgency to the ongoing
debate among policymakers on how best to deal with one of the
world's most reclusive and repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for example, should the United States and the United
Nations provide millions of dollars in food and other assistance to
prop up a government that spends an estimated 25 percent of its
gross domestic product on the military while its population starves
to death? Why not just leave the nation of 21 million people in
isolation, letting it collapse from within?
</P>
<P>
   That may no longer be an option, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a hardliner on North Korea,'' says Bill
Taylor, senior vice president for international security at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, D.C.
``My position has always been that the best policy toward North
Korea is to do nothing _ don't hurt them but don't help them either
_ and eventually that regime is going to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   But as North Korean leader Kim Jong Il shows no sign of losing
his grip on power and fears grow of Pyongyang's military
capabilities, Taylor is questioning some of his past assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe they would lash out, like some fear, if they
implode,'' said Taylor, who has traveled extensively in North
Korea. ``But now I'm beginning to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a country with the world's worst human rights record _
the biggest Stalinist regime on the planet. It's a starving country
_ two to three million people have starved to death _ where
industry is totally on the rocks and they have no fuel but what we
give them.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite its weaknesses, North Korea always seems to have an
ace in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its ballistic missile program, Taylor said, it
has a ground force of some 1.1 million troops, two-thirds of them
deployed near the demilitarized zone and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   It has hundreds of short-range missiles that threaten the
region.
</P>
<P>
   It has a suspected underground nuclear facility at Kumchangni
that U.S. intelligence officials believe is large enough to house
facilities for making plutonium and other weapons-grade material.
The North says the United States can have a look, but first must
agree to pay $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed to have a sizable stockpile of chemical weapons,
including nerve, blister, choking and blood agents, and has been
conducting intensive research on biological weapons for three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seoul is naked,'' says Taylor. ``Pyongyang knows it has got
Seoul, Tokyo and Washington in a bind. There is no missile defense
of Japan, where we've got U.S. troops, and there is no missile
defense of the South, where there are 80,000 Americans _ troops and
other residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the strongest proponent of engagement with North
Korea today is the South, a radical switch from the days when Seoul
opposed any contacts, particularly by third countries. Now, under
President Kim Dae Jung's so-called ``sunshine policy,'' business
and social ties are encouraged while northern provocations are
played down.
</P>
<P>
   But this comprehensive engagement policy, while beginning to
show some signs of success, is also out of necessity, Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South Koreans have to do it. ... It's a necessity if
they're going to recover economically, if they're going to reduce
tensions and get international investment. If tensions go up, it
will be the end of the South Korean economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, North Korea knows that the South cannot for the
foreseeable future afford reunification _ however it might happen.
Estimated costs for South Korea of a German-style reunification of
the peninsula range from $200 billion to as much as $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Koreans want reunification in their hearts, but they
can't afford it,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea has us over a barrel right now and they know it
and they're going to get what they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
