<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO ALLIANCES SEEK NEW ROUTES TO INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Two separate industry alliances to be announced Monday share a
similar goal: creating alternatives to the personal computer _ and
to Microsoft's operating systems _ for access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In one announcement, IBM, Motorola, Sun Microsystems, Lucent and
10 other companies have agreed to create standards based on Sun's
Java programming language to connect smart devices ranging from
computers to dishwashers. In a separate deal, US West and Network
Computer plan to announce a schedule for trials of AT-TV, which
will integrate the Internet, telephone and television.
</P>
<P>
   DATA FLOW IN A SUPER-FAST PIPELINE
</P>
<P>
   The promise of a super-fast, highly reliable Internet moved a
step closer to reality when three dozen universities across the
United States were linked to a new national research network that
moves data at 1,600 times the speed of the high-speed lines that
many universities and businesses already use.
</P>
<P>
   A WORDY BATTLE OF BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Labor government of Tony Blair, the prime minister of
Britain, has had an extraordinarily rocky relationship with the
news media since it came to power on a tidal wave of good will
nearly two years ago. In a nation where there is no sense of open
government or of the public's right to know, the government has had
little compunction about openly attacking the news media when it
does not like the way it is being covered.
</P>
<P>
   FOR OLIVETTI, MINNOW HUNTS WHALE
</P>
<P>
   As Olivetti pursues its $60 billion unsolicited bid for Telecom
Italia, Italians seem captivated by the sheer daring of a minnow
seeking to swallow a whale. But many question what the bid means
both for Telecom and for Italy's drive to be a more open market.
</P>
<P>
   OMNIPOINT SET TO END ROAMING FEES
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of communications giants, Omnipoint,
a small wireless phone carrier that operates mainly in the
Northeast, is expected to announce plans Monday that eliminate
long-distance and ``roaming'' charges, executives close to the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING IN MACHO HOME PAGE
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to capitalize on the allure of Internet stocks, an
entrepreneur in Bethesda, Md., plans to raise $7.5 million in a
stock offering for Efox.net, an electronic-commerce Web site that
focuses on ``the heterosexual man's favorite pursuits: ladies,
automobiles, sports and stocks.'' The women who pose for the site
are to each be paid with 500 shares of Efox.net stock.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ORIGINAL CONTENT ON WEB
</P>
<P>
   The number of articles written exclusively for the Web sites of
newspapers and magazines is growing, according to a study to be
released tomorrow that is based on a survey completed by 192
newspaper editors and 170 magazine editors. The study reports that
the amount of original material on Web sites has grown along with
the proliferation of the sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
