<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      02-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI'S MOVE FOR TELECOM ITALIA WAS AIMED AT SURGING WIRELESS
MARKET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ROME _ As any traveler here knows, the tribe of Italians who do
not walk around with a cell phone hanging from one ear is facing
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that roughly 48 percent of Norwegians and
Swedes, and fully 58 percent of Finns own them, Italy is more in a
league with France and Britain, with roughly 60 million people
each. Among Italians, 36 percent of potential users have wireless
phones, compared with 22 percent in Britain and 18.8 percent in
France. Even fewer Germans _ 17 percent of 80 million _ use them.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that something like this might happen led Carlo
De Benedetti, the chairman of Olivetti SpA, the typewriter maker
turned computer company, to decide in the 1980s that mobile phones
might be what Olivetti needed to replace its ailing computer
business.
</P>
<P>
   The shift cost him his job. By 1996, Olivetti had generated so
much red ink and debt that its main shareholders _ British and
American pension funds _ replaced De Benedetti with one of his
proteges, Roberto Colaninno.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, Olivetti had joined with several big international
partners, including Germany's Mannesmann AG and Bell Atlantic and
Vodafone of the United States, to form a phone business with six
million subscribers, making it the No. 2 Italian phone business
after the former state phone company, Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   So eyebrows were raised when Colaninno, 55, announced a week ago
that Olivetti would sell its phone business for $8 billion to its
phone partner, Mannesmann, then raise $50 billion more through debt
and make a $60 billion unsolicited bid for its far bigger rival,
Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are these guys, and can they handle this?'' Franco
Bernabe, the Telecom chairman, asked about Colaninno and the
investors around him, an associate recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The remark, a tone of wonder mingled with doubt, appeared last
week to catch the ambivalent mood of Italians, who seemed
captivated by the sheer daring of a minnow seeking to swallow a
whale, yet questioned what the bid meant both for Telecom and for
Italy's drive to be a more open market.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's decision to swallow Telecom, a company five times its
size, represents one of the biggest hostile takeover attempts by
any company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there really is a rational explanation,'' said an
analyst at a large German brokerage who requested anonymity. Eighty
percent of Olivetti's value was its mobile phone business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Colaninno's bid, he noted, was ``predicated on asset
stripping'' by selling off Telecom businesses _ possibly including
a share in Telecom's mobile phone unit, Telecom Italia Mobile, at a
time when the phone business is rapidly shifting from fixed-line to
wireless. The enormous debt would drain Telecom at a time when
increased competition was putting intense pressure on phone costs
throughout Europe, squeezing industry margins.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts, however, said the potential for turning Telecom
into a leaner, more efficient phone company gave Colaninno's plan
an inner logic.
</P>
<P>
   From an industrial point of view, said Peter Roe, an analyst at
Paribas Securities in London, ``it makes sense, and you can justify
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecom has a very strong position in the domestic market and
a strong balance sheet,'' he said. ``It's a very significant
company in Italy and a large international player as well. So
you're going up the size scale very quickly when you take on
Telecom Italia.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecom had floundered since the Italian government took it
public, and successive executives have done little to sort out its
tangled problems _ not the least of which is getting its cost
structure down by reducing its bloated staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had aspirations to take it, molding it to your image,
now is the time to do it,'' Roe said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, was that Telecom shareholders, disgusted
with management's dithering, voted last fall to hire Bernabe, 49,
who earned his spurs in the preceding six years reorganizing the
former state oil giant, ENI SpA, and taking it public. So the
question came down to Colaninno versus Bernabe.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe lost no time elaborating a turnaround plan, proposing to
Telecom's board that he merge it with the profitable mobile phone
unit, Telecom Italia Mobile, shed noncore activities like phone
equipment manufacturing, and sell minority stakes in foreign phone
companies that had no strategic value.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Telecom's board ordered Bernabe to move ahead,
despite Olivetti's hostile bid, and present them with detailed
plans.
</P>
<P>
   But Italian securities regulators hampered that effort over the
weekend. They had rejected Olivetti's offer, saying it provided
insufficient details, but they approved a renewed bid on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Under corporate governance laws enacted in July, companies
subject to takeovers are precluded from adopting ``poison pill''
maneuvers meant to block bids. Only a favorable vote from more than
30 percent of the company's owners at a shareholders meeting can
decide otherwise, and analysts said that would be unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bernabe is seeking to persuade Italians,
generally more committed not to the quick kill but to finding
competitive edge, that Colaninno's bid, if successful, would
fatally weaken Telecom _ and with it, Italy's telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Telecom's union leaders, he cited figures meant as
much for Telecom's shareholders as for its employees. If
successful, he calculated, Olivetti's leveraged bid would leave
Telecom with annual debt service of $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As if to impress Italian politicians fearful of higher
unemployment and their union backers alike, he declared that
Telecom, to offset such financial burdens, would be forced to lay
off up to 35,000 of its 126,000 employees, beyond the 20,000 to
25,000 he believes must go if Telecom is to be competitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
