<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN-(SLAN     02-28 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED STARTING TO RESPOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins were faltering. Their lead was fading,
their attack was stagnating and Washington was rolling. Who else to
the rescue but . . . Travis Reed?
</P>
<P>
   In this season of changing lineups and rotation roulette, Reed,
a sophomore forward, has gotten lost in the lunacy. A regular in
December, his confidence and minutes plunged in the second half of
conference play.
</P>
<P>
   It all changed Saturday, when Washington chopped a 21-point
deficit to eight midway through the second half. Reed entered with
6:39 left and quickly stopped the Huskies' surge with a driving
layup. On the ensuing possession, he found Jerome Moiso for a short
baseline jumper. A minute later, Reed scored the first of six
consecutive points.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done _ when he had scored eight points in three
minutes _ UCLA's lead was 18 and the Bruins were cruising to a
79-62 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were real loosey-goosey and Trav came in hungry,'' guard
Baron Davis said. ``That's what we need from him. He provided a
spark off the bench. He took over the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Reed's best performance since Feb. 4, when he scored 13
points against Oregon. In the next six games _ with big men Jerome
Moiso and Dan Gadzuric injured and the Bruins desperate for
frontcourt production _ Reed was no help, with 11 points and 11
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistent play led to inconsistent minutes: seven one game,
20 the next, then two, then 11. He was not comfortable and he could
not gain confidence. Now, with Gadzuric out for the season, the
Bruins need him desperately. Saturday, finally, he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show I can still play,'' he said. ``I've been
struggling lately. Subbing in and out messes with my confidence,
but we were winning. I've been practicing real hard lately; I know
you play like you practice. That's what I've got to do without the
big guy.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Loyd farewell: Seldom-used senior guard Brandon Loyd played
his final home game Saturday and departed without remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask if I wish I had stayed closer to home, and I
don't,'' said Loyd, a native of Tulsa, Okla. ``I don't regret one
moment here. I've made some incredible friends. It's paradise here
compared to Oklahoma. I'd love to do it all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Loyd has at least three games left, the Bruins aren't
likely to displace his fondest memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sophomore year, all the stuff we went through after coach
(Jim) Harrick got fired, and about eight of us were playing,'' he
said. ``It was a special group to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stats of the weekend: UCLA scored 100 points Thursday against
Washington State, the most by a Pac-10 team in a conference game
this season. The Bruins' 39-point winning margin Thursday was their
largest in Pac-10 play since a 40-point victory over Washington in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   __ Short and painful: Reserve guard Rico Hines has not fully
recovered from the broken right foot that forced him to miss six
weeks. Although UCLA's medical staff prefers he not play, Hines
insists, so he's been placed on a limited-minutes program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hard-headed and stubborn and I won't leave my guys,''
Hines said. ``I can only play five or six minutes a game. Even if I
wanted to go more, I couldn't. It hurts too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines played six minutes against Washington (one assist) and
then iced his foot.
</P>
<P>
   __ There's no Rush: Kareem Rush, JaRon's younger brother and a
UCLA recruiting priority, visited campus this weekend. A 6-foot-4
shooting guard, he has narrowed his choices to UCLA and Missouri
and won't decide until April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the school and I like the program,'' he said. ``Having
JaRon here is an added bonus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
