OFF THE WALL: How will this Worm turn? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any armchair Toni Grant _ or, if you're Chick Hearn, any Travis
Grant _ can predict what's next in the Lakers' ``As The Worm
Squirms'' made-for-NBA soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   For Dennis Rodman, it'll be one of two things:
</P>
<P>
   1) Los Angeles, a city where cross-dressing is not a crime, will
provide him with a comfort zone he's never experienced before and
he'll thrive.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be on a 24/7 adrenaline rush, making the short hop to
Vegas between morning shootarounds and prime-time games, playing
HORSE at the Chateau Marmont driveway at 4 in the morning, partyin'
like it's 1999. And he'll cause enough distraction so Kobe Bryant
and Shaquille O'Neal can do their own things.
</P>
<P>
   Or . . .
</P>
<P>
   2) Los Angeles, a city that tends to yawn at even the most
absolute absurdity, won't be shocked enough by his behavior and
that'll drive him even more into a funk.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing one more teammate say, ``We don't care what he
does off the court, it's what's on the court that matters,'' he'll
feel used, abused and even more confused. And one day, he just
won't show up, wandering aimlessly down Melrose looking for another
instant-credit tattoo parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are convinced his behavior adds up to a classic case
of ADD _ that's Attention Deficit Disorder to those who are just
skimming this _ wonder why he hasn't already been a disruptive
force on a juvenile team trying to find its identity.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, two games into his Lakers career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be on his best behavior for a couple of games, eager to
please and to prove everyone's wrong about him, but eventually
he'll go back to what we've seen because that kind of person bores
him,'' author David Halberstam was saying last week to anyone who'd
ask.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam, who while compiling his book ``Playing For Keeps:
Michael Jordan and the World He Made,'' had a chance to observe
Rodman for all of last season, says he has heard from NBA
beat-writer friends that Rodman's selfishness will get the best of
everyone eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more volatile today than earlier in his career and no
amount of success or public adulation will fill that essential hole
within him,'' Halberstam said. ``That hole may push you to succeed,
but it never gets filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``His binge drinking will catch up with him and his behavior
will get more and more erratic. There were times when Phil Jackson
and Michael Jordan really had to sit him down and talk to him about
it. He's not someone who can take care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   So where's Jack Haley? . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Bulls GM Jerry Krause told the Chicago Tribune about Rodman:
``We didn't have a problem with him in practice. That was one of
the biggest misperceptions while he was here. He missed very few
practices. He was always on the verge of just getting fined _ he'd
show up two minutes before. But he didn't (routinely) miss
practices and nobody ever covered for him while he was here.'' . .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Lakers locker room now has a two-drink minimum. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Last team to change coaches in a season and win an NBA title
was the '82 Lakers, who canned Paul Westhead at Magic Johnson's
behest and yanked Pat Riley out of the broadcast bin. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Hey, Del: Nice guys ALWAYS finish last. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Fashion-police alert: The New Jersey Nets are going to break
out the first non-tank-top jersey in NBA history for their game
Thursday. It'll look more like that sleek sleeveless V-neck that
the University of Cincinnati wears. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Shaq is supposed to appear at a fashion trade show later this
month when his TWISM sportswear line is relaunched. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ According to some who care, Vancouver Raptors rookie guard
Vince Carter might have the best odds in the ``Next Jordan'' race.
Just three problems: a) he's in Vancouver, b) he's in Vancouver,
and c) can't shake this image of him screaming at Gomer Pyle. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ !racpay!Spike Lee's new movie, ``Love and Basketball,'' has
Keyshawn ``Just Give Me the Damn Cue'' Johnson reading for the lead
role since the New York Jets receiver quit work on the Oliver Stone
flick ``Any Given Sunday,'' reports the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's agent, Jerome Stanley, said KeyJ wasn't happy with
Stone because ``the character was ill-defined.'' Or was it more
that he felt neglected sitting around on the set all day without
being used. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Next up in the Flutie Flakes-raise-money-for-my-foundation
drive is Cal Ripken Jr. launching a ``limited-edition cereal'' in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Which will be followed up Reggie Jackson's bean-filled toys
called ``Mr. Octobears'' to raise dough for his kids group. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Now if they can only figure out a way to hold a World Match
Play championship so that the final four isn't Magee College vs.
the University of Huston and Maggert A&AMP;M vs. UPate. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Golf's newest attraction should be Senior PGAer Allen Doyle,
whose slapshot style has to conjure thoughts of Happy Gilmore. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ Andre Agassi admits in Tennis magazine that one of the
biggest mistakes he's ever made was doing that ``Image Is
Everything'' commercial for Canon. ``That really misrepresented who
I am at a fundamental level,'' said Mr. Shields. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Jamir Jagr garage sale update: The Pittsburgh Penguins have
told creditors they've lost $90 million over the last three seasons
and expect to lose another $20 million more next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
