<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL BOMBS LEBANON AFTER A GENERAL IS KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel conducted an aerial bombardment Sunday night
of what it said were four Party of God guerrilla strongholds deep
inside Lebanon, stung into action by a week of attacks that
culminated in the killing of a general and three other Israelis in
southern Lebanon earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The airstrikes took the conflict away from the Israeli-Lebanon
border and into the heart of Lebanon, risking an escalation of
ping-pong attacks between the Israeli army and the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy bombing ended a day of intense conflict in the
low-level war in South Lebanon, beginning with unsuccessful rocket
attacks on northern Israel. The final catalyst for their attack,
Israeli officials said, was a roadside bomb Sunday morning that
killed the four Israelis, including Brig. Gen. Erez Gerstein, 36,
who became the highest-ranking officer to die in southern Lebanon
in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist, Ilan Roeh, 32, of Voice of Israel Radio, was also
among those killed. He was accompanying the general in order to
``see things up close,'' his boss, Shalom Oren, said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear late Sunday night what toll Israel's bombing
raids had taken, and whether there were any civilian casualties. At
midnight, Israel's Channel Two television reported at least 10
dead, citing Lebanese media reports.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting counterattacks, the army ordered residents of northern
Israel to report to shelters, and Qiryat Shemona, the northernmost
town, emptied out on Sunday night, as residents fled south or took
refuge underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight you hear the thunder of jets coming back from inside
Lebanon,'' said Army Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz at a 9:15 p.m.
press conference in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Mofaz said that fighter planes struck Party of God headquarters
in the heart of the Bekaa Valley city of Baalbek and three other
targets, all of which were chosen because they were ``pure
Hezbollah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest we wait until the pilots land and for our
investigation to get clear answers,'' Mofaz said. ``But the planes
carried out their mission well. There were good hits on the
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning's roadside bomb was the second serious blow to
the Israeli army in less than a week in southern Lebanon, following
a guerrilla ambush that left three elite unit officers dead last
Tuesday. The ambush, in which Hezbollah fighters attacked Israeli
paratroopers with machine guns and grenades, was unusual in that it
involved direct conflict rather than bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush had revived the episodic political debate here over
Israel's longstanding military presence in southern Lebanon. Israel
has occupied a nine-mile-deep border zone in southern Lebanon since
1985 to protect its northern towns.
</P>
<P>
   Along the border and inside Lebanon, the Israeli army skirmishes
daily with Hezbollah, or Shiite Muslim, guerrillas, who are backed
by Iran, with weapons supplied through Syria. With each year,
Israel has faced increasing pressure, internationally and at home,
to withdraw its troops.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly volatile when a fresh wave of deaths
takes place during an election campaign, as is happening now.
Public pressure builds for the Israeli government to act: to
withdraw troops unilaterally; to pursue peace negotiations with the
Syrians, who effectively control Lebanon; or to conduct heavy
airstrikes in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Elections often bring out an incumbent's urge to be bold. Sunday
night's raids will inevitably be seen as partly a political move by
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, an effort to strengthen
his image as a tough defender of Israel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1996, during the last campaign, Shimon Peres began a
retaliatory battle with Hezbollah that became a troubled
16-day-long air assault in which about 200 Lebanese citizens were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not seek a deterioration of the situation in Lebanon,''
Netanyahu said Sunday night. ``But we cannot accept what is
happening there. We cannot accept these losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was putting northern Israel at risk, Netanyahu said,
``People in the north say: `Don't worry about us; we'll manage. Go
ahead. Beat up on them. We're willing to sit in the shelters.' If
we don't act, things will get much worse. If we were to sit with
our hands folded across our chests, then I would fear for the
northern settlements.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup opinion poll published on Friday found that 63 percent
of those surveyed did not believe the Netanyahu government was
doing enough to resolve the situation in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombing was made public Sunday night, Linda Ben Zvi,
a spokeswoman for the Fourth Mothers' Movement to Leave Lebanon,
said she feared that the government's reaction would be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing our boys home in boxes, so we can't think in
terms of macho and pride,'' she said. ``It was a failed policy from
the beginning, and the longer it gets, the clearer it gets, and the
higher the price we're paying. We should unilaterally withdraw, and
then, like every other country, defend ourselves from within our
own borders.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Sunday night what Israel planned militarily
beyond the initial airstrikes. At the 9:15 p.m. conference, Defense
Minister Moshe Arens, Netanyahu and Mofaz all said they would not
back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's response will not be the last if the situation
doesn't change,'' Arens said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
