<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BODE-MEDIA-ART-540     02-28 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BODE-MEDIA-ART-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER `WASHINGTON WEEK IN REVIEW' HOST WAS JUST GETTING HIS COAT
ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Iowa, N.C., Mich.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The irony, said Ken Bode, munching on chips and
salsa on an afternoon when he would normally have been at work, was
that he had planned to give up his Washington gig anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Commuting here from Evanston, Ill., where he is dean of the
Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University, to be the
host of ``Washington Week in Review,'' meant spending two and a
half days a week away from his wife, and he was tired of missing
her.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to renegotiate his contract for the PBS
program, he said, ``I was going to say, `Let's do this for one last
year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, that won't be necessary. After clashing with a
new boss who thought the show's quiet discussions of targeted tax
cuts and Kosovo needed a little more edge and attitude, Bode was
pushed out last week and had to tune in from a friend's place and
watch his fill-in smile and thank him for his five years of
service.
</P>
<P>
   He had wanted to go on one last time and, before saying ``So
long,'' get a panel of four Pulitzer Prize winners talking about
the nature of punditry, the argument culture and the ``TV
wasteland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make Tom Friedman come on and say what he thinks about
Clinton's morals!'' Bode said of the New York Times columnist, one
of his regulars. ``He talks about the collapse of the Asian
economy, and if that's too dull, OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward news reporters, who are supposed to be
objective, loudly sharing their opinions all over television has
been a concern of Bode's for years. A decade ago, as a political
correspondent for NBC News, he asked his bureau chief to forbid him
to go on ``The McLaughlin Group'' because he did not have the
stomach for what he calls ``that food fight.''
</P>
<P>
   One small comfort is that Bode (pronounced BO-dee), 59, appears
to have beaten back ``attitude.'' For now, he has probably saved
the show from such proposed improvements as visiting high school
journalists and man-on-the-street interviews.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of bad publicity and questions about whether even
public television now requires journalists to break chairs over one
another's heads, the program's producer, WETA-TV, has made clear it
won't be fiddling with the format. WETA even announced that for a
few months the host will be Paul Duke, who was moderator for 20
years and makes Bode look like Geraldo.
</P>
<P>
   Bode seems hurt, certainly, and a bit at loose ends. After a
long lunch, he seems to feel there ought to be some place to hurry
off to. But it is also clear that the real compensation for him is
that he has a life to go back to.
</P>
<P>
   His friends tell you right off he's not one of these
ultra-driven Washington types who thinks a night off television is
dead air _ as do, frankly, a couple of his regular guests, who in
interviews seemed quite moved by the nobility of their sacrifice in
staying off Friday's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's outstanding, but he also seems normal,'' said Elizabeth
Piersol, Bode's producer, who was also dismissed, apparently for
remaining loyal to him. She called him ``the person I've worked
with with the most integrity,'' adding, almost by way of
explanation, ``He doesn't have to live here full time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Which is how he wanted it. Ten years ago, in the prime of his
career as a national political correspondent, Bode quit and moved
his family to Indiana so he could spend more time with them. At the
time, he says, laughing, even they didn't really get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me one day. I was in Boston debating Pat Robertson on
journalism ethics and I had to get home because my daughter was
giving the commencement address for her sixth-grade class. I called
her and told her I'd be there. Then you know how you put the phone
down and it rings right away? It was the New York desk saying, `On
Friday I need this piece.' I said, `I'll do it, but after the
commencement.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew then,'' he said, ``that my problem was, I've got the
best job but I've also got one chance to be a father, and I'm
losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bode grew up in Hawarden, Iowa, where his family owned a small
dairy that went under when milk bottles gave way to cartons. He
earned a doctorate in political science from the University of
North Carolina and taught at Michigan State and the State
University of New York at Binghamton before moving into journalism.
Soon after his epiphany in Boston, he returned to academia, to
build a broadcast journalism program at DePauw University and to
raise his family in Greencastle, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   They were not immediately grateful. ``I was on a bike ride with
my 11-year-old, and she's crying. Finally, she says, `Dad, I think
it's a big comedown to go from being a Washington national
correspondent for NBC to teaching where Dan Quayle went to
college.'''
</P>
<P>
   But she came around, and both daughters ended up loving Indiana,
where they collected ``19 varsity letters between the two of
them,'' he brags, and he spent evenings in school gyms. Last year,
with both girls at Kenyon College, he took the Northwestern job.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the ugliness of the last week, it is hard to feel
sorry for Bode when he talks about how his family reacted. His
daughter Matilda, president of her senior class, sent flowers. His
daughter Josie, captain of the rugby team, wrote, ``Tell me the
name of this guy. I've got a bunch of pals.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Margo, a writer and designer of educational materials
for children who are learning disabled, penned a love letter. ``She
said, `We are starting another new phase together. Let's have
fun.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
