<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER FRESH START FOR DAVEY JOHNSON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Md, Calif.)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ He's back, after yet another year of
involuntary leave. Well, officially he resigned from his job with
the Baltimore Orioles, but Davey Johnson opted for that path rather
than wait to be fired, which would inevitably have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson nearly missed gaining his new job. He was hired a couple
of weeks after Felipe Alou rejected it, deciding instead to remain
with the Montreal Expos. So Johnson is wearing Dodger Blue, or gray
(Saturday's workout uniform of the day) or white (Monday's).
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I have been envious of guys like Walter Alston and
Tommy Lasorda, who made their careers in one spot,'' Johnson said
of two of his predecessors, who managed the Dodgers for a combined
43 years. ``But I've been blessed in that I've had the opportunity
to manage some great Mets teams and some great athletes in
Cincinnati and Baltimore. Now I've got a fine club here.''
</P>
<P>
   An expensive club, to be sure. How fine? He will find out as the
season progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the infusion of Rupert Murdoch's money, the Fox-owned
Dodgers have been the talk of the off season, mostly critical talk.
Kevin Brown's $105 million contract has been the object of most of
the criticism, but contrary to popular belief, the nouveau riche
Dodgers are still pikers compared with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   With 22 players signed by each team, the Dodgers have a $77.5
million payroll, the Yankees $86.7 million _ although at those
rates, who wants to quibble over a few million here or there?
</P>
<P>
   The point is that General Manager Kevin Malone, backed by Fox's
desire to have a championship team, has positioned the Dodgers for
a run at not only a division title but also something beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Brown, Malone has added Devon White in center field and
Todd Hundley behind the plate, plus the relief pitchers Alan Mills,
Mel Rojas and Greg Cadaret, to go with the holdover newcomers from
last season: Gary Sheffield, who will play left field while Raul
Mondesi returns to right; Mark Grudzielanek, who is competing with
Jose Vizcaino for the shortstop's job; the starting pitchers Carlos
Perez and Dave Mlicki, and the closer Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the financial resources Fox brings to the table, it
allows this team to go into spring training with as much experience
as we've had since I've been here,'' said first baseman Eric
Karros, who, with seven years, is the team's senior member. ``All
of the positions except for third base have experience. In the
past, because of payroll constraints, you'd have a couple young
guys, unproven guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman is Adrian Beltre, who will celebrate his 21st
birthday the day of the team's third game of the season. He batted
only .215 in 77 games for Los Angeles last season, but Johnson is
intent on having him in the lineup instead of the more veteran Dave
Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third base is settled as far as I'm concerned,'' Johnson said.
``I'm impressed with this kid. I'm glad the general manager and the
people in the front office like to go with a young player. I like
to help them get established. I like young players to step up. It
gives energy to ball clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   When a young player from a team's minor league system makes the
major league team, Johnson said, it excites the other players in
the system. ``I like that,'' he said. ``I'm going to do everything
I can to make it easy for him to establish himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, though, is not the team's biggest question mark. That
punctuation is reserved for Hundley, whose surgically repaired
right elbow could hold the key to how far the Dodgers go. Hundley
himself said the elbow is fine, and Johnson concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was a gamble we could make,'' Johnson said. ``We
needed more left-handed bats and a left-handed bat to protect
Sheffield. It was really a no-brainer gamble. It was something you
had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, Hundley's elbow does not hold up under
the stress of daily throwing to second base to get runners who will
surely test him, the Dodgers have as replacements only the kind of
young players Johnson said he likes. Between them, Angel Pena and
Paul LoDuca, who was born in Brooklyn 14 years after the Dodgers
left, have 12 games of major league experience.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson sees Hundley making a strong comeback from a season
in which he was willing to humiliate himself by playing the
outfield for the Mets, just to be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's kind of driven, if you want to know the truth,''
Johnson said. ``For a lot of reasons, maybe several million reasons
involving New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has 105 million reasons driving him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the contract will be that big a deal,'' said the
right-hander, who has pitched in the past two World Series with two
teams. ``All the hubbub about the contract will be there to a
degree, but once we get started the emphasis will be on what we do
as a team. The contract isn't going to change what I do as a
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, like his No. 1 pitcher, has been a winner. He leads all
active managers with a .575 winning percentage, and the 10 teams he
has managed for entire seasons have finished first (six times) or
second. Yet he keeps getting time off, two years between New York
and Cincinnati, one year between Baltimore and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stress in this job can age you,'' Johnson said, seeking
something positive in the periodic interruptions to his managerial
career. ``I've been very fortunate that I've been healthy. And I
had a year off from being second-guessed.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
