<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-N     02-28 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTFUL WORKOUT ON THE STAIRMASTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This city declared a snow emergency on Thursday, and
the opening of a four-day engagement by Mark Morris' company was
canceled at the Wang Center for the Performing Arts. Such are the
vagaries of living in a car culture.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday night, the theater was packed for two fresh and
vigorous premieres on a program billed as Mark Morris Dance Group
and Yo-Yo Ma. The pieces are very different.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston premiere of ``Falling Down Stairs,'' which Morris
has adapted from choreography for a film, his dancers actually do
fall down steps and perform a staircase dance that Bill (Bojangles)
Robinson would admire.
</P>
<P>
   In the world premiere, ``The Argument,'' three couples in search
of a marriage counselor finally make peace. The latter work, which
featured Mikhail Baryshnikov as a guest, was the crowd pleaser; it
is clever and witty. But ``Falling Down Stairs,'' more legible in
its broad strokes of movement, is richly textured and one of
Morris' best works in years, largely because it is so original.
</P>
<P>
   Ma, the cello soloist in ``Falling Down Stairs'' and playing
with the pianist Ethan Iverson in ``The Argument,'' was onstage in
both works. He was in the pit for the familiar ``Rhymes With
Silver,'' set to Lou Harrison's music. Ma was the living link among
the works, but there is another link between the two newest pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Both are set to dance forms, although they are very different in
style and period. Bach's Baroque dance forms in his Third Suite for
Unaccompanied Cello are virtually unacknowledged as such by Morris
in ``Falling Down Stairs.'' But the folk dances evoked in
Schumann's ``Five Pieces in Folk Style'' get an occasional
good-natured nod in ``The Argument.'' Nonetheless, there are no
rustic lads and lasses among the three combative and sophisticated
urban couples here, despite an occasional mock mazurka.
</P>
<P>
   One might say that Morris is working against the music in ``The
Argument,'' and that in ``Falling Down Stairs'' he is working with
it in an oblique way. He captures the shifting mood of the Baroque
dances in the Bach suite; his sculptured groupings translate the
gravity, for instance, of the suite's stately sarabande.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the program was indeed ``Falling Down Stairs.'' If
Morris and Ma have embarked on what looks like a good humored
journey in compatibility, it is thanks to Ma's initiative.
``Falling Down Stairs'' was originally choreographed by Morris for
one of six films that Ma commissioned for ``Yo-Yo Ma, Inspired by
Bach,'' a series of videos that explore Bach's Six Suites for
Unaccompanied Cello.
</P>
<P>
   The stage version, performed only once before, in Berkeley,
Calif., in 1997, will be seen at a single performance at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music on March 30. Baryshnikov will perform
that night, but unlike Ma will not tour with the company to other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   To consider a musician of Ma's stature an accompanist in this
context would be unjust and misleading. Because he is part of the
show when he is onstage, it is easy to see how invigorated he is by
the dancers' response to his playing. The physical proximity of the
music creates less of a distance between sound and movement than is
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Morris used the descending scale as a conceit for his opening
image. Most of the 15 dancers on a set of bleacher-style steps turn
to the audience and fall prone. Isaac Mizrahi's costumes, velvet
robes that range from long to very short, reveal the bare-legged
dancers' undies during their frequent leaps, runs and tilts. But
under Michael Chybowski's grand lighting, the rich hues of the
velvet suggest a social mix of the courtly and the cloistered: a
polite orgy in a cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The suite's prelude suggests a series of simultaneous solos and
introduces the falling, running and rising motifs of the
choreography. Often some dancers are on the floor while others rise
and thrust up a fist.
</P>
<P>
   The allemande section is the closest to a Baroque pattern. The
dancers perform several line dances. But even here there is some
hearty arm swinging, the same sense of unruliness. The courante
brings in several trios and small circling groups before there is a
wonderful onrush of chain dances that end in revolving swirls and
whirlpools. A dancer is tossed up.
</P>
<P>
   The sarabande is slow and the choreography concentrates on
dancers moving arms while rooted to one spot. The dancers pose in
groups and at the end a woman holds her arms out atop the steps.
The bourree is humorous and an exercise in structure. Nine dancers,
divided into trios on the tiered steps, move their palms in
prayerlike gestures in unison, and finally in canon. In between, a
group below is set loose.
</P>
<P>
   The closing gigue is the staircase dance done with two or four
dancers running up and down at different times as the ensemble
below turns and whips around. At the top of the stairs, three men
eventually strike a woman in slow motion until she shoots up, her
arms out in an instant resurrection. Below, the populace raises
fists and runs out, vanquished by the final image.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Argument'' starts off with Morris running in and out and
then Marjorie Folkman, marvelously supercilious, in a combative
duet with Baryshnikov in the kind of male chauvinist pig role he
had in Twyla Tharp's ``Nine Sinatra Songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, as there, he grabs a partner's arm and she throws him off.
The choreography is straightforward and both dancers are
wonderfully understated.
</P>
<P>
   If Baryshnikov, in a black turtleneck, looks gaunt and austere,
Morris, virtually popping out of his shirt, looks cheerfully portly
as he embraces Tina Fehlandt to a slower folk tune. The dance is
less hostile but the movement quirkier. Ruth Davidson and Shawn
Gannon have the tantrum duet, full of stamps and fist shaking. It
is the eye-catching section and very well performed, right up to
the momentary truce of a waltz.
</P>
<P>
   There is a section for two overlapping pairs and one in which
Morris, still the best dancer in his company, offers an arm-waving
generic folk dance until a reprise of the first section's music
assembles the entire cast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
