<HEADLINE>
BABY, I TOLD YOU THISN'T SUCH A GREAT IDEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, conceive a baby this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   If you're a USC or UCLA football fan with Internet access, you
should have known better. You probably won't make it to this year's
Trojans-Bruins clash on Nov. 20 _ or in about 266 days.
</P>
<P>
   A ``sports event conflict catcher and conception blocker'' at a
Web site called The Baby Center
(http://www.babycenter.com/conflicts) is supposed to inform
parents-to-be which of 3,000 sporting events they'll likely miss as
the result of a conception within a particular time frame.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not convinced the game will interfere with the
delivery, the site also has a link to Mapquest that gives detailed
instructions and a map from whatever sporting venue you'll be at to
the nearest hospital.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Fantasy Sports Players Association, a nonprofit trade
organization that wants to protect consumer rights for fantasy
leagues, has what amounts to a fantasy baseball seminar this
weekend in Tampa Fla., that can be accessed through several Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The FSPA site (http://www.fantasysportspa.com) is one place to
start. Also check the site of the United Sports Fans of America
(http://www.usfans.com) and The Fantasy Sports Search Engine
(http://www.usfantasy411.com).
</P>
<P>
   __ A home-study radio play-by-play sportscasting course taught
by Pepperdine basketball play-by-play man Al Epstein and longtime
voice coach and sports broadcaster Lou Riggs is part of the
curriculum offered on the Virginia-based Columbia School of
Broadcasting site (http:/columbiaschoolbroadcas.com/sports4.htm).
</P>
</TEXT>
