<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YESTERDAY: GIBSON DIDN'T GET JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of event from the
book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Most Memorable Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis):
</P>
<P>
   __ March 1, 1940: At Gilmore Stadium in Hollywood, Los Angeles'
own Hammerin' Henry Armstrong seeks his fourth different
weight-division championship. But a 10-round draw against Ceferino
Garcia means Garcia keeps his middleweight title.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 2, 1940: In what turns out to be his final race, the
legendary Seabiscuit rallies to win the sixth-ever Santa Anita
Handicap. He does it in a track record of 2:01 1/5 for the mile and
a quarter in front of more than 68,000 spectators, some of whom saw
him break down in a race a year earlier that nearly ended his
career. (94).
</P>
<P>
   __ March 3, 1985: Willie Shoemaker becomes the first jockey to
pass the $100 million mark in career earnings, riding Lord at War
to victory in the Santa Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 3, 1984: Peter Ueberroth, president of the L.A. Olympic
Organizing Committee, is elected to replace Bowie Kuhn as the sixth
commissioner of Major League Baseball after the '84 Summer Olympics
are finished. He stays in office five years.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 3, 1988: Newcomer Kirk Gibson storms out of the
Dodgers' Vero Beach training camp for a day, upset because teammate
Jesse Orosco played a practical joke on him _ the old
eye-black-in-the-hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 4, 1950: Johnny Longden rides Noor to an American track
record of 2:52 4/5 at Santa Anita and, more impressively, to a win
by inches over the legendary Citation in the San Juan Capistrano
Handicap before 58,730.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 5, 1994: At the refurbished 70-year-old Grand Olympic
Auditorium, Oscar De La Hoya wins a 10-round TKO against Jimmi
Bredahl for his first professional belt, the WBO's junior
lightweight title. It is De La Hoya's 12th pro fight. (97)
</P>
<P>
   __ March 5, 1984: Signing an unheard of $40 million contract,
Steve Young becomes property of the USFL's Los Angeles Express,
which makes him, as well as agent Leigh Steinberg, a bit of a
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 6, 1983: The USFL opens its first spring season with
five games, including the Express losing to the New Jersey Generals
and Herschel Walker at the Coliseum before more than 34,000.
</P>
<P>
   __ March 7, 1969: Wilt Chamberlain establishes a Lakers
franchise record with 42 rebounds in a game against Boston.
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays: Wednesday: Former Dodgers reliever Scott Radinsky
(31); Friday: Former UCLA basketball star Michael Warren (53).
Saturday: Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal (27). Sunday: Former USC
football star Lynn Swann (47) and Angels and Ducks head man Michael
Eisner (57). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
