<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remlinger seeks control, stability
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ To say this is a fresh start for Mike
Remlinger is redundant.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old left-hander has spent his entire career bouncing
around from place to place, and it was only two years ago that
Remlinger became a full-time major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   He was a first-round draft pick of the Giants after leaving
Dartmouth College. Since then, he's been traded four times and
played in 11 cities in the minors and majors, from Phoenix to
Calgary, Seattle to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But this move to Atlanta _ which came as part of the Denny
Neagle for Bret Boone deal _ feels different.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I went to Atlanta for Camp Leo, just meeting the
people I met there, I finally feel comfortable,'' Remlinger said.
``I feel at home. The attitude of the players, the staff, the
people of Atlanta just driving around looking for a place to stay,
people were real friendly. Basically everything is geared toward
one thing and that's winning. To me that's been my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   So have control problems.
</P>
<P>
   He has long been known for having good pitches _ a curveball,
two different fastballs and a changeup he's developed in the past
several years. But he has failed to consistently getting them over
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger was Cincinnati's Opening Day starter last year, but by
the end of the season he was back in the bullpen after winning only
five of his last 18 decisions. He finished with an 8-15 record and
a 4.82 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati did give him the chance to pitch 80-100 more innings
than he would have if he'd been a reliever all year. But when his
name came up in trade talks, he was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger had heard Philadelphia, Seattle and Tampa Bay
mentioned as possibilities, but the end result was what he liked
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with enough organizations to know the grass isn't
always greener,'' Remlinger said. ``This is ideal for me. Stay in
the National League, have the best pitching staff in baseball. Guys
you have to work with every day, just watch and learn. Plus having
a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't start, unless Kevin Millwood or Bruce Chen falters or
someone gets hurt. But for Remlinger, that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I need to do, whatever they ask me to do, I don't
care because I'm going to help this team win,'' Remlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   He said part of his past problems came from wanting to do too
much, and playing for a team like Atlanta, he won't feel like he
has to. Plus he'll be around two of the best control pitchers in
baseball in Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That alone will make a big difference,'' Remlinger said.
``Watching those guys and learning from them, their habits, what
they do to keep themselves in that groove or what they do to get
back into it if they're a little bit off.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger also sought some advice for his control problems this
offseason, though he didn't want to say from whom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a point where I wasn't happy to just be here and just
getting by,'' Remlinger said. ``What I'd seen myself do at times
was what I felt I should do all the time. I feel like people who
are saying `You could be one of the best lefties in the National
League' are right. So to myself I said, `What do I need to do to
get there?' For me it all comes down to focus and concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I'm going to pitch as well as I've ever pitched
before,'' he said. ``I've shown flashes of it in the past. So it's
not a question of whether I can do it, it's a question of whether I
can do it time and time again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
