<SLUG> BC-IOC-EXPULSIONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Implicated IOC members deny wrongdoing
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The top International Olympic Committee
official investigating the Salt Lake bidding scandal said Sunday it
was urgent that the committee end the crisis to ``stop the
bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking fatigued as he returned to his hotel from a second day
of closed-door meetings over the scandal, Dick Pound, the IOC
member from Canada, said his inquiry was not yet finished even
though it had hoped to wrap up its work Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to discuss details of the inquiry but said his
commission will probably complete its report within a week and send
its recommendations to the IOC executive board. The board can
exonerate members, warn them or ask for their expulsion by a vote
of the full IOC membership at an emergency session scheduled March
17-18.
</P>
<P>
   Pound's commission has spent more than two months reviewing
allegations related to Salt Lake's successful bid for the 2002
Winter Game. So far, 24 members _ a fifth of the committee's
membership _ have been implicated. Pound's commission thus far has
recommended the expulsion of nine members, four of whom have
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials have indicated that few of the remaining members
under investigation have done anything to merit expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday if he was feeling pressure to conclude the
investigation, Pound wearily nodded yes. ``We've got to stop the
bleeding by March 17,'' he said. ``This death by a thousand wounds
isn't much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three members appeared Sunday before the inquiry
commission, which met under tight security at Olympic headquarters
here. Phil Coles of Australia, Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador, and
Ashwini Kumar of India each told the six-member commission that he
had done nothing to violate IOC ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo, who has been recommended for expulsion, said he spent a
half hour with the commission and expressed optimism that he would
be reinstated. ``I told them the truth, which is my habit,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a January report, Pound's commission said Arroyo and his
daughter accepted payments from the Salt Lake bidding committee.
Arroyo said the allegations were false.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar, who was accused of improperly accepting a plane ticket
from the bidding committee from a relative, also said he has been
falsely accused.
</P>
<P>
   Coles, appearing with his lawyer, denied charges he made four
unauthorized visits to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Salt Lake ethics panel reported that the IOC
members or their families benefited from more than $1.2 million in
cash, travel, medical care and other improper inducements.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
