</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-REPORT-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER AND FEAR STILL STALK GUATEMALAN SURVIVORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICHICASTENANGO, Guatemala _ Ana Morales, 80, walks one hour
each day to an exhumation site here in the highlands, and one hour
back. Curled up in her multicolor Quiche Indian dress and shawl,
she sits on the edge of a road off a main highway, but rises to her
feet whenever a team of anthropologists makes a find _ a sock, a
bone, a set of teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Her only goal now, she said, is to find a son who was abducted
while working as a street vendor in Guatemala City in 1981. He was
the second son she lost in the more than 30 years of civil war here
that left 200,000 Guatemalans dead or missing.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the first one, who, Mrs. Morales, said was
bludgeoned with a shovel by people who accused him of being a
guerrilla, was left for her to claim and give a proper burial.
Exactly what happened to her second son, she may never know.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when a truth commission blamed the Guatemalan
government for acts of genocide against the Mayan people during the
war, it sought to nurture national unity by offering the first
official acknowledgment of the atrocities committed in the
conflict, which ended with a peace accord between the government
and guerrillas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But even now, for thousands of survivors like Mrs. Morales, the
idea of reconciliation remains abstract. The war is over, they say,
but the effort to trace loved ones and to bring those responsible
for their deaths to justice goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assassins are alive, with their families, and I lost two
children,'' Mrs. Morales said, speaking through a Quiche
interpreter. ``I want to know who killed my children. I want to
know the face of the assassins.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission found that the military and allied paramilitary
groups were to blame for an overwhelming majority of abuses during
the war, and that the political and judicial systems acted as
accomplices. It cited instances of gross cruelty, including the
killing of children, and said civilians had often been forced by
the army at gun point to rape, mutilate and kill.
</P>
<P>
   The department of Quiche, in Guatemala's west, was a major site
of massacres during the war, and the ``truth'' spoken by the
commission simply put an official seal on what many here had
already seen.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, among the small crowd gathered around two pits where
forensic scientists dug up remains of some of the Guatemalans left
buried in hundreds of clandestine cemeteries scattered around the
country, those looking for children, parents and husbands said they
welcomed the report for vindicating the victims and bringing the
world's attention to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission contributed to spreading the word about what
happened in Guatemala so that the tragedy is not repeated,'' said
Isabela Mejia, 45, who said her husband was fatally shot during a
1981 army incursion as he sought refuge in the mountains. ``My hope
is that my children never have to live through that again.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Guatemala tries to repair itself, fear remains among
the Mayan people who make up about 60 percent of the country's
population. It was they who suffered most during the war, the
commission found, largely because of institutional racism and
because the Guatemalan army saw them as natural allies of the
Communist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Morales, who said she saw neighbors killed in a 1982
massacre and was forced out of her home for two years during
``scorched earth'' operations that wiped out entire Mayan
communities, still cringes when she runs into soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen all over again because the army is always on
the road,'' she said. ``I saw it with my own eyes that they killed
people. We are waiting for the army detail to withdraw. There's
peace, but the army is still in our community. When I see them, I
still feel like running.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sara Vazquez, a board member with a victim's group called Group
of Mutual Support, which is assisting in the exhumations, said she
last saw her husband in 1984, when neighbors saw two armed men
throw him into the back of a Jeep. A few hours later, three dozen
military police officers stormed her house, she said, telling her
that they were acting on a call accusing her husband of harboring
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Ms. Vazquez, 39, says she has not told her three
adult children the truth about their father, who was a 24-year-old
labor organizer when he disappeared. Instead, seeking to keep them
from vengeance and the bitterness that consumes her, she has
convinced them that he left the family for another woman. ``I don't
want them to be resentful,'' she said. ``I'd rather have them think
their father abandoned them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vazquez keeps searching for her husband even though five
years ago she started a new family and now has a fourth child with
her boyfriend. She criticized the truth commission for not giving
the names of the military officials responsible for criminal acts.
She scoffed at its recommendation that President Alvaro Arzu
Irigoyen and the ex-guerrilla commanders assume responsibility in
the name of the state and ask all Guatemalans for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forgive assassins,'' she said, breaking down.
``They left my home disintegrated. I want them to tell me where my
husband is. After 15 years of struggling to find out, I haven't
achieved anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said it was too late for official apologies since the
military governments that caused the most suffering are no longer
in power. Some were also skeptical of the commission's call for
reparations. Although some victims' groups are seeking compensation
for material losses and ``moral damages,'' some here said they
doubted that a government that has neglected its poor population
for so long would now make any meaningful amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it would happen,'' said Ana Albatian, 25, who
came here with two of four children in tow searching for her
missing father. ``What for? So that we forget our loved ones?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day there will be social justice, but we have to get
organized and fight for it,'' she added. ``And there has to be
international pressure for the Government to abide by the peace
accords.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mayan people, their suffering is all the greater, as
they believe that a body must be given proper burial before the
spirit can progress to the next world. That is why Mrs. Morales,
who lives with her three other children, has traveled here for
years looking for her missing son, who was 40 when she last saw
him. ``I don't know whether he's alive or dead,'' she said. ``I
have to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is dead, she said, she worries that his body could have
been thrown into a river or a down a ravine and that his spirit is
not at rest. She wants to be able to bury him in a cemetery and
bring him flowers. Only then, she said, could she herself die in
peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
