A2417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-GULF-NYT &LR;      02-28 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GULF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANSHEE BREEZE WINS EASILY AS 2 STAR FILLIES ARE WITHDRAWN FROM
RAMPART HANDICAP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The Rampart Handicap fell apart as a prime
test for star fillies Sunday when Harpia was withdrawn because she
didn't seem frisky, and later when the speed filly Lines of Beauty
was scratched and Angel of a Mom unseated her jockey during the
post parade and was also withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gulfstream Park was left with James Tafel's Banshee Breeze,
last year's champion 3-year-old filly, who stepped smartly forward
in her 1999 debut and flew home 5{ lengths in front of Glitter
Woman to win the Rampart.
</P>
<P>
   Banshee Breeze did it after her trainer, Carl Nafzger, said she
would be operating at 95 percent of her customary form. She had not
raced since November, when she ran second by a nose to Escena in
the Breeders' Cup Distaff. But before that, she had clicked off
victories in the Coaching Club American Oaks, the Spinster and the
Alabama, and closed the year by winning 6 times in 10 starts and by
running in the money all 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was impressive today,'' said Nafzger, who also trained
Banshee Breeze's sire, Unbridled, winner of the 1990 Kentucky
Derby. ``There wasn't anybody in there. I wanted Harpia in there
for the speed. I'm disappointed for anyone who couldn't run. I know
how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the wave of scratches, the field was cut to five
fillies and the only one with a true chance of outrunning the star:
Glitter Woman, who had run in the money in 20 of her 21 races. But
the scratches removed the two fillies expected to show early speed
and force the issue: Harpia, who had won her last five starts, and
Angel of a Mom, who had won 5 of 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought this morning that the speed horses
would both be scratched?'' said Mike Smith, the rider on Glitter
Woman. ``I had no choice but to go to the lead. I tried to set a
slow pace, and I had a horse left when the winner challenged me.
But my horse just wasn't good enough. After all, that other horse
is a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Shug McGaughey, who trains Glitter Woman, agreed. ``The race
changed with the scratches,'' McGaughey said. ``She got beat by a
good horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, who switched off his regular ride on Glitter Woman
to ride Banshee Breeze, said: ``It was a champion-type race, and
that's what she is. Just awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Banshee Breeze loped along easily, while Glitter Woman inherited
the early lead from the missing speed horses. She ran second after
half a mile, still second after three-quarters. Then, as they
turned for home, Bailey reached for his whip but never used it.
Banshee Breeze shot into the lead and beat Glitter Woman, who had
four lengths on Timely Broad.
</P>
<P>
   The winner ran the mile and a sixteenth in 1:42 4/5, paid $3.20
for a $2 bet to win and added $120,000 to a bankroll that passed
$1.5 million. Next, Nafzger said, she will continue her pursuit of
another championship in the Apple Blossom at Oaklawn Park on April
10.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
