<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TRANSPLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BREAK WITH TRADITION, JAPAN ALLOWS TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For the first time in Japan, doctors performed a legal
heart transplant on Sunday, striking at a taboo on taking organs
from patients whom Japanese traditionally do not consider dead.
</P>
<P>
   As 100 reporters watched on closed-circuit television, doctors
removed an ailing heart from a man in his 40s and stitched in a
healthy one. The operation was an ethical and emotional milestone
in a country that has long believed that death comes only after the
heart stops beating and the body turns cold.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, Japan was locked in a fiery debate over
transplants and was pondering the definition of death. Many
Japanese feel uneasy about defining brain death as the end of life,
and doctors usually continue to treat patients as long as their
hearts are still beating.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the developed world, however, a person is considered
dead if the brain stops functioning, when healthy organs can still
be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese Parliament passed a law in 1997 permitting doctors
to remove organs from brain-dead patients, and compromised on the
definition of death, saying that brain-dead patients would be
considered dead only if they had specified that they wanted to
donate their organs. But the law had not been applied until
Sunday's heart transplant, which is only the second in Japan's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Juro Wada performed the first 31 years ago in a legally
ambiguous environment, and when the recipient died, the doctor was
accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, thousands of Japanese have flown overseas to
get transplants, or have simply died.
</P>
<P>
   In the first stage of Sunday's operation, doctors at the Kochi
Red Cross Hospital in western Japan removed the heart, liver and
kidneys from the brain-dead patient, the nation's first legal organ
donor, who was in a coma after suffering a stroke and a brain
hemorrhage. Details about the donor, even sex and age, are being
kept confidential until after the funeral, at the request of the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The recovering heart recipient spoke a few words at a university
hospital in Osaka, where his operation was performed.
</P>
<P>
   The liver went to a 43-year-old resident of Nagano, in Japan's
first such transplant. The kidneys are going to people in the south
and north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
