<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS FLEE TO KOSOVO BORDER TO ESCAPE ARMY'S SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENERAL JANKOVIC, Yugoslavia _ More than 2,000 people fled their
villages during heavy fighting in southern Kosovo Sunday and
swamped a major border post in a desperate effort to cross over to
safety in neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav army artillery and anti-aircraft guns could be heard
battering the mountainous region west of the border post of Deneral
Jankovic in the late afternoon. It was the most serious fighting in
the Serbian province since the peace talks with ethnic Albanian
separatists ended inconclusively last week. Serbia is one of two
provinces in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign observers trying to monitor a cease-fire in Kosovo for
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe have
watched the army move large amounts of armor and troops into the
border region in recent days. Now they seem to be putting it to use
to clear and take control of a swathe of territory along the border
and overlooking the main road.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from several villages just west of the border post said
that fighting had started early in the morning and that soldiers
had stormed their villages in large numbers. About 90 percent of
Kosovo residents are ethnic Albanians, most of whom are Muslims,
and many thousands have fled their villages because of the fighting
since the government cracked down on separatist rebels a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Imam Hasan Hasalari, the Muslim leader of the village of
Rejance, said an army troop truck pulled up outside his home at
7:30 in the morning. The soldiers fanned out and two took up
positions in his garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid to go out,'' he said. ``Then just 500 yards away
heavy shooting broke out and big explosions. Then I was afraid to
stay in the house. I saw people running out the back and I climbed
out of a window and ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasalari ended up with 2,000 to 3,000 others clamoring to cross
the border at Deneral Jankovic, but they found their way blocked by
Serbian police. Turned back because they had no papers or
passports, the refugees stood in the street all day in rising panic
as police carried out house-to-house searches in the border
village.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening the refugees had been given shelter in houses
there.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one house just off the main street, about 30 women and
children filled a single room. Shemsije Sermjani, a nervous young
woman with dark rings round her eyes, told of how they had fled
their village, Palivodenica, at 10 in the morning. ``We heard
shooting and saw army patrols moving up into the hills above,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two weeks, we had been watching the troop movements
around. We were all ready to leave at any moment.'' She said that
her 80-year-old father and her brother had stayed in the village to
watch their house and animals. ``We don't know what will happen,''
she added. ``It is very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers said Serbian forces had begun Sunday's action by
attacking the village of Pustenik, a known stronghold of ethnic
Albanian guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, and then swept
on through neighboring villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are ethnically cleaning villages in a five-kilometer area
of the border,'' said one monitor there, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. He said he thought Serbian forces were trying to take
territory before peace talks resume on March 15 and that the
operation did not specifically seem to be against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have moved to reinforce their position,'' he said. ``It
is all part of the politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
