<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE PRESIDENT ADMITS INTEREST IN 3D TERM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Seven months after he announced he was
leaving office, President Carlos Saul Menem says he will run for
re-election if his supporters can legally overturn a constitutional
ban prohibiting a third consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's aides say that he is convinced the country needs him in
office to resist the financial contagion spreading from neighboring
Brazil and that he is committed to negotiating a treaty with the
United States over the next few years that would replace the peso
with the dollar as Argentina's currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a possibility of running in the primaries, I'll do
it,'' Menem said in a radio interview on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Menem remains far behind in the polls, and, with the ruling
Justicialist Party's primary vote due in May or June and the
general election scheduled for October, he may be running out of
time. But since he was first elected as a dark-horse candidate in
1989, he has repeatedly surprised analysts with his political
resourcefulness and cunning.
</P>
<P>
   After Brazil's problems accelerated with its Jan. 13
devaluation, Menem's standing in opinion polls improved somewhat.
He is generally credited with ending Argentina's long history of
hyperinflation by pegging the peso's value one-to-one to the dollar
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine constitution prohibits three consecutive
presidential terms. A 1995 amendment specifically barred Menem from
a third term, since the Constitution was written after he was
already in his first term. Menem's supporters are appealing to the
Supreme Court to strike that amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say the case will be a test of the independence of
the judiciary. Over the years, court rulings have favored Menem.
But since he announced he would step down, the courts have shown
increasing independence.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's aides said he could run in the primary while waiting for
the Supreme Court to make a ruling. They said Carlos Reutemann, a
senator from Santa Fe Province, could run as Menem's vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Menem is a bitter enemy of Eduardo Duhalde, the Buenos Aires
governor and current leading Justicialist candidate for president.
Even if Menem were to lose re-election to the Buenos Aires mayor,
Fernando de la Rua, who is the Alianza presidential candidate,
analysts say Menem does not want to risk losing his leadership of
the Justicialist party to Duhalde.
</P>
<P>
   The former president, Raul Alfonsin, a leader of the Alianza
opposition coalition, said Congress should consider impeaching
Menem for attempting to subvert the Constitution. He said Menem was
acting strangely due to a ``strange psychological state.'' Menem
responded angrily, saying no one should listen to Alfonsin because
``he couldn't govern the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
