</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-VOTE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBASANJO APPEARS TO BE VICTOR IN NIGERIA VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct byline)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, a former military ruler
who campaigned as being the only man capable of holding together
this vast and fractious country, on Sunday appeared to have won an
overwhelming victory in the first presidential election here in 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   His challenger, Olu Falae, immediately disputed the fairness of
the vote, held Saturday after years of promises by dictators to
move Nigeria, the most populous country in Africa, toward
democracy. It remained unclear, however, whether he would formally
contest the result.
</P>
<P>
   International election monitors, led by former President Jimmy
Carter, said they had witnessed fraud by both sides and other
irregularities, but probably not enough to have swayed the outcome,
which was substantially in Obasanjo's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Official results on Sunday night showed that the retired general
had garnered 62 percent of the votes, compared to 38 percent for
his opponent, from 33 out of 36 states, plus the federal capital.
</P>
<P>
   A victory for Obasanjo would cap a tumultuous period in the
history of Nigeria, ruled until last June by a dictatorship that
had turned the country, the world's sixth-largest oil producer and
the biggest military power in West Africa, into an international
pariah.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be the culmination of an extraordinary personal
journey for Obasanjo, who was released just eight months ago after
serving three years in prison for criticizing the military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Falae, a former finance minister, disputed the fairness of the
election early Sunday evening. ``I said if General Obasanjo won a
free and fair election I would congratulate him but clearly this is
not a free and fair election,'' Falae told journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear whether Falae would formally contest the
results, particularly since they showed him trailing by almost 7
million votes, with the margin widening in Obasanjo's favor as more
returns came in.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials are scheduled to announce final results on
Monday when they will also formally declare the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who led a team of American election monitors, praised
the current military government's commitment to the transition to
civilian rule and the conduct of officials at the Independent
National Election Commission, which oversaw the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center and the National Democratic Institute said in
a report on the elections that there was ``no evidence indicating
that electoral abuses would have affected the overall outcome of
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been a pattern of nationwide fraud or
irregularities,'' Carter said in an interview. But he said that
monitors had observed fraud and irregularities in a number of
states, including ballot-boxes that were stuffed, vote tallies that
were inflated and results that were manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   Clement Nwankwo, chairman of the Transition Monitoring Group, an
umbrella organization of Nigerian organizations that dispatched
thousands of observers on Saturday, said that Obasanjo would have
to win over the public, because the irregularities had been serious
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner must immediately embark on popular measures to deal
with the severe economic problems of this country and build popular
support for himself,'' Nwankwo said.
</P>
<P>
   If Falae contests the results, he will have to appeal his case
to a tribunal, which can decide to hold elections again in certain
areas or throughout the country. The new president is scheduled to
take over on May 29.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most significant for Obasanjo might be the effect of a challenge
by Falae on people in the south. According to the results released
Sunday night, he performed according to expectations by winning
most of the north. But Falae won the southwest, which is dominated
by the Yoruba, one of the three main ethnic groups in Nigeria,
along with the Ibo in the southeast and the Hausa-Fulani in the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are Yoruba. But because of Obasanjo's close ties to the
North, many of his fellow Yoruba distrust him and consider him a
candidate imposed by the northern-dominated military.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoruba have been angry especially since one of their own,
Moshood K.O. Abiola, a billionaire businessman, had his apparent
victory in the 1993 presidential elections annulled by a northern
general. That led to five years of brutal dictatorship under
Abacha, which ended only with his sudden death last June. After
Abiola also died unexpectedly a month later, Gen. Abdulsalami
Abubakar, the current president, announced a timetable for
elections and handover to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Falae was the candidate of the Alliance for Democracy, which is
essentially a Yoruba party with little reach outside the southwest.
The All People's Party, which is strongest in the north, joined
forces with the Alliance for Democracy and presented Falae as their
common candidate.
</P>
<P>
   During a weeklong campaign period, Falae attacked Obasanjo as a
soldier in civilian disguise and described an Obasanjo presidency
as a continuation of military rule. The theme resonated among many
Nigerians weary of the military, which has ruled Nigeria for all
but 10 years since independence from Britain in 1960. But Falae was
unable to spread his message because of poor organization and the
shakiness of the alliance that backed him.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Obasanjo tried to use his military past to his
advantage by arguing that he was the only one close enough to
military officers to prevent them from snatching back power, as
they have done in the past. He would serve as a bridge, his
campaign argued, to a civilian administration.
</P>
<P>
   His party, the People's Democratic Party, enjoyed the most money
and the backing of the retired military elite. The party dominated
in elections since December for local and statewide government
seats, as well as the national assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
