<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2429 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FOOT-LADN     02-28 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FOOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CSUN FOOTBALL, SPRING IS IN AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spring isn't officially here for another three
weeks. But the calendar is different in the Cal State Northridge
football office. Spring practices begin today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few teams go this early,'' head coach Ron Ponciano said.
``Most teams go in April. I like getting it done quickly. I do not
want to drag out spring football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just as soon get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN expects to dress 85 players for the first practice. The
Matadors will be out on the field five days a week for the next
three weeks and will scrimmage every Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect CSUN to be doing anything intricate. Ponciano has a
different plan this spring than last year: He wants simple drills
and simple schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus more on the fundamentals,'' he said.
``We've got to be more sound. There will be nowhere near the amount
of blitzing you saw last spring.''
</P>
<P>
   With the season opener against Southern Utah six months away,
Ponciano also gets to see the results of the offseason workouts he
designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done more long-sprint work,'' said Ponciano, who doubles
as the strength-and-conditioning coach. ``Some of our fat guys have
lost some weight. This is the only time we're going to improve our
physical standing in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano wants the Matadors to be tougher and leaner. He says he
wants a team that will push Big Sky opponents around. He wants to
shed the ``finesse'' label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitudes and our bodies are changing a little bit,'' he
said. ``Time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in offensive linemen like Ernie Fierro (6-foot-6, 310)
and Johnny Acosta, a transfer from Chaffey College who signed on
Feb. 4, helps. Fierro, a transfer from Nevada, and Acosta, who is
still attending Chaffey, will not participate in spring drills, but
Ponciano believes they will make an impact in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys will be sorely missed this spring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal for the Matadors in the next three weeks is to
determine a backup quarterback behind Marcus Brady, last year's Big
Sky newcomer of the year. Josh Fiske, a senior, is listed second on
the depth chart (see box) behind Brady. The 6-foot-3, 205-pounder
from Santa Ynez has been considered a good candidate to move to
wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fiske) is an athlete we need to have on the field
somewhere,'' Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   David Lins, a senior from Crespi High and Valley College, is the
third quarterback who should battle Fiske for the backup spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
