<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHUMER-850(2TAKES     02-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER, AS SENATOR, CHANGES TACTICS FROM HIS DAYS IN THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charles Schumer says his personal life has not
changed that much since he became New York's junior senator. He
still buys suits at a discount clothier, stays at budget hotels and
urges people to call him Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer, a Democrat, is sweating the details of a change in
his political life. No longer just the representative for parts of
Brooklyn and Queens, he now must understand the problems, weather
the complaints and be the voice of 17 million constituents,
including many who think he is a city-centric liberal who could not
care less about them.
</P>
<P>
   With his straight-A-student relentlessness, Schumer, 48, has
immersed himself in issues important to upstate communities, from
rising air fares in Syracuse to falling milk prices in Watertown,
from low pay at Fort Drum to high electric rates in Jamestown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason why Rochester, with its great companies and
its great institutions, shouldn't be a high-tech mecca in the
entire Northeast,'' he told reporters at the opening of his
Rochester office last month. ``That's one of the things I intend to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer is also worrying about how he will play to another
audience: his 99 fellow senators. Theirs is a more intimate and
courtly club than the House; individual members have far more power
to shape legislation, personal relations are paramount to success,
and brass-knuckle politics are usually frowned upon.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Schumer was widely considered an effective and
tireless legislator and made himself an expert on a range of
issues, including gun control and banking. But his critics, and
many allies, also viewed him as an incorrigible self-promoter who
could be abrasive and partisan at times. To succeed in the Senate,
they say, he will have to rein in some of those tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to understand that better than Schumer. Accused in
the past of grabbing credit for legislation that others wrote, he
says he plans to allow more senior senators to take the lead on
legislation he once sponsored in the House. He has also been
turning down invitations to appear on television talk programs, he
says, partly to avoid causing resentment among his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And after years of attacking House Republican leaders, he says
he is learning about bipartisanship in the Senate, vowing to style
himself after the late Sen. Jacob K. Javits, a liberal New York
Republican known for working well with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of renewed bipartisanship that emerged during
impeachment is real, he said in a recent interview. ``I go into a
room with senators, I start thinking, `I get 50 of these guys to
support me on something, I can pass it,''' he said. ``You don't
begin to think that way when there are 435.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on what he described as his attempts to defer to more
senior colleagues, he said: ``As a freshman member, you do things
differently. Whenever there is a group of people talking, I'll
defer to my senior colleagues first, then say my piece.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then added slyly, ``But it's a small group, so it's
less of a wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, old habits can die hard. Some of Schumer's colleagues
expressed amazement at how often he appeared before the microphones
outside the Senate chamber or on television interviews during the
Senate impeachment trial in January.
</P>
<P>
   And when he delivered a stand-up routine at the Washington Press
Club Foundation's congressional dinner last month, Schumer was
widely panned when he took several barbed shots at House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The act, which was written by his staff with the assistance of
the comedian Al Franken, a fellow Harvard graduate, opened with
Schumer poking fun at himself for being a publicity hound. But the
ballroom fell silent when Schumer quipped that Rep. Bob Barr, a
conservative Republican from Georgia, was preparing legislation
titled the Defense of White Marriage Act.
</P>
<P>
   And the silence broke into hisses when Schumer turned to House
Speaker Dennis Hastert and said, ``I'd like to congratulate Denny
on his appointment by Tom DeLay.'' DeLay, the House whip, has been
singled out by some Democrats as being the most powerful Republican
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debacle,'' one Washington weekly, Roll Call, called the
performance. ``Over the top,'' several Republicans said. Even Josh
Isay, Schumer's chief of staff, said, ``I wanted to crawl under the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seriously thinks that the performance will damage
Schumer's standing in the Senate. But it confirmed some people's
impressions of Schumer as hard-edged and partisan, congressional
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   His friends say the misstep has already been forgotten. Schumer,
they contend, is destined for Senate stardom because he is a
natural-born legislator, a pragmatist who can sidestep ideology to
get things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is a very wide open place,'' said Sen. Richard J.
Durbin, a Democrat from Illinois who shares a town house on Capitol
Hill with Schumer. ``That plays to his strength. He's a bright
fellow _ I guess you'll have to write that, won't you? _ and he
will be a major player.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has devoted much of his time since the election to
traveling around the state, particularly to the regions north of
the New York City suburbs, traditionally Republican territory that
he has vowed to win in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   He has pledged to put three upstate issues at the top of his
legislative agenda: reducing air fares, cutting utility costs and
creating jobs. He has also said he will travel anywhere in the
country to lobby executives to locate offices upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed me with a lot of energy,'' Schumer said in
Rochester. ``And I want to put a lot of that energy into helping
companies understand what a great place upstate New York is for
relocating.''
</P>
<P>
   During his upstate tours _ he has made about a dozen since the
election _ Schumer plays the eager student, not shy about asking
questions, or showing off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with Kodak executives in Rochester, Schumer
noted that he majored in chemistry for two years at Harvard, and
offered some educated guesses as to why silver is light sensitive.
And in a private meeting with officials at Monroe County Community
College, he apparently let slip about his perfect scores on the
Scholastic Aptitude Test.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got more people skills than you'd expect for someone who
got 1600 on his SATs,'' Dr. Peter Spina, the college president,
said after the session.
</P>
<P>
   In his fashion, Schumer has also tried to demonstrate that he is
not just another downstate politician who has no interest in
upstate's problems until election time. One technique: tell jokes
about the city.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner of business leaders in Jamestown, Rep. Amo Houghton,
a Republican from Corning, gave Schumer a red corduroy hat with the
letters, A-M-O. Schumer put the hat on his head, and said with a
wide grin, ``In my district, they would pronounce this ammo.'' The
room broke up.
</P>
<P>
   His trips, Schumer contends, have already affected his votes.
During a November visit to Fort Drum, he rode in a tank and
received a tour from a two-star general who complained about the
Army's problems in recruiting and keeping soldiers. The visit
convinced Schumer of the need for increasing military pay, and he
voted for such legislation last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Schumer said, he might have dismissed the bill by
saying, ``Maybe we should be spending this on other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, whose family lives in the Park Slope section of
Brooklyn, said his frequent travels have not prevented him from
devoting Saturdays to his wife and two daughters, Alison, 9, and
Jessica, 14. He has made every one of Alison's Sunday basketball
games with the 78th Precinct Youth Council, and he still faxes home
solutions to his daughters' math homework problems almost nightly,
his wife, Iris Weinshall, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weinshall, a deputy commissioner in the city's Department of
Citywide Administrative Services, said being a senator has also not
changed Schumer's taste for modestly priced blue and gray suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A salesman said to him, `Now that you're a senator, you should
buy a more expensive suit,' '' she recalled. ``Chuck said forget
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has spent much of his time in recent days fielding
questions about the potential Senate candidacy of Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who campaigned with him four times last year. Some of his
critics say they think Schumer harbors secret hopes that Mrs.
Clinton will not run, because she would outshine him in the Senate.
But Schumer scoffs at such talk and shows nothing but enthusiasm
about the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``We developed a closeness in the campaign, where she just
knocked my socks off,'' he said. ``In the middle of this whirlwind,
and for her, it was a whirlwind in every conceivable way, there was
this woman, calm, resolute, doing exactly what she set out to do.
Which, to my benefit, was to help elect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer says he is uncertain about his role in helping to build
the state Democratic Party. Some Democrats have asked him to take
the party's reins, as Alfonse D'Amato did with the Republican Party
18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer said he expects to fall somewhere between D'Amato,
who ran his party with an iron fist, and Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who stayed aloof from the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an area where I think you have to go slowly,'' he said.
``I said in the campaign, and I feel exactly that way now, I want
to help build the party. I don't want to run it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that D'Amato was admired in New York and Washington for
his skill in directing federal funds to the state, Schumer is
careful to tell his audiences that he will work hard at
``delivering'' for them. But he also notes that the senators he
admires the most, like Javits, were experts at both enacting major
legislation and bringing home money.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said his greatest frustration this year has been the
impeachment trial, which caused the Senate to postpone other work.
Boyishly enthusiastic, fond of pumping both fists to show approval,
he said he is thrilled to be finally getting down to legislating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The honeymoon hasn't worn out,'' he said. ``It will wear out.
And it should. I shouldn't be judged on winning the election, but
on what I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
