<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZY KINGS FALL TO STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For 20 minutes Sunday afternoon the Kings pressured the
Dallas Stars, desperately trying to produce the tying goal.
Unfortunately for the Kings, this sudden persistence followed 40
minutes of indifference and simply was too late.
</P>
<P>
   It had been too late, in fact, ever since Joe Nieuwendyk of the
Dallas Stars scored 31 seconds into the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first shift of the game, we got caught on a 4 on 1,''
coach Larry Robinson said disgustedly. ``That's not being ready.
That's being stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed Nieuwendyk's goal was a stunning goaltending
exhibition by Stephane Fiset, an overdue and futile display of
intensity by the Kings and the usual exasperation from Robinson
following a 1-0 loss before a sellout crowd of 16,928 at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have guys playing at the end of their sticks, trying
not to get hit,'' said Robinson, who relied heavily on eight
forwards in the third period and benched Yanic Perreault for the
final 20 minutes. ``You can't have that.... It should have been
about 7-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were blanked for the eighth time, with Dallas goalie
Ed Belfour recording his 44th career shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Kings found themselves holding their breath
hoping winger Donald Audette had nothing more serious than a bruise
from a last-minute slash to the left foot by Dallas defenseman
Richard Matvichuk, who received a game misconduct. Glen Murray was
slashed on the leg in the closing minute, but he stayed in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minute, with Matvichuk and Mike Modano serving
penalties and Fiset off for an extra skater, the Kings briefly had
a three-man advantage but were unable to capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sit back,'' Audette said. ``As long as we sit back,
we're not going to create chances.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Kings (23-33-5) fell to 2-2-1 on a six-game
trip that ends Wednesday against the Mighty Ducks at the Pond. More
significantly, they failed to gain ground in the playoff race,
remaining three points behind eighth-place San Jose. After 61
games, the Kings have as many losses as all of last year, four
coming to Dallas, all by one goal. The Stars (38-11-9) are 10-0-6
against the Kings in the last 16 meetings and are 8-1-1 in their
last 10 games, allowing just 17 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be a tough game,'' Robinson said, ``yet we
didn't give an effort until the third period.''
</P>
<P>
   It took less than a minute for the Kings to make the mistake
that would haunt them the rest of the day. When Kings defenseman
Sean O'Donnell and winger Sandy Moger were unable to control the
puck along the right boards, the Stars gained an outnumbered rush
and only Doug Bodger remained back defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Pat Verbeek made no mistake with the puck, sending a
cross-ice feed to Nieuwendyk at the top of the right faceoff
circle, and Nieuwendyk rifled it past a helpless Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the day, Fiset was the only reason the Kings
stayed close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to do my job out there,'' he said after his
33-save effort. ``Right now, me and Jamie (Storr) have to stay
strong and do the job on the ice. That's going to be the only way
if we're going to make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were at their most dominant in the second period,
winning 14 of 17 faceoffs and outshooting the Kings 18-4. In the
third period the Kings outshot Dallas 7-6 but couldn't get anything
past Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win a game with (18) shots,'' defenseman
Rob Blake said. ``What'd we have, 11 shots in the first two
periods? If we can't score one goal, what's the use?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
