<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUNK-DRIVING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURATEURS WORRY `THE GIULIANI THING' WILL KEEP DOWN BAR BILLS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few days ago, Marc Sherry, co-owner of the Old
Homestead restaurant in downtown Manhattan, overheard a comment
that sent a chill down his spine. After perusing the menu, one
customer said to another, ``Maybe we shouldn't have that bottle of
wine due to that Giuliani thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry says he supports Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose
administration has unsheathed a new weapon in the fight against
drunken driving, seizing the cars of those arrested. Sherry adds
that the mayor is a friend, and a frequent customer of the Old
Homestead, which has a longstanding reputation for its high-end
steaks, including Kobe beef from Japan that goes for $125 a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the idea of eating one of his steaks without a
bottle of wine strikes him as incomprehensible. ``Why would
anybody,'' he asked, ``want to drive to a New York City steakhouse
if you can't have a bottle of wine? Think about it. You're buying a
$125 steak, and you're not going to have a glass of wine? Yeah,
you're going to have lemonade with a $125 steak.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir
kicked off the new crackdown on drunken driving, the city's
restaurateurs seem divided on the car-seizure policy and its
effects on their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Maioglio, the owner of Barbetta, an Italian restaurant in
the theater district, predicted a long-term benefit for restaurant
owners. ``The cost of our insurance to cover accidents after
drinking is very expensive,'' she said. Customers, she said, ``can
sue us because we served them too much to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we tell them they're drunk and cannot have any more to
drink, they can sue us for insulting them,'' she said. ``The whole
thing is a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   New York is one of the last remaining cities in the country
where people can get almost everywhere by mass transit or taxi, and
drunken driving _ their own, anyway _ is not a big worry.
</P>
<P>
   The places most likely to feel pinched are those in the city's
cultural centers, like Lincoln Center and the theater district,
where out-of-towners flock.
</P>
<P>
   Before a performance, many people want dinner and at most one
glass of wine: having spent at last $50 for a ticket, nobody wants
to nod off during the show. But afterward, they may want to stop
for a drink _ and that is when restaurant owners expect the new
drunken driving policy to hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People drinking all night _ that's no good,'' said Peter
Chimos, an owner of Frankie and Johnny's, a steak-and-martini place
in the heart of the theater district. ``But this is too extreme.
They will be afraid to drink anything. The mayor _ he does a good
job as mayor. But this is too far. We've got to have a little fun,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the new policy went into effect, the police say they have
made at least 34 drunken-driving arrests and seized at least 26
cars on which they expect to begin forfeiture proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hunt, the executive vice president of the New York City
chapter of the New York State Restaurant Association, said he did
not anticipate any decrease in customers or alcohol consumption.
``People are not going to not go out,'' he said. ``And they can't
go to a musical in New Jersey, unless it's a dinner theater.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
