u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-PROSPECTS-4     02-28 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PROSPECTS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIELD OF OPTIONS, ALL YOUNGER AND CHEAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Replaces skedded BBA-YANKS-POSADA.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The primary field here is filled every day with
New York Yankees stars, Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams and Paul
O'Neill and Roger Clemens. But Manager Joe Torre likes to slip away
at least once a day to Field No. 2, to spy on the organization's
top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Johnson, a 20-year-old first baseman, slashes line drives,
as does shortstop Alfonso Soriano. Ryan Bradley fires his darting
sinker, and Luis DelosSantos slings fastballs with arms seemingly
as long as telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, will not go so far
as to call any of these youngsters untouchable _ one or two
significant injuries to the pitching rotation and the Yankees could
suddenly be in pursuit of Philadelphia's Curt Schilling _ but the
value of young players has soared in recent years. With the average
major-league salary approaching $1.5 million, a team can save
itself millions of dollars if a young player contributes.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson is a viable option at first base, the Yankees could
pay him a total of $1 million to $2 million over his first three
seasons. Keeping Tino Martinez, on the other hand, might cost $6
million or $7 million a year once his contract expires after the
2000 season; over a three-year period, the Yankees might save $20
million if Johnson is good enough to step in for Martinez. Gone are
the days when top prospects were idly traded away.
</P>
<P>
   There are those in the Yankees' organization who believe that
Johnson will be ready to replace Martinez in two years. Johnson, a
nephew of the former infielder Larry Bowa, is seen as a modern-day
player with an old-fashioned work ethic: Tall and strong, a great
fielder with an extremely quick bat, he wears his baseball pants
high, just below the knee, and thrives on practice. ``I just love
the guy,'' said Lee Mazzilli, Johnson's manager at Class A Tampa
last season. ``He always wants to play, and he'll play hurt. I'd
say to him, `Hey, I'm giving you a day off,' and he would say,
`Why?'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a left-handed hitter, batted .317 with 17 home runs and
drove in 58 runs in 303 at-bats, and he is expected to start at
Class AA Norwich this year. ``He is the Man,'' Cashman said. ``He's
got everything, except for the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson grew up in the San Francisco area, but he was always a
Phillies fan because of Bowa, his uncle, and he once served as a
batboy in spring training for Philadelphia. His favorite player was
Lenny Dykstra _ he loved Dykstra's gritty style _ but as a shy
teen-ager, Johnson never raised the nerve to speak to the
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   He is not so quiet with his bat. ``We've asked about him all the
time,'' a general manager of another team said in the off-season,
``but there's no way they're trading him. He's on a fast track to
the big leagues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Soriano, 21, will probably beat him there. He played in Japan
before sitting out last year and earning the right to become a free
agent. Lin Garrett, the Yankees' director of scouting, watched him
work out last summer and reported that if Soriano were available in
the draft, he would be the first pick overall. The Yankees signed
him to a four-year deal at $630,000 a season, and Soriano then
dominated the Arizona fall league.
</P>
<P>
   A native of the Dominican Republic, he is 6 feet 1 inches and
slightly built, but wiry strong; the reliever Mike Buddie threw
batting practice to him in recent days and was surprised by how
hard the right-handed-hitting Soriano could drive the ball to
right-center field. Scouts who have seen him play say Soriano has
great hands defensively, can throw and run well, and will be ready
for the big leagues sometime in the 2000 season. He bats with his
stance slightly open and his hands held high, and he is a good
enough hitter to be moved to third base, assuming that Jeter
remains the Yankees' shortstop for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 23, pitched briefly for the Yankees last year, after
jumping from Class A to the big leagues in little more than a
month. A right-hander, he is big and thick, the way Clemens is,
with a crew cut, and throws a hard sinking fastball that bores in
on right-handed batters. He has a split-fingered fastball, as well,
but wants to develop a changeup this season. Bradley will probably
start the season as a starter for Class AAA Columbus, but the
Yankees believe he has a future as a short reliever, with his nasty
Goose Gossage-like aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has always been an idol to Bradley, and they both like
to intimidate. While pitching for Arizona State, Bradley once
beaned Troy Glaus, then the third baseman for UCLA and now with the
Anaheim Angels. Bradley subsequently drilled Glaus in the ribs and
cursed the UCLA bench, drawing eventual retaliation from the
Bruins. Bradley will live with the reputation of a headhunter.
``That's not necessarily a bad thing,'' he said, referring to his
style as ``effectively wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre repeatedly mentions DelosSantos, 21, as someone he likes
to watch. ``He's just a baby,'' Torre said. After the Yankees
refused to include him in the trade for Chuck Knoblauch last year,
DelosSantos struggled in Class AA before being sent back to Class
A. The right-hander will open this year in Class A.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done,'' Cashman said, ``I really think
he's going to be something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
