<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT HERO CRASHES PARTY IN SAN RAFAEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Prime Timber and Honest Lady got together
Sunday at Santa Anita in the San Rafael Stakes, billed as the
season's first meeting of male and female Kentucky Derby
contenders. Then another man came between them.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Desert Hero went around them, after threatening to
climb over them. Blocked near the rail in midstretch, the colt and
jockey Corey Nakatani had to veer toward the grandstand to find a
clear path in the final yards of the 1-mile race for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   And when 10-1 shot Desert Hero sprinted to the wire a neck in
front of a rusty Prime Timber, with tired Honest Lady less than a
length farther back in fifth, the Derby campaign had a strong new
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if he finished within three lengths of the winner,
he'd have a chance of being a Derby horse, because he's bred to go
(1\ miles),'' said Wally Dollase, who trains the son of 1993 Derby
winner Sea Hero for Saudi Arabian Prince Ahmed bin Salman.
``Obviously, if he'd gotten through (the traffic), he'd have won by
three or four lengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero paid $22.80. He was clocked in 1:36.45, not fast for
the San Rafael, a prep for the April 3 Santa Anita Derby, the
western steppingstone to the May 1 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But if the victory wasn't brilliant on paper, the ability of the
smallish bay colt with the blond tail to escape trouble in the
stretch was dazzling to the eye. Especially since this was only his
second start, following a two-length maiden win at 6{ furlongs on
Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber and Gary Stevens rushed from seventh to contention
on the outside on the far turn. The colt led in the final strides,
and might have felt the effects of a 2{-month layoff since a
second-place finish in the Hollywood Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   Honest Lady and Kent Desormeaux led at the top of the stretch as
the daughter of Seattle Slew bid for her third straight win, but
she soon flattened out, backing up into Desert Hero. ``I might have
rushed her a bit into the first turn,'' Desormeaux conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Capsized finished third, Love That Red fourth in the nine-horse
race.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Silver Charm was assigned a race-high 124 pounds, Free
House 123, Puerto Madero 122 for Saturday's Santa Anita Handicap.
Puerto Madero carried 120, Silver Charm 126 when they finished
first and third in the Jan. 30 Donn Handicap in Florida. Other Big
'Cap weights: Event of the Year 119, Malek 118, Dr Fong 117, Sidon
114. . . . Jose Santos received the George Woolf Award in a
between-races ceremony. . . . After two carryovers, the pick-six
paid $408,670. . . . Banshee Breeze, the Eclipse Award winner as
last year's top 3-year-old filly, won the $200,000 Rampart Handicap
by 5{ lengths at Gulfstream Park in Hallandale, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
