<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYONS-IMPACT-945(2TAK     02-28 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS-IMPACT-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PREACHER'S FAITHFUL BACK BOTH SINNER AND FELON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The minister who had preached to Hillary
Clinton, who had been courted by politicians and corporate leaders
eager to tap his influence in black communities nationwide, now
awaits his sentencing for convictions on racketeering and grand
theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as a bailiff pressed the Rev. Henry J. Lyons'
ink-stained fingertips on a white card, supporters inside and
outside the Florida courthouse prayed, cried, sang and swore
support for the man they saw as a persecuted prophet.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to matter that prosecutors had built a mountain
of evidence against him, proving that Lyons, president of the
National Baptist Convention, USA, Inc., had even stolen money,
about $250,000, donated to rebuild burned black churches.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to matter that prosecutors had proved, with a
paper trail of his own signatures, that he had sold out the good
name of what is perhaps the largest black religious organization in
the United States, that he had made $4 million from peddling that
influence and then used that money to live in a style that included
luxury cars, waterfront property and expensive jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Even as prosecutors presented their most incriminating evidence,
his home church here seemed united behind him, the convention did
not formally call for his resignation, and religious leaders, from
as close as Tampa Bay and as far as Gary, Ind., filled the
courthouse pews in support.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what God called him to do,'' said the Rev. Manuel
Sykes, 42, a St. Petersburg pastor and a friend and close supporter
of Lyons'. To Sykes and many others, Lyons, 57, is not a criminal
but a strong leader, a stirring preacher and a good businessman who
should not be ashamed of living well.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong support, Lyons' actions have not been without
consequence. Religious experts say his conviction will damage the
credibility of the convention, and calls for his resignation as
president are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   For Lyons, who was convicted on Saturday on one count of
racketeering and two of grand theft, the verdicts may finally take
from him the power that mere accusations and indictments could not.
</P>
<P>
   As a community leader, he calmed rioters in St. Petersburg after
a black man was shot to death by the police. As the leader of a
black religious organization that claims a membership of 8.5
million (prosecutors called this figure grossly inflated), he had
President Clinton's ear, was courted by members of Congress and was
paid huge sums by corporations for entree into black communities so
that they could sell burial plots and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He had affairs, which were forgiven. He lived lavishly, which
was accepted. He was ultimately accused of crimes, which were
mostly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a good preacher will hide a multitude of sins,'' said
Robert Franklin, president of the Inter-Denominational Theological
Center in Atlanta, the largest black seminary in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are showing mercy,'' Franklin said, ``without a sense
of accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons faces a prison sentence of eight and a half years, and
this spring he will stand trial on federal charges of money
laundering, tax evasion, extortion, bank and mail fraud, conspiracy
and other crimes. An aide who was his co-defendant in the state's
trial, Bernice Edwards, was acquitted of the only charge against
her, racketeering, but she faces similar federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lyons remained steadfast throughout the trial. And
when it was all over and the verdict was in, they prayed again for
God to set things right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wanting your answer, Lord,'' said the pastor's wife,
Deborah Lyons, who inadvertently set in motion the investigation
into Lyons' business dealings when she set fire to a $700,000
waterfront home after finding that her husband had bought it with
Ms. Edwards. She is on probation for setting the fire but now says
she never really believed her husband was cheating on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your servant,'' Mrs. Lyons prayed outside the
courtroom after the verdict. ``Bless him, Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been detractors, and the conviction of Lyons will,
religious experts say, further erode his support both in the
convention and in his own Bethel Metropolitan Baptist Church. One
high-ranking member of the convention, as well as some other
religious leaders, is already calling for him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   But his having hung on for so long _ in 1997 he survived a fight
on the convention floor to oust him as president and wound up with
a vote of confidence _ is proof of the power the man had not only
in his own church and community but in the 100-year-old convention.
</P>
<P>
   The length of his fight and the outcome, religious experts said,
will hurt the credibility of the convention, which has given its
presidents such autonomy that they have been able to run the
denomination's business _ including millions of dollars in
membership money _ from a briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   But it may also lead to changes, to checks and balances,
religious leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The real losers, in the legacy of Henry J. Lyons, are the people
who put their faith in him, said experts on black churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``These well-intentioned people are attempting to bring closure
to a very painful episode in their lives by circling the wagons and
presenting a strong defense to the outside world,'' Franklin said.
``It's important to know these people had shared good times
together and trusted their leader as a visionary and as an
effective builder. This is a gesture of remembering the good
days.''
</P>
<P>
   But as they tried to live in that past, Franklin said, they
ignored their responsibilities to their faith.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The parishioners who should have held Lyons accountable have
failed,'' Franklin said. ``It's very difficult for me to understand
this, because it really is an abdication of their adult moral
responsibilities. I'm disappointed that people were not able to
separate two very important issues: the state of Lyons' soul, and
his capacity to lead the congregation and the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian mercy should extend to the first case,'' he said,
``not the second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Long, also a minister in St. Petersburg and a
loyal follower of Lyons, said that critics of the minister acted
from ``jealousy,'' and that preachers were not expected to live in
poverty as proof of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters wanting to speak with members of Lyons' congregation
have been chased from the church, and on Sunday morning church
members kept watch in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But around the country, a push for Lyons' resignation as
president of the convention seems to be growing among black
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no tolerance for a convicted felon to continue as a
spiritual leader of the churches,'' said the Rev. Franklyn
Richardson of Mount Vernon, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Calvin Butts, pastor of the Abyssinian Baptist Church
in Harlem, in New York City, is also calling for Lyons to step
down, saying his actions have rendered the convention ineffective
and damaged its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Even black Christians with no connection to the scandal were sad
and angry about how Lyons' actions reflected on black churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't claim to be a religious leader'' and betray the
congregation, said Johnnie Whittaker, 30, a Miami bondsman. Black
people, he said, ``need to hold their head up high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
