<HEADLINE>
AUDETTE INJURED IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Compounding the Kings' 1-0 loss Sunday afternoon was a
painful sight they've seen far too often this season: a key player
writhing on the ice in agony.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings are hoping right wing Donald Audette's bruised
left foot _ courtesy of a last-minute slash by Dallas Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk _ will not cause him to miss any
games. Audette had to be helped to the dressing room and after the
game his foot was heavily wrapped in ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slashed me once,'' said Audette, who underwent X-rays that
were negative. ``I slashed him back and that's when he two-handed
me. He's just a (expletive) loser. I'll get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just treat the symptoms and see how he is,'' trainer
Peter Demers said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Much ado about Fleury: Did the balance of power shift from
Dallas to Colorado on Sunday when the Avalanche acquired star right
wing Theo Fleury from Calgary?
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey didn't sound too worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really involved in the Fleury conversations in any
depth,'' he said. ``It may not be very popular, but it's quite
possible this is our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said, ``I'm sure everybody will be
focused in on Colorado now. It will be a good challenge for
everybody, including us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are expected to make a pitch for Fleury when he
becomes an unrestricted free agent on July 1, assuming he hasn't
already signed with Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stars dominance: How long has it been since the Kings beat
the Stars? Barry Melrose was the Kings' coach the last time it
happened, back in the 1995 lockout season. Since then, including
Sunday's loss, the Kings are 0-10-6 against Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
