<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-725(2TAKES)-     02-28 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANGEROUS NETS HAVE FIZZLED INTO DUDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Just three weeks ago, the New Jersey
Nets were being touted as one of the best teams in the National
Basketball Association. Fueled by young talent and an uptempo
offense, they were hailed as a potential conference champion, the
new hoop darlings of the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   But disaster has struck in the form of a 2-10 record, rendering
the Nets the league's most disappointing team by far and leading
people throughout the organization to wonder what has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries, particularly a sprained right ankle that has kept
point guard Sam Cassell out for most of the season, have certainly
been a factor. But as they prepare for Monday night's rematch with
the Boston Celtics at the Fleet Center, there seems to be more to
it than that. After all, Miami, Cleveland and the New York Knicks,
all of whom beat the Nets without key starters, have stayed afloat
despite injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While Coach John Calipari and his players talk about it being
early, the Nets might be out of the playoff picture already. In
this shortened 50-game season, their 2-10 record is comparable with
a 3-16 start in the standard 82-game season.
</P>
<P>
   Besides injuries, four factors seem to be at the heart of the
Nets' exercise in underachievement: Calipari's sudden inability to
get the best out of his players; the Nets' lack of a sophisticated
halfcourt offense; the loss of Sherman Douglas to free agency, and
expectations that were too high.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Calipari can have staying power in the NBA has been an
issue since he joined the Nets in 1996. His constant barking on the
sideline and collegiate motivational tactics have grated on his
professional players, and that might be a problem this season.
Chris Gatling has asked to be traded, and Scott Burrell was visibly
upset by Calipari's decision to send him to the scorer's table last
Tuesday against the Knicks. Calipari did that to motivate another
player on the floor, not to send Burrell into the game as a
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible sign that Calipari might not be getting through
to his players is the significant statistical decline of everyone
on the team except for Keith Van Horn. Four of the Nets' top nine
players are shooting below 40 percent from the floor, and the team
is ranked 28th in the league in scoring (84.7) and field-goal
percentage (.389). Even Calipari admitted that the drop in player
production implicates him, though he insisted that he has not lost
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at how do I get guys to play better, which has
never been an issue for me in my coaching career,'' Calipari said.
``Guys have had career years every year they've played for me.
Individual players are not playing up to their level, and that's
bothered me. But there has been no breakdown of the players. That's
a cop-out. It all comes down to we need to win a couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing players love about Calipari is his affinity for
fast-break basketball. The speedy, shoot-it-when-you're-open game
plan is every player's dream, but because the Nets have been unable
to run with consistency, the offensive package has become
nightmarish.
</P>
<P>
   Because they have been outrebounded in nine games, the Nets have
been forced to play slower, which has exposed Calipari's minimalist
approach to the halfcourt game. He relies heavily on isolations,
which at times makes his club look like five strangers playing in a
schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're terrible at the halfcourt game,'' Jayson Williams said.
``We've got to run and gun. We're undermanned and undersized.''
</P>
<P>
   In defending his offense, Calipari noted that it worked last
year. But that is because the unorthodox Cassell thrives in an
offense that is based on improvisation. That is not the case with
Cassell's backup, Eric Murdock, or for Kittles and Kendall Gill,
who have also played point guard this year. Not one is as creative
as Cassell as a playmaker, which results in the need for a more
disciplined halfcourt attack. But Calipari has refused to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense is very simplistic,'' said Murdock, who played for
Coach Pat Riley in Miami last season. ``We don't run a lot of sets.
There is a lot of freedom out there, and at times it does look
scrambled. Sometimes it's easy to guard because a lot of times the
spacing and the timing of the plays are not the best.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantages have been glaring in the clutch, as the Nets
have surrendered fourth-quarter leads in five of their last six
losses. Calipari said that his late-game strategy is to isolate his
best players _ Van Horn, Kittles or Cassell _ in one-on-one
situations, and let them create. But that system has become
terribly predictable, especially with Cassell on the sideline and
Kittles struggling offensively. Down the stretch, it is a safe bet
that the Nets will go to Van Horn on the wing and ask him to juke
or blow by his man for a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to run, the Nets' small lineup has become a drawback, and
after Saturday's loss to Boston, Calipari spoke of the possibility
of playing Jim McIlvaine, Williams and Van Horn on the frontline.
He has been apprehensive about using McIlvaine and Williams
together because neither player is an offensive threat, and Van
Horn would have a more difficult time taking small forwards off the
dribble. But at this point, what is there to lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing lineups is an alternative,'' Calipari said. ``I just
don't know if we're at that panic button yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' management, coaches and players have said that the
absence of Douglas, last season's backup point guard, has been
especially glaring. Douglas, who signed with the Los Angeles
Clippers as a free agent, helped the Nets win numerous games and
offered a more traditional alternative to the erratic Cassell.
Douglas, a pure point guard, gave the team direction in the
halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't call him `the General' for nothing,'' Gill said of
Douglas. ``It's nothing against Eric Murdock, but everybody liked
playing with Sherm. When he came in the game, everybody got lifted.
I can't tell you how much he meant to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, who averaged 16.8 points and nine assists in 11 starts,
also pushed Cassell to play harder, better and sometimes while
injured. Privately, people within the organization have questioned
whether Cassell, out of fear of losing his starting job, would have
returned by now from his ankle injury if Douglas were still on the
team, and if, out of a desire to renegotiate the final three years
of his five-year, $15 million contract, he was now extending his
recuperation time to prove his value to the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their opinion,'' said Cassell, who has a torn ligament
in his ankle. ``I love this game and I want to play. I wouldn't
quit on my teammates like that. That's not in my character.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets tried to retain Douglas, offering him a three-year,
$5.8 million contract that was turned down by his agent, Eric
Fleisher. A day later, Fleisher called back to accept the offer,
but Calipari, wanting to fill out his roster as soon as possible,
had already pressed the club into signing Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, all the preseason praise the Nets received raised the
stakes tremendously, making their slow start seem all the more
calamitous. If the expectations had been more realistic, Calipari
and his players might not look like such failures. The Nets
believed the hype. Williams predicted a ridiculous 35 victories _ a
figure that would compare with 57 in an 82-game season _ and most
of his teammates overlooked the Knicks as obstacles to an Eastern
Conference championship. Perhaps their grand impression of
themselves led them to lose the edge they had as a team playing for
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only made the playoffs by one game last year,'' Gill said.
``We're a good team, but people were thinking we were going to win
the NBA championship this year. Just because we played the Chicago
Bulls tough in the first round of the playoffs, everybody thought
we had arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, everybody thought wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
