 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, March 1 on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055.
</P>
<P>
   MISSION _ Today, Mission Bay is 303 acres of rusting rail yards
and dusty warehouses on San Francisco's southeast flank. But city
business, political and academic leaders are betting that early
next century, Mission Bay will be a world center for biomedical
research _ and the magnet that attracts some 20,000 academic,
biotech and drug industry jobs to one of San Francisco's
underdeveloped corners. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   ATM _ Animated advertisements are coming to an automated teller
machine near you. Starting today, 340 Wells Fargo ATMs in the Bay
Area will display three promotional messages during each
transaction. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS _ Get ready to get unplugged. Dozens of companies are
developing products that will give mobility to the wired masses,
allowing consumers to perform everyday tasks such as surfing the
Web and sending e-mail from handheld devices with a wireless
connection. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   THE NET FILES _ In the land where stock quadruples in a day,
creating instant billionaires, is there room for an Internet
phoenix? The powers that be at PointCast hope so. The onetime
hot-shot firm is undergoing a radical reincarnation to reverse its
fortunes, according to sources. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   BIOSCOPE _  &LR;   &LR; Richard Brewer, chief executive of Scios Inc., is
expected to walk into work this morning and lay off a third of
Scios' 270 employees, close its drug manufacturing plant and sell
its three-building campus in Mountain View. ``We cannot continue
business as usual,'' Brewer said. ``There hasn't been a reality
check on this company for a while.'' By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC _ The MP3 phenomenon has shifted from college dorms to
boardrooms. The past two weeks has brought a flurry of
announcements from the likes of major companies such as Sony Corp.,
IBM and Texas Instruments, each promoting its own new advancements
in controlling online music distribution and halting the spread of
illegal MP3 formatted songs.
</P>
