<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-PREVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alou, Expos: Back to the future
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Felipe Alou had at least 97 reasons to do it.
Any sane man would have had the motivation to leave the game's most
troubled franchise last winter when Los Angeles called with an
offer to manage the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's Montreal Expos lost 97 times a year ago, the franchise's
worst season in 22 years, and scored the fewest runs in the
National League (644) while leading the majors in errors (155).
</P>
<P>
   The path out the door in Montreal this decade has been worn,
with Pedro Martinez, Larry Walker, John Wetteland and Moises Alou
leading an annual parade of talent out of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A sensible man, Felipe Alou should have gone, too. Yet he found
himself standing before his seventh Expos team this week, welcoming
it to another spring camp. He has found two reasons to offset the
other 97: a new three-year contract and a sense of history, taking
him back to 1993 when the Expos' farm system delivered him a
powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent is there,'' Alou said. ``They're not as mature as
'93, but you can see the movement upward. If you could give a club
like this an every-day left fielder, a set-up guy and another
starter _ you see I mention three players only. That's it. That's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos expect to recover from their 1998 bruising with the
long-term notion that they can contend seriously in 2000. The
payroll will be a paltry $20million this year, but that is
nearlydouble from a season ago. General manager Jim Beattie, vice
president Bill Stoneman and super scout Fred Ferreira all signed
long-term deals last winter, solidifying the front office. And to
stanch the talent runoff, outfielder Rondell White, catcher Chris
Widger and closer Ugueth Urbina all agreed to multi-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, however, would not have been enough to keep Alou if
not for a final factor. Vladimir Guerrero, his 23-year-old right
fielder, is the sort of player to construct a team around, and the
Expos tied him to a five-year $27 million contract for that exact
reason. In just his second full season, Guerrero hit .324 last year
with 38 homers and 109 RBIs and displayed what many baseball people
think is the best arm in the majors. If this franchise has hope,
Guerrero will lug it to the plate every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is he can do whatever he wants to
do,'' Beattie said. ``The guy has a chance to win any (hitting)
title he really sets his mind to.''
</P>
<P>
   While Andruw Jones is still plumbing his potential in Atlanta,
Alou already has compared Guerrero to a young Roberto Clemente.
Houston outfielder Moises Alou, Felipe's son, went a bit further
this month by suggesting that Guerrero could be the best Latin-born
player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human,'' Guerrero said through interpreter/infielder Jose
Vidro. ``God is the one in charge of me. If (Moises) said those
words, I'm very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero and Jones will spend their careers in eternal
comparison. While Jones established a defensive standard in 1998
with his first Gold Glove season, Guerrero's superior power numbers
_ .546 career slugging percentage compared with Jones' .472 _
signaled his arrival as a polished slugger. Furthermore, Guerrero
only has to be told things once.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both talented kids,'' Beattie said. ``I know Andruw
has had a few run-ins with discipline. We don't have any of those
here. Actually, you have to tone Vladimir down a little bit. His
enthusiasm has him playing out of control sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero leveled his eyes when questioned about how he will
improve in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work the same as I did last year,'' he said.
``You've got to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
