<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON COMETS GUARD GOES HOME AFTER SUCCESSFUL SURGERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRIAN McTAGGART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kim Perrot walked gingerly into a room full of
reporters whom she greeted with a familiar smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see you guys made it back,'' she said. ``I know you weren't
expecting me to be back, but I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who has seen the Comets 5-5 point guard play
basketball would have been foolish to believe Perrot would let a
battle with brain and lung cancer keep her off her feet, much less
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, dressed in a black and yellow warm-up suit and a Comets
WNBA championship cap, left the University of Texas M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center on Sunday just four days after doctors removed a
golf-ball-sized tumor from her brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank God for getting me through this,'' Perrot
said. ``Secondly, I want to thank my family and people around the
world who supported me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, 32, announced Feb. 22 she was suffering from alveolar
adenocarcinoma, a cancer that starts in the lungs but spread to her
brain. Wednesday's craniotomy was to remove the largest tumor from
her brain, which was causing headaches, dizziness and other
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Raymond Sawaya, chairman of the department of neurosurgery,
said the tumor was close to the part of the brain that controls
functions on the right side of Perrot's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raised the bar to some extent, and the concern doing the
surgery was we might be affecting that,'' he said. ``It was a
delicate surgery because of the location of the tumor. But I was
very pleased with how it turned out. One of my greatest fears
because of who she is and her professional accomplishments is that
we wouldn't want her to lose any strength in her right hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ritsuko Komaki, a radiation oncologist who will oversee
Perrot's treatments, said Perrot's excellent health improves her
chances of beating the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not expect any problems going into radiation therapy,''
she said. ``I would like to take care of whatever is left over,
which are very small spots. I'm confident we can get rid of the
small spots in her brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the first, and perhaps most difficult step, is behind
her, Perrot's path to recovery will be long. She will begin 2 1/2
weeks of radiation treatments in about a week to remove several
smaller tumors on her brain. She will then undergo six months of
chemotherapy treatments to remove multiple lesions on her lungs,
which is where the cancer originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first part of the journey was very successful,'' Perrot
said. ``I'm on my way to the second step, and it's going to be a
struggle. But I feel strong and ready to take on the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot appeared in good spirits as she left the Houston hospital
with several family members, including her mother. Perrot opened
and closed her right fist to show reporters she had lost no
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot will receive one radiation treatment a day, five days a
week for 2 1/2 weeks. Komaki said the treatments will be done on an
outpatient basis and will take ``only a couple of minutes'' and
will not make her sick. During this time, Perrot will take steroids
to reduce the swelling in her brain.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot said that although her recovery is the primary issue with
her, she wants to resume her basketball career at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've done all my life,'' she said. ``The fact
that all that can be taken away is kind of difficult. But I have
faith in God and the best doctors in the world and work for a great
organization. I know that I'm going to be back on the court one
day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
