<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIRELESS-WIRELESS_SFC     02-28 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-WIRELESS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 COMPANIES ARE WIRED ABOUT UNTETHERED TECH  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to get unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of companies are developing products that will give
mobility to the wired masses, allowing consumers to perform
everyday tasks such as surfing the Web and sending e-mail from
handheld devices with a wireless connection.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers soon will be able to trade a stock through a handheld
computer, access their company's intranet from a cell phone and
order a pizza from their personal display assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of wireless data has been around for years, but the
race to supply customers with anytime-anywhere Internet access
seems to have taken off in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as 3Com Corp., Microsoft Corp. and Cisco Systems
recently have announced products or partnerships focused on
wireless Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, 3Com's Palm Computing division will roll out
the Palm VII, a personal display assistant with a built-in wireless
connection for Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Communications and Netscape &LR;   &LR; Communications Corp. have
teamed up to provide Web browsing via Nextel's cell phones. And
Netscape's rival, Microsoft, recently announced two new ventures to
provide wireless data to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco also is making its first foray into the wireless world,
announcing a $1 billion, five-year-deal with Motorola to provide
Internet access via cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say the race to provide customers with
wireless Internet access is under way because of the popularity of
the Web and the abundance of cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 million people worldwide use cell phones, and that
number is expected to grow to 1 billion by 2005. On the corporate
front, the Gartner Group predicts that there will be 54 million
mobile workers in the United States by 2003. Most of them probably
will want access to the Internet, their e-mail and their company's
internal network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, what people become comfortable with in the wired
world, they start to demand in the wireless world as well,'' said
Albert Lin, an analyst with The Abernathy Group who follows
wireless companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, like Metricom, which makes a wireless modem
called Ricochet, spotted this trend early and already are offering
products for portable computers and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into a business today, almost everybody has a cell
phone,'' said John Wernke, Metricom's vice president of marketing
and sales. ``It's become prolific. The same is going to be true for
wireless data.''
</P>
<P>
   Metricom has 27,000 subscribers in three cities, including San
Francisco, who get unlimited Internet access for $30 a month.
Wernke said Metricom plans to be in at least 50 cities by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Ricochet and other wireless products take off
remains to be seen. That's because the same mobility that gives
wireless access its appeal also has an unfortunate drawback: slow
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the products on the market and some of those being
planned have slow connection speeds. Industry watchers say that
could dampen the appeal of wireless products.
</P>
<P>
   Ricochet offers a speed of 20 kilobits per second, which is
slower than what most dial-up modems deliver. The company does plan
to increase the speed of its product in July, Wernke said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential stumbling block for wireless data is the bulk
and difficulty of some of the planned products. Qualcomm's PDQ
phone, which marries a PalmPilot with a cell phone, is bigger and
heavier than both devices on their own. And those who have tested
it say it's complicated to master.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wireless devices have to be easy to use and have
demonstrated functionality,'' said Roberta Wiggins, wireless data
analyst with the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins pointed to products like 3Com's Palm VII _ which will
allow users to surf the Web, track stocks and send e-mail from the
handheld organizer _ as potential successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palm has been popular as an organizer, and if the wireless
communications capability is integrated and easy to use, I think it
will be pretty natural evolution for the Palm users,'' Wiggins
said.
</P>
<P>
   A new crop of ``smart phones,'' or next-generation cell phones,
now being developed are expected to give consumers easy wireless
Internet access though they still are three to five years away.
</P>
<P>
   And for tasks such as simply sending e-mail, many of the
Internet cell phones being planned probably will suffice, Wiggins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Nextel's cell phone with Web access and the
technology being developed by companies like Wireless Knowledge, a
joint venture between Microsoft and San Diego's Qualcomm Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Knowledge's products eventually will allow people to
get their personal and corporate e-mail from various devices,
including cell phones and two-way pagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No.1 thing people want to take mobile is their e-mail,''
said Tom Clarkson, vice president of marketing for Wireless
Knowledge. ``Our technology will enable them to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But some are more excited about the wackier, more far-out things
that wireless Internet access can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Using a cell phone, consumers eventually could download money
from the Internet onto a smart card. Other people could have their
hearts wirelessly monitored by doctors to prevent cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Jetsons-like applications,'' said Don
Listwin, executive vice president at Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cole, who tracks the wireless industry for Renaissance
Worldwide, said he expects the next generation of cell phones to
drive the wireless data market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These phones will have broad business and consumer appeal
because they marry powerful voice, video and data applications,''
Cole said. ``That's the holy grail of wireless, and as people see
the costs of equipment and devices drop significantly, the wireless
data market is going to take off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
