<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: HIRSHHORN MAKEOVER; PERFORMING FOR WOMEN'S HEALTH;
NEW BALLET IN HOUSTON; A SINATRA PREMIERE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Texas)   (js) 
 By LAWRENCE   VAN   GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With expanded wall space, improved lighting, platforms for
sculpture and new carpets, the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture
Garden in Washington is showing off artists like Thomas Eakins,
Edouard Vuillard, Edward Hopper and Fernand Leger in the 14
third-floor galleries that have just been renovated. The
reinstallation, ``The Hirshhorn Collection at 25: Celebrating
Modern and Contemporary Art,'' begins the 25th-anniversary year of
the museum, the Smithsonian Institution's showcase for modern and
contemporary art, which opened in October 1974 with a core
collection from the financier and art patron Joseph H. Hirshhorn.
Information: (202) 357-2700.
</P>
<P>
   Gesundheit
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Shubert Theater, normally home to ``Chicago,''
gets a new cast Monday night: performers like Zoe Caldwell, Uta
Hagen and Eartha Kitt; ``Chorus Line'' alumnae like Priscilla Lopez
and Donna McKechnie, as well as Marisa Tomei, Anne Meara and
others. The vehicle, at 7, is ``Nothing Like a Dame,'' a program of
music, dance and theater that supports the Phyllis Newman Women's
Health Initiative of the Actors' Fund of America. A few guys will
be around, too. Information: (888) 326-3849.
</P>
<P>
   First Steps
</P>
<P>
   There is a dance premiere on Thursday when the Houston Ballet
performs ``Indigo,'' by the Australian choreographer Stanton Welch,
who is also creating works for the San Francisco Ballet, the Royal
Danish Ballet and the Australian Ballet. An abstract work for eight
dancers set to two Vivaldi cello concertos, ``Indigo'' will be
paired with Bournonville's ``Sylphide,'' with the Cuban star Carlos
Acosta, in six performances at the Wortham Center through March 14.
Information: (800) 828-2787.
</P>
<P>
   Encore
</P>
<P>
   A Sinatra premiere is beckoning. The rarity is the first
American showing of ``This Is Sinatra!,'' a 1962 British television
special that captured him swinging through 29 songs in 90 minutes
during a performance at the Royal Festival Hall in London. Screened
by the Museum of Television and Radio Tuesday at the Directors
Guild of America in Los Angeles and on Wednesday at the museum's
site in New York, ``This Is Sinatra!,'' running through May 30 on
both coasts, opens the 16th annual William S. Paley Television
Festival at the museum's Los Angeles site. Through March 16, the
event salutes significant shows like ``The Twilight Zone'' and
``Thirtysomething,'' and people like Carl Reiner, with screenings
and discussions. Information: New York: (212) 621-6800; Los
Angeles: (310) 786-1000.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
