<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-THE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  
  
</HEADLINE>
 NET FILES _ SF CHRON   PointCast Seeks Net Redemption 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In the land where stock quadruples in a day, creating instant
billionaires, is there room for an Internet phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   The powers that be at PointCast hope so. The onetime hot-shot
firm is undergoing a radical reincarnation to reverse its fortunes,
according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunnyvale company exploded on the scene in 1996 with free
software that delivered news and information from the Internet
directly to computer users.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  But many consumers and corporations complained that their Net
connections were too slow to handle the onslaught of data, and
PointCast lost subscribers. Its membership dipped to 1.3 million
this year, from 1.5 million, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  But in a few weeks, the ``push'' pioneer is expected to announce
that it is teaming up with several Baby Bells (Pacific Bell and
BellSouth are the most commonly rumored partners) to deliver news
to consumers over high-speed Internet connections, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Isn't that the same business that PointCast
flopped at? PointCast hopes that this will be a whole new ballgame.
By going into business with the telcos, the reasoning goes,
PointCast will sidestep the slow connectivity problems that
bedeviled its own service.
</P>
<P>
   The telcos, which so far haven't capitalized on the Internet,
want to fuel the Web's next growth spurt by providing faster
connections.
</P>
<P>
   But the phone companies will face fierce competition from
players like AtHome, which uses cable TV lines to provide Internet
access up to 100 times faster than traditional dial-up connections.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AOL and other Internet service providers also want to
get into the ``broadband'' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who have Internet access at home want faster
service. This is where most of the industry's growth will come over
the next few years,'' AOL chief executive Steve Case said in an
interview this month.
</P>
<P>
   And PointCast hopes to cash in on that growth. Its potential
match with the Baby Bells seems a natural: PointCast CEO David
Dorman is a former executive at Pacific Bell, SBC Communications
and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   He and other PointCast officials declined  &LR;   &LR; to comment on the
company's imminent plans.
</P>
<P>
   If the new scheme catches on, PointCast will make another stab
at an initial public offering, probably this year. It ditched an
IPO last year after apparently failing to spark investor interest.
</P>
<P>
   But is that soon enough? The company is in danger of becoming a
footnote in Internet history, the most egregious example of online
hype deflated by market realities.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, it was so confident _ some claim delusional _
about its long-term financial prospects, it spurned a $400 million
takeover offer from Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   PointCast can only hope that it can rise from the ashes. If not,
it could end up becoming the answer to a question in Trivial
Pursuit about failed Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAKING SEVERAL LISTS &QL; 
The explosion of e-mail and bulletin boards has made juggling
online mailing lists for specific topics and friends confusing.
Until now.
</P>
<P>
   OneList.com ( &LR; www.onelist.com &LR; ) of Palo Alto has devised a
mailing list system that lets users create and manage e-mail lists
or subscribe to a spectrum of current lists for disparate topics
such as jokes, medical support, culture and games. And it's quick,
easy and free.
</P>
<P>
   So far, plenty of people have taken to the software. In one
year, Onelist.com has gained 2 million users and processes 10
million e-mail messages daily. By the end of the year, the company
expects to handle 3 billion messages a month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONSTER NUMBERS &QL; 
Speaking of scary growth, consider Monster.com ( &LR; www.monster.com &LR; ),
the largest online recruitment agency in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Maynard, Mass., company _ which received kudos for its stark
black-and-white Super Bowl ads depicting pessimistic young
jobseekers _ is used in six countries (United States, Canada, the
United Kingdom, Australia, the Netherlands and New Zealand) and is
about to add three more (Belgium, France and Germany). Some 35,000
companies post 180,000 openings on the site, which also lists 1
million resumes. Its stock has nearly doubled, to $57.38, over the
past several months.
</P>
<P>
   And evidently, it scored some touchdowns of its own after the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder Jeff Taylor said the number of job searches on
the site the day following the big game jumped to 2.2 million _ up
from an average of about 173,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IMPEACHMENT! THE MOVIE &QL; 
The virtual polls open tomorrow at Theglobe.com
( &LR; www.theglobe.com &LR; ), the Web community that is asking its 9.3
million members to cast a fictitious movie titled ``Impeachment!
The Movie,'' about you-know-what. The publicity stunt is part of
the company's Oscar coverage this month.
</P>
<P>
   Before the voting starts, the Net Files has some casting
suggestions: a younger Delta Burke as Monica Lewinsky, Jack Lemmon
as Ken Starr, ``Felicity'' star Keri Russell as Chelsea Clinton,
Mike Myers in drag as Linda Tripp (although John Goodman's classic
portrayal of Tripp on ``Saturday Night Live'' would be hard to
top), Billy Bob Thornton as James Carville, and Robert Guillaume as
Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think? Drop us an e-mail at  &LR; jswartz &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Vicariously experience a year of living dangerously in Vietnam at &LR; 
www.deros.com &LR; . The digital book traces East Bay resident Michael
Horton's tour of duty from 1967 to 1968.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at top-quality short films and animated features,
check out &LR;  www.atom.com &LR; . The site, debuting today, also accepts
the works of filmmakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
