u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-SYRACUSE-NY     02-28 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES REBOUND AT EXPENSE OF ORANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ The Connecticut Huskies waited for the last
hours of February to reassert themselves as contenders in the
coming National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, and the
result was a perfect 10. In the 10 minutes that opened the second
half, the Huskies shot 10 of 10.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stretch in which Khalid El-Amin bore down the Carrier
Dome court with his teammates swarming like they were termites in
an abandoned barn, gobbling up 15 breakaway points. It was a
stretch in which Richard Hamilton dropped in bombs as if a magnet
attracted them to the bottom of the net. Sunday, the Huskies
recaptured the verve, precision and chest-bumping swagger that had
made them the nation's top-ranked team for 10 consecutive weeks.
They looked as if they played for a team that felt it deserved to
win another Big East title.
</P>
<P>
   When that 10-minute burst finally ended with a missed shot, the
Huskies had turned a halftime deficit of 2 points into a 15-point
lead. Their 24-7 run powered a 70-58 thumping of No. 24 Syracuse _
the team that had knocked them from the No. 1 spot by handing them
an embarrassing 59-42 loss on the first day of February.
</P>
<P>
   That loss sent the Huskies stumbling through a month of sluggish
play that tumbled them to No. 4 in the national ranking and
probably sent them across the country as the No. 1-seeded team in
the West Regional in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But after the game here, the Huskies made a statement that was
backed by their 25-2 regular-season record, including 16-2 in the
Big East and 9-0 on the road. They made a statement with their
fifth outright Big East title in six years, a statement about who
has the best team heading into this week's conference tournament at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard it all year,'' said Hamilton, who finished the
game with 26 points. ``First it was St. John's. Then last week it
was Miami. The new Beasts of the East? We're still the team to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   They are because they recovered magnificently from a first half
in which they shot 31 percent, coughed up the ball five times and
looked as listless as they had in their past four games: a loss to
Miami and closer-than-they-should-have-been victories over Seton
Hall, Rutgers and Providence.
</P>
<P>
   But those 10 minutes of perfection powered a 69 percent shooting
percentage in the second half for the Huskies as they harassed the
Orangemen on defense, then raced down the court and dunked on them
on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they didn't get back very well on defense, so we
wanted to push them,'' said El-Amin, who scored 21 points. ``Push
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped push Syracuse into having to play deep into the Big
East tournament. The Orangemen (19-10, 10-8) will be seeded No. 4
when they open the tournament against Boston College on Wednesday.
Syracuse _ along with fifth-seeded Villanova (20-9, 10-8), which
will play West Virginia on Wednesday _ needs to make a case that
the conference deserves a fourth and fifth NCAA bid behind the
Huskies, Miami and St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fourth-place team in the Big East doesn't get in,
there's something very wrong,'' Syracuse Coach Jim Boeheim said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orangemen could have nailed down a tournament bid by
duplicating a first half that threatened to blow out the Huskies in
front of a noisy capacity crowd of 30,367.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen scored the game's first 9 points, built a 10-point
lead and employed a smothering 2-3 zone that had Connecticut Coach
Jim Calhoun shouting at his players to make better decisions. The
Orangemen also had the Huskies outmanned: Jake Voskuhl,
Connecticut's 6-foot-11-inch center, was a late scratch because of
a sprained left foot. A stress fracture in that foot had kept him
out of the teams' first meeting. Albert Mouring, Connecticut's
sixth man, was also unavailable Sunday because of a sprained right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   They were hardly missed during the Huskies' helter-skelter
second-half start. Connecticut's defensive pressure forced Syracuse
into shooting 25 percent, and the Huskies outmuscled the Orangemen
by 37-27 on the backboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get back on defense,'' Boeheim said, beginning a
litany of his team's shortcomings in the second half. ``They
pounded us on the boards. We didn't get any movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, meanwhile, rediscovered their sense of ball
movement and, well, fun. Calhoun pointed to his team's 19 assists,
which ranged from Kevin Freeman bombs to a streaking Rashamel Jones
to the niftier drives and dishes that El-Amin executed under the
basket. Freeman, who pulled down 13 rebounds, smiled as he recalled
the perfect 10 minutes of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were relaxed, and when we started forcing turnovers, we
grew confident,'' he said. ``Then the ball starts zipping around
the court. We shared it, and when you do that, we're back to
playing like we did in December.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said that he looks at the Huskies' season as two
chapters. The 19-0 start spoiled his team, which was then tested by
its 6-2 finish. The trick now, Calhoun said, is to take the best of
both parts of the season first to Madison Square Garden, and then
to the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've been in a shooting slump these last few
weeks,'' Calhoun said, acknowledging that he has joined in the
public dissection of what has been wrong with the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun added: ``We've been in a passing slump. We haven't moved
the ball. But we've responded with character. It's admirable,
really. We've had a pretty decent season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
