<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2475 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE_SFC     02-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE/TOM ABATE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Scios CEO Says Plant Closure, Layoffs Needed to Save Company 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; In this new weekly column, biotech reporter Tom Abate will take &LR; 
 &LR; you behind the scenes of the Bay Area's biotechnology industry, &LR; 
 &LR; looking at the companies, people and issues that are &LR; 
 &LR; transforming how we treat disease. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Richard Brewer, chief executive of Scios Inc., is expected to
walk into work this morning and lay off a third of Scios' 270
employees, close its drug manufacturing plant and sell its
three-building campus in Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot continue business as usual,'' Brewer said. ``There
hasn't been a reality check on this company for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Hired five months ago as part of a shareholder-instigated
shakeup of the board and management, Brewer said the cuts are only
part of his prescription to transform Scios from a nonperformer _
the stock, worth $25 in 1991, trades at under $10 today _ into a
Wall Street favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first drug is close to approval, we've got cash, and we're
close to $400 million in market capitalization,'' Brewer said. ``We
have a chance to move up past $500 million (in market cap) and then
to a billion,'' the threshold at which institutional investors
become interested in companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest variable in Scios' future is outside Brewer's
control. Last month, Scios cleared the second-to-last regulatory
hurdle toward approval of its first drug, Natrecor. Designed to
relieve shortness of breath and other life-threatening symptoms
associated with congestive heart failure, Natrecor would be aimed
at a $250 million market.
</P>
<P>
   But before Scios and its marketing partner, pharmaceutical giant
Bayer AG, can tout Natrecor, they need final approval from the Food
and Drug Administration. Though Brewer is confident that Natrecor
will pass FDA muster, the agency still might decide that Natrecor
needs more safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, meanwhile, faces trials of his own. Three times since
1993, disgruntled Scios shareholders have floated resolutions to
sell, dissolve or otherwise shake up the firm. The most recent
revolt in 1997 eventually resulted in the ouster of former CEO
Richard Casey. A fourth initiative, this one suggesting the sale of
the company, will be on the proxy statement when Scios holds is
annual shareholder meeting this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's reorganization could boost the stock and silence the
critics. But today, the former Genentech executive must explain the
severance packages to 90 fired workers while persuading the 180
survivors to move into a smaller building in Sunnyvale where Scios
already has a research lab.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its ills, Scios has more than $90 million in cash and
could raise another $20 million by selling the three Mountain View
buildings. Brewer said he'll use that money to buy promising drugs
from smaller, cash-starved biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to get our assets working harder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INDUSTRIAL ANNIVERSARY &QL; 
It was 25 years ago that two Bay Area professors showed the world
how to snip strands of DNA from one microbe and paste the genetic
material into another organism. This discovery of recombinant DNA
technology paved the way for the biotech revolution.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, the University of California at Berkeley will hold
a daylong series of events to celebrate these seminal experiments
by former University of California at San Francisco biochemist Herb
Boyer and Stanford University geneticist Stanley Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Bay Area residents can learn more about the
science of gene-splicing at a three-hour course taught by Desmond
Mascarenhas, an instructor at the UC Berkeley Extension and
director of research at Celtrix Pharmaceuticals in Santa Clara.
There is a $20 registration fee.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, a panel of scientific luminaries, including
three Nobel laureates, will discuss the ethical, legal and
commercial ramifications of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Headlining the afternoon panel, which is free and open to the
public, will be Harvard University's James Watson, who earned his
Nobel for the co-discovery of DNA. Fellow prize-winners J. Michael
Bishop of UCSF and Paul Berg of Stanford will be joined by seven
other Bay Area leaders in the commercial, scientific and
sociological realms of biotech.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a stunning lineup that the afternoon session surely
will fill up. UC will provide overflow seating and a video feed to
accommodate those who can't get seats in Wheeler Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   You can reserve a seat online at  &LR; www.berkeley.edu/unex &LR; 
 &LR; /biotech.  &LR; Or call the UC Berkeley Extension, (510) 642-4111, in
which case you'll need to know the course numbers. For the free
afternoon session, it's EDP 056614. For the morning course, the
magic numbers are EDP 056044 _ and your $20 credit card payment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
