<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2476 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MUSIC_SFCHRON &LR;      02-28 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MUSIC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Firms Jockeying to Be First In MP3 Music Revolution  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; The MP3 phenomenon has shifted from college dorms to boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The past two weeks has brought a flurry of announcements from
the likes of major companies such as Sony Corp., IBM and Texas
Instruments, each promoting its own new advancements in controlling
online music distribution and halting the spread of illegal MP3
formatted songs.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies, which just a year ago paid no attention to the
MP3 songs being distributed largely by college students and
tech-savvy music fans, now are scrambling to be first in line when
the digital music revolution starts to change the way consumers buy
music.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is software used to squeeze the size of audio files, so they
can be more easily stored on a computer hard disk and transmitted
on the Internet. In the past year, its popularity has soared with
half a million songs _ both legal and pirated _ distributed on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's trying to lay their cards on the table and jockey
for position,'' said Rick Fleischman, senior marketing director for
Liquid Audio, a Redwood City online music company. ``This is now
the prime time ... to come out and show your stuff and get known.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in Los Angeles, more than 275 people representing
about 100 companies like Sony, Microsoft and Liquid Audio attended
the first official meeting of the Secure Digital Music Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Spearheaded by the Recording Industry Association of America,
the SDMI's mission is to come up with common technical standards
that will allow consumers to buy and play digital music no matter
what device they use.
</P>
<P>
   The group is seeking methods to stop music piracy that it says
was spawned by MP3's popularity. However, the SDMI also will help
shape how the recording industry sells copyright-protected digital
music in the long term, as well affect the distribution of other
digital products like audio books and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ambition of the initiative is the biggest in my
experience,'' said newly named SDMI Executive Director Leonardo
Chiariglione, head of Telecom Italia's research center.
Chiariglione is renowned for his work in the early 1990s as chair
of the original MPEG group that established audio and video
compression standards that became the basis for the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies began promoting their own technologies last
week in advance of the SDMI meeting. Sony announced a microchip for
music players and recorders to prevent piracy and software to
encode music.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio said it will team with chipmaker Texas Instruments
to develop a device that plays copyright-protected digital music in
portable devices like the Rio PMP300, Diamond Multimedia System's
handheld MP3 music player.
</P>
<P>
   And San Jose software-maker InterTrust Technologies Corp. said
it is working on security software with Fraunhofer IIS, a German
firm that originally developed the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   Chiariglione said the SDMI won't choose one technology over
another, which could segment the market into ``a series of niche
markets that will defeat their own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   An SDMI working group will start meeting this week to nail down
security standards for portable devices like the Rio by June 30.
Meanwhile, another group will try to hammer out ``more
encompassing'' standards'' by March 31, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
