</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKINGDOGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T SUBSTITUTES FRED WILLARD FOR TALKING HOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the typically staid AT&AMP;T Corp. began a new unit called the
Lucky Dog Phone Co. last October with a barrage of offbeat
television advertisements featuring talking dogs, it seemed an
inspired idea.
</P>
<P>
   But the advertisements, which featured real dogs with dubbed-in
celebrity voices and were created by Young &AMP; Rubicam New York, may
have been perceived as over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Dog was the first new brand created by AT&AMP;T in its
113-year history to avoid mentioning AT&AMP;T itself. And the company
and some telecommunications analysts say that as a business, the
Lucky Dog 10-10-345 ``dial-around'' discount long-distance
operation is on track.
</P>
<P>
   But as an advertising campaign, the talking dogs' short run is
over. The advertisements featuring the dogs ended in December and
in the last few weeks AT&AMP;T has been introducing their replacement:
Fred Willard, the comedic actor, who is featured in Lucky Dog's
new, more conventional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As with the previous ads, the target audience is a more
price-conscious part of the market than would be attracted by the
AT&AMP;T brand. And the cornerstone of the Lucky Dog concept remains
the same: The consumer is not supposed to know that Lucky Dog is
part of AT&AMP;T. (The No. 2 MCI Worldcom Inc. offers its own
hide-the-brand discount services, the 10-10-321 and 10-10-220
services sold under the Telecom USA name.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says it meant all along to eventually clamp the muzzle on
the anthropomorphic dogs. But some advertising and marketing
experts say the concept was too wacky from the start. Jack Trout,
president of Trout &AMP; Partners, a marketing strategy firm in
Greenwich, Conn., said the talking dogs may have been too unusual
to convey a sense of legitimacy about the Lucky Dog operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dog was a dog of an idea,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
guys out there screaming numbers, and there is a question of who is
legitimate. The AT&AMP;T program probably looked less legitimate with
the dogs than anybody. They just got too cute. Now they're trying
to make this thing seem a little more real.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes A. Roth, senior executive director of Landor Associates, a
brand consulting firm that is a unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., is
another who thinks the previous campaign may have gone astray.
``Sometimes cuteness gets in the way of message,'' he said. ``In
advertising this kind of service you have one big job: to sell-in
memory of the numbers. And people don't remember numbers that
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``My guess is that they went out and discovered that
Lucky Dog got a lot of attention and it set it apart, but if you
remember Lucky Dog and don't remember how you access Lucky Dog, I
guess you didn't do all that good of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not, of course, how Howard E. McNally, Lucky Dog's
president, quite sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial campaign did exactly what we wanted it to do,'' he
said. ``It gave us a lot of bark and a little bit of bite. It got
us presence. We then needed to focus on a call to action: `Pick up
the phone, dial 10-10-345.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he added, ``we're trying to make sure they remember the
number, and we're having a lot of fun with Fred Willard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Lippert, the advertising critic for the trade
magazine Adweek, is not impressed. She said Lucky Dog was not
distinguishing itself with Willard, since so many other phone
promotions already use comedians and comedic actors. MCI Worldcom,
for example, uses or has used Dennis Miller, George Carlin and
Christopher Lloyd in television advertisements, and AT&AMP;T is
currently employing Paul Reiser to promote the AT&AMP;T brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very weak centrist move,'' Ms. Lippert said.
``Obviously they were trying to be small and edgy. Then if that
didn't work, they try to go to the other extreme.'' Her conclusion?
``As long as there are phone companies there will be jobs for aging
comedians.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how successful or dreadful the Lucky Dog advertising
campaign may turn out to be, there are some analysts who think AT&AMP;T
would win either way.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Adamik, a communications analyst for the Yankee Group, a
technology consulting firm in Boston, said that Lucky Dog had
become one of the dial-around market leaders. But because the new
services are still used mainly by companies like MCI to take
business away from AT&AMP;T, he said, AT&AMP;T would benefit even if the
entire segment disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wreck the category, it's still to their advantage,''
he said. Adamik quickly added that he did not believe wreckage was
AT&AMP;T's goal. Still, ``if they can in some way contribute to the
demise of the industry, they win, because they still have the
lion's share of the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
