</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GETTING ALONG IN CONGRESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 1:
</P>
<P>
   Congress has long had a famously unhealthy tendency toward
coziness. Senators and representatives assail each other in public,
but voters wonder whether they then retire to their racquetball
courts, watering holes and dinner parties to make mutually
beneficial deals, especially when it comes to rules on ethics and
gifts. But today the clubby old atmosphere of Congress is looked on
with something approaching nostalgia. The public seems more worried
these days by its culture of partisanship, pettiness, revenge and
the resulting paralysis. Some lawmakers have begun talking like
apostles for a new 12-step program to restore healing and civility.
</P>
<P>
   You would think politicians would not need lessons in listening
to each other. But after a year of hectoring over President
Clinton's personal conduct, they are not a bad idea. This month
House members plan a return to Hershey, Pa., where they held a
retreat two years ago. This time they have invited John Hume, the
Catholic leader who won a Nobel prize for helping to bury ancient
ethnic hatreds in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In similar fashion, the Senate seems to look back on its closed
session in the Clinton impeachment trial as a kind of epiphany, or
at least a group therapy session. Senators get misty-eyed about
discovering their own humanity and want to keep the spirit alive,
though the impeachment votes were overwhelmingly partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggestions for the Congressional sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Republicans have to recognize that their extreme
dislike of Clinton need not preclude legislative agreements.
Thinking clearly about strategy might help. Last week, the new
House speaker, Dennis Hastert, and other Republican leaders
complained that Clinton might carry out a sneaky plan to offer
policies that Republicans would reject, and then use the
confrontation as a campaign issue. Really, what will that White
House think of next? It seems only the other day that the GOP was
accusing Clinton of the opposite: adopting Republican policies like
the balanced budget and welfare reform and embracing them as his
own. This is not distrust. It is confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, meanwhile, have their minds on more down-to-earth
concerns. They want Hastert to at least tell them what bills will
be taken up the following week. They also want committee
assignments that reflects their gains in the last two elections,
noting that the lopsided majorities of Republicans on committees
have not changed since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans note that they are treating the Democratic minority
no worse than they were treated when they were the minority. That
is why it was sensible for Richard Gephardt, the Democratic leader,
to promise that if he becomes speaker after the next election,
which is not a bad bet, he will do no less than what he is asking
Republicans to do now.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to restore comity to the Congress is to let the
majority of Americans have their views count, and to have
majorities of lawmakers in Congress be able to pass legislation
even if hard-line party ideologues oppose it. There are probably
solid majorities in the House and Senate for campaign finance
reform, raising the minimum wage and a patient's bill of rights
that includes the right to sue health maintenance organizations. A
bipartisan consensus has emerged on limited tax cuts and more money
for education and defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic leaders must realize that if the
popular will is bottled up for the sake of narrow partisan
advantage, no amount of happy talk will raise Congress' esteem.
Results are what count. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
