<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS ISSUED : MAGNETIC VIDEOTAPE THAT RECORDS BOTH ANALOG AND
DIGITAL SIGNALS ; SUNSCREEN FOR CLOTHES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Pa., N.J. , Ohio)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When confronted with the advent of the digital, high-definition
television age, many people immediately want to know whether they
will still be able to watch their collections of videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers of videocassette recorders know the answer has to
be yes, since consumers would rebel at the idea of a digital
technology that makes their home videos, children's Disney movies
and personal copies of ``Titanic'' obsolete. Even though new
generations of VCRs will have to be equipped to play both analog
and digital tapes, many people will keep using their existing
players for years.
</P>
<P>
   Since digital recordings may provide sharper pictures, movie
studios and video rental companies will want to be able to offer
them to their customers. But they will have to continue to stock
analog recordings for those who have not rushed out to buy new
digital-ready VCRs. For video sales and rental businesses having to
stock both analog and digital copies of videotapes will create cost
and space problems.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate this problem, Christopher Strolle of Glenside, Pa.,
and Jung Wan Ko, from Lawrenceville, N.J., have patented a magnetic
tape that can record both analog and digital signals. Their patent
belongs to the Samsung Electronics Co. of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional videotapes rely on recording heads that trace a
slanted track that is micrometers wide onto magnetic tape. The
heads leave unused or ``guard'' space in between those tracks. The
tracks are traced at specific angles to prevent ``mis-tracking,''
or the distortions that can result when a signal is picked up from
an adjacent track during playback.
</P>
<P>
   The invention exploits the fact that extra signals can be
recorded on this unused portion of the tape. The conventional VHS
tracks are straddled by tracks used for recording and reproducing a
high-definition signal, though the inventors say the space could
also be used for a wide screen or other television signal. The
track containing the standard VHS signal is traced at specific
intervals, widths and angles. The track containing the
high-definition signal is half the width of the VHS track so that
two tracks of the high-definition signal can fit between each of
the VHS tracks.
</P>
<P>
   This format ``allows one tape to record both a high-definition
television signal and a standard VHS signal'' and ``provides a way
to avoid the problem of having to carry a dual inventory of tapes
in a tape sales or rental business.''
</P>
<P>
   Strolle and Ko received patent 5,870,522.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunscreen for Clothes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunscreens protect skin from the ravages of direct sun, but what
about clothing? Procter &AMP; Gamble &UR;  &LR; believes that fabric _ or at
least the colors in fabrics _ could use protection against the sun,
too. The company owns a patent issued to John Cort Severns for a
compound that can be added to a conventional clothing dryer to make
clothes resistant to sun fading.
</P>
<P>
   The patent covers a mix of antioxidants, sunscreens and fabric
conditioners that are resistant to light and do not stain. Similar
antioxidants already are used in detergents to stabilize bleach,
and to prevent yellowing in detergents and softeners.
</P>
<P>
   Severns favors a dryer sheet over a rinse to deliver the
compound to clothing, because he says research has shown that
sheets can do the job with half to a quarter as much compound as
required in a rinse.
</P>
<P>
   The sheet would be tossed in the dryer with wet clothes; heat
from the drying cycle melts the compounds and releases the
antioxidants and sunscreens onto the clothes. Severns' patent said
the compound would ``reduce the fading of fabrics from sunlight.''
</P>
<P>
   He received patent 5,869,443.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
