<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PISTONS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNINSPIRED KNICKS FALL TO PISTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ During Detroit Pistons games, the
technicians in the rafters of the Palace like to shine a spotlight
on the energetic creatures who are acting the craziest in the
stands. And everyone in the place looks at the attention-getting
guys jumping up and down, and everyone responds with an emotional
roar.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks would like to borrow that spotlight. They
would like to shine it on their starters and locate Charles Oakley.
They would like to shine it on their bench and discover John
Starks. They are desperate to find anyone _ any trace of a lift,
any speck of energy _ to pull them out of an unsightly funk that
has left them drained of all emotion when they take their act on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no Oakley, and there is no Starks. Once again, the
Knicks showed up as stone-faced and detached as subway passengers
Sunday, barely reacting when the Pistons pushed them and jostled
them toward franchise lows. Apparently, pride could not motivate a
Knicks team that lost, 89-68, even though Grant Hill scored just
four points.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's total did not matter. The Knicks were not a threat, not
when their final total was seven points short of the franchise low,
not when their 27-point second half was one point short of the team
low for a half.
</P>
<P>
   With this ghastly accumulation, the Knicks (8-5) lost their
second game in a row and suffered their third road defeat by double
digits this season. Somehow, they forget to pack their personality
when they leave home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves on being a hard-nosed, tough, blue-collar
team,'' said Larry Johnson, who scored 12 points playing on a sore
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't seen it. You have to have emotion and guys
picking each other up. Oakley didn't show a lot of emotion. But if
you played with him, you could see all the hard work that he came
with every night, taking charges, diving on the floor. You say:
`Man, that guy is playing his heart out. We got to play with him.'
It's hard. Someone has to step up and we need to feed off him. You
need a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one took on that responsibility Sunday. A halfhearted effort
in perimeter defense allowed the 35-year-old Joe Dumars, who scored
21 points, to lose Charlie Ward and Allan Houston and bounce free
for four 3-pointers. A weary shooting effort resulted in the Knicks
hitting just 36 percent of their shots.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to respond to the Pistons' intensity turned a
five-point game early in the third quarter into a 27-point Detroit
lead eight minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Not one Knick responded during Detroit's blistering 26-4 run.
Houston looked drained, still battling the demons he has found at
the Palace in the three years since he spurned the Pistons as a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   After making just 4 of 12 shots for 13 points Sunday, Houston is
a miserable 11 for 44 as a Knick in Detroit. Patrick Ewing was of
no help, either. Inexplicably, Eric Montross, a vagabond with
limited skills, raced around a flat Ewing for loose balls and
disrupted his shot.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ewing, who shot 3 for 7 and was held to an abysmal six
points, his lowest total since Dec. 18, 1996: ``I got kind of
winded at the beginning of the game, and I was trying to wait to
catch my second wind.''
</P>
<P>
   It never came for him, for anyone. As the Pistons broke the game
open in the third quarter, coach Jeff Van Gundy, who the previous
night had been given liquids intravenously in a local hospital
because of a stomach virus, turned three shades of green. This game
was not the elixir he was counting on for a team beginning a
three-games-in-three-nights stretch. The brutality of this season
has just begun for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season is slipping quickly,'' Van Gundy said. ``It can
change very quickly in this league. You're going well and then,
suddenly, you have a bad streak.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Right now, there is no one to break the spell. The team
president, Ernie Grunfeld, thought Dennis Scott could fill that
need. He was supposed to be the new Starks, the new emotional lift
off the bench. But Scott has struggled to find a rhythm, and has
made just 5 of 24 shots from 3-point range. Perhaps it was not so
coincidental that Scott played just five minutes Sunday and was
pulled after missing his only shot of the day _ from 3-point range
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I was surprised,'' said Scott, when asked
about how few minutes he played. ``I'm just staying patient.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are not patient times. The Knicks face an impatient
schedule that is just kicking in to its fire-drill pace. They need
to find a burst of energy, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put a halt to this,'' Houston said. ``We just need
to get some energy and emotion out there.''
</P>
<P>
   They need someone to take the place of Oakley and Starks under
the spotlight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
