<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-COYOTES-40     02-28 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-COYOTES-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS PREVAIL AS COYOTES CAN'T TAKE ADVANTAGE OF PENALTY KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ALEX YANNIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils found themselves
two men short for 68 seconds early in the final period Sunday
afternoon at Continental Arena. To make matters worse, Scott
Stevens, their captain and cornerstone of the penalty-killing unit,
was sitting in the penalty box, next to Krzysztof Oliwa.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were in serious trouble, but they escaped from that
situation and went on to a 4-1 victory over the Phoenix Coyotes,
thanks in large part to brilliant penalty killing by defensemen
Scott Niedermayer, Ken Daneyko and Kevin Dean while down two
skaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was real big,'' Daneyko said of Phoenix's lost
opportunity. ``The key was that we played good positioning. We had
success with three defensemen in that situation because Nieder
pursued the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer played the point man in the triangular scheme that
killed the two-man disadvantage. His speed, skill and vision
allowed him to be effective, but he gave credit to his teammates,
especially goalie Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur made 26 saves and improved his record this season to
27-17-8. Two of his biggest saves came during that two-man
disadvantage, which began 39 seconds into the final period when
Stevens joined Oliwa in the penalty box. Both were in for roughing.
The Devils were leading, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That five-on-three was huge because if we allow one, it's a
new game,'' Brodeur said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I think our special teams made the difference,''
said Brodeur, who was beaten only by Bob Corkum's shot from the
left circle at 1 minute 47 seconds of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's loss was the seventh in the last eight games for the
Coyotes (30-20-10). They have produced nine goals in that stretch,
while allowing 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a strong game, but we're not scoring any goals,''
said coach Jim Schoenfeld, whose team was shut out by the Rangers,
3-0, on Friday. ``It's hard on our goaltender because every mistake
he makes is magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin has allowed soft goals, but he is the best
goaltender the Coyotes have and they play him as often as they can.
Khabibulin has lost six of his last seven starts, bringing his
season record to 24-15-6.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Pederson, Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and Brian Rolston
scored New Jersey's goals, in that order, helping the Devils
improve their home record to 14-12-6 and their overall record to
33-20-8.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Devils are one of the league's leading teams thanks to their
special teams and occasionally brilliant goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they scored four goals Sunday, coach Robbie Ftorek
of the Devils said his team played better in the 3-3 tie Thursday
at Boston, its previous game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a good job killing penalties, obviously,'' Ftorek said,
``but I think we played better in Boston. We had better speed in
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston was one of the happier Devils. His goal was his 19th of
the season and set a career high over his five seasons in the
league, all with the Devils. He is one of Ftorek's favorites and he
sees plenty of ice time with the special teams besides his regular
shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the way I've been playing,'' Rolston said.
``I'm getting more confident killing penalties and I'm getting my
share of goals. I never looked at the numbers at the start of the
season, but I'm happy to pass 18. That was my high. I just want to
play consistent hockey and continue to improve.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
