<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-GIFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS OF EDUCATION HOPING BIG-MONEY GIFTS ARE BECOMING A TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass., N.Y. Pa.)  (rk) 
 By   MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Schools of education have long struggled as the
fund-raising also-rans on university campuses, since even the most
successful teacher is likely to have far less to give back to alma
mater than, say, a grateful mogul or surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   So there was as much astonishment as gratitude last week when
the University of Connecticut announced the largest gift in its
history _ $23 million, with all but $2 million of it bound for the
School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   It is the biggest donation ever made directly to a school of
education, according The Chronicle of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   The donor, Raymond Neag of Reading, Pa., is a businessman who
was a political science major in the class of 1956 but has a niece
who is a professor at the School of Education. It is just such
hidden connections that education schools have to troll for when
seeking donors.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni alone will not do it: a survey released in May by the
National Education Association found that the average salary for
the nation's teachers in 1997 was $38,611.
</P>
<P>
   Development officials say that only divinity schools raise less
money than schools of education. And they say the fund-raising
hurdles have only become higher in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's troubled classrooms have become a hot political
issue, the fancy theories born in education schools have been
blamed as part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Neag's contribution followed two other huge pledges to schools
of education in recent months: $20 million to the University of
Southern California, in September, and $10 million to Boston
College, on Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   As at UConn, the gift to the School of Education at Boston
College was the largest gift in the institution's history, making
the once-humble trainers of teachers look like the new fashion in
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These donations may be presaging a new era,'' said Susan H.
Fuhrman, the dean of the Graduate School of Education at the
University of Pennsylvania. ``These donors are making the statement
that improving education ranks up there with eradicating a dreaded
disease and that education schools are an important player, which
has not been a universally recognized fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph S. Brosnan, the vice president for development and
external affairs at Columbia University Teachers College, added,
``We don't have the obvious wealthy donors that schools of law and
business and medicine have, but there is a sense among some
philanthropists that this is education's turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston College gift was from Peter S. Lynch of Fidelity
Investments. In announcing the donation along with his wife,
Carolyn, he said, ``While our colleges and universities are the
envy of the world, the schools in many of our inner cities are in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   If three big gifts do not quite constitute a trend, deans of
several leading schools are scrambling to make them the start of
one. After Barbara and Roger Rossier announced their $20 million
gift to the University of Southern California School of Education
last fall, Dean Guilbert C. Hentschke used his new Rossier School
of Education letterhead to send a note of encouragement to 800
other of his fellow education deans and department heads. He
enclosed a fat packet of clippings and newscast excerpts describing
the Rossiers' gift, and he offered his wish that ``their act of
faith inspires others.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Harvard's education school announced that as part of
a universitywide capital campaign, it had raised its share _ $60
million _ a year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Kessner, a professor of history at the City
University of New York Graduate School who has studied the history
of philanthropy, said that the cluster of recent gifts bodes well
for other education schools. ``Not only does it legitimize their
request, but it encourages donors who see there are others who buy
the idea,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
