<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2502 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BCW-WCCWOM-LADN     02-28 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BCW-WCCWOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK'S LAST-SECOND SHOT RIMS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Everything was there for Pepperdine's
Rasheeda Clark. The open look at the basket. The chance for
redemption. The glory of a West Coast Conference women's basketball
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bounced off the rim. Nothing had changed. Pepperdine
came up a little bit short in its bid for a WCC Tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's, not Pepperdine, is going to its first NCAA
Tournament after beating the Waves 72-69 on Sunday in front of
1,811 at Toso Pavilion. The Waves (21-8) had their winning streak
snapped at eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaels (26-6) had barely finished cutting down the net,
though, when Pepperdine head coach Mark Trakh talked about a
possible at-large berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the waiting game and the lobbying game,'' Trakh said.
``We're going to crank out a lot of letters to the people on the
(selection) committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's field is announced Sunday. For Clark, a sophomore
All-WCC guard, it isn't soon enough. Her miss in the final seconds
here was a replay of the Waves' 60-58 loss to St. Mary's at home on
Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to make it is to shoot it,'' said Clark, who
scored 14 of her 16 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine trailed 70-69 with 20 seconds left when the Waves got
the ball on a turnover. Clark drove the lane at the 10-second mark
and her eight-foot jumper was off. Pepperdine scrambled for the
rebound, but the ball went out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Berg made two free throws for the Gaels with one second
left to provide the final score.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine trailed 70-60 with 2{ minutes left when Clark made a
layup that started the Waves on a nine-point run which ended on
Clark's 3-pointer with 1:29 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've played (the Gaels), it's been a game of
runs,'' Trakh said. ``I think if we played them again it might go
down to the last shot.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look like it would be close in the game's first 5{
minutes, when Pepperdine blew out to a 15-3 lead. St. Mary's, which
placed four players on the all-tournament team (Clark made it from
Pepperdine) didn't panic and took advantage when the Waves went
nearly eight minutes without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament MVP Tracy Morris (19 points) made a 3-pointer with
5:25 left in the first half that gave the Gaels a 27-25 lead.
Pepperdine never led again, though it tied the game twice in the
second half in the midst of a 16-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves will resume practice later this week after a few days
off. If the NCAA doesn't come calling, then an NIT bid will
probably be offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NIT is another game,'' Clark said. ``I think that's what
everybody wants, another game.''
</P>
<P>
   And another shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
