<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-PERPWALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN PERPS MAY PREFER WALK OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let us, for one disorienting moment, imagine a world
without ``perp walks.'' Suppose detectives had just cracked a
notorious case, but the press were no longer able to photograph the
alleged perpetrator walking along in the custody of the police.
</P>
<P>
   To give the public a glimpse of him, newspapers and television
stations would start buying old snapshots and home videos from
disgruntled relatives and neighbors. The evening news might show a
videotape of an accused serial rapist giving a drunken toast at a
wedding, or a father happily playing in the park with the children
he is accused of bludgeoning to death with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Would this be a better world? It might please Allen G. Schwartz,
the federal judge in Manhattan who ruled last week that a suspect's
constitutional rights had been violated by a perp walk. But the
perps themselves would probably resent having the masses see their
private snapshots and videos, especially since the pictures would
be a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   When you're an accused serial rapist or hammer-murderer, you do
not want to be seen laughing it up. You want to project the
sobriety captured in artists' renderings of the very first perp
walk, the armed angel escorting Adam and Eve out of Eden. Even if
you, unlike the original sinners, are innocent, you must
acknowledge that something has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Your changing social status necessitates a rite of passage,
which anthropologists define as having three stages. The perp walk
is the first stage, called separation, in which you're stripped of
your old status. That leaves you outside the social structure in
what is called the betwixt-and-between stage. The final phase,
reintegration, comes after the verdict, when you're assigned a
fixed status as either a convict or a law-abiding citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ritual like the perp walk eases social anxieties about
someone whose status is unclear,'' said David Kertzer, an
anthropologist at Brown University and the author of the book
``Ritual, Politics and Power'' (1988, Yale University Press). He
said the walk symbolically reconciles people's contradictory
feelings about the perp: while they think he's probably guilty
(since most defendants are eventually convicted) and hope the crime
has been solved, they also believe that he should be presumed
innocent and treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Displaying the person in handcuffs,'' Kertzer said, ``is a
ritual degradation that publicly signals his change in status from
an ordinary citizen, like ripping the stripes off the shoulders of
a military officer. The police presence during the walk reinforces
our desire for moral boundaries to be enforced. But we're also
afraid of police power run amok, so we expect the police to act
decorously, and it's reassuring to see the perp's rights being
protected by other social institutions, like the courthouse where
he's being taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, perp walks in New York are generally far from
decorous. The press corps often looks more like a mob at a
lynching, which is the wrong rite of passage for the situation. The
poor perp typically emerges from a police station into a gantlet of
flash bulbs and hides his face as he stumbles down the steps,
whereupon a police officer grabs his head and shoves him down into
a car.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no reason it couldn't be done properly. Instead of
haphazardly staging perp walks on cramped stairways and sidewalks,
the police could build a special structure, maybe something like
the classic bridge in Venice connecting the Doge's Palace with the
prison, the Ponte dei Sospiri, or Bridge of Sighs, named after the
convicts' sounds during that rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   If New York had a grand Ponte dei Perps, with assigned places
for the press and room for a stately parade, perps could walk in
dignity. They could heed Edward W. Hayes, whose standard advice to
perps was repeated in Tom Wolfe's ``The Bonfire of the Vanities''
by Tommy Killian, the lawyer modeled on Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said you should never hang your head,'' Hayes
said. ``The more guilty a client is, the more I tell him to hold
his head up. And the few that are innocent, I tell them not to
worry about being forever scarred by the perp walk, because when
they're acquitted they'll get publicity then, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the idea of eliminating perp walks appalls Hayes.
``Without that reward, detectives would lose their motivation,'' he
said. ``Trial lawyers like me would stop going to tailors. A lot of
my clients would be upset, too. What's the point of taking up a
life of crime if you can't star in a perp walk?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
