<HEADLINE>
COMING OFF BENCH MIGHT SUIT RODMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kurt Rambis' rotation is starting to take
shape and it includes a bench role for a seven-time rebounding
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman has entered the last two games _ to thunderous
cheers _ just after the seven-minute mark in the first quarter. And
the Lakers' new coach said that might become the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what he brings off the bench,'' Rambis said. ``I think
it's important for teams to have spark coming off the bench. He
brings that spark to the crowd and an excitement that only the Worm
can bring to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis and Rodman discussed the matter Saturday and Rodman said
he was OK with the role. It seems to suit him. Rodman has 21
rebounds in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Rambis) knows his players have to go out there and split
time and have to be unselfish to win games,'' Rodman said. ``You
have to bite your tongue and your pride and just go out there and
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, continuing with the starting five he inherited, is going
with Travis Knight at power forward, and he is moving former
starter Robert Horry back to his natural position of small forward,
behind Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rambis on Rodman: Whatever: On Saturday, Rodman reported to
practice a half-hour late, and Rambis said he might issue a fine.
On Sunday, Rambis' ire was directed at reporters for continuing to
ask about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are making an unbelievably big deal out of something
that I don't find to be a big deal,'' he said. ``It's just
something we knew we were going to have to deal with. We have made
accommodations for several ballplayers on this team to make them
feel at home and comfortable. What's important is what they're
doing out on the basketball court for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gonna flip out every time something like that
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Barkley's pain: Charles Barkley, back in action two weeks
after knee surgery, said he came close to hanging it up entirely
this offseason, and might have if not for a talk with buddy Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very close to quitting before I had my talk with
Michael,'' Barkley said, citing ``the horrible attitude the team
had. And I was in pain all year (from a hernia), which didn't help.
. . . Michael challenged me to rededicate myself, give it one more
shot, so I can leave on my own terms, not mad or bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley nearly retired when, during the lockout, he realized,
``I didn't miss playing. I swear to God. I really enjoyed taking my
daughter to school and playing golf every day. It wasn't like I was
sitting at home, saying I miss the season. I didn't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Elden Campbell stayed home with the flu and did
not travel with the team to Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
