<SLUG> BC-RAC-RAFAEL-STAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE VICTORY CREATES SURPRISE DERBY CONTENDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Desert Hero, a son of the 1993 Kentucky Derby
winner Sea Hero, making only his second lifetime start, won
Sunday's $200,000 San Rafael Stakes at Santa Anita by a neck in an
upset that surprised even his trainer, Wallace Dollase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't expect that,'' said Dollase, who trains the horse
for the Thoroughbred Corp. of Prince Ahmed bin Salman of Saudi
Arabia. ``We figured if he was within three lengths, we had a shot
at a Derby horse. He's a fast, intelligent horse who's bred to go
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero _ who paid $22.80 for $2 to win, covered the mile in
1:36 2/5 and won for the second straight time _ became the latest
contender for the May 1 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But no winner of the San Rafael has ever won the Derby, which is
somewhat reassuring news for the also-rans, particularly the Bob
Baffert-trained Prime Timber. Baffert's colt raced outside most of
the way and took the lead from the favored Honest Lady in the
stretch but could not hold off Desert Hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm discouraged that we didn't win,'' said Gary Stevens, Prime
Timber's jockey. ``He doesn't want to run past horses. He's running
at about half-speed through the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who has a barn full of Derby contenders led by the
early favorite Exploit and the filly Silverbulletday, called the
race ``a good, hard work'' for Prime Timber. Honest Lady, who had
an exceptionally fast half-mile workout Friday for the Hall of Fame
trainer Bobby Frankel, led at the top of the stretch but finished
fifth, less than a length behind the winner. Capsized closed fast
for third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have rushed her a little bit into the first turn, and
she got aggressive on me around the first bend,'' said Kent
Desormeaux, Honest Lady's jockey. ``She'd never been around two
turns, so I would say this filly more or less went to school
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero, ridden by Dollase's son-in-law, Corey Nakatani,
would have won easily with a cleaner trip. Nakatani saved ground
along the rail down the back side but was blocked behind a wall of
horses as the field turned into the stretch. At the eighth pole,
Nakatani had to take up sharply behind Honest Lady, and then swung
the winner three wide in the late stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a big horse, but because of his versatility he was
able to go around those horses and still kick in,'' said Dollase,
who had given the $575,000 yearling purchase three months off to
heal a toe infection before he romped in a maiden race here on Feb.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Dollase, Nakatani and The Thoroughbred Corp. combined to win
this race a year ago with Orville N Wilbur's.
</P>
<P>
   Dollase had been thinking of shipping Desert Hero to the
Arkansas Derby in April, but said he now will point to the April 3
Santa Anita Derby, the final West Coast prep for the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
