<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`8MM' SNUFFS ITS RIVALS AT THE BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Murder-mystery ``8mm'' showed plenty of life at
the nation's multiplexes as it dominated offerings with an
estimated $14.3 million at 2,373 theaters during the Friday-Sunday
period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony release, starring Nicolas Cage as a private eye
descending into the sordid world of snuff films, took in more than
the combined total of the next highest grossers _ Paramount's
fourth weekend of ``Payback'' with $6.9 million at 2,852 theaters
and Disney's opening of romantic drama ``The Other Sister'' with
$6.7 million at 1,343 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said ``8mm,'' with a reported $40 million budget,
performed in line with expectations and credited the studio for
effectively marketing a movie with edgy subject matter and limited
appeal beyond male customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony is pretty good at making movies for target audiences,''
said film analyst Arthur Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
agreed, saying, `` `8mm' is not a movie that women and the date
crowd attended.'' He predicted it will finish second next weekend
following Sony's teen drama ``Cruel Intentions'' and finish its
domestic run at about $46 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sony spokesman Ed Russell said ``8mm'' played equally well
throughout the country and acknowledged that the studio decided to
take a fairly straightforward approach to publicizing the movie.
``We would have done a disservice for people to go into theaters
not knowing what the film was about,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the slate posted generally respectable numbers and
overall business totaled about $75 million to finish down 3 percent
from the same weekend a year ago, when ``Titanic'' was in its 11th
week of release on its way to $600 million overall. Year-to-date
totals are down 12 percent; top grossers during 1999 so far are
``Patch Adams'' with $84 million and ``Payback'' with $66.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly no major slump and there's enough different
product to keep attracting customers,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executive Chuck Viane said the studio was pleased with
the opening for ``The Other Sister,'' with Juliette Lewis as a
mentally challenged teen-ager, and will add about 400 theaters
Friday to take advantage of strong word-of-mouth among moviegoers.
Bucksbaum said female customers had supported ``The Other Sister''
strongly and predicted it could top $30 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' third weekend of ``Message in a Bottle'' finished
a close fourth with $6.4 million at 2,545 theaters to go past $41
million overall, followed by Disney's third weekend of ``My
Favorite Martian'' with $5.2 million at 2,349 sites and Universal's
second weekend of ``October Sky'' with $4.8 million at 1,700
locations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
