<SLUG> BC-IRAN-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMERS APPEAR TO GAIN IN IRANIAN VOTING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ Dealing a blow to Iran's powerful and puritanical
hierarchy, millions of Iranians cast their votes for a movement
that calls for sweeping change toward a more open and pluralistic
society.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns Sunday night from the first local elections since
the Islamic Revolution two decades ago were counted inside a mosque
converted into election headquarters _ a symbolic setting for a
nation struggling to place democracy within the walls of state
religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the votes were counted, the conservatives moved to
fight back, arresting Mahsan Kadivar, one of the most popular
reform candidates for Tehran's city council, on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The election represents a battle for the soul of Iran. The
rising popularity of new reformers, led by President Mohammed
Khatami, threatens the entrenched conservatives such as spiritual
leader Ayatollah Khamenei, constitutionally Khatami's superior.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have counted 40 percent of the votes but said results
would not be completed for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers crowed over their early showing, which indicates
pro-Khatami candidates leading in all 15 council seats in Tehran.
Results from at least 20 cities showed women candidates as
front-runners _ nearly all of them supporters of Khatami, who has
encouraged women to play a bigger role in political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``These elections show that the process of reform is now
irreversible. There is still a long way to go, but it can't be
turned back,'' said Ibrahim Yazdi, leader of the Freedom Movement
Party, who has been arrested several times for his reformist views.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid Jalaepour, editor of the independent Neshat newspaper,
said: ``In some ways, this election was more important than the
presidential election'' that brought Khatami to power in 1997 with
70 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not just for the ruling elite to get elected, but a
chance for new faces to emerge and for people to become invested in
the process,'' Jalaepour added.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the arrest of Kadivar was ``clearly politically
timed'' and an important sign that the conservatives recognized
that ``the ground is moving beneath their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Early tallies from the Friday vote indicated that Kadivar was
among the highest vote-getters in the crucial Tehran council race.
The candidate learned of his showing from inside a jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials went to his home Saturday and reportedly
charged the cleric with undermining the religious authority of
Khamenei by speaking out against the decree that grants ``The
Leader'' overriding executive powers.
</P>
<P>
   As a leading thinker on democracy and Islam, Kadivar coined the
phrase ``theo-aristocracy'' to refer to the clerical hierarchy that
controls the military, key ministries, and huge sectors of the
economy. ``What we have is a theo-aristocracy, and what we need is
a theo-democracy,'' he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most powerful symbol of the way in which Iran is
trying to forge a new democracy within the context of an Islamic
Republic was the election headquarters itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the Interior Ministry, a hulking bureaucratic office tower,
an old auditorium was converted into a mosque at the beginning of
the Islamic Revolution. Prayer rugs normally lie about the large,
open room. Government employees use the space for daily prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the space was filled with telephone banks for officials
to record the vote. A large electronic tallying board lit up as the
districts reported. An Iranian TV crew prepared a live shot.
</P>
<P>
   But because it is a mosque, none of the men working in the
US-style election center were wearing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the room, Ahmad Shojaii busily scribbled results on forms
in a dizzying election that saw some 300,000 candidates vying for
200,000 seats on councils in towns, villages, and cities. There
were 4,000 candidates for the 15 seats in the Tehran council alone.
An estimated 25 million out of Iran's 30 million eligible voters
went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   For Shojaii and the other election workers the tallying was
daunting. Shojaii, 41, one of the young bearded student radicals
who took to the streets to topple the US-backed shah in 1979, still
has the beard, although now it has a touch of gray. He looked up
from the piles of election forms and frantically ringing phones and
said, ``Revolution is a lot more exciting than democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an election spread out across Iran's vast desert plains and
fertile mountain valleys, government officials predicted that the
reformists would easily win two-thirds of the local council seats.
If this holds true, it will provide Khatami with much-needed
support for his effort to broaden culture socially and
economically. But the vote was also a reminder that voters who
elected him are growing impatient with the slow pace of change.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Parliament member Ahmed Nori, whose brother was the
failed challenger to Khatami in 1979, looked tired and defeated
after checking on the early returns.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the early results, saying that the candidates in
the rural areas such as his province near the Caspian Sea are
solidly behind Khamenei and the traditional conservatives who back
him. ``These are people who care about improving the efficiency of
government. They are thinking about sewer systems and bus lines,
not big ideas like democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Iranians were finding out in the last few days, democracy can
be messy. After tens of thousands of candidates nationwide had
plastered campaign posters and leaflets on every building, bus
stop, storefront, and light station they could find, the streets
were a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Armies of Tehran municipal workers fanned out across the capital
trying to scrape the posters off the walls and sweep up streets
littered with campaign refuse. The glue on the posters has made
them nearly impossible to strip away.
</P>
<P>
   One municipal worker, Navid Asghari, was trying to remove a line
of more than 50 consecutive posters of a female candidate in the
traditional black head covering. Ahead of them on the same wall
along a main street in downtown Tehran were hundreds more candidate
posters that would have to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Asghari said, ``this is what you call democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
