<DOCNO> NYT19990228.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-28 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-BUSH-1STLD-WRI     02-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS OF ALL STRIPES LINING UP BEHIND GOV. BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: Changes spelling of name from ``Bolling'' to ``Boling'' in
graf that begins ``These supporters.'' No other changes.)  
 (ATT: Iowa, Mich., N.H., N.J., Tenn., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The Rev. Louis P. Sheldon, an
uncompromising conservative who heads a national group called the
Traditional Values Coalition, has built his career on denouncing
homosexuals. But Sheldon may back a prospect for the Republican
presidential nomination whose oratory on the subject has been
decidedly tame: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pragmatic,'' said Sheldon, who has never been known as
pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   April Boling, an accountant who is active in California's
Republican Party, said the issue most important to her is support
for abortion rights, but that she too favored Bush, even though he
is against abortion. ``I'm not as uncomfortable with his politics
as some of the others,'' she said. ``And his father used to be pro
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon and Ms. Boling, both of whom attended the California
Republican Party's winter convention that closed here Sunday,
represent opposite, often antagonistic, wings of their party.
</P>
<P>
   But their support of Bush underscores an extraordinary turn in
Republican politics: an early, and colossal, outpouring of
Republicans of all stripes who have set aside their ideological
convictions to support a governor who has yet to formally announce
his intentions _ and who is untested and largely unknown on the
national stage.
</P>
<P>
   From Capitol Hill to state legislatures, Republicans around the
country have declared their support for Bush in what has become an
almost daily drumbeat of endorsements that has been encouraged _
but not always choreographed _ by the governors' advisers. On
Friday, for example, more than half of the nation's 31 Republican
governors professed their allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father, George Bush, did not enjoy such vast support at
this point when he ran for president in 1988 _ and as vice
president, he was the heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   But here at the state party convention, there were several
telling demonstrations of Bush's immense popularity. While seven
presidential contenders traveled to California to make their case
to hundreds of partisans, Bush kept to his past practice and stayed
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in dozens of random interviews, rank-and-file
delegates, political professionals and state legislators said they
intended to back Bush. Though many said they had never even heard
him speak in person, they spoke as if Bush's nomination was
inevitable. Twenty-six state legislators in California have signed
a petition urging Bush to run.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy has left Bush's rivals stunned, envious and, in some
cases, deeply dispirited and feeling shut out of the competition a
year before the actual voting begins. Already, it has transformed
the presidential nomination battle into a contest not of who is the
best candidate but who would be the best second choice.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle found himself being quizzed on
national television this morning about what he had to offer that
Bush did not. And privately, advisers to some candidates said their
best hope was that Bush would succumb to an as-yet-unknown scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee has been trudging
through Iowa and New Hampshire seeking the nomination for years but
has only been endorsed by two governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking about all the governors who came up to me
after the nomination last time and said, `If we had supported you,
we might have won the election,''' Alexander lamented in an
interview. He contrasted his years of experience with Bush, whom he
described as ``off to a promising beginning,'' adding that ``the
last fresh face the party nominated was Dwight D. Eisenhower.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate who is also running for the
second time, likened the commotion to the case of Colin Powell, who
ultimately decided not to seek the Republican nomination in 1996.
``Part of it is being able to project on to somebody anything you
want,'' he said in an interview. ``You saw it with the Powell
phenomenon. You saw it back in '72 with Muskie before he hit the
campaign trail. So I think you can watch it with wry amusement.''
</P>
<P>
   Short-lived or not, many Republican politicians here and around
the country said they had never seen such early rallying, and that
it was all the more stunning because Bush was not an heir apparent
like a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in interviews why they were so enthusiastic, most
Republicans cited pragmatic concerns, namely polls showing that
Bush, overwhelmingly, is the early favorite for the nomination and
could beat Vice President Al Gore in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   These supporters say they are so starved to regain the White
House that they concede that they do know too many details of
Bush's stewardship _ and do not particularly care. Ms. Boling, for
instance, said she did not know the extent of Bush's opposition to
abortion, but was confident that ``at least he has not taken a
position that's so offensive that it's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives and moderates alike seem to have convinced
themselves that Bush shares their views. Bruce Thompson, a
three-term California assemblyman who describes himself as one of
the most conservative legislators in the state, said, ``Listen,
this is the next Ronald Reagan _ there's no question in my mind.
The main thing is the guy can win. We're a party out there just
floating around.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has never met Bush, and never heard him speak _ except
on television. Yet that did not stop him from establishing a group
that printed and distributed thousands of ``Bush 2000'' placards
and lapel stickers at the convention here. He spent all weekend at
a booth where he showed delegates the Bush web site he created, and
a homemade videotape of assorted Bush television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Thompson and four other legislators staged a rally
at a pizza parlor in Sacramento to express their devotion. Rather
than attend a lunch featuring Forbes, about 200 delegates wandered
to the pizza party, where participants chanted, ``Bush 2K! Bush 2K!
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only game in town,'' Allan Hoffenblum, a longtime
Republican analyst based in Los Angeles, said as he scanned the
crowd at the pizza rally. ``We're so desperate for a candidate who
gets more than 38 percent of the vote statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other contender who was popular at this gathering, and
at similar Republican events around country, was Elizabeth Dole,
who, like Bush, was a no show.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Alcox, who sells T-shirts and buttons at Republican
events around the country, said his homemade Bush and Dole
paraphernalia are by far the best sellers. ``Bush and Dole are
always neck-and-neck everywhere I go,'' said Alcox. ``The rest? You
can forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whom she would support for president, Cheryl Brandwood, a
53-year-old delegate here, said with certainty, ``George Bush and
Elizabeth Dole will be the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Schroeder, the outgoing chairman of the California
Republican Party, warned that there are dangers in people pinning
all their hopes on one candidate. He noted that Bush may have
difficulty meeting the now astronomical expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way too early to say the race is in the hands of one
person unless he makes a mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides frustration among the other candidates, the ardor for
Bush, who was elected two a second term last year by a huge margin,
has caused bruised feelings. Alexander was taken aback when Gov.
John M. Engler of Michigan recently said that Bush would make a
more appealing candidate because ``you've got a governor of the
'70s versus the governor of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows better than that,'' said Alexander who was governor
of Tennessee from 1979 to 1987. ``I can remember very well when an
attractive young state senator named John Engler in 1983 came to
Nashville and spent 30 minutes with me asking what it would take to
make a good governor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
