<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEDVED SCORES HAT TRICK AS RANGERS TRIP UP FLYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Rangers were in need of a stand-in,
someone capable of being great until the Great One's neck mends.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers coach John Muckler turned to Petr Nedved on Friday,
imploring the slumping center to raise his game, to keep the team's
hopes alive through what figures to be the season's toughest
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved answered with three goals and one assist Sunday as the
Rangers defeated the reeling Philadelphia Flyers, 6-5, in an
afternoon thriller at Madison Square Garden. Adam Graves scored
twice and Mike Richter made 21 saves as the Rangers won their
second straight and improved their record over the past five games
to 4-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of carrying the Rangers (25-28-7) had become too much
for Wayne Gretzky, their leading scorer this season with 57 points.
He will be out for at least two weeks with a bulging disk in his
neck.
</P>
<P>
   That weight now rests on Nedved's slender shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Nedved do, in his biggest challenge since joining
the Rangers last November? He responded against the big, bad Flyers
with a convincing effort, his best of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just Nedved, Graves and Richter. Defensemen Brian
Leetch and Ulf Samuelsson and rookie forward Manny Malhotra were
superb as well.
</P>
<P>
   The match might have been the Rangers' most riveting performance
on Broadway this season. For a welcome change, there was never a
dull moment. Especially not with Nedved playing the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took a 5-2 lead in the second period, then were in
danger of blowing the game late in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers who were getting the bulk of the scoring chances,
tied the score at 5-5 and came close to scoring the go-ahead goal a
few times. The crowd was getting antsy.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Nedved took command, the way Gretzky has done so
many times.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied and the clock showing less than eight
minutes remaining, Nedved streaked down the left side boards after
the puck. Eric Desjardins swiped at the lanky center with his
stick, and he appeared to catch Nedved's skate, sending Nedved
tumbling to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers' coach complained afterward that Nedved took a dive.
But no matter, the Rangers, who had scored three goals with the man
advantage, were given the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved did not allow the opportunity to pass. The Rangers set up
shop in the Flyers' zone, and seconds later, Nedved snapped a
one-timer past goalie John Vanbiesbrouck at 13 minutes 32 seconds
for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously going to have more responsibilities,'' Nedved
said of his talk with Muckler before Friday's victory over the
Phoenix Coyotes. ``And I'm going to have to step up and be the
go-to guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Desjardins's tripping penalty, Flyers coach Roger Neilson
said: ``Well, the last one was a real dive by Nedved, which I don't
blame him for at all. He won the game with it. But you hate to lose
a game on calls like that, especially in the third period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' victory moved them past idle Montreal and into 10th
place in the East, three points behind Boston and Florida for the
conference's eighth and final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Flyers from second place to fourth. The
Flyers are 2-7-2 in their last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved not only carried the Rangers' offense but was also
assigned to mark the Flyers' best player, Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros scored a goal and assisted on John LeClair's goal, but
considering that Lindros and LeClair are the scoring leaders in the
NHL, it wasn't a shabby defensive showing for Nedved and his
linemates, Graves and John MacLean.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers led the Flyers by 5-3 entering the third period, but
Philadelphia scored twice to tie the game. The first goal was
notched by LeClair at 1:21, the second by Mikael Renberg at 8:41.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing with more energy than we have been,'' said
Samuelsson, who assisted on Nedved's first goal. ``We realize that
our backs are against the wall and there's no time to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers matched the Flyers' energy in the opening 20 minutes
and escaped the period tied at 2-2. Lindros and Keith Jones scored
for Philadelphia, and Graves and Nedved scored for the Rangers.
Graves' goal came on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long day for Vanbiesbrouck, who faced 26 shots. He
didn't look good on either of the Rangers' first-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   On Graves' first goal, Vanbiesbrouck skated out of his crease to
clear the puck, but his pass hit Graves on the hip and the puck
rolled into the net at 8:16. Nedved scored his first goal on a
wrist shot that sailed over Vanbiesbrouck's glove.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Scott Fraser scored his first goal of the
season to stretch the Rangers' lead to 3-2 at 3:57. Nedved's second
goal of the game gave the Rangers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more players than just Petr stepped up,'' Muckler
said. ``That was a real exciting hockey game. That was tough
hockey. We stood up to the challenge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-28-99 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
