crime nightmare, but still maintains the paramilitary unit, which
now has 29 members who are used nearly full time. In Meriden, as in
other cities, the SWAT teams arrest people for minor offenses,
attacking small crimes as a way to send a larger message about who
is in control. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) FRESNO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-II-2,
2-28 -- A SWAT team in Fresno, Calif., patroling an area called the
Dog Pound where drug dealing is concentrated, detain a man for
driving a car with a broken taillight. Special Weapons and Tactics
squads, once used exclusively for the rare urban terrorist incident
or shootout have transformed themselves through the crack years in
the United States, and now do everything from routine street
patrols to nightly raids of houses. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) FRESNO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-II-1,
2-28 -- In Fresno, Calif., more than in any other city,
paramilitary police have become a part of everyday life. Police
Officers Randy Tafoya, left, and Rudy Tietjen of the Violent Crime
Suppression Unit load their weapons at the start of a shift.
Special Weapons and Tactics squads, once used exclusively for the
rare urban terrorist incident or shootout have transformed
themselves through the crack years, and now do everything from
routine street patrols to nightly raids of houses. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- REPUBS-BUSH, 2-28
-- Bruce Thompson, a three-term California assemblyman who
describes himself as one of the most conservative legislators in
the state, mans a George W. Bush campaign booth at the California
Republican Party 1999 Spring Convention in Sacramento, Calif.
``Listen, this is the next Ronald Reagan -- there's no question in
my mind. The main thing is the guy can win. We're a party out there
just floating around,'' says Thompson. (Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ANGOLA, La. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- RIDEAU PROFILE, 2-28 --
Wilbert Rideau, 57, watching other inmates on farm detail at the
Louisiana State Penitentiary, has entered the 38th year of a life
sentence for one of the most vicious murders ever committed in
Louisiana. As a journalist and editor, Rideau has been honored with
some of the profession's most coveted prizes. Now having branched
out into film making, his second work, ``The Farm: Angola U.S.A.,''
is nominated for the Oscar for best documentary feature. (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) RAVA-RUSKAYA, Ukraine -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- UKRAINE-POLAND,
2-28 -- A road leading from the Polish border into Ukraine is one
of the main arteries of the ``shuttle trade'' in goods from Poland,
many smuggled illegally. Goods are cheaper in Poland and can be
resold to Ukrainians at a huge profit. They are especially cheap if
nobody pays the sky-high duties that the Ukrainian government has
imposed on many goods to protect domestic competitors. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- TV-BODE-MEDIA, 2-28 -- Ken
Bode, 59, dean of the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill. Bode was recently forced out of his
public television job as host of ``Washington Week in Review,''
after clashing with a new boss who thought the show's quiet
discussions needed a little more edge and attitude. ``I don't make
Tom Friedman come on and say what he thinks about Clinton's
morals!'' says Bode of the New York Times columnist. ``If he talks
about the Asian economy, and it's too dull, OK.'' (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEWTON, Mass. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- DRAGON-MARKETPLACE,
2-28 -- John Shagoury, Dragon Systems' president, and Janet Baker,
a co-founder and chief, also standing, watching use of
speech-recognition software. Dragon says it is poised to exploit
the trend toward smaller, lighter computerized devices. A laptop
equipped with voice-recognition software doesn't need a large,
comfortable keyboard. And if the speech technology is good enough,
it doesn't need a keyboard at all. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-RIVERA, 2-28 --
The New York Yankees' Mariano Rivera, one of the most dominant
relief pitchers in the American League. Rivera's fastball --
typically in the range of 93 to 96 mph -- used to be as straight as
a city street; now it possesses more turns and bends than a
mountain highway. ``It all depends on how you grip the baseball,''
says Rivera. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) YONKERS, N.Y. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- HMOS-REVIEW, 2-27 --
After enrolling in managed care, Milagros Lebron visits Dr. James
Sayegh in his Yonkers, N.Y., office. For a variety of reasons --
fears of consumer backlash, legislative intervention or large jury
awards -- managed-care plans appear to be denying little care,
notwithstanding all the well-publicized horror stories and growing
complaints as HMOs become commonplace in American society. (Chris
Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLE FERRY, N.J. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- NJ-EXOTIC-PETS-2,
2-27 -- Joseph D'Angeli in his basement compound which contains a
dozen fruit bats from Egypt and Indonesia, with wingspans of up to
five feet. For D'Angeli, bats are not so much his pets as his
passion. All his neighbors know about the unusual creatures in his
basement, as do hordes of schoolchildren to whom he gives lectures
and audiences at the Liberty Science Center in Jersey City.
``Children call me the real Batman, but some of them get upset when
I don't have a cape on.'' (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHERRY HILL, N.J. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- NJ-EXOTIC-PETS-1,
2-27 -- Joseph Bush, the Monkey Man of Cherry Hill, with two of his
three capuchin monkeys from South America, who watch television
from their cages in his home when they aren't on the road with him
playing bar mitzvahs, conventions or Atlantic City casinos. Bush
keeps his companions in a spare bedroom and is one of 10 people in
the state of New Jersey licensed to keep monkeys. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
