<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/28/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- HEARST-BLACK-MEDIA, 2-28 --
A dinner in early February in the ballroom of the New York Hilton,
in honor of Cathleen Black, left, the president of Hearst
Magazines. Tom Brokaw, right, was the presenter. (George M.
Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- PODHORETZ-CONNECTIONS, 2-28
-- Norman Podhoretz, who edited Commentary magazine for 35 years.
Podhoretz's writings from the late 1950s embodied opposing trends
in themselves. His first book of literary criticism, ``Doings and
Undoings,'' contains traces of radicalism as well as conservatism.
In his new memoir, ``Ex-Friends'' (Free Press), so hotly contested
is he as a political and intellectual figure that simply the
declaration of friendship or ex-friendship with him has tended to
be viewed in some circles as a declaration of war. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Fe. 28, 1999 -- WOMEN-DOCTORS-2, 2-28 -- Dr.
Holly Andersen, 36, one of only a handful of female cardiologists
in Manhattan, examining a patient in her office. Dr. Andersen says
she realizes the conflicts she will have if she decides to have a
family. ``Being a woman in medicine there are not that many
paradigms we can look to and say 'This is how they did it this is
the way I can do it too,''' says Dr. Andersen. ``You have to work
on it yourself.'' (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Fe. 28, 1999 -- WOMEN-DOCTORS-1, 2-28 -- Dr.
Gail Bauchman with her 19-month-old twin daughters, Avital,
sitting, and Natalia, found she had to cut her work hours to care
for her family. Bauchman, who built a bustling private practice in
New York, decided to take a part-time job at the Mount Sinai
Adolescent Health Center, for a fraction of her earnings as a
private practice doctor. The situation works for her, but was
hardly what she had hoped for. ``There is this problem with finding
the middle ground,'' says Dr. Bauchman. (Nancy Siesel/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-PROSPECTS,
2-28 -- Nick Johnson, a 20-year-old first baseman, is one of the
New York Yankees top prospects this year. If Johnson, a nephew of
the former Philadelphia Phillies infielder Larry Bowa, is able to
replace Tino Martinez, the Yankees current first baseman, the
Yankees could pay him a total of $1 million to $2 million over his
first three seasons. Keeping Tino Martinez, on the other hand,
might cost $6 million or $7 million a year once his contract
expires after the 2000 season. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LAGOS, Nigeria -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- NIGERIA-VOTE, 2-28 --
Nigerians waited their turn to vote at a polling station in the
Idi-Araba community, which is comprised mostly of muslims from the
north. Most Nigerians in the area are supporters of presidential
candidate General Olusegun Obasanjo, who was released just eight
months ago after serving three years in prison for criticizing the
military rule. Obasanjo on Sunday appeared to have won an
overwhelming victory in the first presidential election in the
country in 16 years. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MERIDEN, Conn. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-II-3,
2-28 -- Meriden, Conn., formed a SWAT team in 1986, when crack
cocaine was starting to appear all over the United States. With a
population of 57,000, Meriden does not fit the image of an urban
crime nightmare, but still maintains the paramilitary unit, which
now has 29 members who are used nearly full time. In Meriden, as in
other cities, the SWAT teams arrest people for minor offenses,
attacking small crimes as a way to send a larger message about who
is in control. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) FRESNO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-II-2,
2-28 -- A SWAT team in Fresno, Calif., patroling an area called the
Dog Pound where drug dealing is concentrated, detain a man for
driving a car with a broken taillight. Special Weapons and Tactics
squads, once used exclusively for the rare urban terrorist incident
or shootout have transformed themselves through the crack years in
the United States, and now do everything from routine street
patrols to nightly raids of houses. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) FRESNO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-II-1,
2-28 -- In Fresno, Calif., more than in any other city,
paramilitary police have become a part of everyday life. Police
Officers Randy Tafoya, left, and Rudy Tietjen of the Violent Crime
Suppression Unit load their weapons at the start of a shift.
Special Weapons and Tactics squads, once used exclusively for the
rare urban terrorist incident or shootout have transformed
themselves through the crack years, and now do everything from
routine street patrols to nightly raids of houses. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- REPUBS-BUSH, 2-28
-- Bruce Thompson, a three-term California assemblyman who
describes himself as one of the most conservative legislators in
the state, mans a George W. Bush campaign booth at the California
Republican Party 1999 Spring Convention in Sacramento, Calif.
``Listen, this is the next Ronald Reagan -- there's no question in
my mind. The main thing is the guy can win. We're a party out there
just floating around,'' says Thompson. (Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ANGOLA, La. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- RIDEAU PROFILE, 2-28 --
Wilbert Rideau, 57, watching other inmates on farm detail at the
Louisiana State Penitentiary, has entered the 38th year of a life
sentence for one of the most vicious murders ever committed in
Louisiana. As a journalist and editor, Rideau has been honored with
some of the profession's most coveted prizes. Now having branched
out into film making, his second work, ``The Farm: Angola U.S.A.,''
is nominated for the Oscar for best documentary feature. (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) RAVA-RUSKAYA, Ukraine -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- UKRAINE-POLAND,
2-28 -- A road leading from the Polish border into Ukraine is one
of the main arteries of the ``shuttle trade'' in goods from Poland,
many smuggled illegally. Goods are cheaper in Poland and can be
resold to Ukrainians at a huge profit. They are especially cheap if
nobody pays the sky-high duties that the Ukrainian government has
imposed on many goods to protect domestic competitors. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- TV-BODE-MEDIA, 2-28 -- Ken
Bode, 59, dean of the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill. Bode was recently forced out of his
public television job as host of ``Washington Week in Review,''
after clashing with a new boss who thought the show's quiet
discussions needed a little more edge and attitude. ``I don't make
