Sayegh in his Yonkers, N.Y., office. For a variety of reasons --
fears of consumer backlash, legislative intervention or large jury
awards -- managed-care plans appear to be denying little care,
notwithstanding all the well-publicized horror stories and growing
complaints as HMOs become commonplace in American society. (Chris
Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLE FERRY, N.J. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- NJ-EXOTIC-PETS-2,
2-27 -- Joseph D'Angeli in his basement compound which contains a
dozen fruit bats from Egypt and Indonesia, with wingspans of up to
five feet. For D'Angeli, bats are not so much his pets as his
passion. All his neighbors know about the unusual creatures in his
basement, as do hordes of schoolchildren to whom he gives lectures
and audiences at the Liberty Science Center in Jersey City.
``Children call me the real Batman, but some of them get upset when
I don't have a cape on.'' (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHERRY HILL, N.J. -- Feb. 28, 1999 -- NJ-EXOTIC-PETS-1,
2-27 -- Joseph Bush, the Monkey Man of Cherry Hill, with two of his
three capuchin monkeys from South America, who watch television
from their cages in his home when they aren't on the road with him
playing bar mitzvahs, conventions or Atlantic City casinos. Bush
keeps his companions in a spare bedroom and is one of 10 people in
the state of New Jersey licensed to keep monkeys. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
