A2649 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-WARRIORS-AZR     02-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-WARRIORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS SHUT DOWN WARRIORS IN FOURTH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Amid all the plays in a scouting report scribbled on a
message board in the Suns clubhouse, one word was added in large,
red letters _ and underlined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Suns lack it, they're a very ordinary NBA team, as they
were while the Golden State Warriors embarrassed them for most of
three quarters Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When they have it, the Suns can look as they did in a dominating
fourth quarter that propelled them past the Warriors, 102-89, at
America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, I thought it was two completely different games by
the same team,'' said Suns Coach Danny Ainge, meaning his
schizophrenic bunch. ``It's been our trend. It's a little bit
frustrating, and it's going to be harmful when we start playing
better teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by reserve forwards Clifford Robinson and Danny Manning, the
Suns bailed themselves out with a fourth-quarter defensive
performance for the record books:
</P>
<P>
   They limited the Warriors to two field goals in 21 attempts
during the fourth quarter, the last coming with 3.5 seconds to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The six Golden State points equaled the fewest points scored
during a fourth quarter in the history of the NBA. Detroit scored
six points in a fourth quarter against Orlando in December of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was Golden State's all-time low, and it set a
Phoenix franchise record for fewest points allowed in any quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even realize they had only six points,'' said
Robinson, who scored 20 points _ eight in the fourth quarter _
blocked three shots and grabbed seven rebounds. ``We were just out
there enjoying the fact we were stopping them, having fun playing
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning wound up with seven points and six rebounds, but he was
a fourth-quarter catalyst, along with point guard Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors are a difficult matchup for the Suns, as they
demonstrated two nights earlier in Oakland, when they outrebounded
the Suns by 11 and won, 94-90.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's game was following a similar pattern. The young,
bigger Warriors were shooting over 50 percent late in the third
quarter and were again dominating the boards. When the Warriors did
miss, they often got the basket anyway after an offensive rebound.
They had a 15-6 advantage in second-chance points going to the
fourth, and both of those field goals in the final quarter came as
the result of offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that's the strength of their team,'' Ainge said.
``They're bigger, stronger and quicker. I think the skill of our
big players is better. But when we match their youthful energy and
enthusiasm, we're a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen until late in the third quarter. The Warriors
scored just one basket in the final four minutes of the third
quarter, thus getting only eight points over a span of 16 minutes
during which the Suns went from 13 points behind to a runaway
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did something that was uncharacteristic of this team the
last seven or eight games,'' said Warriors veteran forward Terry
Cummings. ``We lost our composure. Some of the calls, some of the
plays, didn't go our way. We took a lot of shots that were totally
out of the context of what we normally do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of get everybody wandering away form it. I've seen it
before. You can see it coming. You have to slow the game down to
almost a crawl and execute your offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Suns limited the Warriors to one shot and got their
running game going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot energy,'' Ainge said. ``I've been in the NBA a long
time, and there's no way on earth a team could play like we did for
48 minutes. That was gear five in the fourth quarter. But we at
least have to be in gear four or three. We're going from gear one
to gear five.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have a nasty habit of falling far behind before they
drop it into overdrive. Sunday's game was the seventh in their last
eight in which they've faced a double-digit deficit. They've
comeback to win four times after trailing by 14 or more.
</P>
<P>
   They did it again, yielding 53 percent first-half shooting to
the Warriors and falling behind by as much as 15 in the third
quarter, playing what Ainge called ``atrocious'' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if our (fourth-quarter) defense was tremendous,
or if it was so bad the rest of the game that it looked
tremendous,'' said forward Tom Gugliotta, who scored 12 of his 20
points in the first quarter. ``We gave them one shot, and it was a
shot (where) we had a hand in their face. We rebounded the ball,
and it kind of ignited our break, allowed us to get into transition
for easy baskets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
