r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-DEATH-AZR &LR;      02-28 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-DEATH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PITCHER KILLED  
 KEN ROBINSON DIES IN ROLLOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM(at) 
 and JANELLE COWGILL(at) 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ One life ended. Others shattered. And in between, a
baseball organization trying to sift through the pieces of its
first _ and what it hopes will be its last _ human tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Robinson, 29, a minor-league pitcher for the Diamondbacks
who was here on a rehabilitation assignment, was killed early
Sunday morning in a one-vehicle rollover on the city's northwest
side.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was a passenger in a vehicle driven by Diamondbacks
minor-league pitcher John Rosengren, who also was here on
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tucson police Officer Mike Brown, &UR; Rosengren, 26,
was booked into the Pima County Jail on one count of second degree
murder after he ``displayed signs and symptoms of impairment'' from
the use of alcohol. A blood sample was obtained from Rosengren; the
results will not be available for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren made his initial appearance in Tucson City Court via
video Sunday afternoon. In addition to his attorney, Tommy Jones,
the Diamondbacks director of minor-league operations was at court.
Bond was set at $75,000 and was expected to be posted late Sunday
night or early today. Rosengren's parents were flying to Arizona
from their home in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   If released, Rosengren would be prohibited by the court from
leaving Pima County and from getting behind the wheel of a vehicle.
His next court appearance will be March 10 at 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Officials from the Pima County Attorney's Office could not be
reached for comment about the second degree murder charge. Bill
FitzGerald, a spokesman with the Maricopa County Attorney's Office,
said manslaughter was the typical charge in such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, 90 percent of the charges filed are for
manslaughter,'' FitzGerald said. ``We would have to look at the
aggravating circumstances, though, to determine that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson leaves behind a wife, Lorrie, and a 1-year-old son,
Chase. The family lives in Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone Sunday, Diamondbacks managing general
partner Jerry Colangelo said the team was trying to put all the
pieces together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're devastated by the fact that the accident even took place
and that the young man lost his life,'' Colangelo said. ``It's a
big blow to lose someone in your organization, and more important
to his wife and child.''
</P>
<P>
   Roland Hemond, the Diamondbacks senior vice president of
baseball operations, spoke with Lorrie Robinson on behalf of the
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts and prayers go out to the family,'' Hemond said.
``This is not an easy time for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter notified the players before their Sunday
morning workout at Tucson Electric Park. Some had already heard
bits and pieces of the news, but Showalter said, ``I wanted them to
hear the truth from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care that it's a baseball team. This is just a tragedy
every way you look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said that the players would be contributing to a fund
set up for Robinson's family and that the organization would do
likewise.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brown, Rosengren and Robinson were heading south on
Silverbell Road shortly after 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle left the east side of Silverbell near Goret Road.
Upon returning to the road, Rosengren apparently lost control, and
the vehicle rolled. Police officers responded at 1:36 a.m.,
paramedics four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had severe head trauma, Brown said, and he was
pronounced dead at the scene. He added that neither Robinson nor
Rosengren was wearing a seat belt. Rosengren was not seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was somber in the Diamondbacks' clubhouse during the
break between workouts for veteran players and those for the
younger prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The player perhaps most affected was pitcher Aaron Small, a
teammate of Robinson's with the Toronto Blue Jays' Triple-A
Syracuse affiliate in 1994 and briefly in 1995, and in the winter
instructional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just went about his business. He was a hard worker,'' Small
said. ``This is a wake-up call that reminds us that there are more
important things out there than baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Small and many of his teammates had just completed a weekly
chapel meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about life and how fragile it is. We said a prayer
for the family,'' Small said. ``I was just joking with him the
other day from across the field. You're never promised tomorrow. It
tells you that in the Good Book.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was claimed off waivers from Toronto on Feb. 17, 1998,
on the advice of Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor, who had
coached both Robinson and Small in the Toronto organization.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after coming to Arizona, Robinson was placed on the
40-man roster, but he never pitched in a game after injuring his
shoulder. He came to Tucson for rehabilitation after surgery and
pitched in one game (two innings) for the Arizona Rookie League
team.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren, a left-hander, pitched for the Detroit Tigers'
Triple-A Toledo affiliate in 1997, then he was released. He signed
with Arizona as a minor-league free agent and was then released
after injuring his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He signed again with Arizona in October after having surgery,
and he joined Robinson in Tucson a few days before the accident.
Minor-league pitchers and catchers not on rehabilitation are due to
report here March 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both those guys were here working hard about four or five
hours every day,'' said Mike Lopriore, the organization's
rehabilitation coordinator and supervisor of minor-league trainers.
``It's a sad, sad thing. I remember Kenny from last summer. He
wanted to get back to the major leagues. He wanted to be
successful. He was a real bulldog.''
</P>
<P>
   Janelle Cowgill can be reached at 444-8332 or at
janelle.cowgill(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
