<SLUG> BC-RAC-NHRA-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATO ATONES FOR OPENER WITH TOP FUEL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. - No more bad dreams and restless nights.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Amato on Sunday exorcised the demons of three weeks ago,
when in a stunning display of mediocrity, he failed to qualify for
the National Hot Rod Association season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Amato erased the nightmare with four wonderfully timed runs in
the Checker Schuck's Kragen Nationals at Firebird International
Raceway Park, capturing the Top Fuel title over runner-up Kenny
Bernstein with a 4.565-second pass at 320.66 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (the season opener at Pomona, Calif.), the morale was
real low,'' said Amato, the only driver to win five Top Fuel
championships. ``We were pulling our hair out. Then, you start
thinking it's going to be a terrible year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some changes; changed everything. Now we're back in
the hunt. This proves hard work pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   What John Force proved in the Funny Car finals was that he could
overcome both the flu and Cruz Pedregon. Saving his best for last,
Force set track records for elapsed time (4.843 seconds) and speed
(317.87 mph) in besting Pedregon (5.095 seconds), who smoked the
tires at half track and was forced off the throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Johnson (6.970, 197.97) also had a date with a trophy,
beating Jeg Coughlin in the Pro Stock final.
</P>
<P>
   But no driver had more to smile about than Amato, who has failed
to qualify only twice in 15 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made runs of 4.60 (seconds) or better four times,'' Amato
said. ``I'm tickled pink. I knew (Bernstein) would be tough. I was
waiting for him to put a number down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein did his best to oblige Amato, unleashing a respectable
4.649-second pass.
</P>
<P>
   On some days, it might have been enough. But not this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got outdistanced,'' said Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA officials announced a record four-day crowd of 81,700, most
of whom attended the final day and watched Tony Schumacher upstage
the three champions.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-round win over David Grubnic, Schumacher recorded the
fastest pass in NHRA history, crossing the quarter-mile finish line
at a mesmerizing speed of 330.23, nearly 4 mph faster than what
record-holder Gary Scelzi (326.44) ran five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But to become an official record, Schumacher needed to post a
subsequent pass within one percent of it, meaning he needed to
reach 326.93 mph. He didn't, but it still was a ride for for the
ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' said Schumacher, who did set a track elapsed time
record during the run with a 4.540-second blast. ``I was stuck to
my seat like Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 1,000 feet, I knew I was on a (good) run. But when I
didn't hear anything on my (headset), I thought it was just a
routine run.''
</P>
<P>
   Routine?
</P>
<P>
   Hah.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason for the radio silence was a wire became
disconnected after Schumacher deployed the parachutes needed to
stop his 6,000-horsepower machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw all the (television) cameras coming at me, I knew
something must have happened,'' Schumacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Something did. Something good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid to say how fast these things will go,'' Schumacher
said.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of the Top Fuel also produced a pair of upsets
that sent some unexpected losers home early.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi (4.677 seconds), the two-time defending NHRA driving
champion, was knocked out by Doug Herbert, who unloaded career
bests of 4.600 seconds at 318.39 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dixon, the No. 3 seed and a former winner at Firebird, was
slow off the starting line and was beaten by 19-year-old Australian
rookie Andrew Cowin.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin lost to Doug Herbert, who lost to Bernstein, who lost to
Amato.
</P>
<P>
   And Amato lost to no one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
