<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCH-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND TO NONE   
 WITH $500,000, MAGEE FEELS LIKE WINNER  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. - Paradise Valley sounds like a golf course in
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Up there, the layout is perfect, the weather divine. No rain.
Bright sunshine. The one time broken clouds appeared, and club
members complained, the improvements committee had them repaired
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise Valley has no rough. No traps. No trouble. Hit a
wayward drive and a cute little squirrel picks up the ball and
deposits it the center of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Magee will tell you no such golf course exists on Earth,
not in Paradise Valley, Ariz., where he lives, or in this San Diego
suburb, home of the La Costa Resort &AMP; Spa.
</P>
<P>
   But Magee wants you to know that even though he didn't win the
$1 million first prize at the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship _ a 38-hole war of nerves _ the experience was close
to heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being ranked No. 50 in a field of the world's top 64
players and advancing to the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as surprised as you guys I'm here,'' Magee said before his
duel with Jeff Maggert.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine losing and being handed a cashier's check for $500,000.
Magee has followed the sun on the PGA Tour for 15 years. He never
earned that kind of money in one tournament, even when he won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard pill to swallow,'' Magee deadpanned, when asked
about finishing second. Looking at him in earnest, the gaggle of TV
types held up their microphones, not knowing if Magee might
suddenly, in delayed-reaction grief, grab one of the mikes and
begin pounding his head with it, flogging himself as punishment for
failing to put his opponent away, and Andrew had his chances.
</P>
<P>
   Magee's smile returned. ``I'll be OK,'' he assured.
</P>
<P>
   Magee is a serious golfer. But he is one in a rare breed of
professional athletes who doesn't take himself too seriously. He
knows what the golfing world wished for, hoped for _ and he wasn't
it. Nor was Maggert, a fine player but one labeled by the media as
being so bland of personality that he has been declared legally
dead in four states.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked whether this format worked, Magee smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work for you,'' he replied cheerfully. Meaning Tiger
Woods and David Duval didn't meet in the final, both having been
eliminated. ``But it worked for ``me.''''
</P>
<P>
   Magee was like a low-seeded school in the NCAA basketball
tournament that quietly works its way through its bracket. He won
his first match (Darren Clarke), then his second (Thomas Bjorn).
Next he beat Bill Glasson, then Shigeki Maruyama, then John Huston.
Close matches.
</P>
<P>
   Few expected Magee to be in the final, but golf is nothing if
not unpredictable. Last year Magee nicked his left finger with a
chainsaw while cutting a tree limb. ``There are better ways to
weaken the grip on your left hand, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   A week later he finished third at the Bob Hope Classic.
</P>
<P>
   All week Magee downplayed the mounting pressure. Drained? ``Not
at all, Magee said. ``I mean, this is a spa.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible for most people to fathom what it must feel
like playing a double round of golf for $1 million. Those of us
Magee's age (36) or older see the amount in print and think of that
old TV series ``The Millionaire.'' Each week Michael Anthony would
present a perfect stranger of modest means a cashier's check in
that dizzying amount, courtesy of an anonymous benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   One million dollars. Asked whether he ever allowed himself to
think about the money during Sunday's match Magee said, ``I thought
about the money all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Who in his right mind wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   Magee twice built a three-hole advantage. But he never could put
away his opponent. On the 38th hole _ the second hole of a
sudden-death playoff _ Maggert chipped from off the green and
watched the ball catch the right corner of the hole and disappear
into the cup. As the instant millionaire danced across the green
and hugged his caddie Magee thought, as he would say later,
``Them's the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed? Sure. Does his wife need to hide the razor blades?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   The ``loser'' will tell you that even if you figure in
inflation, $500,000 will buy a lot of consoling. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
