<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DEVILS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES CONTINUE TO SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After being pounded at home by Anaheim
and Philadelphia by a combined 9-2 margin, the Coyotes convinced
themselves that they needed to go on the road, spend a lot of time
together and find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be good for us to get away for a while,'' Keith
Tkachuk predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's been almost two weeks now, and they're as lost as
they've ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be good to get home now,'' Tkachuk grumbled
after the Coyotes were drilled yet again, this time by a 4-1 count
Sunday afternoon by the New Jersey Devils at jampacked Continental
Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seventh loss in eight games for the Coyotes
(30-20-10), who fell to 1-5 on their seven-game trip with one more
stop in Boston on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, then they come home to greet the two-time defending Stanley
Cup champion Detroit Red Wings on Friday. And surging Anaheim is
only seven points back in the race for the No. 4 Western Conference
playoff seed.
</P>
<P>
   So what the heck is the problem?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Coyotes have scored just nine goals in the
last eight games and only seven in the first six games of this
trip. It hasn't been for a lack of effort, however. They've
recorded 161 shots since they left town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We generated some good opportunities in the second period
today, but opportunities get you squat,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said. ``You have to score. If the other team only gets three
chances and they score on all three, that's all that matters. All
that matters is the results, and we're just not getting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is scoring. Not the role players. Not the rookies. Not
the top dogs. Jeremy Roenick has just three goals in his past 28
games, none in his last eight. Tkachuk has just four in his past 19
and two in his last 11. Rick Tocchet has four in his last 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the puck on the stick of the right player at the right
time, they're in good position,'' Schoenfeld said, ``but we're
either fanning on the shot, we're missing the net, we're burying it
into the goalie or the goalie's making a big save.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, one of the NHL's best, stoned them lots of times
on his way to a 26-save performance. His All-Star counterpart,
Nikolai Khabibulin, faced 25 shots and might be slipping a tad.
</P>
<P>
   Things started well, though. On Phoenix's third shift of the
game, Bob Corkum picked up a loose puck in the neutral zone, and on
the Coyotes' first rush into Devils territory, he fired a shot that
rung off the far post and found the net.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey picked up the pace right away.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Pederson tied it with a long slap shot that Khabibulin
probably should have stopped, and with four minutes left in the
opening period, the Devils took the lead for good on a power-play
goal by Petr Sykora, his 21st.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' power play, ranked second to last in the league?
Don't ask. For the record, they went 0 for 6 on Sunday. After six
games on this trip, they have connected just twice in their past 22
man-advantage situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play's killing us,'' Tkachuk said. ``That's the
biggest problem, the power play. We just can't seem to get it
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick said he's confident the Coyotes can bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going though a hard stretch, and it's something we have
to battle to get out of,'' he said. ``Hopefully, it makes us a
better team after we do get out of this. I know it did last year
when we were struggling, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Devils Coach Robbie Ftorek doesn't think the Coyotes are playing
like dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey listen, that's a good team we beat over there,'' he said.
``Every team goes through slumps and some trying times. They'll be
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't give into it,'' he said. ``We're in a hole, and
the deeper the hole gets, the harder it is to get out of it. You
don't just spring out of it. You've got to scratch and claw and
climb your way out of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
