<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRANKLIN-RAFTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING'S COMING UP ROSES FOR RAF TER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - At 26, Australian Patrick Rafter seems to
have just about everything going his way.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fourth-ranked pro tennis player in the world at the
end of 1998, No. 2 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   He has won two U.S. Opens in a row and in January, teamed with
Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden to win the doubles title at the Australian
Open. He's 17-4 in U.S. Open matches and the first Australian to
win a title in that tournament since John Newcombe in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   He has won more than $7 million since he turned pro in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter will be seeded second, behind Pete Sampras, when the
Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic, an ATP Tour satellite, opens
today at the Scottsdale Princess Resort. In the first round, Rafter
will play an unseeded Alex O'Brien, a former player for Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more that makes Rafter special.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he's a heartthrob for female fans, voted one of
the sexiest men by ``People'' magazine in 1997. He's tall, handsome
and soft-spoken. He also is from a large, close family. And he
likes little children _ in fact, he contributes money to their
well-being. He's adored in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   What else could this guy want?
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one thing, to play as much golf as possible while he's
in Scottsdale. For another, to beat Sampras, Andre Agassi or
whoever else stands in his way of a title.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this tournament is a tuneup for far more profitable
competition on the tour at Indian Wells, Calif., and Key Biscayne,
Fla. But that doesn't mean he doesn't like it here.
</P>
<P>
   ``These courts are fantastic,'' Rafter said Friday. ``I had a
good hit today and yesterday. It's good to be back on a surface
that I feel comfortable on. We don't have courts like this Down
Under.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most endearing things about Rafter is his modesty.
Perhaps that comes from growing up in a big family with modest
means. There were nine children, six of them boys, and his parents
donated substantial amounts of their income to help others.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't start out too well in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 17, I was not very good,'' Rafter said. ``I was No.
10 in Australia and hadn't developed. It took me four years on the
tour to find out what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother Geoff, an acupuncturist and masseur, invested
everything he had _ $14,000 _ to pay for his brother's trips to the
closest ATP satellite tournaments in Asia, according to ``Tennis
Magazine.'' He also became Patrick's coach.
</P>
<P>
   His brother taught him mental discipline, but Rafter eventually
believed he needed more technical coaching and dropped his brother
as coach.
</P>
<P>
   But his career is still a family affair. Geoff has become his
merchandising director; his oldest brother, Steve, is his manager
and agent; brother Peter is his business assistant; and
sister &UR; Louise handles his substantial charity work. After his wins
in the U.S. Open, he donated $600,000, the majority of his purses,
to children's programs at a hospital in Brisbane, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter isn't intimidated by Sampras, but he has a lot of respect
for his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what the pressure is like for No. 1,'' he said.
``He's been there six years in a row. It tells you about the talent
of this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Rafter is touring with his brother, who now divides his
time between Bermuda and British Columbia when he's not playing.
Peter was on the road with Patrick for 16 weeks last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat likes his family traveling with him,'' Peter said. ``He
can be himself.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 Agassi will play unseeded Fernando Meligeni at 6:30 p.m.
Tuesday, followed by a match between Sampras and unseeded Ramon
Delgado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
