<HEADLINE>
TELEMACO HEADED FOR THE BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _  &UR; Amaury Telemaco isn't going to lie. His goal is to be
a starter in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, willing to face the truth, and where the
Diamondbacks are concerned, that means a job in the bullpen in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old right-hander was picked up by the Diamondbacks
in May after he was waived by the Chicago Cubs. He was in the
Arizona bullpen, then joined the rotation and started 18 games. He
finished with a 6-9 record for the Diamondbacks, 7-10 overall.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of three free agents _ left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson
and right-handers  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre and  &UR; Armando Reynoso _ has
pushed Telemaco back into a role as a long reliever and perhaps an
occasional closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I want to be a starter, and I'll never give up on that,''
said Telemaco, a native of the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to pitch in the major leagues. If they want me to
be a starter, I'll be there. If they want me to be a middle
reliever, I'll be there. If they want me to be a closer, I'll be
there. Just give me the ball. I'm ready for anything and will
prepare in any way I can.'' &QL; 
Young arms in spotlight &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the chance that  &UR; John Patterson,  &UR; Nick Bierbrodt and
 &UR; Brad Penny have been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   The three young phenoms are scheduled to pitch two innings
apiece today in the team's first intrasquad game of the spring. It
will begin at approximately 10:15 a.m. at Tucson Electric Park. A
second intrasquad game will be played at 1 p.m. Tuesday at the
minor-league complex across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a big experience for them to reach back on,''
Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Penny, who was the organization's minor-league
pitcher of the year in 1998 with a 14-5 record at Class A High
Desert, hopes to face as many of the veterans as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to see what we can do,'' he said. ``Why not? We don't
have anything to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He probably won't get his wish. Showalter said he likely will
play most of the veterans on Tuesday. &QL; 
Ball strikes back &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez wasn't smiling Sunday after hitting a
ball off a portion of the metal batting cage and having it strike
him in the mouth, loosening the veneer from a front tooth.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a dentist as a precautionary measure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
